<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Balloon Quest-Savior </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Around-the-world sailor likely savior of around-the-world
</HEADLINE>
balloonist
 &UR; With BC-Balloon Quest &QL; 
 &UR; By ROHAN SULLIVAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ Australian skipper Laurie Piper's
homecoming after five years at sea in his home-built yacht will
have to wait. First he must rescue American adventurer Steve
Fossett, whose balloon came down in the South Pacific.
	   Piper and his crew, including daughter Jana, are expected to be
the first to reach Fossett after diverting from the last leg of
their leisurely circumnavigation of the globe when the emergency
calls went out early Monday.
	   Fossett, a millionaire adventurer from Chicago, went down Sunday
night near the Chesterfield Islands, about 500 miles (800 km) off
Australia's east coast, two-thirds of the way through a planned
around-the-world voyage.
	   When rescue authorities in Australia sent out emergency
bulletins to any ships in a 200-nautical-mile radius of Fossett's
emergency beacon signal, Piper's boat Atlanta was already on the
way, having been alerted by a ham radio operator friend in Port
Vila, Vanuatu.
	   Fossett was bobbing in a lifeboat in the Coral Sea after a
French military plan found him Monday morning.
	   A long-time sailor, Piper said he had taken part in rescue's
before, but never saved a balloonist. He expects Atlanta, the
60-foot (18-meter) wooden schooner he built at his home in Eden,
New South Wales state, to reach Fossett by Monday evening.
	   ``We'll have a dinghy with an outboard ready to launch,'' Piper
told The Associated Press by radio phone.
	   ``We'll pick him up as soon as we get there and bring him on
board, give him a cup of coffee, wrap him up and put a good feed in
him.''
	   A fully medically equipped New Zealand Navy tanker is an
estimated three or four hours behind Atlanta, and authorities
expect that Fossett will be transferred on board and brought to
Townsville, in Australia's Queensland state.
	   Authorities hold safety concerns about the rescue because the
region is dotted with reefs, many of which are uncharted. Piper
said he has sailed the reefs before and knows the area.
	   ``I know it is treacherous around there but I am quite sure
we'll be okay.''
	   ``We were just coming home after five years out ... the
Caribbean, the Mediterranean, all over the place,'' he said.
	   He said conditions Monday afternoon were calm after a night of
storms with lightning and high winds to the north and south of the
Atlanta.
	   Piper said he was about 50 nautical miles from Fossett's
position and was motoring at 7.5 knots. He expected to arrive at
the area about 7 p.m. local time (0900 GMT). 	   
</TEXT>
