w1137 &Cx1f; wstm-
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Singapore-IslamicBank     08-17 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Islamic Banking </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Islamic banking faces challenge of global integration
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By LAURINDA KEYS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ The high risks, lower profits and short-term
asset structures linked to banking according to Islamic law were
highlighted Monday at a conference seeking ways to make the system
practical within the global financial structure.
	   Islamic banking, which replaces interest with profit-sharing and
aims to adhere to other Muslim practices, ``has yet to realize its
full potential by overcoming various challenges it continues to
face,'' Syed Jaafar Aznan, a vice president at the Islamic
Development Bank based in Jiddah, Saudi Arabia, said in the keynote
speech opening the two-day conference.
	   ``Some scholars have argued that one of the distinguishing
features of Islamic banking is risk sharing,'' said Jaafar. ``A
major challenge for Islamic banking and Islamic bankers is to
develop financing modes based on profit and loss-sharing, which do
not expose the Islamic banks to unnecessary risks.''
	   He outlined other problems, such as:
	   _ the inability of Islamic banks to punish defaulters by
charging a penalty;
	   _ entrepreneurs with promising projects prefer loans with fixed
charges and a greater share of profits and are reluctant to seek
Islamic bank financing, while those with doubtful projects prefer
the profit-sharing system;
	   _ without a lender of last resort, such as a central bank,
Islamic banks must keep higher reserves, cutting into profits;
	   _ Islamic banking is geared to short-term loans and short-term
assets.
	   ``The Islamic financial tools have largely been limited to
conventional instruments developed centuries ago,'' Jaafar said.
``We must examine what needs are being fulfilled by instruments of
modern finance, such as options, derivatives, hedging, etc., and
either adapt them to meet the Shariah (Islamic law) requirements or
invent Islamic alternatives to them.''
	   Jaafar said that the financial crises in Southeast Asia had
highlighted a disadvantage of conventional banking, which does not
always focus on the viability of a project, since the lender is
protected through security and interest payments.
	   ``Islamic banks, since their lending is on a profit and loss
sharing basis, out of necessity have to focus on the viability of
the operations they are financing,'' he said.
	   Abdullah Tarmugi, Singapore's minister-in-charge of Muslim
affairs, told the conference, ``Islamic banking cannot fully
replace conventional banking except, perhaps in some Muslim
countries.
	   ``The main challenge facing Islamic banking is to become more
sophisticated and competitive and to forge greater linkages with
the conventional banking system,'' he said.
	   The modern Islamic banking movement started in the early 1960s
in Malaysia and Egypt, and the Islamic Development Bank and the
Dubai Islamic Bank were established in 1975.
	   The International Association of Islamic Banks says that as of
1995, there were 186 registered Islamic banks and financial
institutions with total assets of dlrs 166 billion. Net profits
were about dlrs 1.27 billion.
	   No central bankers were among the approximately 200 delegates
from 19 countries at the Asia Islamic Banking and Finance
conference. 	   
</TEXT>
