w1138 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Australia-BritishBack     08-17 0168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-British Backpacker </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
British backpacker's parents say no hope she is alive
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BRISBANE, Australia (AP) _ The parents of a British backpacker
missing in a southeast Queensland state forest said Monday they
have given up hope of their daughter being alive.
	   Lionel and Beth Bridge, from Carlisle, arrived from London on
Sunday to help police search for their 28-year-old daughter Celena,
a keen bushwalker and environmentalist.
	   Police said Bridge was last seen on July 12 when she left
Crystal Waters, a bush location west of Maleny in the Sunshine
Coast hinterland. It is about 45 miles (75 km) northwest of
Brisbane.
	   Bridge failed to appear at a birdwatcher's meeting at nearby
Kenilworth the following weekend.
	   Bridge told reporters Monday, ``We have no hope _ it's a
terrible thing to say but we've got to be realistic.''
	   Police said there were no indications of foul play and they
believe the young woman may have been hurt in an accident in the
state forest. 	   
</TEXT>
