w1140 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Singapore-Hospitals     08-17 0278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Hospitals </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Singapore hospitals cut rates as economic crisis hurts revenue
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Private hospitals in Singapore are reducing
their charges in response to falling occupancy as the economic
crisis reduces their revenues, a newspaper reported Monday.
	   Four such hospitals _ including the two largest private
institutions, Mount Elizabeth and Gleneagles _ have dropped some of
their room rates by as much as 40 percent, according to The Straits
Times.
	   They are hoping to attract patients shying away from these
normally more expensive alternatives to government-run hospitals,
the report said.
	   Since the economic crisis took hold, occupancy at the 505-bed
Mount Elizabeth Hospital has averaged about 60 percent, the paper
reported.
	   A spokesman for Parkway Group Healthcare, which owns Mount
Elizabeth and Gleneagles hospitals, told the newspaper that the
cuts would lure more patients.
	   Lee Cheow Seng, the head of Thomson Medical Center, which has
also cut room rates, was quoted as saying that the measures were
``sensitive to the economic climate here in Singapore and the
region.''
	   Singapore boasts excellent public and private medical
facilities, which earn a significant portion of their revenue from
foreigners from neighboring countries who come specifically for
medical attention.
	   The private hospitals' cuts put some of their room rates below
those of government institutions, which subsidize many medical
costs, the report added.
	   However, private hospitals earn much of their profits from
itemized expenses other than room charges, and most costs are
higher than government facilities. 	   
</TEXT>
