w1144 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEA-Lebanon-WarDispla     08-17 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-Lebanon-War Displaced,0882 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Years after fighting, those displaced are a bitter reminder of
</HEADLINE>
Lebanon's civil war &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos NY302-303 of Aug. 10, Graphic LEBANON DAMOUR &QL; 
 &UR; By ZEINA KARAM &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   DAMOUR, Lebanon (AP) _ Toufic Metni vividly remembers the terror
of fleeing as a 16-year-old from his hometown to escape marauding
Muslim fighters, an attack that killed 23 of his relatives.
	   It was nearly two decades before he got back to Damour.
	   ``We left as children and returned with children of our own,''
Metni, now a 38-year-old father of four, says of his generation's
travails during Lebanon's 1975-90 civil war.
	   He is among some 355,000 Lebanese _ 10 percent of the population
_ who fled or were driven from 900 communities in the
Christian-Muslim fighting.
	   The displaced remain a bitter reminder of the war. No more than
30 percent have gone home even though the accord that ended the
conflict gave priority to drawing refugees back and a plan to
accomplish that was adopted in 1993.
	   The lack of progress is blamed on political disputes, lack of
government funds and some people's unwillingness _ or fear _ to go
back.
	   Many Lebanese have strong emotional ties to home villages, and
legal ones, too, because people still must travel to their old
villages to do official chores like voting and registering birth
and deaths.
	   But what had been expected to unite Lebanese _ repatriation _
has caused division. In particular, Metni and other Christians,
losers in the war, complain they are not receiving as much help as
displaced Muslims or the Druse, an offshoot of Islam whose
followers were heavily in the fighting.
	   ``The civil war will never be over until the last displaced
person returns to his home and village,'' said Pierre Helou, who
leads the Maronite League, a Christian political group.
	   The government already has spent dlrs 500 million on moving
people back to their homes. But a government ministry created to
oversee repatriation says it needs dlrs 1.2 billion more to finish
the job.
	   The focal points of the ``return'' are the Chouf and Aley
districts of central Lebanon where Christians and Druse mainly
lived before the war. There, people were chased from once-shared
towns, and others lost homes when Druse took over villages that had
been exclusively Christian.
	   The man who led the eviction of the Christians _ Druse militia
chieftain Walid Jumblatt _ is now the government minister in charge
of bringing them back.
	   In early July, he blamed Prime Minister Rafik Hariri's
cash-strapped government for the slow progress, saying it is
concentrating on business and tourism development ``at the expense
of people's dignity.''
	   Hariri, who has earmarked dlrs 50 million for returning people
this year, responded by promising ``every displaced person will get
what he deserves until not a single one remains away from his
home.''
	   There is disagreement over how many displaced Lebanese have
returned home _ estimates range from 15 percent to 30 percent.
	   Hisham Nasseredine, director general of the Ministry of the
Displaced, says one reason for the diverging figures is that not
everyone who got compensation used it to go home.
	   ``Some people ... instead bought a car and a cellular phone,''
he said.
	   Survivors of the dead and returning families receive up to dlrs
20,000 each to rebuild houses and lives. Squatters also are paid to
abandon occupied homes, and some Druse have received compensation
to ``reconcile'' with returning Christian neighbors.
	   Metni, a public service employee, said the government aid is
merely ``symbolic'' in places like Damour, about 12 1/2 miles (20
kilometers) down the coast from Beirut, due to the extent of
destruction.
	   ``All that was left of our house was the garden,'' said Metni,
who has rebuilt his family's one-story home since moving back in
1994.
	   Half-completed buildings dot the town. The church is slowly
being repaired, and workers are installing new telephone lines. The
public school reopened last year with just 12 students; it now has
100.
	   Still, only about 8 percent of the town's pre-war population of
32,000 has returned. Among the returnees, many remain angry about
the past and anxious about the future.
	   Metni, for one, has kept the apartment he has in a Christian
suburb of Beirut. ``Who knows, we might need it one day,'' he said.
	   While anger remains in Christian Damour over the killings of
several hundred townspeople in 1976, there is bitterness, too, in
the Druse mountain town of Kfar Matta, site of a 1983 massacre by
Christian militiamen.
	   ``This town had 107 people killed. ... We are still awaiting the
political decision'' on government compensation, Kfar Matta's
mayor, Fouad Khaddaj, said on a recent TV talk show.
	   Some feel the problems of getting people back to their homes
will ease as fears and grudges fade. But attachment to land also
can diminish with time.
	   Afaf Salibi, 58, who fled to a Christian suburb of Beirut 15
years ago with her three children, thinks she will never return to
her hometown of Dibbiyeh.
	   ``Even if we had the money to fix our house, my children do not
want to go back,'' she said. ``Our home there means nothing to them
now.''
</TEXT>
