<SLUG> BC-Embassy Bombings, 1st Ld-Writethru,0722 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pakistan returns bombing suspect to Nairobi
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with new information about bombing suspect, TRIMS. No
pick up. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos NAI101-106 &QL; 
 &UR; By DAVE CARPENTER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) _ The entourage of FBI agents grows in
Nairobi as more investigators try to learn whether the trail of
evidence from the deadly embassy bombing leads to a suspect whom
authorities have brought back from Pakistan.
	   The Pakistan Foreign Ministry and another government source said
Sunday that Mohammad Sadik Howaida was handed over to Kenyan
authorities last week, bypassing U.S. investigators in Pakistan.
	   The Pakistani national newspaper The News, quoting unnamed
government sources, said Sadik gave a determined confession to
planning the bombings and claimed the attack was sponsored by Osama
bin Laden, a Saudi harbored in neighboring Afghanistan who U.S.
officials have identified as a possible suspect.
	   The News said Sadik is a 34-year-old Palestinian engineer. He
reportedly told investigators six other conspirators slipped
through the Karachi airport Aug. 7 and apparently made it to
Afghanistan, where they had been told they would be congratulated
by bin Laden.
	   A Pakistani spokesman said Sadik was arrested on his arrival at
the Karachi airport from Nairobi on Aug. 7, the day twin bombings
at the U.S. embassies in Nairobi and Dar es Salaam, Tanzania,
killed 257 people and wounded at least 5,500 more.
	   A government source in Pakistan, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said Sadik was returned Friday to Nairobi.
	   U.S. officials in Islamabad and Nairobi refused to discuss
Sadik.
	   ``This is a matter in which we are working very closely and very
hard with our Kenyan colleagues. I can't make any comment,'' said
the FBI's assistant agent-in-charge of the Nairobi investigation,
Hardrick Crawford. ``This is an ongoing investigation.''
	   U.S. officials have said that bin Laden, who has been vocal in
his hatred of the United States and is among the world's most
militant sponsors of terrorism, was a possible suspect in the
African bombings.
	   Pakistani Foreign Ministry spokesman Tariq Altaf said
immigration officials determined that Howaida's Yemeni passport was
forged, and he was interrogated by Pakistani officials.
	   A ministry statement identified Howaida as an ``Arab national''
without elaboration, a phrase that in Pakistan usually means
someone from the Middle East.
	   The mourning and the cleanup both continue in Nairobi.
	   American workers wearing helmets were going through the damaged
embassy building over the weekend, occasionally pulling out
magnifying glasses to inspect something before tossing it out the
window onto a heap below.
	   Newsweek magazine reported that investigators have found a
220-kilogram (100-pound) steel driveshaft believed to have belonged
to the pickup truck that carried the bomb to the embassy in
Nairobi. The shaft, found a kilometer (more than a half-mile) from
the site, contains part of the vehicle identification number, the
magazine said, quoting unidentified sources.
	   In Washington, FBI spokeswoman Debbie Weierman would not comment
on the report.
	   Even 10 days after the bombing, thousands of Kenyans still line
up at police barricades erected in a wide circle around the site,
gazing quietly at the wreckage. Others crowd around newspapers laid
out for sale on the sidewalk, reading headlines to learn the latest
developments in the investigation.
	   ``I am very much shocked,'' said Igonisius Mbaka, a 30-year-old
farmer from a village who was getting his first look at the damage
Sunday.
	   A memorial mound of flowers and shattered concrete slabs from
the wrecked buildings lies unattended now, behind the embassy in an
area where the public is no longer allowed.
	   The roses are closing up and fading and scrawled tributes and
messsages left there are yellowing, but their messages remain
poignant.
	   ``We mourn our brothers and sisters together the nation,'' read
one.
	   Kenyan police have said they detained about five people for
questioning in the case.
	   In a show of support for both East Africans and embassy staffers
abroad, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright was planning
brief stops Tuesday in Dar es Salaam and Nairobi. 	   
</TEXT>
