<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-Kosovo-The Serb Side,0962 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Angry and entrenched: Serbs fear ethnic Albanian control in Kosovo
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos NY192-193 &QL; 
 &UR; By ANNE THOMPSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JANINA VODA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Day and night, the Serbs stand
guard. Hiding in the cornfield with their hunting rifles. Crouching
in the village trenches. Lurking in a camouflage blind in the
forest, a machine gun trained on an enemy just 200 yards (meters)
away.
	   The defense has been going on since 6:20 a.m. on June 29, when
the crack of gunfire jolted men from their beds.
	   The Kosovo Liberation Army _ the secessionist ethnic Albanian
rebels, the ``terrorists'' _ had come to take the village.
	   With their rifles, and help from Serb police who eventually
arrived, villagers repelled the rebels. But the KLA just fled down
the road and seized the village next door. Since then the Serbs
have been on high alert, scared and furious that ethnic Albanians
might actually manage to take control _ not just of their houses
but of all of Kosovo province.
	   Janina Voda is 30 households, a speck of a place that has the
misfortune of abutting an unofficial line between regions inhabited
by Serbs and the KLA. But Serbs throughout Kosovo feel equally
entrenched.
	   They are the minority in Kosovo's 2 million people, outnumbered
9-to-1 by ethnic Albanians who overwhelmingly want independence for
the province on the southern tip of Serbia, the republic that
dominates Yugoslavia. President Slobodan Milosevic is determined to
keep Kosovo, and five months ago he sent troops to crush the KLA.
	   Still, Milosevic has offered Kosovo autonomy, which likely would
mean ethnic Albanians would govern. If that happens, some Serbs say
they'll leave. Serbs have lived in Kosovo since medieval times, and
land has been in Serb hands for generations. But ethnic Albanian
control is too bitter a pill to swallow.
	   ``I'm planning to get out, to leave everything behind,'' says a
41-year-old villager standing by the trenches, who gave only his
initials, S.J.
	   ``I'll go deeper into Serbia, where else? Where else can I save
my children's lives?''
	    &UR; ___
	   With the United States and Europe trying to broker autonomy
talks, many Serbs here express resentment, feeling that the world
doesn't care about the Serb side of the story. ``Everyone wants to
know about the ethnic Albanians, and no one asks about the Serbs,''
Kosovo police spokesman Col. Bozdar Filic complained recently.
	   Understanding the Serb side takes a brief history lesson, but
history in Kosovo is relative to who is talking. Albanians and
Serbs both claim to have settled here first, and each claims
oppression at the hands of the other.
	   For the Serbs, the trouble started in 1389 when the Turks
pummeled them on a Kosovo battlefield. The facts of this famous
trouncing are murky down to the question of whether it was even a
clear defeat. But more important than facts _ at least in Kosovo _
is what people THINK happened.
	   Some certainties: Turks ruled for five centuries until 1913,
when they pulled out and Kosovo returned to Serb control. Under
Yugoslav communist dictator Josip Broz Tito, ethnic Albanians in
Kosovo had autonomy. Fast forward to 1989 and Milosevic, who in a
nationalist fever revoked the autonomy, sacked thousands of
Albanians from jobs and ended Albanian-language teaching in state
schools.
	   Since then, the Albanians have boycotted Serb rule in protest _
creating an underground government and refusing to pay taxes or
vote in elections. Last year, the KLA began attacks on Serb police,
and war erupted in full on Feb. 28.
	   For Kosovo Albanians, the war is about Serb oppression of their
human rights. On the Serb side, the war is more about history,
about the 14th-century humiliation by the Muslim Turks and the
Albanians _ mostly Muslim _ who want once again to rob Serbs of
ancient lands.
	   Out in the cornfield, an old man waits gleefully to gun down KLA
rebels with his rifle.
	   ``We will make them do this,'' he says, moving his hand across
his chest in an Orthodox Christian cross.
	    &UR; ___
	   Sitting at their kitchen table around cups of Turkish coffee,
the Stankovic family grows infuriated by suggestions that ethnic
Albanians lack rights. In fact, the Stankovics argue, it is the
Albanians themselves who refuse to exercise the rights they have.
	   If the Albanians did not boycott elections, they could have 30
seats in Serbia's 230-seat parliament. And how dare Albanians not
pay taxes or work in Kosovo, drawing income instead from relatives
in Germany or Switzerland.
	   ``If they were willing to use their rights, they could have
everything they want and still respect the state,'' says Goran
Stankovic, a lawyer for a nearby coal mine. ``We, the minority, are
using our rights. They just refuse to accept anything Serb.''
	   His mother, Stanojka, is weeping.
	   ``Damn this world if you need to stay awake all night in the
trenches and fear for your life,'' she shouts. ``If my son goes
out, I don't know if he'll come back.''
	   Also at the table is Simo Spasic, a bull-necked family friend
who says the KLA kidnapped his brother. The rebels have admitted
kidnapping Serbs, and Spasic's brother is one of about 180 missing
people that the International Red Cross hopes to find.
	   ``They want to kill all the Christians left in Kosovo,'' Spasic
says. ``But even if they kill my brother, I would never leave.
Maybe I'd leave my village, but Kosovo, never.''
	   Spasic is already gone from his village, living since June in a
makeshift hut since the KLA took over Simovac _ the village down
the road. For four generations, his family has owned a red-brick
compound with plum and pear orchards.
	   A KLA commander now has his office there.
</TEXT>
