<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Floods </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
China builds up last dike protecting top oil field from floods
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By RENEE SCHOOF &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Soldiers piled sandbags in a rush to build up the
last defense of China's largest oil field from the raging waters of
the Nen River on Monday.
	   The river already broke through two other dikes protecting the
oil field and Daqing, a city of 2.3 million people. The third
embankment was the last chance to save the oil field from a flood
that would bring disastrous losses.
	   Meanwhile, farther south in central China, the Yangtze River
reached a new record height of 45.22 meters (149.2 feet) Monday at
Shashi city.
	   Officials had warned that if the river went over 45 meters
(148.5 feet) it may be necessary to dynamite dikes and deliberately
flood an area south of Shashi where 500,000 people live to
safeguard cities farther down the river.
	   This summer's floods _ the worst on the Yangtze in 44 years _
have killed more than 2,000 people nationwide and left millions
homeless. The new crest threatened waterlogged dikes that protect
cities and farms downstream.
	   Near the Daqing oil field in the northeast, soldiers, officers
and oil field workers piled sandbags two meters (6.6 feet) high
along a five-kilometer (3.1 mile) embankment, but still needed to
double the height, the state-run Xinhua News Agency reported.
	   About 11,600 oil workers and their families were trapped without
power, food or water at two large state farms on the Nen River,
Xinhua said. An evacuation was slowed by a lack of boats, it said.
	   Flooding at Daqing closed 527 oil wells, reducing output by
6,821 tons last week. Daqing has 25,000 wells that produced 60.9
million tons of oil last year.
	   The second dike protecting the oil field collapsed on Saturday
despite efforts by 2,000 soldiers to pile up sandbags. Thousands of
people had to be evacuated.
	   ``I heard people start to scream and run around blindly when
they learned the dike was breached,'' the China Daily quoted Liu
Hai, a farmer living 3 kilometers (1.9 miles) from the second dike,
as saying. The paper said he had been walking for a day trying to
find his wife and children.
	   No casualties have been reported yet in the Nen River floods,
the paper said.
	   The third dike, 15 kilometers (nine miles) east of the one that
collapsed Saturday night, would be a ``life-and-death defense'' for
the city of Daqing, the China Daily quoted Wang Yang, an army
captain in charge of the dike, as saying.
	   Meanwhile, the level of China's mightiest river, the Yangtze,
continued to rise slowly. Some 2.7 million civilians and soldiers
worked on embankments of the river to protect farms and cities from
floods.
	   ``The situation is still extremely serious. There can be no
letup,'' the Wenhui Daily reported Sunday.
	   In Inner Mongolia in north China, authorities were trying to
rescue 76,000 people stranded by the flooded Ulyji Muren River,
Xinhua said. About 70,000 other people cut off by the river had
been rescued, it said.
</TEXT>
