r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Indonesia-NationalDay     08-17 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-National Day </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
At presidential palace and in a prison, Indonesia celebrates
</HEADLINE>
independence
 &UR; AP Photos
 &UR; By CHRISTOPHER TORCHIA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) - Celebrating Indonesia's national day,
flag-bearing officers strutted at the presidential palace Monday
while traditional dancers sashayed for political prisoners in a
jail yard.
	   From five-star hotels to slum shacks, red and white Indonesian
flags and banners festooned the capital, a festive display belying
the economic hardship that millions are suffering.
	   Police and soldiers were posted at intersections following
rumors that riots might break out during the celebrations, but the
streets were quiet.
	   With Indonesia's economic turmoil stripping people of jobs and
driving up prices, fears linger of more deadly unrest like the
riots in May that helped oust former President Suharto.
	   Some ethnic Chinese, whose shops and homes were targeted in the
Jakarta upheaval that killed about 1,200 people, left the country
amid rumors of violence on Monday.
	   Despite the uncertainty, President B.J. Habibie presided over a
show of pomp on the lawn of his palace, saluting phalanxes of
soldiers who paraded to brass band tunes and waved to choirs of
schoolchildren.
	   Foreign ambassadors and government officials were on hand for a
flag-raising ceremony. Indonesia declared independence from Dutch
colonial rule in 1945. The Dutch left four years later after
failing to quell nationalist forces in a war.
	   Suharto, whose hold on power was dislodged by riots over price
increases and student protests, did not attend the ceremony.
	   On Saturday, Habibie made a marathon speech to Parliament in
which he apologized for widespread human rights abuses during
Suharto's 32-year authoritarian rule.
	   At Jakarta's Cipinang jail, a justice ministry official
announced sentence reductions for some inmates.
	   But some political prisoners there said Habibie should prove his
willingness to guide Indonesia toward democracy by releasing all
jailed opponents of Suharto. So far, he has released dozens.
	   ``We've been treated by the Habibie regime as a commodity,''
said pro-democracy activist Budiman Sudjatmiko, whose 13-year
prison term for subversion was cut by one month.
	   Budiman is head of the People's Democratic Party, a political
party that was banned under Suharto but has since been legalized.
	   To mark independence day, traditional dancers from western Java
island entertained about 200 prisoners, who later played games,
climbing up a flagpole to grab prizes, such as T-shirts or bottles
of water.
	   In a snub to Habibie, prominent opposition figure Megawati
Sukarnoputri, who is the eldest daughter of Indonesia's founding
President Sukarno, staged her own independence ceremony in Jakarta.
	   ``It's better for me to be with the people together, feeling all
the difficulties and concerns,'' Megawati told several hundred
supporters, some wearing headbands with slogans that read
``Reform.''
	   Megawati, who urged democratic change when Suharto was in power,
was ousted as leader of the minority Indonesian Democratic Party in
June 1996 by a government-backed party faction. 	   
</TEXT>
