<SLUG> BC-Japan-Racketeering </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Reports: Police question two men on suspicion of extorting airline
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Tokyo police on Monday began questioning two men on
suspicion of extorting as much as 20 million yen (dlrs 140,000)
from Japan Airlines Co., news reports said Monday.
	   The alleged extortion was reportedly in return for promising to
ensure trouble-free shareholders' meetings for the airline, the
Nihon Keizai newspaper said without quoting sources.
	   JAL, Japan's largest airline, is the latest company to be named
in a crackdown on racketeering that caused the arrest last year of
executives from top companies such as Nomura Securities Co.,
Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank Ltd. and Mitsubishi Motors Corp.
	   Authorities plan to formally arrest the alleged racketeers once
they have gathered sufficient evidence, the newspaper said.
	   A number of JAL executives have already admitted involvement in
the scheme and their case will soon be forwarded to the Public
Prosecutor's Office, the report said.
	   One of the two being questioned allegedly heads a racketeer
group, while the other is the president of an artificial flower
company which the authorities believe to be controlled by the
notorious Sumiyoshi-kai underworld syndicate, the Asahi newspaper
said.
	   JAL is suspected of hiding payments to the racketeers under the
pretext of leasing artificial flowers, according to the Asahi.
	   Police suspect the men helped manage JAL shareholders' meetings
since 1990, the Asahi said. 	   
</TEXT>
