<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Littering </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Singapore considering stiffer penalties for litterbugs
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Clean-conscious Singapore will probably
increase the punishment for littering because the number caught
strewing trash or dropping cigarette butts is sharply increasing, a
newspaper reported Monday.
	   Under current law, litterbugs are either fined or forced to
clean public areas wearing bright neon vests under a penalty
referred to as a Corrective Work Order.
	   Since this mildly humiliating practice was introduced in 1993,
about 2,000 people have served such a sentence, according to The
Straits Times.
	   But Singapore's Environment Ministry is now considering
combining these punishments, and increasing the fine and duration
of the Corrective Work Order, according to the report.
	   The ministry caught 5,858 people littering during the first half
of 1998, nearly triple the number apprehended in the same period
last year, according to the newspaper.
	   The maximum fine for the first littering offense is 1,000
Singapore dollars (dlrs 570), and 2,000 Singapore dollars (dlrs
1140) for subsequent violations.
	   Corrective Work Orders range from half an hour to three hours of
collecting trash in public locales. 	   
</TEXT>
