<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Indonesia-Protest </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Filipino-Chinese protest rapes and killings in Indonesia
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos Available &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Hundreds of Filipino-Chinese, many of
them school children, protested Monday in front of the Indonesian
Embassy to denounce rapes and killings of ethnic Chinese women in
Indonesia during unrest in May.
	   ``We want justice. We want justice,'' chanted more than 500
demonstrators during an hour-long protest rally coinciding with the
53rd anniversary of Indonesian independence from Dutch colonial
rule. The embassy was closed for the holiday.
	   The protest was spearheaded by members of the Philippines
Coalition against Atrocities in Indonesia, composed mainly of
Filipinos of Chinese ancestry.
	   ``We are here to pray that justice be given to the victims of
the May riots in Indonesia specially against the
Indonesian-Chinese,'' said Gina Ang, the principal of a Chinese
school in suburban Pasig City.
	   Hundreds of uniform-clad children from five Chinese schools were
among the protesters. They were joined by Buddhist monks and Roman
Catholic priests and nuns.
	   ``We are here to disturb, to disturb Indonesia's conscience,''
said Rev. Roberto Burgos. ``Only people without consciences will
rape women.''
	   An Indonesian security officer, who tried to stop the protest,
was loudly booed. ``We are Filipinos. We are not Indonesians. You
cannot stop our protest,'' the demonstrators told the officer.
	   He had to be escorted by rally leaders to stop some protesters
from trying to hurt him. At least on protester hit the security
officer with a placard before he could enter the embassy compound.
	   Women's groups in Indonesia allege 168 women and girls were
raped during May's riots, with many of them ethnic Chinese who were
targeted for their affluence. Thousands of Chinese-owned houses and
buildings were ransacked and burned.
	   While Chinese make up only about four percent of Indonesia's
population, they control much of the economy and have been targeted
as scapegoats for the country's financial crisis.
	   Indonesia, the world's fourth-most-populous nation, has been hit
the hardest by Asia's economic meltdown.
	   China has demanded the Indonesian government take firm action to
protect ethnic Chinese citizens, and protesters in Taiwan, Hong
Kong and the United States have called for those responsible to be
arrested. 	   
</TEXT>
