<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dollar higher in Tokyo, Japanese stocks decline
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with closing stock, mid-afternoon bond and currency &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The U.S. dollar rose against the yen Monday,
following concerns Friday in New York trading about economic
stability in Asia and Russia. Tokyo stock prices fell.
	   The dollar bought 146.47 yen as of mid-afternoon, up 1.59 yen
from late Friday in Tokyo and above its late New York rate of
146.35 yen.
	   Persistent doubts about Russia's currency and economy led to a
surge in the dollar against the yen and other currencies in New
York on Friday, traders said.
	   Concerns about a new round of sell-offs in Southeast Asian
currency and stock markets also sent investors scurrying for the
safe haven of the greenback.
	   But the dollar's gains faltered in Tokyo after Japanese
officials signaled their readiness to prop up their currency.
	   Eisuke Sakakibara, a vice finance minister known as ``Mr. Yen''
for his influence on currency markets, warned authorities were
ready to intervene should the dollar rise to 147 yen.
	   That was quickly followed by comments by Haruhiko Kuroda, the
head of the International Bureau at the Ministry of Finance, who
said Japan remains committed to defending its currency.
	   ``We have been saying we will act in foreign exchange markets
appropriately, as needed,'' Kuroda said, adding that the dollar has
grown too strong against the yen.
	   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the benchmark 225-issue Nikkei
Stock Average fell below the psychologically significant 15,000-yen
level for the first time since mid-June.
	   The Nikkei dropped 329.27 points, or 2.18 percent, to close at
14,794.66 _ its lowest since June 17. On Friday, the Nikkei index
sank 258.09 points, or 1.68 percent.
	   The market's dive stemmed, in part, from a worsening of
sentiment following a decline in U.S. stocks traded on Wall Street
Friday, traders said.
	   The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 34.50 points, or
0.4 percent, to 8,425.00, its lowest close since late February and
9.8 percent below its peak of 9,337.97 on July 17.
	   Investors are also worried about the fate of a set of bills
designed to stabilize Japan's shaky financial system, said Eiji
Tomaru, a manager at the investor information group at Kankaku
Securities Co.
	   Opposition lawmakers have criticized the government's banking
legislation as a taxpayer-funded bailout which doesn't punish inept
executives.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section tumbled 16.77 points, or 1.43 percent, to 1,152.03.
The TOPIX fell 12.91 points, or 1.09 percent on Friday.
	   Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese
government bond fell to 1.160 percent from Friday's finish of 1.175
yen, pushing its price up to 112.04 yen from 111.94 yen.
 &UR; (mef-cd-dj) 	   
</TEXT>
