<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Commonwealth Games-Thorpe </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thorpe adds butterfly to games program
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ Australia's 15-year-old world swimming
champion Ian Thorpe has set himself up for a hectic Commonwealth
Games program by deciding to contest the 200-meter butterfly for
the first time at a major meet.
	   Thorpe has succeeded as a freestyler, having won the 400-meter
world title earlier this year in Perth. He also holds the
Commonwealth record for the 200-meter freestyle.
	   Thorpe is not even ranked in the top 50 in the world for the
200-meter butterfly but has been selected as the third Australian
in the event for the Sept. 10-21 Commonwealth Games in Kuala
Lumpur, Malaysia.
	   ``We were approached about swimming the 200 fly. That's the only
reason we're swimming it,'' said Thorpe's coach Doug Frost. ``It
wasn't through choice to go after it and chase it. We're just
swimming it because the opportunity was there and it's after his
main events.''
	   Thorpe, who is younger than his shoe size of 16, will contest
six events in KL: the fly; 100-, 200- and 400-meter freestyle; and
two relays.
	   Thorpe recorded his Commonwealth record of one minute, 47.24
seconds in the 200-meter freestyle at the Commonwealth trials,
beating world champion Michael Klim and showing the form which many
believe have him poised to break Italian Giorgio Lamberti's
nine-year-old world mark of 1:46.69.
 &UR; (tjh) 	   
</TEXT>
