w1185 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Malaysia-Anwar     08-17 0281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Anwar </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Finance Minister calls for transparency in international markets
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Malaysia's finance minister called
Monday for transparency in the international financial system,
saying global players should adhere to the same rules they
advocate.
	   Anwar Ibrahim, who is also deputy prime minister, said it was
``lopsided'' to demand transparency and disclosure from poor
countries and not from wealthier economies.
	   ``Why must poorer countries accept these measures while the
international community is absolved of it?'' Anwar said at a forum
for Islamic leaders in Kuala Lumpur.
	   Malaysian leaders have often blamed Western currency speculators
for plotting to destroy the Southeast Asian economy, once counted
among the world's fastest growing.
	   Malaysia has tried a range of measures to boost its shrinking
economy. The government has estimated the economy will contract by
up to two percent this year. Independent analysts predict it could
be as much as 5 percent.
	   ``Hedge funds and currency traders have to accept the same
rules. You want disclosure, you disclose where the funds are
from,'' Anwar said, adding that it was unlikely affluent economies
would initiate reform of the international financial system.
	   ``We don't expect them to change the ground rules. To them, it's
not a moral issue, it's a dollar issue,'' Anwar said.
	   At the same time, Anwar said that regional economies should not
be complacent as poverty, corruption and excesses continue to
prevail in several of the countries hard-hit by the Asian crisis.
	   Overcoming these weaknesses would ``continue to be a daunting
task,'' he said. 	   
</TEXT>
