<SLUG> BC-Russia-Economy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russia devalues ruble
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; URGENT &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: STANDS as writethru to BC-Russia-Ruble. UPGRADES attribution,
Yeltsin interrupting vacation, heading to Kremlin, ADDS background,
analysis. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos planned &QL; 
 &UR; By MAURA REYNOLDS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ After weeks of financial turmoil, Russia sharply
devalued the shaky national currency, the ruble, on Monday, in a
move expected to cause hardship for Russian consumers and rattle
international markets.
	   The Central Bank lowered its target exchange rate for the ruble
from about 6.3 to the dollar to 9.5 to the dollar.
	   President Boris Yeltsin interrupted his vacation and headed to
the Kremlin for a crisis meeting with his prime minister, Sergei
Kiriyenko.
	   A ruble devaluation had been widely rumored, in part because the
government faces heavy debt payments in coming days and weeks.
	   The government also forced a restructuring of short-term debts,
saying it would halt payment on government treasury bills and
impose a 90-day moratorium on payments of ruble-denominated foreign
debt.
	   The devaluation was expected to raise the prices of imports sold
in Russia, which account for a large percentage of Russian consumer
goods, including more than half the food sold in stores.
	   However, it was also expected to ease the government's budget
crunch, making it possible to pay months of wages and pensions owed
to hard-pressed Russians.
	   Central Bank chairman Sergei Dubinin said the government actions
are designed to help Russian citizens and domestic producers and
hurt ``financial speculators'' who have been fleeing Russian
markets for months, Interfax said.
	   Finance Minister Mikhail Zadornov said the devaluation would
also help spur investment in Russian industry.
	   The devaluation was expected to lead to the collapse of many
Russian commercial banks, who are over-dependent on now devalued
ruble assets. However, the government and Central Bank said they
would pool the resources of leading banks to limit the damage.
	   They also proposed legislation to strengthen controls over
Russian financial markets in an effort to halt further capital
flight.
	   (mr)
</TEXT>
