<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Culminating months of financial turmoil, Russia devalues ruble
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; URGENT &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with quotes from Chubais, parliament likely to hold
emergency session. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos planned &QL; 
 &UR; By MAURA REYNOLDS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ After weeks of financial turmoil, Russia sharply
devalued the shaky national currency, the ruble, on Monday in a
move expected to cause hardship for Russian consumers and rattle
international markets.
	   The Central Bank lowered its target exchange rate for the ruble
from about 6.3 to the dollar to 9.5 to the dollar.
	   President Boris Yeltsin interrupted his vacation and headed to
the Kremlin for a crisis meeting with his prime minister, Sergei
Kiriyenko.
	   A ruble devaluation had been widely rumored, in part because the
government faces heavy debt payments in coming days and weeks.
	   The government also forced a restructuring of short-term debts,
saying it would halt payment on government treasury bills and
impose a 90-day moratorium on payments of ruble-denominated foreign
debt.
	   ``The government's action is an adequate and timely response to
the very grave financial situation which threatened the nation's
political and economic stability,'' said Anatoly Chubais, Russia's
liaison with international lenders who is widely respected in the
West.
	   ``The Russian leadership has taken these steps only after
exhausting other options,'' Chubais said, blaming the country's
financial strait on the Asian crisis and a recent drop in world oil
prices.
	   The devaluation was expected to raise the prices of imports sold
in Russia, which account for a large percentage of Russian consumer
goods, including more than half the food sold in stores.
	   However, it was also expected to ease the government's budget
crunch, making it possible to pay months of wages and pensions owed
to hard-pressed Russians.
	   Central Bank chairman Sergei Dubinin said the government action
was ``aimed at protecting Russian citizens and domestic
producers.''
	   ``The government has decided to act in favor of them and against
traders in the hard currency and bond markets,'' he said according
to the ITAR-Tass news agency.
	   The money tied up in stock speculation ``will now be directed to
the real sector of the economy and serve the interests of all
Russians,'' Dubinin said.
	   The devaluation was expected to lead to the collapse of many
Russian commercial banks, who are over-dependent on now devalued
ruble assets. However, the government and Central Bank said they
would pool the resources of leading banks to limit the damage.
	   They also proposed legislation to strengthen controls over
Russian financial markets in an effort to halt further capital
flight.
	   Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov, who has been critical of the
government's economic policies, announced that the parliament is
likely to agree to hold an emergency session next week.
	   Yeltsin has called on the opposition-dominated parliament to
convene in a special session to endorse austerity measures demanded
by the International Monetary Fund and other lenders. In the
absence of parliamentary approval, Yeltsin has imposed many of the
measures by decree.
	   (mr)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
