<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Floods, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
China builds up last dike protecting top oil field from floods
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Yangtze receding, official saying no need to
explode dikes; ADDS tiger evacuation. Edits to tighten.
 &UR; By RENEE SCHOOF &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Soldiers piled sandbags in a rush Monday to build
up the last defense of China's largest oil field from the raging
waters of the Nen River.
	   The river broke through two other dikes protecting the oil field
and Daqing, a northeastern city of 2.3 million people. The third
embankment was the last chance to save the oil field from a flood
that would bring disastrous losses.
	   To the south, in central China, the Yangtze River reached a new
record height of 45.22 meters (149.2 feet) Monday morning at Shashi
city, home to a half million people.
	   Officials earlier warned that if the river went over 45 meters
(148.5 feet) dikes might be dynamited to deliberately flood an area
south of Shashi and safeguard cities down river. But a flood
control official said the water level dropped slightly later
Monday.
	   ``There's been a turn for the better,'' said the official who
gave his surname, Xu. He predicted the water would not rise so high
to make destroying dikes necessary.
	   This summer's floods are the worst on the Yangtze in 44 years.
Some 2.7 million civilians and soldiers worked on embankments of
the river to protect farms and cities from floods.
	   Near the Daqing oil field, 1,000 kilometers (600 miles)
northeast of Beijing, oil workers and soldiers worked day and night
piling sandbags two meters (six feet) high along a five-kilometer
(three-mile) embankment by Monday, but they needed to double the
height, the state-run Xinhua News Agency reported.
	   About 11,600 oil workers and their families were trapped without
power, food or water at two large state farms on the Nen River, and
their evacuation was slowed by a lack of boats, Xinhua said.
	   Flooding at Daqing closed 527 oil wells, reducing output by more
than 2 million gallons (7.6 million liters) last week. Daqing has
25,000 wells that produced 17.9 billion gallons (68 billion liters)
of oil last year.
	   The second dike protecting the oil field collapsed on Saturday
despite efforts by 2,000 soldiers to pile up sandbags. More than
2,000 people were evacuated.
	   ``I heard people start to scream and run around blindly when
they learned the dike was breached,'' the China Daily quoted Liu
Hai, a farmer living 3 kilometers (two miles) from the second dike,
as saying.
	   The third dike, 15 kilometers (nine miles) east of the one that
collapsed Saturday night, would be a ``life-and-death defense'' for
Daqing, China Daily quoted Wang Yang, an army captain in charge of
the dike, as saying.
	   In Inner Mongolia in north China, authorities were trying to
rescue 76,000 people stranded by the flooded Ulyji Muren River,
Xinhua said. About 70,000 other people cut off by the river had
been rescued, it said.
	   Rescuers also moved 52 Siberian tigers from a breeding and
research center near Harbin, the capital of Heilongjiang province
east of Daqing, to another station of the center 250 kilometers
(150 miles) away.
	   The tiger preserve, a tourist attraction, is near the Songhua
River, which is expected to crest at Harbin on Wednesday bringing
the worst flooding in 50 years.
</TEXT>
