<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Balloon Quest, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Radio contact made with Fossett, who says he is fine
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with radio contact being made, Fossett reporting he is
fine; ADDS quotes from rescue skipper, other details. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos SYD101-103
 &UR; With BC-US-Cross-Pacific Sail
 &UR; By ROHAN SULLIVAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ American millionaire adventurer Steve
Fossett gave a thumbs up to his rescuers and said he was fine
Monday, hours after the balloon he was trying to fly around the
world crashed into the sea, authorities said.
	   Fossett has been in regular radio contact with a Royal
Australian Air Force Hercules C-130 since about lunchtime Monday,
when a rescue plane from Sydney reached the balloon crash site in
the Coral Sea, east of Australia.
	   ``He reports being fine,'' Australian Maritime Safety Authority
spokesman Robin Poke told The Associated Press.
	   A French military plane dropped a 15-man life raft to Fossett at
about 8.40 a.m. (2240 GMT Sunday) Monday, after reaching the site
near the Chesterfield islands, about 500 miles (800 km) off
Australia's east coast, the French Navy in Noumea, New Caledonia,
said.
	   The French plane circled Fossett until its fuel began to run
low, then headed back to its home base in Noumea, Poke said.
	   ``He has been waving to the aircraft as they fly overhead,
giving the thumbs-up,'' said New Zealand defense forces spokesman
Lt.-Cmdr. Bill Morley.
	   The New Zealand navy tanker Endeavour is one of three vessels
rushing to the site. An Australian ketch, the Atlanta, was closest
and skipper Laurie Piper said he expected to reach Fossett by about
7:00 p.m. local time (0900 GMT).
	   ``We'll have a dinghy with an outboard ready to launch,'' Piper
told The Associated Press by radio phone.
	   ``We'll pick him up as soon as we get there and bring him on
board, give him a cup of coffee, wrap him up and put a good feed in
him.''
	   Endeavor was about three hours behind Atlanta and was due at the
site at about midnight Monday (1400 GMT), Morley said.
	   Fossett had been two-thirds of the way to his goal. The balloon
was 500 miles (800 km) off the Australian coast heading toward its
final destination of Argentina, in South America, when contact was
lost, said Alan Blount, director of mission control for the journey
at Washington University in St. Louis, Missouri.
	   Seas in the area were relatively calm but the crew was concerned
because the area is near a coral reef that could be full of sharks.
It was shortly after midnight Australian time when the balloon ran
into trouble.
	   Australian Maritime Rescue Center spokesman Brian Hill told
Australian Broadcasting Corp. radio that Fossett came down near the
Bellona Reefs, an uncharted region which could make ship navigation
and the rescue difficult.
	   About five hours before Fossett's warning locator sounded,
meteorologist Bob Rice had cautioned the balloonist he was
approaching strong thunderstorms _ and that they would be nearly
impossible to avoid.
	   ``There's a good chance that there might have been a lightning
hit on the capsule,'' Rice said. ``But these balloons are very
strong. It's just too early to know what happened.''
	   Fossett was equipped with a wet suit and life raft, and the
capsule of the balloon is seaworthy, but not leakproof.
	   Fossett still had to cross a massive stretch of the Pacific
Ocean between Australia and Argentina and had at least another five
days of travel before he was expected to reach South America, from
where he took off on Aug. 7.
	   Fossett, from Chicago, was making his fourth attempt to fly
around the world. He has also run marathons, climbed mountains and
raced in the Iditarod dog sled race in Alaska.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
