r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Indonesia-EastTimor     08-17 0302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-East Timor </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
East Timorese rebel leaders gets four months cut from sentence
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ The government on Monday cut four
months from the 20-year sentence of East Timor's rebel chief,
resisting international pressure to free him.
	   After the announcement, guerrilla leader Xanana Gusmao
reiterated a call for President B.J. Habibie to release all
political prisoners to prove his commitment to democratic change.
	   ``If this is a regime of reform, Habibie has to release all
political prisoners without preconditions or criteria,'' Gusmao
told reporters in Jakarta's Cipinang prison.
	   Gusmao was arrested in 1992 for fighting against Indonesian
control of East Timor. Under former President Suharto, Indonesia
invaded the former Portuguese colony in 1975 and annexed it a year
later.
	   In an annual tradition, Indonesia freed dozens of prisoners
nationwide and granted sentence reductions to others to mark
independence day Monday. In East Timor, authorities freed 17
prisoners and cut the terms of 220 others, all of them criminals.
	   But the government has refused calls from international human
rights groups and foreign leaders, including European lawmakers and
South African President Nelson Mandela, to free Gusmao.
	   The government has indicated that Gusmao will not be freed until
a peace settlement had been reached over the disputed territory.
	   Habibie has offered a measure of autonomy for East Timor and
wants to maintain Indonesian authority. Gusmao and other East
Timorese activists have demanded a vote on independence for the
territory of 800,000 people.
	   ``Autonomy is only a process for a transitional period,'' Gusmao
said Monday. ``In the end, we have to find out the general view of
East Timorese through a referendum.''
</TEXT>
