<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Albania-NATO Exercise,0394 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO flexs military muscle to help contain Kosovo crisis
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ADAM BROWN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TIRANA, Albania (AP) _ As a dozen jet fighters soared overhead,
about 1,700 troops from the United States and other countries began
a five-day military exercise Monday to show the alliance's
readiness to contain the crisis in neighboring Kosovo province.
	   Troops from 14 nations will conduct training for parachute
supply drops, vehicle and foot patrols, marksmanship and other
non-offensive drills in the Albanian mountains. Ten other nations
have sent observers.
	   Navy Capt. Steve Burnette, spokesman for the exercise, said the
operation, ``Cooperative Assembly 1998,'' was to ``provide
stability and help contain a regional crisis.''
	   The Americans and Europeans fear the fighting in Serbia's Kosovo
province, where ethnic Albanians are fighting for independence,
could spill over into neighboring countries with large Albanian
communities.
	   Hundreds have died in fighting in Kosovo since Serb police
cracked down on the separatist KLA in February.
	   Although the Albanian government supports a peaceful solution to
the crisis, rebels of the Kosovo Liberation Army maintain bases in
the north of the country, from where they smuggle arms and
ammunition into Serbia.
	   The Albanians here are struggling restore the structures of
government, including effective internal security, after last
year's nationwide riots which exploded following the collapse of
pyramid investment schemes which bankrupted much of the population.
	   As military bands played the national anthems of participating
countries, a dozen jets from six nations flew overhead in a display
of military power.
	   Despite NATO's commitment to stability here, the exercise began
as American diplomats and their families were leaving Albania as a
precaution following the attacks on the U.S. Embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania, which killed 257 people.
	   Washington has also warned Americans against traveling to
Albania and offered to assist any of its 890 citizens registered
with the embassy to leave the country.
	   Recent reports that Albanian and U.S. authorities cooperated in
arresting at least five Egyptians in Albania who were suspected of
international terrorist links has heightened fears over the safety
of American citizens. 	   
</TEXT>
