<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Switzerland-Earns-Roche </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Roche announces 3 percent rise in half-year profits
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BASEL, Switzerland (AP) _ Swiss pharmaceutical group Roche on
Monday announced that its first-half net profit rose 3 percent on
the previous year to 2.5 billion Swiss francs (dlrs 1.95 billion).
	   January-June net profit in 1997 was 2.43 billion Swiss francs
(dlrs 1.63 billion).
	   ``The strengthening of operations as a result of the acquisition
of Boehringer Mannheim and Tastemaker and above-average growth in
pharmaceuticals and diagnostics sales had a positive impact on
operating profit,'' Roche said in a statement.
	   In May 1997, Roche announced the acquisition of Corange Ltd.,
the parent of diagnostics company Boehringer Mannheim and
orthopedics unit DePuy, with DePuy being considered a non-core
activity.
	   The group added that the integration of Boehringer Mannheim is
largely complete.
	   In July this year, Roche announced the sale of that unit to
Johnson and Johnson of the United States for dlrs 2.9 billion.
	   Excluding DePuy, Roche's group sales in the first half totaled
12.53 billion francs (dlrs 8.4 billion), up 35 percent from 9.3
billion (dlrs 6.2 billion) francs in the same period of the
previous year.
