w1228 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Pakistan-EmbassyBombi 1stLd-Writethru   08-17 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Pakistan-Embassy Bombing, 1st Ld-Writethru,0652 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Most U.S. Embassy staff to leave Pakistan following handing-over of
</HEADLINE>
bombing suspect &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Americans warned to leave Pakistan, embassy
closing. ADDS byline. TRIMS. No pickup. &QL; 
 &UR; By DONNA BRYSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) _ Most U.S. Embassy personnel were
leaving Pakistan and other Americans were urged to join them Monday
after a suspect in the East African embassy bombings was caught in
Pakistan and turned over to Kenyan authorities.
	   U.S. Embassy spokesman Richard Hoagland said all but about 50 of
the usual contingent of nearly 120 in the Islamabad embassy and
consulates in Karachi, Lahore and Peshawar would leave under
security orders from the State Department. They and their families
will begin leaving Tuesday, he said.
	   ``American citizens currently in Pakistan are urged ... to
consider seriously departing Pakistan,'' the embassy added in a
statement. It noted airports were open and commercial flights
available, but added the embassy was arranging additional flights.
	   Figures on the numbers of Americans other than embassy staff in
Pakistan were not immediately available.
	   In Washington Sunday, the State Department updated its
``worldwide caution'' for Americans, warning specifically against
``all travel to Pakistan .'' The State Department issued a similar
warning hours after the Aug. 7 embassy explosions in Nairobi, Kenya
and Dar es Salaam, Tanzania and cited the potential for more
threats.
	   The revised worldwide caution referred to ``subsequent threats''
without elaboration. Hoagland refused to say whether a specific
threat had prompted the Pakistani warning.
	   Americans in Pakistan have been advised to be on the alert since
last November, when four American oil workers were gunned down in
the southern port city of Karachi following the conviction of
Pakistani Mir Aimal Kasi in the United States in the 1993 killing
of two CIA agents. In March, cement barricades were erected on the
roads leading to the high-walled U.S. Embassy compound in
Islamabad.
	   In a brief statement Sunday, Pakistani Foreign Ministry
spokesman Tariq Altaf said a man identified as Mohammad Sadik
Howaida arrived at the Karachi airport from Nairobi on Aug. 7, the
day of African bombings that killed 257 people. Immigration
officials suspected Howaida's Yemeni passport was forged. He was
interrogated by Pakistani officials who determined he had some link
to the African bombings and handed him over to Kenyan authorities.
	   The News, a national Pakistani newspaper, quoted unnamed
government sources Monday as saying Howaida claimed the attack was
sponsored by Osama bin Laden, a Saudi harbored in neighboring
Afghanistan who U.S. officials have identified as a possible
suspect in the bombings.
	   Bin Laden has been vocal in his hatred of what he sees as U.S.
imperialism and pledged to drive U.S. troops out of bases in places
like his native Saudi Arabia.
	   The News said Howaida was a 34-year-old Palestinian engineer who
confessed to helping plan the bombings. He reportedly told
investigators six other conspirators slipped through the Karachi
airport Aug. 7 and apparently made it to Afghanistan, where they
had been told they would be congratulated by bin Laden.
	   A government source had told The Associated Press on condition
of anonymity that U.S. investigators who came to Karachi were
denied access to the suspect.
	   Pakistan's decision to hand Howaida over to Kenyan rather than
American officials may have been prompted by the case involving
Kasi, the Pakistani convicted of killing two CIA employees during a
shooting spree in Virginia in 1993.
	   When Kasi was arrested in Pakistan in June 1997 in a joint
FBI-Pakistani operation, angry Pakistanis accused their government
of groveling before U.S. power. 	   
</TEXT>
