w1231 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Cambodia-Utilities     08-17 0342
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Utilities </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cambodian utilities prices to skyrocket next month
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ Utilities prices in Phnom Penh are
expected to skyrocket next month, led by a 60 percent increase in
electricity rates, officials said Monday.
	   The new power rates will force other utilities companies to
dramatically raise their prices, said Mann Chhoeun, a city
official.
	   The Cambodia Daily newspaper reported that water charges could
be pushed 40 percent higher.
	   The price hikes, which were put off until after last month's
parliamentary elections for political reasons, have been blamed on
the drop in the value of Cambodia's currency and the rising price
of diesel oil.
	   Word of the price increases has incensed Phnom Penh residents
who say they cannot afford the higher rates. Many complain that
they are already often overcharged by corrupt officials.
	   ``No one can survive the new costs,'' said Meas Bun, 63, an
employee at National Museum. ``My salary is only 35,000 riel (dlrs
10) a month. I will have to cut my use of electricity.''
	   As of Sept. 1, the power company Electricite du Cambodge will
increase the charge per kilowatt hour from 350 riel (10.2 cents) to
the riel equivalent of 16.5 cents for residences and for industrial
enterprises that use more than 250 kilowatt amps per hour, company
officials said.
	   Embassies, hotels, private banks, entertainment clubs,
commercial buildings, rental housing and foreigners will be charged
the equivalent of 19 cents per kilowatt hour, a 9.5 percent
decrease from the current commercial fee, in effort to get them to
stop using their own generators and start using city power.
	   Public institutions and small enterprises will be charged the
riel equivalent of 17.5 cents.
	   ``The raise is unavoidable,'' said Tan Kim Vin, a power company
official, who explained that the company has been losing more than
dlrs 1 million a month since Jan. 1. ``In a market economy, if you
don't pay attention to financial sufficiency, you go bankrupt, you
die.''
</TEXT>
