<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Vietnam-Dengue Fever </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dengue fever outbreak affects 3,030 in one province
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HANOI, Vietnam (AP) _ An outbreak of dengue fever, fostered by
an ongoing drought, has left four people dead in the central
province of Quang Binh, the Labor newspaper reported Monday.
	   It said 3,030 people, including more than 900 children, had
contracted the mosquito-borne virus as of Aug. 11, and there were
no signs the outbreak is being brought under control.
	   Vietnam has been hit hard by dengue this year, with a number of
deaths in the Mekong Delta from a particularly bad strain of the
disease.
	   The drought in central Vietnam, the second this year, has
created ideal conditions for a dengue epidemic by turning many
rivers into strings of stagnating ponds where mosquitoes breed.
	   Neighboring Quang Tri province has reported 10,200 cases so far,
although no deaths have been attributed to dengue.
	   Dengue infects an estimated 50 million people each year in a
geographic band around the equator. It causes fever, joint pains,
chills and, in serious cases, hemorrhaging.
	   Patients can take several weeks to recover and there is no
vaccine.
</TEXT>
