w1238 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HongKong-Japan-WarAnn     08-17 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Japan-War Anniversary </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hong Kong marks victory over Japanese in Sino-Japanese war
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos HK101-3
 &UR; By PRISCILLA CHEUNG &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Chief Executive Tung Chee-hwa on Monday marked
the 53th anniversary of Hong Kong's liberation from Japanese troops
in the Sino-Japanese war with scores of veterans who fought under
the Chinese Communist banner.
	   About 1,000 people, including scores of elderly veterans, some
sporting mainland military medals, attended the solemn ceremony in
sweltering heat at a war memorial in the rural New Territories
bordering China. They sang war songs, and several veterans
exchanged stories of their experiences.
	   It was the first time the post-handover government gave official
recognition to the 1,000-strong local Independent Battalion, which
fought for Hong Kong's liberation during the war, said the
organizer, Lo, a Hong Kong delegate to China's legislature.
	   Lo said the colonial government refused to acknowledge the
troops' contribution for decades for political reasons, and that
this was the first time survivors staged a high-profile event in
Hong Kong to mark the anniversary.
	   Last year, Tung drew criticism for failing to organize any
official activities to mark Hong Kong's liberation. The government
announced earlier an official ceremony would be held during the
Chung Yeung Festival in autumn, when Chinese traditionally
commemorate their ancestors.
	   Hong Kong was returned to Chinese rule in July 1997, ending more
than 150 years of British rule.
	   ``These people should be remembered,'' for their contribution,
Lo said.
	   One veteran, Tsui Yung-tak, 72, said he patrolled the outlying
Lantau island for Japanese soldiers and local thugs nightly. He
said he feared he would be killed when Japanese troops captured him
one night because ``three people from my village had been killed
already.''
	   He said he was released after being left partially blind in a
brutal beating.
	   Wong Tan-tai, 76, wearing three medals, proudly showed off a
scar from a bullet that went through his neck.
	   ``We were known to be tougher than anynone else,'' he said.
	   Tung, followed by several Hong Kong-based Chinese officials and
community leaders, laid wreaths at the foot of a monument built in
1989 for Sino-Japanese war victims. He greeted the veterans, but
didn't give a speech.
	   Meanwhile in downtown, a group of activists that China regards
as subversives also organized their own commemoration.
	   About 40 people later marched to the Japanese consulate calling
for Japan to apologize for wartime atrocities and compensate the
so-called ``comfort women,'' Asian women forced into prostitution
for Japanese soldiers. But the office was closed for the national
holiday.
	   Hong Kong suffered greatly under three years and eight months of
Japanese occupation between 1941-45.
	   The Communist army organized a 1,000-strong battalion after the
British surrendered the territory. Lo said about 400 veterans
survive, with half of them living in Hong Kong.
	   David Lan, the territory's secretary for home affairs, also
attended another ceremony with former local and British servicemen.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Hong Kong-Japan-War Anniversary; CT:i; 
