r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NewZealand-StolenPain     08-17 0303
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-New Zealand-Stolen Painting </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Stolen French painting recovered
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   AUCKLAND, New Zealand (AP) _ A French painting stolen and
damaged in a daylight raid at Auckland Art Gallery earlier this
month was recovered by police in New Zealand on Monday.
	   The 1874 oil painting ``Still on Top,'' by French-born artist
Jacques-Joseph (James) Tissot, was valued at up to U.S. dlrs 1
million before it was taken by a gun-wielding thief on Aug. 9.
	   Police recovered the work after armed officers searched a
cottage in the township of Waikaretu.
	   The painting was located under a bed but small pieces of the
canvas were missing and there were several rips. The work was still
attached to its frame at the bottom but had been cut away at the
other three sides.
	   Gallery director Chris Saines admitted he was ``shattered'' when
he saw the damage but was confident it could eventually return to
public display.
	   ``It's been a tumultuous day,'' Saines said. ``There was the
excitement of hearing about the recovery and then the devastation
of seeing the painting in the condition it is.''
	   Saines said there was no doubt the value of the painting had
fallen as a result of the damage and he said restoration would take
about a year.
	   ``It's quite remarkable what contemporary conservation can do,''
Saines said.
	   The likely course of restoration included relining the work,
putting it down on to a new canvas backing and infilling the bare
patches if the missing pieces could not be found.
	   He said one piece of luck was that much of the major damage was
away from the areas of intricate detail.
	   A 48-year-old unemployed man appeared in Pukekohe District Court
Monday charged with three counts of aggravated robbery including
the one at Auckland Art Gallery. He was remanded in custody. 	   
</TEXT>
