w1247 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEA-Italy-VirtualPapa     08-17 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-Italy-Virtual Papacy,0604 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Vatican forging Internet connections with far-flung bishops
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By DANIEL J. WAKIN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   VATICAN CITY (AP) _ From Washington to Warsaw, the pope's
brother bishops and his diplomatic soldiers will soon grow closer
with a new computer network.
	   Working out of the Internet Office behind the Vatican's walls,
church experts are building a network that will let bishops enter a
password and download instructions and documents direct from Rome.
	   Meanwhile, Vatican nunciatures, or embassies, will be provided
direct access to the Vatican's computers. Instead of using a local
Internet server to log on via the Vatican's Web site, diplomats
will tie into Vatican computers through private phone-line
connections.
	   Envoys and the office of the Vatican's secretary of state will
be able to exchange diplomatic instructions and field reports _
whether about persecution of Roman Catholics or the state of
church-run hospitals _ instantly and securely via e-mail.
	   The direct hookup will be a major boon, particularly in
countries where Internet connections must be made through
state-controlled servers, said Sister Judith Zoebelein, technical
director of the Internet Office.
	   When it comes to governments that may be hostile to the church,
``the last thing we want is our e-mail sitting there,'' she said.
	   Diplomatic messages will be encrypted for added security, she
added.
	   The two projects, expected to be in place by the end of the
year, fit in with major strides in technology under Pope John Paul
II, who has shown himself adept at spreading his message with the
tools of the digital age.
	   He has set up a Vatican broadcasting office, recorded the rosary
on compact disc and is moving forward with an authoritative Vatican
Internet site for laymen.
	   The Web site started simply, giving the text of John Paul's 1995
Christmas message and providing a destination for e-mails.
	   Three-and-a-half years later, the site's developers have plans
to create what looks uncannily like a virtual papacy.
	   Programmers are working on having the site provide live audio
feeds of the pope's words, starting with his Sunday blessing; video
clips of papal activities; and an electronic archive of every papal
document this century.
	   ``We are thinking of a thousand things,'' said Bishop Claudio
Maria Celli, who runs the Vatican administration and oversees the
Internet Office.
	   By 2000, Celli predicts, all the teachings of this century's
nine popes will be available on the Internet. That includes the 20
thick volumes of John Paul II, who is one of the most prolific
popes in recent times.
	   Celli acknowledges there is a danger of a loss of authenticity
for some Catholics who experience their faith through cyber means.
	   ``The road to God needs participation in a community. The
Internet offers elements, but it doesn't substitute this road,'' he
said.
	   Security is another major concern. The Vatican invested heavily
in protective measures in setting up its Internet computers.
	   Hackers try to break in to the Vatican's computers six or seven
times a day, Zoebelein said.
	   ``All you have to do is get in and change a document, and you
can change profoundly (church) teachings,'' she said.
	   Citing security concerns, she would not discuss the names given
the computers in the 11-computer cluster, which was donated by
Digital.
	   The Vatican previously has revealed that three of them are named
after the archangels Gabriel, Raphael and Michael _ God's
messengers to man, according to Catholic tradition.
</TEXT>
