<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Indonesia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chinese protest attacks against Indonesian Chinese
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos Available

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ More than 100 students tried to protest Monday
outside Indonesia's embassy to protest attacks against ethnic
Chinese, but police who had banned the demonstration let just four
through to present a petition.
	   The Beijing students were protesting brutal attacks against
ethnic Chinese in Indonesia during riots in May that helped bring
down President Suharto.
	   Chinese women angered by rapes committed during the riots and
what they said was their own government's fainthearted response
also appealed Monday to the United Nations to investigate.
	   The students who gathered outside the embassy and demanded to
see the ambassador did so even though police last week refused to
grant permission for a demonstration, citing public order concerns.
	   Police kept the students back from a fenced-off compound housing
the embassy building. After prolonged discussion with a group of
students, the police allowed four male students wearing shorts and
T-shirts to go into the compound to meet an embassy spokesman and
submit a petition.
	   The students, who marched in arm-in-arm, gave the spokesman
documents and a T-shirt marked with the slogan ``Protest the
violence, punish the murderers.'' It was covered with student
signatures on one side and a handwritten letter to the Indonesian
government on the other.
	   Uniformed police kept the other protesters across the street.
That group of about 100 cheered when the four walked out of the
compound.
	   Workers at a construction site and some passers-by paused to
watch the gathering, something not seen on Beijing streets for
years.
	   Chinese authorities are wary of any civic protests, fearful that
they could escalate into larger demonstrations against the
government. Officials are doubly anxious to keep a lid on any
protests at Beijing university campuses because they initiated
massive pro-democracy demonstrations in 1989.
	   A women's group of writers and journalists also asked last week
for police permission to demonstrate outside the embassy on Monday,
which marked Indonesian national day, but were turned down.
	   Instead, about 40 women attended a meeting Monday in a Beijing
hotel, listening to speakers who tearfully condemning the rapes of
ethnic Chinese women and young girls. They accused their own
government of reacting late and weakly to the atrocities.
	   The women released a letter that they planned to forward to U.N.
Secretary General Kofi Annan, as well as a protest note to
Indonesia's ambassador in Beijing.
	   The students said they wanted to know what action Indonesia's
government planned to take to prevent ethnic Chinese from being
attacked again. They also called for an end to laws that allow
discrimination against ethnic Chinese and an accounting of the
government's actions in the May unrest.
	   The students also unfurled a banner in English that read ``All
these things to be answered for.'' But police made them take it
down within seconds. Police also prevented reporters from speaking
with the students. 	   
</TEXT>
