<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Asian Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Asian markets fall on concerns over U.S. stocks and regional
</HEADLINE>
currencies

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Asian stock markets fell Monday on concerns
over the slump on Wall Street and shaky regional currencies, with
the key index in Tokyo tumbing more than 2 percent.
	   Tokyo's benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 329.27
points, or 2.18 percent, to close at 14,794.66 _ its lowest since
June 17, and below the pschologically significant 15,000-point
level. On Friday, the Nikkei index sank 258.09 points, or 1.68
percent
	   Traders blamed the drop in part to a worsening of sentiment
following a decline in U.S. stocks traded on Wall Street Friday.
	   The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 34.50 points, or
0.4 percent, to 8,425.00, its lowest close since late February and
9.8 percent below its peak of 9,337.97 on July 17.
	   Concerns about a new round of sell-offs in Southeast Asian
currency and stock markets also sent investors scurrying for the
safe haven of the greenback.
	   The U.S. dollar was quoted at 146.47 yen as of mid-afternoon, up
1.59 yen from late Friday in Tokyo and above its late New York rate
of 146.35 yen.
	   Malaysian shares were also trading lower at midday because of
the concerns over Asian currencies.
	   The Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange's Composite Index fell 4.12
points, or 1.3 percent, to 323.86.
	   In Taipei, share prices closed lower as investors were worried
about Taiwan's slowing economy. On Friday, the Taiwanese government
cut its 1998 economic growth forecast to 5.3 percent _ the lowest
since 1985 _ from 6.02 percent.
	   The Taipei market's key Weighted Stock Price Index fell 97.99
points, or 1.3 percent, to 7,273.85.
	   New Zealand share prices closed lower, with brokers saying the
local market mirrored a fall on the U.S market Friday and investor
caution relating to domestic political uncertainty. The NZSE-40
Capital Index fell 3.60 points, or 0.1 percent, to 1,937.97.
	   Philippine shares losed lower on late profit-taking. The
30-share Philippine Stock Exchange index fell 2.21 points, or 0.1
percent, to 1,335.71.
	   Australian share prices also slumped during a gloomy trading
day. The All Ordinaries Index fell 32.2 points, or 1.3 percent, to
2,536.8.
	   In Seoul, share prices closed lower on continued concern over
the unstable Japanese currency. The Korea Composite Stock Price
Index fell 2.99 points, or 0.9 percent, to 301.62.
	   Singapore shares opened mostly lower, dragged down by Friday's
fall on Wall Street.
	   The markets were closed in Hong Kong and Indonesia for holidays.
</TEXT>
