u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SouthAfrica-BothaTria     08-17 0363
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Botha Trial </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
South African ex-president Botha begins last day of trial
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By PAUL HARRIS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) _ Lawyers for P. W. Botha argued
during closing arguments Monday that a contempt charge against the
hard line apartheid-era president should be dismissed.
	   Attorney Lappe Laubscher said the Truth and Reconciliation
Commission made technical errors in calling Botha to appear.
	   Botha, 82, ignored the summons, claiming that the panel probing
atrocities committed under white rule wanted to humiliate him by
forcing a public appearance after he had supplied more than 1,700
pages of written answers.
	   A motorcade brought Botha to court, and whisked him through a
back entrance after a security scare. Police said a ``suspicious
package'' in the lobby was later found to be harmless.
	   Wearing a dark blue suit, Botha smiled and joked with supporters
and family when he entered the courtroom.
	   Forcing Botha to appear became a key test of the commission's
credibility, especially with many black people who accuse it of
being too soft on top members of apartheid governments.
	   Commission lawyers wanted to question Botha on the role of the
State Security Council, a shadowy security body he headed during
the 1980s when a violent crackdown on anti-apartheid groups reached
its peak.
	   During his trial Botha's defense team has been confronted with
documents and witnesses who allege the council authorized the
killing of black liberation fighters.
	   With a verdict set to be delivered in about a week, the trial is
now nearly at an end.
	   Botha's spokesman, Paul Lombard, said Botha was looking forward
to the end of a tiring case. ``It doesn't matter who you are, or
how old you are. Something like this will take it out of you,'' he
said.
	   If convicted Botha faces up to two years in jail or an
unspecified fine. Given his age and frail health a fine is
considered more likely.
	   As usual security was tight, with rolls of razor wire and armed
police ringing the court in George, a small coastal town about 240
miles (390 kilometers) east of Cape Town.
	   (ph/djw)	   
</TEXT>
