</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKorea-Hyundai </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police raid on strike-bound Hyundai Motor Co. appears imminent
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo
 &UR; By KYONG-HWA SEOK &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ The government appealed for a
negotiated settlement of a labor dispute at Hyundai Motor Co.
Monday amid signs of an imminent police intervention.
	   ``We don't have time to stumble any longer,'' Labor Minister Lee
Ki-ho told reporters before leaving Seoul to visit striking Hyundai
workers in Ulsan, 280 kilometers (175 miles) southeast of Seoul.
	   He said police would break up the strike if the dispute is not
resolved soon. News reports said the number of riot police in Ulsan
was being increased from 4,500 to 13,000
	   The national news agency, Yonhap, said a raid could come in a
day or two.
	   The nation's largest auto firm has been idle since July 20 when
its 26,000-member union went on strike to protest spreading
layoffs. About 2,000 workers and their family members have since
been picketing the company's main plants.
	   Chief presidential spokesman Park Ji-won said earlier Monday
that the government's patience in dealing with the problem is
limited.
	   ``The government wants both sides to come up with a compromise,
but law should be upheld under any circumstances,'' he told
reporters.
	   His reference to the law apparently reflected the government's
position that the Hyundai strike is illegal because it was called
without a request for mandatory government mediation.
	   Past police raids on Hyundai and other major strike-bound plants
resulted in violent clashes with workers. Hyundai's union is known
for its militancy.
	   Hyundai's unionized employees want the company to take back
1,600 workers it fired July 31 because of sharply falling domestic
sales.
	   Hyundai, which earlier got rid of 6,100 workers by offering them
enhanced early retirement packages, insists it has to reduce its
work force in line with slumping demand for its cars.
	   The Korean Confederation of Trade Unions, a major umbrella labor
group, threw its strength behind striking Hyundai workers Monday by
declaring that other members under its control will go on strike if
police launch a raid on Hyundai plants.
	   The confederation, which claims a membership of 500,000 in car,
steel, shipbuilding and other key industries, also said it will
pull out of talks with the government and management on labor
problems.
	   As of Monday, Hyundai said the strike had cost it dlrs 535
million in lost production. Nearly 75 percent of that amount would
have come from exports, it said.
	   Hyundai Motor, a subsidiary of Hyundai group, South Korea's
second largest conglomerate, has been operating at 40 percent of
its annual capacity of 1.25 million cars.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
