<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Commonwealth-Weather </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Officials predict clear weather for Commonwealth Games
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Athletes and visitors to the
Commonwealth Games that open in September are likely to enjoy
clear, haze-free air, because no forest fires have been reported
this month, the meteorological department said Monday, according
the national news agency Bernama.
	   Many nations participating in the 10-day games that begin on
Sept. 11 have voiced concerns that air pollution from brush fires
may affect the health of athletes.
	   September 1997 was one of the worst months for haze in Malaysia.
Smoke billowing from blazing forests in Indonesia blanketed the
region, closing down airports and schools and causing thousands of
people to seek treatment for respiratory disorders.
	   More than 6,000 athletes and officials from 70 nations are
expected take part in the games billed as the second largest sports
event after the Olympics.
</TEXT>
