<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Vietnam-Iron Deficiency </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Children, pregnant women lack iron in diet
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HANOI, Vietnam (AP) _ Researchers are trying to figure out the
best way to add iron to fish sauce to overcome a deficiency that
affects a large part of Vietnam's population, the director of the
National Institute of Nutrition said Monday.
	   Professor Ha Huy Khoi said a 1995 survey showed that more than
50 percent of Vietnamese women of reproductive ages and children
suffer from iron deficiency, mainly due to poor diet.
	   The mostly seriously affected groups are pregnant women and
children under age 2, he said.
	   Local and foreign economists have estimated that iron
deficiencies result in the loss of some dlrs 200 million a year due
to the low productivity of affected workers.
	   Fish sauce was chosen as the possible solution because it is
used virtually every day. The problem is how to add iron without
affecting taste.
</TEXT>
