<DATE_TIME> 08/17/1998 04:55:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w1263 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Albania-NATOExercise 1stLd-Writethru   08-17 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Albania-NATO Exercise, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO flexes military muscle to help contain Kosovo crisis
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS with new details THROUGHOUT; security heightened due
threats by Islamic groups, new quotes, BACKGROUND; no pickup. &QL; 
 &UR; By ADAM BROWN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TIRANA, Albania (AP) _ As a dozen jetfighters soared overhead,
about 1,700 troops from the United States and other countries began
a five-day military exercise Monday to show the Alliance's
readiness to contain the crisis in neighboring Kosovo province.
	   Security was heightened because of concern over Islamic
extremists following explosions at U.S. Embassies in Africa and the
arrest of several Egyptians here, reportedly in connection with
religious violence in Egypt.
	   Albanian troops cordoned off the air base adjacent to Rinas
International Airport where the opening ceremony was held. American
and German troops also manned checkpoints.
	   Troops from 14 nations will conduct training for parachute
supply drops, vehicle and foot patrols, marksmanship and other
non-offensive drills in the Albanian mountains. Ten other nations
have sent observers.
	   Navy Capt. Steve Burnette, spokesman for the exercise, said the
operation, ``Cooperative Assembly 1998,'' was to ``provide
stability and help contain a regional crisis.''
	   The Americans and Europeans fear the fighting in Serbia's Kosovo
province, where ethnic Albanians are fighting for independence,
could spill over into neighboring countries with large Albanian
communities.
	   Hundreds have died in fighting in Kosovo since Serb police
cracked down on the separatist KLA in February.
	   ``We want to have an impact that NATO is just around the
corner,'' U.S. Adm. Joe Lopez, NATO commander of Allied
Forces-South, told reporters. ``Belgrade and any belligerents in
the region will get the same message _ that NATO is ready. NATO has
a wide range of contingencies and options ranging from peace
support to combat operations.''
	   Albania's defense minister, Luan Hajdaraga, said the the NATO
show of force ``is important to discourage'' any move by the
Serb-led Yugoslav government to drive ethnic Albanians from Kosovo.
	   Although the Albanian government supports a peaceful solution to
the crisis, rebels of the Kosovo Liberation Army maintain bases in
the north of the country, from where they smuggle arms and
ammunition into Serbia.
	   The Albanians here are struggling restore the structures of
government, including effective internal security, after last
year's nationwide riots which exploded following the collapse of
pyramid investment schemes which bankrupted much of the population.
	   As military bands played the national anthems of participating
countries, a dozen jets from six nations flew overhead in a display
of military power. In addition to the military portion of Rinas
airport, exercises will take place in three other locations: a
training area Bize, the village of Kunje and the capital Tirana.
	   Despite NATO's commitment to stability here, the exercise began
as American diplomats were and their families were leaving Albania
as a precaution following the attacks on the U.S. Embassies in
Kenya and Tanzania, which killed 257 people.
	   Washington has also warned Americans against traveling to
Albania and offered to assist any of its 890 citizens registered
with the embassy to leave the country.
	   Recent reports that Albanian and U.S. authorities cooperated in
arresting at least five Egyptians in Albania who were suspected of
international terrorist links has heightened fears over the safety
of American citizens.
	   Burnette said security was normally strict for NATO exercises
but acknowledged that controls had been tightened ``because of some
threats by Islamic groups.'' He declined to elaborate.
	   The largest contingent in the exercise comes from Italy which
sent about 500 troops. The Italians increased their participation
after the Americans scaled down their numbers because some warships
were diverted to Africa to provide security for Americans in the
Congo, where rebels are seeking to oust President Laurent Kabila.
	   Other large-scale participants, including the Americans,
Germans, French, Turks and Canadians, have sent about 200 troops
each.
	   ab-me-reid
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Albania-NATO Exercise, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:ENGL;)
