<HEADER>
w1264 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEA-Colombia-PeaceWor     08-17 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-Colombia-Peace Worries,0754 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Army pullout for peace worries Colombians
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With FEA-Colombia-Rebel Village &QL; 
 &UR; By JARED KOTLER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   VISTA HERMOSA, Colombia (AP) _ Nervous police still guard rubble
left from an assault by leftist guerrillas who flattened their
barracks with everything from mortar fire to a homemade tank built
from a tractor and a steel garage door.
	   Combat raged all night and an officer was killed repelling the
April rebel attempt to take this forlorn town that has suddenly
moved center stage as Colombia's new president tries to end a
34-year civil war.
	   Now all that bravery may have been in vain.
	   President Andres Pastrana, who took office this month, is
offering the country's most powerful guerrilla army the opportunity
to walk back into Vista Hermosa, about 110 miles (175 kilometers)
south of the capital, Bogota, without firing a shot.
	   The prospect is worrying residents in this and four other
southern municipalities. Pastrana plans to demilitarize by November
to create a secure venue where peace talks can be held with the
15,000-member Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC.
	   ``There are people who want to leave town because they're
afraid,'' said town secretary Jaidy Pedreros. ``But if we're to
have peace someday we're going to have to make a sacrifice.''
	   Pastrana last week reaffirmed his decision to pull government
forces from the towns, which together comprise a 16,200-square-mile
(41,960 square-kilometer) swath of high-rent savannah _ twice the
size of El Salvador _ where farmers graze cattle, plant rice,
plantains and tropical fruits, and grow coca, the raw material for
cocaine.
	   Military leaders have warned against the move, saying the FARC
will take advantage to strengthen its stranglehold on southeastern
Colombia while expanding the cocaine trade that yields ``war
taxes'' for the rebels, their largest income source.
	   Those concerns multiplied after a rebel offensive on the eve of
Pastrana's Aug. 7 inauguration left a major anti-narcotics base in
ruins. As many as 143 police and soldiers were killed and 129
captured.
	   Pastrana has insisted that drug trafficking will not increase
with the demilitarization. The five towns ``will be converted into
a laboratory for peace,'' he said. Many observers feel, however,
that the wealthy and effective rebels have little incentive to lay
down their arms.
	   The guerrilla's recent show of strength was a reminder of the
tenuous grip government forces hold in a region dominated by rebels
for decades and impoverished by central government neglect.
	   Like the Vista Hermosa base, the government's police and army
posts in the four other municipalities are vulnerable, isolated
outposts.
	   In a drizzle one recent morning, police and soldiers patrolled
this town's streets. Without venturing too deeply into the
rebel-infested countryside, the men provided relative peace of mind
for about 4,000 urban residents.
	   Guerrilla threats against candidates forced the cancellation of
elections last October, but about 2,000 residents braved rebel
bullets to vote in the first round of presidential elections on May
31.
	   ``Those people can't be expecting anything good if the
guerrillas take over,'' said Gen. Freddy Padilla, commander of the
army's 7th brigade in Villavicencio, about three hours north.
	   The troop presence may also be a deterrent to right-wing
paramilitary groups, who moved into the region exactly one year
ago, carrying out brutal massacres of civilians they suspect of
rebel sympathies. Some residents fear Vista Hermosa's history as a
rebel stronghold would make it a prime target for the militias.
	   Town officials are trying to calm those fears. They say the
threat of violence will be lessened if the Red Cross and other
civilian agencies are allowed to move in as the troops pull out.
	   But grocery owner Dalia Castano, one of the few residents
willing to give her name to reporters, says the prospect of an army
exit has already dried up investment, depressed business and sent
property values plummeting.
	   Saying she and every other merchant in Vista Hermosa must pay
off the rebels for the ``right'' to be in business, Castano
believes the army's removal will upset a stalemate between the
guerrillas and the government that had at least made a difficult
life predictable.
	   ``The people in the capital think we're living in a war, but we
actually have a kind of peace,'' she says.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-FEA-Colombia-Peace Worries; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
