<HEADER>
w1265 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEA-Colombia-RebelVil     08-17 0447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-Colombia-Rebel Village,0446 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Colombian rebel commander says he'll never lay down weapons
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With FEA-Colombia-Peace Worries &QL; 
 &UR; By JARED KOTLER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   El PINALITO, Colombia (AP)_ Revolutionary slogans spray-painted
on a bridge are the only outward signs of rebel control in this
village in Colombia's war-wracked south. But it doesn't take a
genius to find the guerrillas.
	   Just ask the kid in the Che Guevara T-shirt and wait while he
disappears in search of ``El Comandante'' _ the local chief of the
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC, the country's
largest rebel group.
	   At the village dock, coca seedlings are passed from canoes to
pickup trucks, which speed the raw ingredient for cocaine off to
the illegal plantations dotting the surrounding plains. Local
merchants praise strict ``laws'' imposed by the rebels _ who tax
the coca trade, impose curfews, fine bar brawlers and banish or
even kill violent criminals.
	   Patience pays off when a mudsplattered jeep pulls up beside a
cantina. Out jumps the rebel chief, who jams his 9mm pistol into
the back of his jeans and takes a seat at a streetside table.
	   Five feet (1.52 meters) tall with a wiry frame and a peasant's
sun-baked face, Comandante Alberto is eager to talk. But he's in no
mood to give up a struggle the rebels have waged since the 1960s.
	   Despite the FARC's pledge to begin peace talks by November with
President Andres Pastrana, the rebels in El Pinalito are grinning
about their recent military victories and more confident than ever
of victory.
	   ``We've made gestures of dialogue with every government,'' says
Alberto, who heads one of the 15,000-member insurgent group's
estimated 63 fighting fronts. ``But the FARC will never give up its
arms. This never even crosses our minds.''
	   A withering rebel offensive before Pastrana's Aug. 7
inauguration inflicted heavy army losses and raised doubts about
whether Pastrana can do much more than accept guerrilla control
over nearly half the national territory.
	   ``They can have their base over there and we'll keep our camp
here,'' said Alberto, gesturing up a dirt road to where an army
company sits a 45-minute drive away.
	   He insists the rebels are still fighting to end poverty and
foreign exploitation. And he scoffs at critics who say the
guerrillas have become little more than a criminal enterprise
feeding off the drug trade.
	   Comandante Alberto also defends his role as judge and
executioner in a village where the rebels are said to carry out
death sentences for unrepentant thieves.
	   ``We want the people to live like one big family, '' he says.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-FEA-Colombia-Rebel Village; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
