<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Caribbean-Summary,1011 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
An overnight summary of Caribbean news
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 
 &UR; BASKETBALL: Webber's agent denies player had marijuana or paid
fine &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) _ Basketball star Chris Webber
``vehemently denies'' he was caught in possession of marijuana or
paid a fine for the offense.
	   Customs Service officials on Saturday reported that Webber
admitted to owning a bag containing 11 grams of marijuana that was
sniffed out by a customs dog at San Juan's international airport on
Friday.
	   A statement said Webber paid a dlrs 500 administrative fine and
was allowed to continue his journey from Dominican Republic to
Barbados on a tour sponsored by the sporting good company Fila.
	   But Webber's agent, Fallasha Erwin, said Sunday there had been a
mixup about who owned the bag.
	   ``A traveling companion claimed ownership of the luggage and
paid the administrative penalty of dlrs 500. However, for unknown
reasons, officials listed Chris Webber as the owner of the bag, not
the traveling companion,'' Erwin said in a telephone call from his
Detroit office.
	   Erwin said the bag contained high-heeled shoes and other items
belonging to Webber's female companion.
	   ``Mr. Webber vehemently denies he had possession of marijuana.
Chris Webber did not pay an administrative penalty of dlrs 500,''
Erwin said.
	   The Customs Service stuck by its original statement.
	   ``I cannot go into details, but what we released yesterday was
the truth and we will back it up,'' said spokeswoman Awilda
Pereira.
 &UR; GUYANA: President to propose relaxed sentence for marijuana
possession
	   GEORGETOWN, Guyana (AP) _ Guyana's government is going to stop
jailing people caught with small quantities of marijuana, President
Janet Jagan says.
	   Jagan said she will introduce a bill that would punish marijuana
users caught with less than five grams with only a fine or
community service.
	   ``We want to give a more common sense approach,'' Jagan said in
an interview on state television Sunday. ``What I am saying is that
small cases are being given heavy fines and I don't think it is
right. In the whole narcotics trade, the hard drugs are the real
drugs that are dangerous to people.''
	   In 1988, Guyana introduced a mandatory five-year jail sentence
for possessing marijuana, in addition to a maximum fine of Guyanese
dlrs 10,000 (dlrs 70).
	   Jagan's party should pass the proposed bill since it holds a
majority in the Parliament.
 &UR; PUERTO RICO: Demolition explosions bring down 17 buildings
	   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) _ Simultaneous explosions reduced 17
apartment buildings to piles of concrete and tangled steel, putting
a thunderous end to two of Puerto Rico's largest housing projects.
	   One minute after workers detonated charges at 9:03 a.m. Sunday,
only the elevator shafts of five buildings in the Pan American
Village and Las Orquideas (The Orchids) housing projects remained
standing.
	   ``We have managed to eliminate that eyesore that stood at the
entrance of San Juan,'' said Housing Secretary Ana Carmen Alemany.
The 27-acre (11-hectare) site is to be turned into shopping, office
and apartment complexes in a project dubbed the ``New Gateway to
San Juan.''
	   Hundreds of spectators and officials from the Guinness Book of
Records attended to investigate the government's claim that it was
the world's largest demolition explosion. They did not immediately
comment on whether the explosion won the title.
	   Police evacuated 300 families from buildings near the demolition
site and blocked off two main highways.
	   Officials from Demolition Inc. said they used 1,200 pounds (540
kilograms) of dynamite to bring down 50,000 tons (45,000 metric
tons) of concrete and steel.
 &UR; GUYANA: Booker-Tate says it will manage Guyana Sugar for three more
years
	   GEORGETOWN, Guyana (AP) _ Booker-Tate Ltd., the British
agricultural firm, says it has won a contract to continue managing
Guyana's sugar industry for another three years.
	   Details were not immediately available, and government
representatives could not be reached for comment Sunday.
	   Booker-Tate has managed the state-owned Guyana Sugar Corp. since
1990 under a restructuring program supervised by the World Bank and
International Monetary Fund.
	   With average annual production levels of 255,000 tons, (230,000
metric tons), Guyana Sugar is the largest producer in the 15-nation
Caribbean Community.
	   The firm said it hopes to double production to 500,000 by
building new factories and putting more land under cultivation to
take advantage of a growing brown sugar market.
	   The demand for brown sugar has grown in part because of
increased sales of U.S. soft drinks to India and China, the company
said in a statement Sunday.
	   Caribbean Community members together produce about 850,000 tons
of sugar annually.
 &UR; DOMINICAN REPUBLIC: Congress opens with political split
	   SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) _ The Dominican
Republic's Congress opened with an immediate dispute over
leadership that split the majority Dominican Revolutionary Party.
	   On Sunday, 10 Revolutionary Party members announced they were
forming an opposition faction in the lower House of Deputies. They
split because the party had chosen Winston Arnaud to preside over
the chamber instead of the incumbent, Rafael Peguero Mendez.
	   The party's share of seats fell from 83 to 73, causing it to
lose its majority in the 149-member house.
	   At the same time, the parties of President Leonel Fernandez and
former President Joaquin Balaguer announced a limited alliance.
	   Together they helped re-elect Peguero to the presidency of the
House of Deputies. Peguero beat Arnaud by three votes.
	   Revolutionary Party lawmakers left in protest. Party followers
burned tires near the Congressional Palace. The demonstrators
accused Fernandez of ``snatching away'' the presidency of the
House. 	   
</TEXT>
