<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Myanmar-Activists, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Myanmar issues veiled threat of violence against foreign activists
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Myanmar government response to US government in
grafs 7,8, ethnic insurgents supporting Suu Kyi grafs 17,18
 &UR; AP Photo BK101

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Myanmar's military government issued a
veiled threat of violence Monday against any foreigners intent on
repeating the pro-democracy leafletting campaign carried out by 18
activists last week.
	   ``The Myanmar people want to live in peace and are angry with
the 18 foreigners,'' wrote Maung Pyi Tha, a pen name for a
government official, in a commentary in Monday's state-run New
Light of Myanmar newspaper.
	   ``The next time any destructionists or saboteurs try to disrupt
the country they will face not only the laws but the people who are
ready to prove their sense of duty,'' he wrote.
	   The same author wrote in a commentary on Saturday, that if he
had apprehended the activists he would have physically assaulted
them.
	   The activists _ six Americans, three Thais, three Indonesians,
three Malaysians, two Filipinos and an Australian _ were arrested
the day after the 10th anniversary of a failed nationwide democracy
uprising in Myanmar, also known as Burma, for handing out
pro-democracy leaflets.
	   On Friday, they were sentenced by a Myanmar court to five years
in prison with hard labor. The government deported them on
Saturday.
	   The Myanmar government said Monday it was distressed that the
U.S. government responded to the release by issuing a statement
saying basic human rights are not protected in Myanmar.
	   ``Bearing in mind the American activists avowed aim is to
overthrow the government of Myanmar, we wonder the U.S. government
will deal with such foreign citizens,'' a Myanmar government
spokesman said.
	   Myanmar government officials frequently speak of
``annihilating,'' and ``crushing,'' the democratic opposition led
by 1991 Nobel Peace Prize winner Aung San Suu Kyi.
	   On Monday, Suu Kyi entered her sixth day of a stalemate with the
military over her right to meet members of her party outside
Yangon.
	   She and three colleagues were stopped in their van by the
authorities 32 kilometers (19 miles) outside the capital while
traveling to the city of Bassein.
	   The military is refusing to let them proceed, insisting there is
a threat of violence against her in Bassein.
	   The only physical attack on Suu Kyi came in Nov. 1996 by a mob
whose members said they were paid by the government.
	   This is the fourth time in two months Suu Kyi has been stopped
at the same roadblock. The government forcibly ended the last
incident by seizing Suu Kyi's car, forcibly restraining her and
driving her against her will back to Yangon.
	   Suu Kyi's party won 82 percent of the seats in parliament in a
1990 election the military refused to honor.
	   The NLD has set an Aug. 21 deadline for the government to
convene parliament.
	   On Monday, the Karen National Union, an ethnic insurgent group
fighting for autonomy from the military government, issued a
statement supporting the NLD's call for parliament to convene.
	   It called the military government's failure to allow the
congress to meet a ``criminal breach of trust,'' and denounced the
persecution of those elected.
	   Of the 385 NLD members elected in 1990, 181 have either been
imprisoned by the government, forced into exile, died or stripped
of their parliamentary status by the government.
	   The rest are living under harassment from the military, the NLD
has said.
</TEXT>
