w1297 &Cx1f; wstm-
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Germany-RussiaEconomy     08-17 0177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Russia Economy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Share prices in German banks drop on ruble devaluation
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ Share prices in Germany's largest
commercial banks dropped across the board Monday in reaction to the
devaluation of the Russian ruble.
	   Shares of Deutsche Bank, Germany's largest commercial bank, fell
3 percent to 132.65 marks (dlrs 73.70) on word of the devaluation.
Commerzbank shares were down 2.3 percent at 58.77 marks (dlrs
32.65).
	   The decline in bank share prices brought down the German stock
market 2.1 percent to 5358.54 points in early trading.
	   Traders said the Russia's 90-day moratorium on the payment of
all foreign credits also pressured share prices. However, the
reaction was based more on perceptions than any real impact since
more than 90 percent of German bank loans to Russia are covered by
guarantees from the German government.
	   German banks had dlrs 30.4 billion in outstanding credits to
Russia at the end of 1997, according to the Bank for International
Settlements.
	   (apdj/cb)
</TEXT>
