<SLUG> BC-Embassy Bombings, 2nd Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pakistan returns bombing suspect to Nairobi
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS with report that second suspect arrested, no comment
from U.S. investigators, FBI statement expected, State Department
warns against travel in Pakistan, grafs 1-21. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos NAI101-106 of Aug. 16 &QL; 
 &UR; By DAVE CARPENTER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) _ The entourage of FBI agents grows in
Nairobi as more investigators try to learn whether the trail of
evidence from the deadly embassy bombing leads to at least one
suspect arrested abroad and returned to Kenya.
	   Amid a flurry of reports and other indications that the
investigation into the Aug. 7 blasts in Nairobi and Dar es Salaam,
Tanzania, was picking up momentum, the FBI said it would issue a
joint statement later Monday.
	   In the wake of reports that a man had confessed to the bombing
in Pakistan before being flown back to Nairobi, a Kenyan newspaper
reported Monday that FBI agents had flown another suspect back
following his arrest in the United Arab Emirates.
	   The East African, citing airport sources, said the suspect is a
Pakistani national who was arrested in Dubai and flown to Nairobi
on Friday on a U.S. military plane. The report did not give the
suspect's name or specify his alleged role in the bombing.
	   A spokesman for the U.S. Embassy in Nairobi, Bill Barr, and
Kenyan police both declined comment Monday morning. A Pakistani
Embassy spokesman, Malik Ashraf, said he was unaware of the second
reported arrest.
	   In Pakistan on Monday, most U.S. Embassy personnel were leaving
and other Americans were urged to join them after the interrogation
and reported confession of Mohammad Sadik Howaida.
	   The U.S. State Department updated its ``worldwide caution'' for
Americans, warning specifically against all travel to Pakistan and
referring to ``subsequent threats,'' without elaborating.
	   The Pakistan Foreign Ministry and another government source said
Sunday that Howaida was handed over to Kenyan authorities last
week, bypassing U.S. investigators in Pakistan.
	   The Pakistani national newspaper The News, quoting unnamed
government sources, said Sadik gave a determined confession to
planning the bombings and claimed the attack was sponsored by Osama
bin Laden, a Saudi harbored in neighboring Afghanistan who U.S.
officials have identified as a possible suspect.
	   The News said Sadik is a 34-year-old Palestinian engineer. He
reportedly told investigators six other conspirators slipped
through the Karachi airport Aug. 7 and apparently made it to
Afghanistan, where they had been told they would be congratulated
by bin Laden.
	   A Pakistani spokesman said Sadik was arrested on his arrival at
the Karachi airport from Nairobi on the day of the twin bombings
that killed 257 people and injured more than 5,500.
	   A government source in Pakistan, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said Sadik was returned Friday to Nairobi.
	   U.S. officials in Islamabad and Nairobi refused to discuss
Sadik.
	   ``This is a matter in which we are working very closely and very
hard with our Kenyan colleagues. I can't make any comment,'' said
the FBI's assistant agent-in-charge of the Nairobi investigation,
Hardrick Crawford. ``This is an ongoing investigation.''
	   U.S. officials have said that bin Laden, who has been vocal in
his hatred of the United States and is among the world's most
militant sponsors of terrorism, was a possible suspect in the
African bombings.
	   Pakistani Foreign Ministry spokesman Tariq Altaf said
immigration officials determined that Howaida's Yemeni passport was
forged, and he was interrogated by Pakistani officials.
	   A ministry statement identified Howaida as an ``Arab national''
without elaboration, a phrase that in Pakistan usually means
someone from the Middle East.
	   Signaling another potential step forward in the case, Newsweek
magazine reported that investigators have found a 220-kilogram
(100-pound) steel driveshaft believed to have belonged to the
pickup truck that carried the bomb to the embassy in Nairobi. The
shaft, found a kilometer (more than a half-mile) from the site,
contains part of the vehicle identification number, the magazine
said, quoting unidentified sources.
	   In Washington, FBI spokeswoman Debbie Weierman would not comment
on the report.
	   Meanwhile, the mourning and the cleanup both continue in
Nairobi.
	   American workers wearing helmets were going through the damaged
embassy building over the weekend, occasionally pulling out
magnifying glasses to inspect something before tossing it out the
window onto a heap below.
	    &UR; Even 10, 1st Ld-16th graf 	   
