<SLUG> BC-Kuwait-Briton </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Court upholds jail sentence for Briton convicted of forgery
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUWAIT (AP) _ A high court has upheld a five-year prison
sentence given a British businessman convicted of forgery, his
lawyer said Monday.
	   But attorney Fadhel al-Jumaili said he expects his client, Ian
Beaumont, 32, of Wetherby, West Yorkshire, to be included in the
next pardon announced by Kuwait's ruler because of his good
behavior in prison.
	   ``He has been in prison for around two years, and I expect this
will be his last,'' al-Jumaili told The Associated Press.
	   The annual amnesty is usually announced on National Day in
February. The ruling by the Cassation Court, which is final, was
issued in June but not immediately made public.
	   Beaumont was found guilty in November 1996 of forging a money
transfer from a Lebanese businessman's account at the Gulf Bank to
his own account in a Swiss bank. He denied the charges and insisted
he had nothing to do with the transaction.
