<SLUG> BC-Koreas-Catholic Priest </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
South Korean Roman Catholic priest to face arrest
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; RETRANSMITTING to remove garble &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ A South Korean Roman Catholic priest
may face arrest for engaging in political activities during his
just ended visit to North Korea, officials said Monday.
	   The Rev. Moon Kyu-hyon and eight other South Korean Catholic
priests were allowed to make a week-long visit to North Korea on
condition that they attend only religious functions celebrating the
Aug. 15 Korean Independence Day.
	   But Moon attended a series of political functions sponsored by
North Korea to denounce rival South Korea, government officials
said.
	   ``As far as we know, his activities and remarks as reported by
North Korean media seriously violated what he had promised in
writing not to attend political functions,'' one Unification
Ministry official said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
	   The official said Moon may be arrested when he returns to Seoul
this week.
	   Moon serves as a co-chairman of the (South) Korean Catholic
Priests' Council for Justice, a human rights group.
	   He was convicted in 1990 of making an unauthorized visit to
North Korea and served three years of a five-year prison term
before being granted amnesty by the government.
	   No one from either North or South Korea can visit the other side
without approval from their governments, which is rarely given.
	   The Koreas have been bitter rivals since the division of their
peninsula into the communist North and the capitalist South in
1945. They fought a bloody three-year war in the early 1950s.
</TEXT>
