<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKorea-Politics </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
South Korea finally has a prime minister
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ South Korea's Parliament finally
ratified Kim Jong-pil as prime minister Monday, six months after
the veteran politician was nominated by the president.
	   Approval came on a 171-65 vote after the opposition Grand
National Party was given the chairmanships of six of the General
Assembly's 13 committees, including defense and foreign affairs.
	   President Kim Dae-jung nominated his coalition government
partner, Kim Jong-pil, to be prime minister right after he took
office on Feb. 25.
	   But the Grand National Party, which holds a majority of seats in
the unicameral assembly, refused to go along and tied up the
nomination in procedural disputes.
	   The president bypassed that difficulty by naming Kim Jong-pil
acting prime minister without parliamentary approval, a move the
opposition claimed was illegal.
	   That dispute and others tied the assembly in knots and it has
accomplished almost no work, despite a crushing economic crisis
that has gripped the nation since late last year.
	   Under mounting public pressure to get something done, the rival
parties compromised on distribution of committee chairmanships over
the weekend and agreed to bring up the nomination for a vote.
</TEXT>
