<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 1st Ld Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Major Albanian stronghold falls to Serb police
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Serbs taking three Albanian villages, details,
information from UNHCR. Trims. CHANGES Logja to Lodja throughout. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos PRI102-106.
 &UR; By ISMET HAJDARI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Serb forces captured three more
villages in western Kosovo, pushing ethnic Albanian militants away
from the province's second-largest city, media reported Monday.
	   Yugoslavia's state-run Tanjug news agency said Serb police
``crushed'' important strongholds of the rebel Kosovo Liberation
Army in the villages of Lodja, Grabovac and Rausic, all just
outside the province's second city of Pec.
	   The push comes a day after the Serbs gained control of the
rebels' main logistical and weapons distribution center, forcing
the KLA to flee into the surrounding hills and forests, abandoning
weapons and ammunition.
	   The pro-Albanian Kosovo Information Center reported government
forces reportedly used tanks and helicopters to attack the village
of Lodja, 70 kilometers (55 miles) southwest of Pristina, and eight
other villages in the area. The center also claimed Serb forces
razed Lodja.
	   There was no immediate information on casualties and the reports
could not be independently confirmed.
	   The KLA is fighting Serb security forces for the independence of
Kosovo, where ethnic Albanians make up 90 percent of the province's
2 million people. Kosovo is in Serbia, the dominant Yugoslav
republic.
	   Over the past two weeks, government forces have succeeded in
driving the KLA from several key villages in western Kosovo.
Government gains have, however, proven difficult to maintain, as
the KLA simply return to an area the moment police move on.
	   Tens of thousands of refugees also remain camped in the woods in
western Kosovo. The U.N. refugee agency based in Geneva, said
Monday it was sending its second in command to meet with leaders on
both sides to call for a cessation of hostilities and full access
for humanitarian operations, spokesman Kris Janowski said.
	   On Sunday, the agency received reports of some 20,000 people
holed up in the woods east of Decane, near Junik, Janowski said.
	   Reporters who visited Junik Sunday found the village deserted,
except for about 15 elderly people who were too old to flee. Some
houses were still smoldering, but most of the village remained
intact.
	   According to Col. Bozidar Filic, a police spokesman, there were
no civilian casualties in the fighting over the town of Junik.
Tanjug said four policemen and two Yugoslav army soldiers died in
the operation. There were no immediate reports of causalities on
the Albanian side.
	   Filic said that by wiping out the rebel stronghold, ``the
territory of Kosovo has been freed for movement in all directions.'
But since fighting began five months ago, gains by government
forces have proven difficult to maintain and it remained possible
the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army could still regroup.
	   Last week, the militant organization named Adem Demaci as the
leader of its political wing. Demaci refuses to work with his arch
rival, moderate leader Ibrahim Rugova, who is favored by the West.
	   The Serb government in Belgrade has invited Rugova's negotiating
team to start peace talks as early as this week.
	   But Rugova had said earlier the government offensive must stop
before he would return to the negotiating table. Rugova favors
independence, but lacks the support of the KLA because he opposes
the use of violence.
	   (pvs/jg)
</TEXT>
