<SLUG> BC-NIreland-Arrests, 1st-Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police arrest five suspects on suspicion of Omagh bombing
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Combines urgent series, adds bomb threat at Stormont &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) _ Police arrested five suspects
Monday on suspicion of involvement of the Omagh bombing that killed
28 and wounded 220.
	   An officer in the Royal Ulster Constabulary, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said the five were arrested at dawn in
their homes near Omagh, 70 miles (110 kms) west of Belfast.
	   Some of those arrested lived in the village of Mountjoy, 3 miles
(5 kms) north of Omagh, others from the village of Sixmilecross 8
miles (13 kms) to the southeast.
	   Among those arrested, the officer said, is a relative of Omagh
politician Dessie Mackey, who earlier this year resigned from the
IRA-allied Sinn Fein party over its decision to accept the Northern
Ireland peace agreement.
	   The officer cautioned that charges against any of the suspects
was not imminent and under Northern Ireland anti-terrorist law they
could be interrogated for up to a week before being charged or
released.
	   This marked the first concrete action by Northern Ireland's
security forces in response to the Saturday car bomb in Omagh,
which has been widely blamed on a dissident Irish Republican Army
group.
	   At Stormont, the center of British administration for Northern
Ireland in east Belfast, meanwhile, staff were evacuated after a
telephoned bomb threat.
	   In recent months there's been several hoax calls made to
different government buildings within the complex.
	   Monday's alert affected the building that houses the Department
of Agriculture, Dundonald House.
	   Police said they were investigating a telephone warning saying
there is a bomb in a parking lot.
	   (sp-acw) 	   
</TEXT>
