<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Vietnam-Motorbike Hike </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Import ban sends motorbike prices soaring
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HANOI, Vietnam (AP) _ A ban on motorbike imports has sent prices
soaring for Vietnam's preferred method of transportation.
	   The ban, announced last month in an effort to reduce the
country's trade deficit, has pushed the price for the most popular
model, the Thai-made Honda Dream II, to dlrs 2,900, up dlrs 600
from six months ago.
	   The government has granted licences for six motorbike joint
ventures with a total capacity of 900,000 units per year. Four
joint ventures have been turning out some 200,000 units per year.
	   The Industry Ministry estimates annual demand at 500,000 units.
	   Roughly 90 percent of Vietnam's traffic is on two wheels. As
people save money, one of their top priorities is to switch from
bicycles to motorbikes.
</TEXT>
