<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Indonesia, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Beijing residents protest attacks against Indonesian Chinese
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS; UPDATES with quotes, women turned away from embassy,
other details, trims; ADDS byline, photo numbers
 &UR; AP Photos BEJ101-104
 &UR; By JOHN LEICESTER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Defying a police ban, more than 100 Beijing
students gathered outside Indonesia's embassy Monday to protest
brutality against ethnic Chinese during riots in Indonesia in May.
	   In a separate display of anger, Chinese women horrified at the
rapes committed during the riots appealed to the United Nations to
investigate the atrocities and accused their own government of
reacting late and faintheartedly.
	   ``We want to push the government to take stronger action,'' said
novelist Zhang Kangkang, one of about 40 women who met in a hotel
after police refused them permission to demonstrate outside the
embassy.
	   Placards put up in the hotel dining hall where the women met
demanded justice. ``A debt of blood should be repaid in blood,''
one said. ``Women's human rights cannot be trampled on,'' said
another.
	   China's Foreign Ministry has urged Indonesia's government to
severely punish rioters who singled out Chinese-owned homes and
businesses for looting and burning and who raped and murdered
ethnic Chinese women.
	   The students who gathered outside the Indonesian Embassy and
demanded to see the ambassador did so even though police last week
refused to grant permission for a demonstration, citing public
order concerns.
	   Dozens of police kept the students from entering the fenced-off,
guarded compound housing the embassy and other diplomatic offices
and residences.
	   After prolonged negotiations, the police allowed four students
to enter the compound to meet an embassy spokesman and to hand over
documents and a T-shirt bearing the slogan ``Protest the violence,
punish the murderers.''
	   The four demanded to know what action Indonesia planned to take
to protect ethnic Chinese from further attacks and called for an
accounting of the government's actions in the May unrest and an end
to laws that discriminate against ethnic Chinese.
	   When the four emerged from the compound, their 100 or so fellow
protesters, who were waiting across the street, erupted into
cheers.
	   The students unfurled a banner in English that read ``All these
things to be answered for.'' But police made them take it down
within seconds. Police also prevented reporters from speaking with
the students.
	   Chinese authorities are wary of any civic protests, fearful that
they could escalate into larger demonstrations against the
government. Officials are doubly anxious to keep a lid on any
protests at Beijing university campuses because they initiated
massive pro-democracy demonstrations in 1989.
	   After their meeting, about 10 members of the women's group of
writers and journalists also went to the embassy to hand over a
letter urging Indonesia to punish those responsible for the rapes
and attacks. But they turned back after seeing the heavy police
guard around the embassy, said one of the women involved. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-China-Indonesia, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
