<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Tajikistan-UN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tajik authorities identify four suspects in killing of U.N.
</HEADLINE>
workers &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   DUSHANBE, Tajikistan (AP) _ The government has identified four
suspects in last month's killing of United Nations workers, and is
negotiating with the opposition for their arrest, officials said
Monday.
	   The suspects are on the territory controlled by the coalition of
main opposition groups, said Tajik Security Minister Saidamir
Zukhurov. Opposition spokesman Sulton Khamadov also confirmed that
negotiations are going on for the suspects' extradition.
	   The four U.N. workers were ambushed July 20 while on a regular
patrol in the mountains about 90 miles (140 kilometers) east of the
capital Dushanbe. All were shot in the the head.
	   Tajik officials initially claimed that the U.N. observers had
died when their car plunged off a cliff. But later they confirmed
the U.N. report of an ambush.
	   Tajik President Emomali Rakhmonov has fired two deputy defense
ministers and reprimanded several top officials for failing to
prevent the attack. He ordered an increase in protection for U.N.
workers in Tajikistan.
	   The main opposition alliance condemned the shootings. It said
the U.N. workers were killed after they met the opposition
commander in the Tavildara region, and were heading for the
government-controlled Garm region.
	   About 70 U.N. observers are stationed in Tajikistan to monitor a
peace deal reached last year that ended five years of civil war in
the former Soviet republic.
	   Despite the peace accord, Tajikistan remains restive. There are
periodic clashes between the hard-line government and the mostly
Islamic opposition. Also, many warlords do not recognize the peace
deal and wage turf battles with one another.
	   The four U.N. workers were: Maj. Ryszard Szcwczyk of Poland;
Maj. Adolfo Sharpegue of Uruguay; civil affairs officer Yutaka
Akino of Japan and a Tajik translator, Jourajon Mahramov.
	   (str/ad/mr)
</TEXT>
