r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Singapore-Markets     08-17 0424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Singapore bourse hits a new 10-year low, currency weakens
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Singapore's stock market continued to slide
Monday, falling to its lowest level in more than 10 years and
hurting the Singapore dollar.
	   Markets in the affluent city-state were growing increasingly
susceptible to the regional economic turmoil, traders said.
	   The benchmark Straits Times Industrials Index skidded 2.9
percent, or 28.65 points, to 945.49. The last time the index closed
below this level was in April 21 1988.
	   The drift below the psychologically important support level of
1000 began last Tuesday, when markets opened after a Monday state
holiday. The index has plummeted more than 35 percent since the
start of the year, when it stood at 1529.84 points.
	   The weak Singapore bourse, aggravated by the weakening of the
Japanese yen, also undermined interest in the Singapore dollar,
which was trading late Monday at 1.76 Singapore dollars to the U.S.
dollar.
	   Cushioned from the most dramatic effects of the regional
financial crisis last year, Singapore is now increasingly feeling
the effects of its trading partners' deteriorating economies and
devaluing currencies.
	   Economists are no longer surprised at major drops in the
Singapore market, and expect it will continue to decline.
	   ``We expect something like a minus 3.5 percent GDP growth next
year,'' said Chia Yew Boon, head of securities research at
Santander Investment Singapore.
	   ``This is really far worse than the last recession'' in the
early 1980s, he said. ``It's difficult to see the bottom right
now.''
	   Santander Investment and other analysts said the Singapore
dollar may have to depreciate by about 30 percent on a real
effective exchange rate basis for Singapore to recover its relative
competitiveness.
	   The latest Singapore research report by U.S. investment bank JP
Morgan said the Singapore dollar ``might need to weaken to around 2
Singapore dollars to the U.S. dollar and even beyond (all else
being equal) in the next few months just to restore
competitiveness.''
	   ``Singapore appears to be losing not only some of its
competitiveness and hence market share in its primary markets, such
as the U.S. and the E.U., but potentially also some of its
traditional role in intermediate electronics,'' economist Ong Sin
Beng said in the report.
	   In a speech Saturday night, Singapore's Senior Minister Lee Kuan
Yew predicted: ``We will have a budget deficit this year, next
year, and maybe the year after.''
</TEXT>
