<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Canada-Election, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cambodian opposition accuses Canadian election advisor of bias
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: CORRECTS election date in 3rd graf to July 26; ADDS 12th graf
with query to Axworthy; edits to conform

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ Cambodian opposition leaders on
Monday accused a senior Canadian election advisor of being biased
in favor of Co-Prime Minister Hun Sen's ruling party.
	   They said comments made by the advisor in a private letter
raised questions about Canada's role in the electoral process.
	   Theo Noel, the senior technical advisor to the National Election
Committee, was sharply critical of the opposition for refusing to
recognize the results of the July 26 election, won by Hun Sen's
Cambodian People's Party.
	   Noel said in a leaked internal document that their allegations
about fraud were ``groundless.''
	   ``The opposition parties, in my view, should now accept the
results of the election and should stop identifying scapegoats to
cover up their divisions and their weakness,'' he wrote in a letter
to Canadian ambassador Gordon Longmuir, also well-known for his
criticism of the opposition.
	   ``I also think that the international community should cut short
supporting the opposition's claims which, up to now, were proven
groundless,'' he wrote.
	   In fact, the election committee dismissed hundreds of opposition
complaints without any investigation. The committee is dominated by
supporters of Hun Sen's party.
	   Noel has defended the letter as a private document representing
his personal views.
	   Prominent opposition politician Sam Rainsy on Monday released
the text of a two-page letter he had sent to Canadian Minister of
Foreign Affairs Lloyd Axworthy, saying that Noel's comments and
tone ``indicate he sides with the ruling party and has sided with
them for some time.''
	   Whatever the reason, he wrote, ``I believe it is entirely
inappropriate for foreign-funded technical advisor to base his
advise on personal bias.''
	   If Noel's actions represent the role Canada and other foreign
advisors played in the elections, ``the implications are very
serious indeed,'' Sam Rainsy wrote.
	   The letter called on Axworthy to ``clarify whether Mr. Noel's
statements and actions are within the scope of the duties of a
Canadian-funded election advisor and whether his stated views
represent the views of the Foreign Ministry of Canada.''
	   Sam Rainsy said his opposition ally, Prince Norodom Ranariddh,
is expected to also sign the letter Monday afternoon.
	   Cambodian held parliamentary elections last month, one year
after Hun Sen ousted Ranariddh as his co-premier in a violent coup
d'etat.
	   The international community provided over dlrs 34 million in
funds to help hold the polls and quickly gave the electoral process
a post-election stamp of approval in what the opposition and some
independent observers considered a rush to judgment.
	   Critics have accused the international community of endorsing a
process which favored Hun Sen's Cambodian People's Party because
they saw his victory as necessary in bringing political stability
back to the country.
</TEXT>
