</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippine peso, stocks close lower
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ The Philippine peso fell against the
U.S. dollar Monday, pushed slightly lower by the devaluation of the
Russian ruble, dealers said.
	   The dollar averaged 43.243 pesos on the Philippine Dealing
System, up 4.4 centavos from 43.199 pesos at Friday's rate.
	   Dealers said the ruble devaluation initially pushed the dollar
to a high of 43.360 pesos, but later settled at 43.250 pesos.
Volume traded was dlrs 109.8 million compared to Friday's dlrs
105.9 million.
	   ``The devaluation of the ruble had an effect, but not a large
one since the market is mostly long on dollars,'' said a trader
from a foreign bank.
	   Market analysts said there was light commercial demand for
dollars at the current rate and potential pressure on the peso
would most likely come from speculative buying.
	   The Philippine Central Bank is expected to keep its high
overnight interest rates throughout the week to repel speculative
attacks on the peso, a trader said.
	   Philippine shares, meanwhile, ended slightly lower Monday,
pulled down by profit-taking toward the close of trading.
	   Preliminary data showed the 30-share Philippine Stock Exchange
index fell 2.21 points to 1335.71 after a strong 34.63-point rise
to 1337.92 on Friday.
	   Early bargain hunting extended Friday's rally following six
straight days of losses until late selling eroded the gains.
	   Continuing concerns over regional and domestic economic
prospects triggered the late selling and the losses would likely
last in the next few days, dealers said.
	   The sectoral indexes were mixed, with the commercial and
industrial and financial counters ending lower.
</TEXT>
