</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ukraine-Mine Blast, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Death toll in Ukrainian mine blast reaches 24
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with President Kuchma announcing national day of
mourning, government helping victims' families; ADDS byline. &QL; 
 &UR; By VIKTOR LUHOVYK &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) _ Rescue workers in eastern Ukraine have
recovered 20 bodies of coal miners who were killed in a methane
blast and were working to retrieve four more, a news report said
Monday.
	   The bodies of four miners believed killed in the blast on Sunday
remain in remote zones of the 19th Communist Party Congress mine in
the Luhansk region, the Interfax news agency reported.
	   Officials working on the site of the explosion said the areas
where the last four dead miners remain were heavily blocked by the
blast and rescue teams would be able to get through them no earlier
than Monday evening.
	   A total of 28 miners were working in the section of the mine
where the explosion occurred. Four survived and are currently
hospitalized with burns.
	   Another 95 miners were underground elsewhere in the mine at the
time of the blast but were evacuated.
	   Five rescue workers who were injured recovering bodies of the
dead miners Sunday were also taken to hospital, officials at the
Luhansk regional department for work safety said.
	   A government commission is working to determine the cause of the
blast, which struck 675 meters (2,228 feet) underground early
Sunday.
	   President Leonid Kuchma sent his condolences to the families of
the killed miners and decreed Monday a day of mourning throughout
Ukraine, the presidential press service said.
	   The government also allocated 792,000 hryvna (dlrs 396,000) to
compensate the victims' families.
	   Two similar accidents occurred at the 19th Communist Party
Congress mine in 1953 and 1957, in which 33 and 22 miners were
killed, respectively.
	   About 200 miners have already died this year in Ukraine's
deteriorating coal mines, many more than in the same period last
year.
	   The number of miners killed on the job has been steadily
increasing in recent years because mines lack the funds needed to
modernize equipment and improve safety conditions.
	   The worst single accident this year occurred in April, when a
methane blast killed 63 workers at a mine in the eastern region of
Donetsk.
	   (vl/mr) 	   
</TEXT>
