</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-NIreland </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
China condemns bombing in Northern Ireland
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ China on Monday condemned the weekend bombing in
Northern Ireland but urged all parties not to allow the violence to
derail the region's peace process.
	   ``We were shocked by the serious bombing on August 15,'' Foreign
Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao said in a statement released by the
official Xinhua News Agency. ``The Chinese government opposes and
condemns all forms of terrorist acts.''
	   Zhu expressed the hope that Britain, Ireland and parties in
Northern Ireland will push ahead with an April peace agreement,
saying that ``an early and lasting peace ... will fully accord with
the best interests of all concerned.''
	   The car bombing in Omagh killed at least 28 people and injured
220. It has been widely blamed on renegade members of the Irish
Republican Army who rejected the peace agreement.
</TEXT>
