w1408 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-Chechnya     08-17 0224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Chechnya </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chechen leader fires top prosecutor in effort to control restive
</HEADLINE>
region &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   GROZNY, Russia (AP) _ Chechnya's parliament has fired the
separatist republic's top law enforcement official in an effort to
clamp down on rising crime, the parliament press service said
Monday.
	   On recommendations from President Aslan Maskhadov, Chechnya's
parliament voted Prosecutor General Khavazk Serbiyev out of office
Sunday, citing ``poor and ineffective work,'' the press service
said.
	   Serbiyev was criticized for failing to find a culprit after an
assassination attempt on Maskhadov which injured him slightly but
killed two bodyguards.
	   The parliament also blamed Serbiyev for a fruitless
investigation into a June attack by gunmen on Chechnya's
government-controlled television station. That attack led Maskhadov
to declare a state of emergency in the mostly Muslim republic.
	   Chechnya has seen an increase in kidnappings, theft, and
violence among armed gangs, Muslim sects and ethnic groups since
its 1994-96 independence war with Russia. Maskhadov's efforts to
fight the outbursts have been mostly ineffective.
	   Despite his fight for independence, Russia considers Maskhadov a
moderate who is trying to rein in lawlessness and keep his
government essentially secular.
	   (str/nw/mr)
</TEXT>
