w1415 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Pakistan-EmbassyBombi 3rdLd-Writethru   08-17 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Pakistan-Embassy Bombing, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0733 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Most U.S. Embassy staff to leave Pakistan following handing-over of
</HEADLINE>
bombing suspect &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: ADDS Taliban comment on bin Laden in grafs 9-10, source saying
U.S. investigators were involved in graf 13. RECASTS to raise
material on Howaida. TRIMS. No pickup. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos planned &QL; 
 &UR; By DONNA BRYSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) _ Most U.S. Embassy personnel were
leaving Pakistan and other Americans were urged to join them Monday
after a suspect in the East African embassy bombings was caught in
Pakistan and turned over to Kenyan authorities.
	   U.S. Embassy spokesman Richard Hoagland said all but about 50 of
the usual contingent of about 120 in the embassy in Islamabad and
consulates in Karachi, Lahore and Peshawar would leave under
security orders from the State Department. They and their families
will begin leaving Tuesday, he said.
	   ``American citizens currently in Pakistan are urged ... to
consider seriously departing Pakistan,'' the embassy added in a
statement. It noted airports were open and commercial flights
available, but added the embassy was arranging additional flights.
	   Figures on the numbers of Americans other than embassy staff in
Pakistan were not immediately available.
	   Hoagland refused to say whether a specific threat had prompted
the Pakistani warning. He also refused comment on the transfer
Pakistani officials reported Sunday of a suspect in the embassy
bombings. The nearly simultaneous explosions in Nairobi, Kenya and
Dar es Salaam, Tanzania on Aug. 7 killed a total of 257 people.
	   In a brief statement Sunday, Pakistani Foreign Ministry
spokesman Tariq Altaf said a man identified as Mohammad Sadik
Howaida arrived at the Karachi airport from Nairobi on Aug. 7.
Immigration officials suspected Howaida's Yemeni passport was
forged. Altaf said he was interrogated by Pakistani officials who
determined he had some link to the African bombings and handed him
over to Kenyan authorities.
	   The News, a national Pakistani newspaper, quoted unnamed
government sources Monday as saying Howaida claimed the attack was
sponsored by Osama bin Laden, a Saudi harbored in neighboring
Afghanistan who U.S. officials have identified as a possible
suspect in the bombings.
	   Bin Laden has been vocal in his hatred of what he sees as U.S.
imperialism and pledged to drive U.S. troops out of bases in places
like his native Saudi Arabia.
	   A spokesman for Afghanistan's Taliban militia told The
Associated Press Monday that the Saudi had nothing to do with the
bombings because he had pledged not to engage in such activities
while living under Taliban protection.
	   ``He cannot engage in any political, let alone military or
terrorist, activities,'' the spokesman, Abdul Hay Muttayn, said by
telephone from the southern Afghan city of Kandahar, where bin
Laden is believed to have a home.
	   The News said Howaida was a 34-year-old Palestinian engineer who
confessed to helping plan the bombings. He reportedly told
investigators six other conspirators slipped through the Karachi
airport Aug. 7 and on to Afghanistan.
	   A government source who insisted on anonymity had at first said
U.S. investigators had nothing to do with Howaida's interrogation
or the decision to send him to Kenya on Aug. 14.
	   But the source acknowledged Monday that Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif had called U.S. President Bill Clinton once a link between
Howaida and the bombings had been established, and U.S. Federal
Bureau of Investigation agents came to participate in the
questioning.
	   The official government statement on Howaida made no mention of
U.S. involvement. Pakistan's attempts hide U.S. involvement may
have been prompted by the case of Mir Aimal Kasi, the Pakistani
convicted of killing two CIA employees during a shooting spree in
Virginia in 1993.
	   When Kasi was arrested in Pakistan in June 1997 in a joint
FBI-Pakistani operation, angry Pakistanis accused their government
of groveling before U.S. power.
	   Americans in Pakistan have been advised to be on the alert since
last November, when four American oil workers were gunned down in
the southern port city of Karachi following Kasi's conviction. In
March, cement barricades were erected on the roads leading to the
high-walled U.S. Embassy compound in Islamabad. 	   
</TEXT>
