<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Greece-Turkish Flag </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Island authorities arrest Turks for raising Turkish flag in port
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KALYMNOS, Greece (AP) _ Six Turks, including a heart surgeon and
a Mercedes dealer, were arrested Monday after allegedly raising
their nation's flag on a lamp post during a local festival,
authorities said.
	   The charges were not immediately clear. But national symbols
evoke strong emotions on Aegean islands near the Turkish coast _ an
area where Turks have questioned Greek sovereignty over many of the
islets and rocky specks.
	   Two years ago, the hoisting of the Turkish flag on the nearby
eastern Aegean islet of Imia, known as Kardak in Turkish, almost
led Greece and Turkey to war.
	   The six Turks arrived on the island of Kalymnos aboard the
22-meter (72-foot) Turkish yacht Eda on Sunday during celebrations
of the island's honey production. One of the group, sailor Gunay
Zeybeker, allegedly raised the Turkish flag early Monday, the
merchant marine said.
	   Officials said the incident was photographed and filmed by
Cengiz Menteseoglu, a partner in a Mercedes dealership in Istanbul,
Turkey.
	   Greeks participating in the local festival nearby ``moved in a
threatening manner against them'' upon seeing the flag, the
ministry said.
	   The group fled on the yacht, but failed to obtain sailing
permission, officials said. The boat's captain, Sevket Gaykan, did
not board and was arrested by port authorities.
	   The Eda was intercepted by a Greek coast guard patrol boat. The
five Turks _ including Menteseoglu's wife Gonca; heart surgeon Dr.
Atilla Kayihan and his wife Leyla _ were led to the island of Kos,
about seven kilometers (four miles) from the Turkish mainland.
	   Court officials in Kos refused to comment on the proceedings.
	   Kalymnos Mayor Dimitris Diakomihalis called the flag raising ``a
very provocative act.''
	   ``These are not isolated actions in my opinion. They are actions
which send many messages,'' he added.
	   Diakomihalis had aroused controversy himself in 1996 by raising
the Greek flag on Imia just after the crisis.
	   (eb-bm) 	   
</TEXT>
