<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Namibia-Angola </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNITA attack on convoy reported in Angola
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) _ UNITA rebels attacked a Namibian convoy
carrying mine equipment, killing the driver and several others, the
Afrikaans newspaper Die Republikein reported Monday.
	   The convoy was ambushed near Malanje, 400 kilometers (250 miles)
east of the Angolan capital Luanda, it said.
	   The newspaper said Jekonia Kandetu, a driver for the Namibian
state-owned transport company Transnamib, was shot dead along with
an unknown number of Angolans. Two other Namibians were among the
injured in the attack Saturday, it said.
	   Angola, which borders Namibia in southwest Africa, has been
teetering on the brink of renewed civil war since late June, with
numerous clashes and deaths reported. Much of the fighting has been
taking place in the Malanje area, where mining is concentrated.
	   The army and rebels have been re-arming and actively recruiting
over the last three months as mutual distrust increasingly
undermined a peace agreement negotiated in Lusaka in 1994.
	   The U.N. Security Council last week voted to extend the Angola
peace-keeping operations until Sept. 15.
	   (str/djw)	   
</TEXT>
