<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP Top Financial News,0602 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   A summary of financial and business news from The Associated
Press at 1100 GMT. Stories carry ``f'' or ``i'' category codes and
move on this circuit in expanded form:
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Asian stock markets fell Monday, with the key
indexes in Malaysia and Thailand tumbling over 3 percent on news of
the devaluation of the Russian ruble. After weeks of financial
turmoil, Russia announced Monday that it would would permit the
value of the ruble to fall about 50 percent _ from about 6.3 to the
dollar to 9.5 to the dollar. Dealers said the devaluation of the
ruble raised fears that more currencies may follow suit and the
currency crisis, which started from Asia last July, would be
prolonged. Prime Minister Mahathir's remarks at a political rally
over the weekend that the Malaysian government intends to introduce
drastic measures to shore up the country's faltering economy also
dampened market sentiment. (ASIAN MARKETS)
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ After weeks of financial turmoil, Russia sharply
devalued the shaky national currency on Monday in a move expected
to cause hardship for Russian consumers and rattle international
markets. The Central Bank said it would permit the value of the
ruble to fall about 50 percent _ from about 6.3 to the dollar to
9.5 to the dollar. The currency market dipped only slightly in
early trading but the street price for dollars immediately plunged
to 9.5 rubles. President Boris Yeltsin interrupted his vacation and
headed to the Kremlin for a crisis meeting with his prime minister,
Sergei Kiriyenko. A ruble devaluation had been widely rumored, in
part because the government faces heavy payments on
ruble-denominated debt in coming days and weeks. (RUSSIA-ECONOMY)
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Seeking to soothe concerns about the nation's
banking system, Japan is willing to use public funds to help
Sumitomo Trust and Banking Co. take over ailing Long-Term Credit
Bank of Japan Ltd., a news report said Monday. The two banks had
announced a merger in June, but rumors that Sumitomo may be getting
cold feet as it learns the true extent of LTCB's bad loans have
sent LTCB's shares to record lows. The government has decided to
use funds originally earmarked for protecting depositors to ensure
that LTCB stays solvent as it merges with Sumitomo, the Yomiuri
newspaper said in its interactive edition. (JAPAN-TROUBLED BANK)
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Malaysia's finance minister called
Monday for transparency in the international financial system,
saying global players should adhere to the same rules they
advocate. Anwar Ibrahim, who is also deputy prime minister, said it
was ``lopsided'' to demand transparency and disclosure from poor
countries and not from wealthier economies. Malaysian leaders have
often blamed Western currency speculators for plotting to destroy
the Southeast Asian economy, once counted among the world's fastest
growing. (MALAYSIA-ANWAR)
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ Utilities prices in Phnom Penh are
expected to skyrocket next month, led by a 60 percent increase in
electricity rates, officials said Monday. The new power rates will
force other utilities companies to dramatically raise their prices,
said Mann Chhoeun, a city official. The Cambodia Daily newspaper
reported that water charges could be pushed 40 percent higher. The
price hikes, which were put off until after last month's
parliamentary elections for political reasons, have been blamed on
the drop in the value of Cambodia's currency and the rising price
of diesel oil. (CAMBODIA-UTILITIES)
</TEXT>
