<SLUG> BC-AP News Summary,0584 </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   A summary of late news from The Associated Press. Some items
have moved on this circuit in expanded form with ``i'' or ``f''
category codes:
	   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) _ Police arrested five suspects
Monday on suspicion of involvement of the Omagh bombing that killed
28 and wounded 220. An officer in the Royal Ulster Constabulary,
speaking on condition of anonymity, said the five were arrested at
dawn in their homes near Omagh, 70 miles (110 kms) west of Belfast.
Among those arrested, the officer said, is a relative of Omagh
politician Dessie Mackey, who earlier this year resigned from the
IRA-allied Sinn Fein party over its decision to accept the Northern
Ireland peace agreement. The officer cautioned that charges against
any of the suspects was not imminent and under Northern Ireland
anti-terrorist law they could be interrogated for up to a week
before being charged or released. (NIRELAND-ARRESTS)
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Serb forces captured three more
villages in western Kosovo, pushing ethnic Albanian militants away
from the province's second-largest city, media reported Monday.
Yugoslavia's state-run Tanjug news agency said Serb police
``crushed'' important strongholds of the rebel Kosovo Liberation
Army in the villages of Lodja, Grabovac and Rausic, all just
outside the province's second city of Pec. The push comes a day
after the Serbs gained control of the rebels' main logistical and
weapons distribution center, forcing the KLA to flee into the
surrounding hills and forests, abandoning weapons and ammunition.
	   KINSHASA, Congo (AP) _ With an army of rebel fighters closing in
on his capital, a defiant President Laurent Kabila said in a radio
broadcast Monday his government will arm the people and prevail.
The embattled president also lashed out at the international
community and accused the western nations of plotting against his
government. The rebels _ a coalition of ethnic Tutsi fighters,
Rwandan soldiers and disenchanted members of Kabila's military _
have been making steady progress toward the capital, a western
diplomat said. (YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO)
	   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) _ The entourage of FBI agents grows in
Nairobi as more investigators try to learn whether the trail of
evidence from the deadly embassy bombing leads to at least one
suspect arrested abroad and returned to Kenya. Amid a flurry of
reports and other indications that the investigation was picking up
momentum, the FBI said it would issue a joint statement later
Monday. The Aug. 7 blasts in Nairobi and Dar es Salaam, Tanzania,
killed 257 people and injured more than 5,500. In the wake of
reports that a man had confessed to the bombing in Pakistan before
being flown back to Nairobi, a Kenyan newspaper reported Monday
that FBI agents had flown another suspect back following his arrest
in the United Arab Emirates. (EMBASSY BOMBINGS)
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Soldiers piled sandbags in a rush Monday to build
up the last defense of China's largest oil field from the raging
waters of the Nen River. The river broke through two other dikes
protecting the oil field and Daqing, a northeastern city of 2.3
million people. The third embankment was the last chance to save
the oil field from a flood that would bring disastrous losses. To
the south, in central China, the Yangtze River reached a new record
height of 45.22 meters (149.2 feet) Monday morning at Shashi city,
home to a half million people. (CHINA-FLOODS)
</TEXT>
