w1445 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EmbassyBombings 3rdLd   08-17 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Embassy Bombings, 3rd Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pakistan returns bombing suspect to Nairobi
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS with FBI, Kenyan police saying suspect being questioned &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos NAI101-106 of Aug. 16 &QL; 
 &UR; By DAVE CARPENTER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NAIROBI, Kenya _ Amid signs their investigation is gaining
momentum, FBI agents intensified efforts Monday to learn whether
the trail of evidence from the twin embassy attacks in East Africa
leads to a Saudi multimillionaire fundamentalist.
	   The FBI confirmed Monday it is questioning a suspect returned to
Nairobi from Pakistan, but said he had not confessed or implicated
anyone else in the U.S. embassy bombings.
	   The Aug. 7 blasts in Nairobi and Dar es Salaam, Tanzania, killed
257 people and injured more than 5,500.
	   Reports in Pakistan had said the suspect had confessed to
planning the bombings and implicated his co-conspirators.
	   ``Mohammed Saddiq Odeh, also known as Abdull Bast Awadh and
Mohammad Sadiq Howaida, has been returned to Kenya by Pakistani
authorities in the late evening of Aug. 14, 1998. He is currently
being questioned by CID officers and FBI special agents,'' said a
joint statement from Sheila Horan, the FBI special agent in charge
of the Nairobi investigation, and Peter Mbuvi, deputy director of
the Criminal Investigations Division of the Kenyan police.
	   ``Mr. Saddiq Odeh has not admitted any responsibility in the
bombings in Nairobi or Dar es Salaam, nor has he implicated anyone
else in those events,'' the brief statement concluded.
	   Meanwhile, a Kenyan newspaper reported Monday that FBI agents
had flown another suspect back following his arrest in the United
Arab Emirates.
	   The East African, citing airport sources, said the suspect is a
Pakistani national who was arrested in Dubai and flown to Nairobi
on Friday on a U.S. military plane. The report did not give the
suspect's name or specify his alleged role in the bombing.
	   A spokesman for the U.S. Embassy in Nairobi, Bill Barr, and
Kenyan police both declined comment Monday morning. A Pakistani
Embassy spokesman, Malik Ashraf, said he was unaware of the second
reported arrest.
	   In Pakistan on Monday, most U.S. Embassy personnel were leaving
and other Americans were urged to join them after the interrogation
and reported confession of Mohammad Sadik Howaida.
	   The U.S. State Department updated its ``worldwide caution'' for
Americans, warning specifically against all travel to Pakistan and
referring to ``subsequent threats,'' without elaborating.
	   The Pakistani national newspaper The News, quoting unnamed
government sources, said Sadik confessed during questioning in
Pakistan to planning the bombings and claimed the attack was
sponsored by Osama bin Laden.
	   U.S. officials have identified bin Laden, an exiled Saudi hiding
out in neighboring Afghanistan, as a possible suspect.
	   The News said Sadik is a 34-year-old Palestinian engineer. He
reportedly told investigators that six other conspirators slipped
through the Karachi airport Aug. 7 and apparently made it to
Afghanistan, where they had been told they would be congratulated
by bin Laden.
	   A Pakistani spokesman said Sadik was arrested on his arrival at
the Karachi airport from Nairobi on the day of the twin bombings.
	    &UR; U.S. officials, 15th graf pvs
	   (cph)
</TEXT>
