<SLUG> BC-Russia-Dagestan </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Wahhabis in southern Russia declare independence
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Islamic fundamentalists in three villages in
Russia's southern region of Dagestan have proclaimed themselves a
``separate Islamic territory'' and refuse to negotiate with
authorities, a news report said Monday.
	   Dagestani officials said that a police post nearest to the
villages of Karamakhi, Chabanmakhi and Kadar in central Dagestan
has come under fire from during the past few nights, the Interfax
new agency reported.
	   Members of the fundamentalist Wahhabi sect have also announced
plans to elect a religious government, saying it would be
independent from central authorities, Interfax reported.
	   Dagestan, which borders breakaway Chechnya, has been troubled by
spillover violence as well as its own conflicts. Dagestan's
Wahhabis have had several recent clashes with police who have tried
to disarm them.
	   Wahhabis in the three villages have set up a checkpoint on a
road to the region and refuse to negotiate with either the
government or religious leaders, said Dagestani Security Council
spokesman Eduard Urazayev, according to Interfax.
	   Dagestan's parliament and Cabinet plan to hold a joint emergency
session on Wednesday to discuss the situation.
	   Russian officials have blamed Wahhabis for recent violence in
several parts of the former Soviet Union.
	   (ad/mr)
</TEXT>
