<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Afghanistan, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russia's border chief travels to Tajikistan to inspect border
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES in new 4th graf with meeting planned between defense,
foreign ministers of four Central Asian nations. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ President Boris Yeltsin ordered his border chief
to Tajikistan on Monday to ensure that the former Soviet Union's
southern borders are secure following recent Taliban victories in
Afghanistan.
	   Federal Border Service head Nikolai Bordyuzha will inspect posts
along Tajikistan's border with Afghanistan and meet local leaders
to discuss threats along the boundary, the ITAR-Tass news agency
said.
	   The former Soviet republics of Tajikistan, Uzbekistan, and
Turkmenistan, now part of the Commonwealth of Independent States,
fear a complete Taliban victory could send an influx of refugees
and weapons across their borders.
	   The presidents of Uzbekistan and Tajikistan, as well as of
nearby Kazakstan and Kyrgyzstan plan to organize a meeting between
their foreign and defense ministers to discuss ways of stepping up
security in the region, the Interfax news agency reported.
	   As part of CIS agreements, Russia keeps troops along the borders
of many former Soviet republics.
	   Yeltsin has said Russia will cooperate with the Central Asian
countries to ``raise a barrier to the Taliban'' by strengthening
those countries' borders with Afghanistan.
	   The Taliban have spread quickly through Afghanistan, imposing a
harsh version of Islamic law. Their recent victories in the north
knocked out major opposition strongholds and they now control more
than 85 percent of the country.
	   Russian officials have not ruled out military action if the
situation worsens.
	   ``We must be prepared to prevent and, if necessary, to country
the radical development of the situation in the region,'' Col. Gen.
Valery Manilov said Friday, according to the Interfax news agency.
	   (nw/ad/mr) 	   
</TEXT>
