r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Germany-Fuel-CellPart     08-17 0187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Fuel-Cell Partnership </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Daimler, Shell working together on fuel-cell technology
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   STUTTGART, Germany (AP) _ Daimler-Benz said Monday it has hooked
up with Shell to expand fuel-cell technology for cleaner cars, the
latest in a series of joint ventures between oil and car companies.
	   Daimler has been working on fuel cells since 1992, which use
hydrogen and oxygen to generate electricity to power a vehicle.
Daimler has been looking for a way to produce hydrogen on board so
that the cars wouldn't have to carry special tanks.
	   The Stuttgart-based automaker said Shell will bring to the
partnership a technology for extracting hydrogen from hydrocarbon
fuels such as gasoline and diesel, meaning electric-car drivers in
the future could fill up at regular gas stations.
	   Early this year, Ford Motor Co. formed a similar partnership
with Mobil Corp. and General Motors Corp. announced an arrangement
with Amoco Corp.
	   Daimler is also working with Ford and Canadian fuel-cell
developer Ballard Power Systems Inc. on developing fuel-cell
components for cars by 2004.
 &UR; (pfg-cb)
</TEXT>
