w1468 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Cambodia-Election     08-17 0400
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Election </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. congressman calls for continued suspension of aid to Cambodia
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ A U.S. congressman said Monday he
would recommend the continued suspension of aid to Cambodia until a
``legitimate government'' is established.
	   In an Aug. 14 letter to King Norodom Sihanouk, Rep. Dana
Rohrabacher criticized last month's parliamentary elections won by
Cambodian leader Hun Sen's ruling political party as ``manipulative
shadow play.''
	   The United States should not continue aid to Cambodia ``until a
legitimate government, that is free of coercion, violence and
fundamental corruption is established,'' said Rohrabacher.
	   Rohrabacher, a California republican, authored an amendment to
the 1998 Foreign Operations section of the U.S. Appropriation Bill
that suspended U.S. funding to the Cambodian government after Hun
Sen ousted Prince Norodom Ranariddh as his co-premier in a violent
coup last year.
	   Hun Sen called for the new elections held July 26 to try to win
back legitimacy and aid lost after his July 1997 takeover. But
critics accuse the Cambodian strongman of rigging the process in
his own favor.
	   Hun Sen's Cambodian People's Party won a slight majority of 64
seats in the polls, but not the two-thirds needed to form a new
government.
	   He has asked Ranariddh's FUNCINPEC party and the Sam Rainsy
Party _ which together won 58 seats in the National Assembly _ to
join him in a coalition government. They have so far refused even
to recognize the polls which they said were marred with
irregularities.
	   Rohrabacher said he has ``strong support'' in Congress to
continue the suspension of aid to the Cambodian government for
1999.
	   That support ``will not be deterred by the bluster or
manipulation by dictators,'' he said.
	   While Cambodia is just a small nation, it ``now plays a pivotal
role to the struggle between freedom and tyranny worldwide,'' he
said.
	   Rohrabacher said that the world's perception of Cambodia's
elections would help determine the future of democracy in other
Asian countries, such as Burma, Indonesia and Vietnam.
	   Rohrabacher also told the king _ who has recommended a three-way
coalition between the CPP, FUNCINPEC and the Sam Rainsy Party _
that he believes a coalition ``based on dishonesty and fear'' will
not save Cambodia ``but will ensure its destruction.''
</TEXT>
