<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Kenya-Julie Ward </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A month after suspect's arrest, prosecution still does not have
</HEADLINE>
evidence &QL; 
 &UR; By GEORGE MWANGI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) _ A month after a suspect was arrested in
connection with the murder a decade ago of British tourist Julie
Ward, the prosecution said Monday it needs at least two more weeks
to put a case together.
	   Prosecutor Stephen Munguti told the court he needed more time to
examine the evidence.
	   Simon ole Makallah, a senior warden in the Kenya Wildlife
Service, was arrested July 17. The following day Attorney General
Amos Wako said there was sufficient circumstantial evicence to
arraign the suspect and hold a second trial in the murder of the
28-year-old Ward, whose burned corpse was found in the Maasai Mara
National Reserve in September 1988.
	   Makallah has not yet been required to enter a plea although he
has been held in jail for a month.
	   Defense Attorney Karieko Tobiko objected to the request for more
time.
	   ``This is an old matter, the alleged offense took place more
than 10 years ago. There has been an inquest. There has been a
murder trial concerning this matter. There has been an
investigation by New Scotland Year,'' Tobiko said.
	   Magistrate Uniter Kidullah said she would rule Tuesday on the
prosecution's request for more time.
	   Tobiko told the court John Ward, the father of the victim, and
Wako told a press coference last month they were sure they had
finally found the man responsible for Miss Ward's death.
	   ``How can they turn around and tell us they are not ready to
proceed? If they are not ready, why are they ready to arrest the
suspect?'' Tobiko told The Associated Press after Monday's hearing.
	   Ward's mutilated and charred remains were discovered in the
reserve on the Tanzanian border Sept. 13, 1988. Officials first
claimed she had been attacked and killed by wild animals.
	   Two park rangers were subsequently arrested and tried for her
murder, but they were found innocent of all charges in June 1992.
Justice Fidahussein Abdullah criticized the police for conducting a
flawed investigation.
	   On March 2, 1996, Wako agreed that new information about the
killing made another ``fair and objective'' investigation
necessary.
	   Ward, a wealthy hotelier from Bury St. Edmunds, England, has
carried on a 10-year campaign to find his daughter's killers and
have them brought to justice.
	   (gm/sl)	   
</TEXT>
