<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Suharto Investigation </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Probe into Suharto's wealth to end in two months: attorney general
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ An investigation into allegations that
Indonesia's ex-President Suharto amassed a fortune during his 32
years in power will be completed within two months, Attorney
General Andi Muhammad Ghalib said Monday.
	   Ghalib told reporters that his office had conducted about 70
percent of the investigation, the official Antara news agency said.
	   ``I think we can finish the job in another two months, I hope,''
he said.
	   Some critics have alleged that the former leader and his family
made billions of dollars from abusing their position and power.
	   Suharto has denied this along with allegations that he used a
string of charitable foundations to make money for himself.
	   Suharto resigned in May after Indonesia's worst economic crisis
in years triggered riots and protests against his authoritarian
regime.
	   President B.J. Habibie, a longtime friend of Suharto who
succeeded him as head of state, ordered the inquiry and has said
that the ex-leader would be held accountable under the law if any
wrongdoing was uncovered.
	   Ghalib said his office would make public its findings and had
been working intensively on the case. Even so, investigators still
needed to analyse bundles of documents.
	   Several weeks ago officials of the attorney general's office
said Suharto had promised to cooperate with their inquiries.
	   Suharto, 77, has rarely been seen in public since his departure
from office.
	   Habibie has also ordered the attorney general to investigate
wider claims of corruption under Suharto's regime.
</TEXT>
