<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIreland-Spain </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Spanish planes leave for Northern Ireland to repatriate bombing
</HEADLINE>
victims
 &UR; With Northern Ireland

<TEXT>
	   MADRID, Spain (AP) _ A Spaniard who was wounded in a 1992 Basque
separatist attack left Monday for Northern Ireland to collect the
body of his 12-year-old son, killed in the Omagh car bombing.
	   Manuel Blasco was among 16 mourners who left from an air force
base outside Madrid aboard two military planes sent to Northern
Ireland by the Spanish government.
	   The Foreign Ministry said Saturday's bombing in Omagh killed two
Spaniards -- 12-year-old Fernando Blasco and 23-year-old Rocio Abad
-- and wounded 12 others.
	   The overall toll of the worst single terrorist attack in
Northern Ireland's history was 28 dead and 220 injured. Police
blamed a renegade offshoot of the Irish Republican Army.
	   The Spaniards were among a group of 28 youths who were studying
English just across the border in the Irish Republic and crossed
into Northern Ireland during a field trip. Abad was helping
supervise the group.
	   The air force said one of two CN-235 planes making the flight to
Northern Ireland was a hospital plane equipped with an intensive
care unit.
	   Doctors traveling aboard it will consult with colleagues in
Northern Ireland to determine which of the injured Spaniards can be
repatriated on Monday.
	   A Foreign Ministry spokesman said two were in critical
condition. Two others have already been released and the other
eight remain hospitalized.
	   Deputy Prime Minister Francisco Alvarez Cascos traveled
separately Monday to visit the wounded in hospitals in Belfast and
Londonderry and show solidarity with the people of Northern
Ireland.
	   Manuel Blasco, the father of the dead boy, has now been
victimized by both of Europe's last two armed movements. On June 9,
1992 he was driving by a Madrid supermarket when a car bomb
exploded, hitting him with shrapnel.
	   Ten military personnel and three other civilians were hurt in
that attack, blamed on the Basque extremist group ETA, which is
fighting for an independent Basque homeland in northern Spain.
	   The 12 Spaniards wounded in Omagh include Blasco's 14-year-old
daughter Lucrecia, who was wounded in the face and ear. Spanish
newspapers quoted relatives as saying she will have to undergo
plastic surgery.
	   Alvarez Cascos, speaking before leaving for Northern Ireland,
said: ``We must all think about how we can provide help in the face
of such a horrible drama: a family crushed twice by terrorism.''
	   (dw)
</TEXT>
