<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sudan-Rebels </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sudanese rebel leader leaves Cairo
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Sudanese rebel leader John Garang left Cairo
for Nairobi, Kenya, on Monday after attending a two-day meeting of
Sudanese dissident groups.
	   Garang, leader of the Sudan People's Liberation Army, left
before the National Democratic Alliance held a final ceremonial
session to close out its discussions, which were closed to the
press.
	   The Eritrea-based alliance of northern Sudanese politicians and
southern rebels opposed to the government, was expected to issue a
final statement after Monday's session.
	   In its Monday edition, the London-based Al-Hayat newspaper said
the rebels had agreed to continue their ``struggle against the
government of Khartoum to bring it down.''
	   Garang echoed that view in an interview with Associated Press
Television last week.
	   ``Our position ... is that this regime is a regime that should
be removed. It cannot be improved,'' Garang said.
	   The southern rebels took up arms in 1983 to demand more autonomy
for the Christian, animist south from the Muslim, Arab north. More
than 1.5 million people have died in the conflict and related
famines.
	   Sudan complained that Egypt's organizing of the meeting was a
boost to the opposition. But President Hosni Mubarak said in an
interview published Monday that he met with the rebels to try to
keep the neighboring nation unified.
	   ``This meeting was held in the interest of our brothers in
Sudan,'' he told the weekly newspaper Mayo of Egypt's ruling
National Democratic Party.
	   Egypt said earlier that it does not want the southern rebels to
gain an independent state since this would interfere with the pact
on sharing Nile River waters which flow through both countries.
 &UR; mae-ggl
</TEXT>
