<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Botha Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Arguments end in trial of South African apartheid president Botha
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with close of arguments, new date for verdict, ANC
comment; trims &QL; 
 &UR; With AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By PAUL HARRIS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   GEORGE, South Africa (AP) _ Lawyers for P. W. Botha contended
during closing arguments Monday that a legal summons from a body
probing apartheid atrocities was ``null and void'' and the case
against the former president should be dismissed.
	   Botha, 82, faces charges of ignoring a subpoeana from the Truth
and Reconciliation Commission. If convicted he faces up to two
years in jail or an unspecified fine.
	   On the last day of trial, defense lawyer Lappe Laubscher said
technical faults in the commission's decision to ask Botha to
testify meant the hard-line apartheid-era leader was under no
obligation to appear.
	   Laubscher said the summons had instructed him to appear before
the Truth Commission as a whole, whereas the hearing he was ordered
to attend was being held only by a sub-division of the panel.
	   ``He was subpoeanaed to appear before the TRC, not the Human
Rights Violation Committee. End of story,'' Laubscher said.
	   Botha claims the commission wants to humiliate him by forcing a
public appearence after he had supplied it with more than 1,700
pages of written answers to commission questions.
	   Laubscher repeated allegations that Botha and Truth Commission
chairman Desmond Tutu struck a deal in 1996 allowing Botha to give
written answers instead of oral testimony. Earlier in the trial
Tutu denied any such agreement.
	   Commission lawyers wanted to quiz Botha on the role of the State
Security Council, a shadowy security body he headed during the
1980s when a violent crackdown on anti-apartheid groups reached its
peak.
	   During his trial Botha's defense team has been confronted with
documents and witnesses who allege the council authorized the
killing of black liberation fighters.
	   Laubscher criticized the prosecution team for calling witnesses
to apartheid atrocities, saying such evidence was irrelevent.
	   Adjourning the case after the lawyers had finished their
arguments, Magistrate Victor Lugaju, who is black, said he would
deliver a verdict on Friday.
	   The long trial has cast light on the racial divisions still
plaguing South Africa, four years after all-race elections ended
apartheid and swept the African National Congress to power.
	   ANC Southern Cape organizer Lanvar Reid, who has monitored the
trial, said he was glad it was drawing to a close, but slammed
Botha for defying the commission.
	   ``The impression you get is that through his defiance he is
hiding something, protecting some people or covering up,'' he said.
	   Given Botha's age and frail health a fine is considered more
likely than a jail sentence, if he is found guilty.
	   As usual security was tight, with rolls of razor wire and armed
police ringing the court in George, a small coastal town about 240
miles (390 kilometers) east of Cape Town.
	   (ph/djw)	   
</TEXT>
