<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iran-Refugees </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Iraqi refugees arrive in Iran from Saudi Arabia
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) _ A group of Iraqi refugees has arrived in
Iran after spending the last six years in a camp in Saudi Arabia,
the Islamic Republic News Agency reported Monday.
	   The 55 Shiite Muslim Iraqis, who were part of 33,000 refugees
living in the Rafha camp in Saudi Arabia following the 1991 Gulf
War, arrived in Iran on Sunday night to settle in Iran, the agency
said.
	   They had sent several letters to Iran's supreme leader Ayatollah
Ali Khamenei asking for permission to live as refugees in Iran, it
said.
	   An official at the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees in the
Saudi capital Riyadh said Saudi Arabia paid for the refugees'
flight. It gave 1,000 riyals (dlrs 266) to children under 2 years
and 3,000 riyals (dlrs 800) to others to help them in their
transition.
	   A total of 3,500 Iraqis are expected to live in the Ibrahimabad
refugee camp in the central city of Arak, Iran's news agency
reported.
	   The refugees coming to Iran have relatives in the country and
more will arrive in the next few days, said Aziz Ahmed, acting
representative of the UNHCR in Riyadh.
	   The 33,000 Iraqis held at Rafha camp on the Saudi-Iraq border
were either defectors from the Iraqi army or were taken prisoner by
the U.S.-led coalition forces and refused to return to Iraq after
the war.
	   Most have resettled in the United States, Australia and some
European countries. Ahmed said the Rafha camp remain open until the
remaining 5,600 refugees find homes in other countries.
 &UR; ti-ggl
</TEXT>
