<HEADLINE>
Fossett rescued from sea after balloon goes down
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; URGENT &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: Combines pvs. ADDS where Fossett is to be taken. Minor edits. &QL; 
 &UR; With BC-US-Cross-Pacific Sail &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos SYD101-103 &QL; 
 &UR; By ROHAN SULLIVAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ The schooner Atlanta picked up American
millionaire-adventurer Steve Fossett on Monday from the Coral Sea,
where he landed when his balloon went down in a storm during his
around-the-world attempt, authorities said.
	   Fossett was safe aboard the 60-foot (18 meter) Atlanta and was
expected to be taken aboard the New Zealand navy tanker The
Endeavor within the next couple of hours, New Zealand Defense Force
spokesman Bill Morley said.
	   He was to be taken to Townsville, Queensland, Australia, said
Judy Jasper, a spokeswoman at Fossett's headquarters at Washington
University in St. Louis.
	   He gave a thumbs-up to his rescuers and said he was fine hours
after lightning struck his balloon and he crashed into the sea,
authorities said.
	   Fossett has been in regular radio contact with a Royal
Australian Air Force Hercules C-130 since about lunchtime Monday,
when a rescue plane from Sydney reached the balloon crash site east
of Australia.
	   Fossett still had to cross a huge stretch of the Pacific Ocean
between Australia and Argentina and had at least another five days
of travel before he was expected to reach South America. He took
off from Argentina on Aug. 7.
	   Fossett, from Chicago, was making his fourth attempt to fly
around the world. He has also run marathons, climbed mountains and
raced in the Iditarod dog sled race in Alaska.
	   A French military plane dropped a 15-man life raft to Fossett at
about 8:40 a.m. (2240 GMT Sunday) Monday, after reaching the site
near the Chesterfield islands, about 500 miles (800 km) off
Australia's east coast, said the French navy in Noumea, New
Caledonia.
	   The French plane circled Fossett until its fuel began to run
low, then headed back to its home base in Noumea, Poke said.
	   Darren Curtis from The TV 7 Network in Australia, who was aboard
the Australian Hercules C-130, talked to Fossett via the plane's
radio.
	   ``He said he was caught in a giant thunderstorm with hail and
lightning which actually ruptured his balloon. He fell 29,000 feet
(8,840 meters) into the ocean,'' Curtis said. ``He says whenard to detect by radar and dangerous to
even the largest vessels.
	   Fossett was equipped with a wet suit and life raft, and the
capsule of the balloon was seaworthy, but not leakproof.
</TEXT>
