r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HongKong-Intervention     08-17 0459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Intervention </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hong Kong monetary chief defends market intervention
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Hong Kong officials ``agonized'' before
intervening in stock and futures exchanges, but the monetary chief
said Monday the drastic decision was necessary _ and might be
repeated _ to stop speculators from manipulating the markets.
	   The intervention on Friday pushed the battered Hang Seng Index
up by 8.5 percent, but critics have contended the move could
undermine confidence in Hong Kong as a free market.
	   The chief executive of the Hong Kong Monetary Authority, Joseph
Yam, said in a letter to the daily Financial Times that officials
stand by their action and that if necessary they will intervene
again ``to deter currency manipulators.''
	   Hong Kong officials contend that speculators are selling off
stocks they don't own in hopes of seeing the price drop _ then
manipulating the market by selling Hong Kong dollars and forcing
officials to raise interest rates. That, in turn, has helped push
stocks lower.
	   ``We do object to people manipulating our currency to engineer
extreme conditions in the interbank market and high interest rates
to make profits in the short positions in stock index futures,''
Yam wrote. ``We have reason to believe there has been such
manipulation.''
	   He said traders have been further upsetting markets by spreading
``malicious rumors of all sorts.''
	   Yam said Hong Kong officials have no objections to people
betting that the Hong Kong stock market will go down, as long as
they don't try to manipulate prices by selling off the currency,
too.
	   Hong Kong pegs its dollar at a stable rate against the U.S.
dollar _ and it has held steady over the past year as many other
Asian currencies saw sharp devaluations amid the region's severe
economic crisis.
	   As speculators have mounted an assault on the Kong Kong dollar,
Hong Kong monetary authorities have been forced to raise interest
rates to defend their link with the U.S. dollar.
	   ``To deter currency manipulation, we took action to tackle the
matter at source, and that meant making sure that those engaging in
this activity lose money,'' Yam wrote. ``We realize that this might
be seen as a departure from our free-market philosophy. That is why
we agonized before this difficult decision was taken. But we feel
we have done the right thing.''
	   Yam said Hong Kong officials will stop intervening and let stock
prices find their own levels _ as soon as the currency manipulation
stops.
	   ``But meantime we shall act to deter currency manipulation,'' he
wrote.
	   Hong Kong markets were closed on Monday for a holiday
commemorating the end of Japanese occupation in World War II.
	   (db-acw)
</TEXT>
