w1544 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Taiwan-PoliceScandal     08-17 0309
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Taiwan-Police Scandal </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Legislator says police driving in style
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) _ In the latest blow to Taiwan's
scandal-tainted police force, a legislator said Monday that
hundreds of police officers drive luxury cars allegedly obtained
through payoffs from illegal businesses.
	   Of the island's approximately 80,000 policemen, 767 drive
Mercedes Benz sedans, and luxury BMWs are even more popular, said
Shyu Jong-shyong, a ruling Nationalist Party legislator who
commissioned a survey of policemen's personal vehicles.
	   Those cars are priced well beyond the financial means of most
officers, Shyu told a news conference.
	   ``Given a policeman's salary it would take them 5-6 years to pay
for them, and that's only if they didn't eat, drink or make spend
money on anything else,'' Shyu said.
	   Shyu said that the more illegal businesses there are in an area,
the more likely policemen are to be found driving luxury cars. That
reinforces suspicions that officers are accepting payoffs in
exchange for protection, he said.
	   Police officials said many officers buy their cars second hand
and ownership doesn't connote wrongdoing.
	   But the revelations come at a bad time for the force.
	   A former director of the police academy was arrested last week
on suspicion of accepting millions of dollars in bribes to rig
examination results for would-be cadets.
	   Kuo Chen-yuan may have accepted up to 25 million Taiwan dollars
(U.S. dlrs 714,000) from applicants, investigators say.
	   Taiwan's police have been undergoing a painful transition from
an instrument of repression during the 1949-1987 martial law regime
to a modern force for policing and solving crimes.
	   But as with Taiwan's government, corruption is believed to be
widespread, and officers are sometimes referred to as ``gangsters
in uniform.''
