w1547 &Cx1f; wstm-
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Japan-Economy     08-17 0385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Economy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Government officials give mixed messages about ``bridge bank''
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Top Japanese finance officials gave conflicting
signals Monday about whether the government's proposed ``bridge
bank'' system would be used if a major bank were to collapse.
	   The ruling Liberal Democratic Party is trying to set up a
government-run bank that would take over insolvent banks and run
them for up to five years while bad loans and remaining assets are
sold.
	   The Bank of Japan Gov. Masaru Hayami said that pre-emptive
measures to prevent collapses such as arranging mergers would be
better than using the bridge bank to mop up bad debts at big banks
that fail.
	   ``First we need to know the situation (for the bank in question)
as soon as we can,'' said Hayami. ``Instead of using the bridge
bank, it is preferable that a merger takes place.''
	   ``A collapse of a major bank would cause turmoil in financial
markets and other economic activities,'' Hayami added.
	   But Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa said the government is
willing to use the bridge bank scheme regardless of the size of the
bank.
	   ``It does not matter if the bank is big or small,'' Miyazawa
said. ``It is possible to use the system no matter what size the
bank is.''
	   Meanwhile, a Cabinet spokesman told reporters that Prime
Minister Keizo Obuchi wanted the ``bridge bank,'' which would be
funded by up to 11 trillion yen (dlrs 76 billion) in public funds,
approved by early October.
	   ``The best scenario is to have the debate completed at both
houses of Parliament... by early October,'' said Deputy Cabinet
Spokesman Akitaka Saiki.
	   But swift approval for the bills could prove difficult. They
have come under harsh criticism from opposition parties which could
block the bills in the upper house of Parliament, where the LDP has
a minority of seats.
	   The ruling party's rivals, led by the main opposition Democratic
Party, say that the use of public funds to take over the assets of
shaky banks would be too soft on bank managers who allowed the bad
loan to pile up.
	   Last week, three main opposition parties _ Liberal, Democratic
and the Peace and Reform parties _ agreed on a tentative plan to
submit banking bills as an alternative to LDP's ``bridge bank''
bills.
 &UR; (may)
</TEXT>
