<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Egypt-Embassy Bombings,0244 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mubarak: Justice is guarantee against terrorism
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ President Hosni Mubarak condemned the
bombings of the U.S. embassies in East Africa and said that justice
was the only guarantee against terrorism, Egyptian newspapers
reported Monday.
	   It was the president's first public comments on the explosions
in Nairobi, Kenya, and Dar es Salaam, Tanzania, that killed 257
people and injured more than 5,500. Among the dead were 12
Americans.
	   ``Justice is the real guarantee against terrorism because
feelings of injustice leads to a state of boiling that cannot be
controlled, which then lead to desperate acts,'' the
Arabic-language Mayo quoted Mubarak as saying.
	   Mubarak did not elaborate, but he appeared to be speaking about
justice for the Arabs.
	   The Arabs have widely criticized U.S. policies in the Middle
East, accusing the Clinton administration of failing to pressure
Israel to follow through on peace deals with the Palestinians and
seriously damaging the peace process.
	   There also has been criticism of U.N. sanctions on Libya, Iraq
and Sudan which have caused economic hardship for the people of
those countries.
	   Mubarak added that acts of violence ``will not solve problems or
reach an objective except bloodletting.''
	   After the explosions, Mubarak dispatched a ton of medical
supplies and 15 top doctors Kenya to help the victims of the
embassy bombing there. 	   
</TEXT>
