w1558 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Taiwan-China     08-17 0401
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Taiwan-China </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Taiwan official calls for respect of flags in China exchanges
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) _ Media reports of Chinese visitors
insulting Taiwan's flag sparked demands Monday that symbols of
state be respected during organized exchanges between the two
rivals.
	   Meanwhile, a top official said private visits between the sides
should be more tightly regulated to prevent Chinese attempts to
foster discord by taking advantage of Taiwan's open society.
	   Flags and national symbols must be respected during exchanges,
regardless of who is playing host, said Shi Hwei-yow, secretary
general of the semiofficial Straits Exchange Foundation and
Taiwan's chief negotiator with China.
	   He said further investigations were being conducted into reports
that Chinese official Li Yafei demanded Taiwanese flags be removed
from meeting rooms and refused to accept souvenir gifts bearing
Taiwan's official name and symbols of state during a recent visit.
	   Taiwan considers such behavior indicative of the haughty
attitude Beijing adopts towards the island it considers a renegade
province.
	   New regulations will deal with such incidents by forcing host
organizations to immediately cut short the visits of their Chinese
guests and prosecute Taiwanese who comply with such demands.
	   Taiwanese media have reported numerous instances of Chinese
visitors leaving in a huff after spotting Taiwan's red, white and
blue flag. A children's choir from China earlier this year canceled
a performance in central Taichung city after spotting a Taiwanese
flag displayed in the room.
	   Taiwan's ruling Nationalists were driven out of China by Mao
Tse-tung's communists in 1949, but retain many of the political
trappings of the mainland regime, along with its official title,
the Republic of China.
	   Private exchanges between the sides began in the early 1980s,
and have continued despite a more than three-year freeze in talks
between their negotiating bodies.
	   But those exchanges need to be more tightly regulated to check
China's attempts to ``break apart Taiwan from the inside,''
foundation Deputy Secretary General Wu Hsin-hsing was quoted saying
by the China Times newspaper.
	   Beijing uses Taiwan's democratic system, that allows advocacy of
both formal independence and reunification with China, to further
its agenda here, Wu was quoted as saying by the paper.
 &UR; (cb) 	   
</TEXT>
