<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Former Communists </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Book closing on case involving East German secret police; opened in
</HEADLINE>
another &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BERLIN (AP) _ Prosecutors plan to drop all remaining charges
against the former head of the East German secret police because of
the defendant's poor health, Berlin's Justice Ministry said Monday.
	   ``He is permanently unfit for trial,'' said spokeswoman Michaela
Blume. ``The files will be closed shortly.''
	   Prosecutors have sought to try Erich Mielke on charges related
to deaths at the Berlin Wall, but he has avoided prosecution
because of poor health and senility. Now 90, he lives in seclusion
with his wife in an apartment in eastern Berlin.
	   Mielke, a life-long communist, was tried and convicted in 1993
for the murders of two Berlin police officers in 1931. Mielke fled
prosecution after the deaths, returning to East Germany only after
it became a communist state.
	   He was sentenced to six years in prison, and was released in
1995 after serving two-thirds of the sentence.
	   Meanwhile, a leader of the successor party to the East German
communists asked Berlin prosecutors Monday to investigate his past.
	   Gregor Gysi, who now is parliamentary leader for the Party for
Democratic Socialism, hopes to clear himself of allegations he was
a secret police informer in the 1970s and '80s, said party
spokesman Juergen Reents.
	   A parliamentary panel report, issued in May after a three-year
probe, found Gysi informed on dissidents he represented as a lawyer
in former East Berlin from 1975 until at least 1986.
	   He has denied the allegations and called the report politically
motivated. But he lost a bid in July before the Constitutional
Court to quash it.
	   That ruling could open the way for parliament to lift Gysi's
immunity from prosecution if prosecutors decide there is enough
evidence to open a criminal probe.
 &UR; (pfg-cb)
</TEXT>
