<SLUG> BC-Sri Lanka-Explosives,0418 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bomb explodes, injures 16 in Sri Lanka
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By DILIP GANGULY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) _ A bomb concealed on a motorbike
exploded in a Tamil city in eastern Sri Lanka Monday, injuring 16
people and partly damaging a bank and two shops, police said.
	   The bomb went off around midday in front of the privately-owned
Seylan Bank at Batticaloa, a provincial capital on the east coast,
said a police officer reached by telephone.
	   ``The explosives were packed in a motor cycle and it exploded
with a huge bang,'' said the officer, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
	   Batticaloa, 220 kilometers (135 miles) east of Colombo, is a
government-controlled down with a Tamil majority. It has been long
contested by Tamil rebels.
	   No one claimed responsibility for the attack, but the military
blamed it on Tamil Tiger rebels.
	   On Sunday, a suspected Tamil militant in the central town of
Kandy swallowed a cyanide capsule moments before the security
forces burst in and found a huge cache of high explosives. A second
alleged courier was captured alive, police said.
	   Police suspect the explosives have been brought from Batticaloa.
	   Acting on an intelligence tip, a joint team from the police and
the army seized 110 kilograms (235 pounds) of explosives in the
raid on a house in Kandy, said Nimal Medivaka, the senior
superintendent of police.
	   They arrested the second person in the house, 90 kilometers (55
miles) east of Colombo.
	   Suicide by consuming cyanide is a trademark of the Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam which is fighting for an independent homeland
for minority Tamils.
	   Some officials said the Tigers might be targeting a new air
force base recently built near Kandy.
	   While most of Sri Lanka's Tamils live in the north and east, the
tea-growing areas of Kandy also have a sizable number of Tamil
workers.
	   In January, the Tigers rammed a bomb-rigged truck into the
country's holiest Buddhist shrine, said to house a tooth of Buddha.
The attack killed 18 people and wounded another 12.
	   Also on Sunday, police defused a bomb near a telecommunication
facility at Eravur near Batticaloa, with enough explosive power to
disrupt telephone services in the city.
	   The Tamils, who make up for 18 percent of Sri Lanka's population
of 18. 5 million, accuse the majority Sinhalese of widespread
discrimination in education and jobs. More than 54,000 people have
been killed since the war began in 1983. 	   
