<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Palestinians, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Palestinian police say they are close to catching detainee
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with protest of university students at Israeli
military checkpoint &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos JRL-101, JRL-102 &QL; 
 &UR; By SAMAR ASSAD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Palestinian police have detained a taxi driver
who gave a ride to a Hamas leader on the run and have new leads
about the whereabouts of the fugitive, the West Bank security chief
said Monday.
	   Imad Awadallah, a key figure in the Hamas military wing, escaped
Saturday from a Palestinian jail in the West Bank town of Jericho.
	   On Sunday, Palestinian security forces launched a massive
manhunt for Awadallah, conducting house-to-house searches in
Jericho and imposing a curfew.
	   The restrictions, which were not strictly enforced, were lifted
Monday after security officials said they were convinced Awadallah
was no longer in town.
	   ``All I can say is that he is not in Jericho,'' said Col. Jibril
Rajoub, head of the Palestinians' Preventive Security Service in
the West Bank. ``We will catch him.''
	   Rajoub said a taxi driver was detained after he gave Awadallah a
ride without recognizing him. ``Awadallah told the driver that he
needed to get to his father who had a stroke,'' Rajoub said.
	   Rajoub would not say where the driver took Awadallah.
	   Awadallah, 29, is a leading figure in Izzedine al Qassam, the
military wing of Hamas that has carried out more than a dozen
suicide bombings in Israel since 1994.
	   Awadallah was arrested by the Palestinian Authority in April and
accused of killing Hamas bombmaker Mohiyedin Sharif as part of an
internal dispute in the organization.
	   Israeli intelligence officials on Sunday briefed Cabinet
ministers on the escape and said there was suspicion that Awadallah
had inside help.
	   Rajoub said a preliminary investigation of Awadallah's jail
break found that the duty officer had left the cell door unlocked.
However, Rajoub said he was certain the officer was negligent and
was not trying to help Awadallah escape. No charges will be brought
against the officer, Rajoub said.
	   ``No one from inside helped Awadallah escape, that is for
sure,'' Rajoub said.
	   In another development Monday, about 150 Palestinian, European
and U.S. students attending the West Bank's Bir Zeit University
marched to an Israeli roadblock to protest against Israeli travel
restrictions for fellow students from the Gaza Strip.
	   Israeli police scuffled with students who tried to walk through
the checkpoint north of Jerusalem, and three Palestinian
demonstrators were arrested. Protesters carried Palestinian,
Spanish, Greek, Italian, British and Israeli flags and held banners
reading ``Education is a right, not a crime.''
 &UR; sa-kl	   
