<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-RugbyL-Super League-Gateshead </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Super League embraces new English club
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LEEDS, England (AP) _ Super League officials have overturned a
decision not to expand their English rugby league structure and
have admitted Gateshead as the competition's 13th franchise.
	   Consortiums from Gateshead, Cardiff and Swansea were vying for
franchises in the top flight British rugby league competition but
were all rejected last week due to problems with their business
plans.
	   However, the Super League executive reconvened at Leeds on
Monday and voted to admit Gateshead to the competition subject to
certain conditions being met by November.
	   Gateshead, near Newcastle in northeast England, was the venue
for games in the Super League roadshow earlier this season.
	   As a new club, Gateshead will be permitted to contract 20
foreign players. News of the admission was relayed directly to
Australia, where former Cronulla Sharks boss Shane Richardson is
assembling the nucleas of a squad.
	   Kerrod Walters, a former Australian test hooker currently
playing for the Adelaide Rams, is reportedly on the verge of
signing as Gateshead's inaugural captain.
	   Super League England chairman Chris Caisley said he was
delighted to welcome Gateshead into the competition.
	   ``The financial guarantees we were looking for have been
forthcoming and Gateshead Council have confirmed their long-term
commitment,'' he said.
	   (jp)
</TEXT>
