<HEADER>
w1578 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Congo 2ndLd-Writethru   08-17 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Congo, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Defiant Kabila calls on people to resist rebels; power out in
</HEADLINE>
Kinshasa
 &UR; Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with gunfire heard in Kinshasa
suburb, government closing shops closed in another suburb. Edits.
No pickup. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos
 &UR; By IAN STEWART &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KINSHASA, Congo (AP) _ With an army of rebel fighters closing in
on his capital, a defiant President Laurent Kabila said in a radio
broadcast Monday his government will arm the people and prevail.
	   A few hours later, though, electricity was lost throughout
Kinshasa _ the second time since the rebels began their advance two
weeks ago. It was not immediate clear what caused the outage.
	   In his speech, the embattled president also lashed out at the
international community and accused the West of plotting against
his government.
	   The West ``has never been supportive of President Kabila simply
because I do not represent their interests,,'' Kabila said on
state-controlled Voice of the People radio. ``We have come and we
will stay here. In any case, the aggressors will fail.''
	   The rebels _ a coalition of ethnic Tutsi fighters, Rwandan
soldiers and disenchanted members of Kabila's military _ have been
making steady progress toward the capital, a western diplomat said
on condition of anonymity.
	   Charging Kabila with corruption and nepotism, rebel leaders
driving to topple the government have captured the western Congo
River port town of Matadi.
	   Many in the rebel movement helped Kabila oust longtime dictator
Mobutu Sese Seko in May 1997, but now say they have been
marginalized by the government.
	   A diplomat in Kinshasa said he had received reports from his
government that the rebels were now near the town of Mbanza-Ngungu,
about 150 kilometers (95 miles) south of the capital.
	   Kabila said Congo was the victim of a plot by neighboring Rwanda
_ which he says is orchestrating the rebellion _ along with the
West.
	   ``The next 24 hours will be decisive,'' Kabila said. ``We must
understand that we must win. This is the message I have for my
people, I am asking them to face up to this plot, to arm
themselves, to support their army, and to defeat the aggressors.''
	   He did not elaborate on why the following 24 hours were so
important.
	   While the situation was tense, life continued largely as normal
in many parts of Kinshasa, with most shops open and markets crowded
with people buying extra provisions.
	   In the Kinshasa suburb of Kingabwa, though, just south of the
city, witnesses said machine gun fire could be heard off and on
Monday as Congolese troops hunted down Rwandan soldiers who were
apparently hiding there. The soldiers are believed to be part of
the Rwandan contingent that had been in Kinshasa when the rebellion
broke out and who had exchanged fire with Kabila's soldiers before
going into hiding.
	   Further south of the city, in the suburb of Ngaba, the
government ordered all the shops closed. No reason was given for
the order, though the suburb is along the road that leads toward
the rebel units advancing on the city.
	   Heavily armed troops have closed all roads leading from Kinshasa
to Lower Congo province, where the rebels are mounting their
advance on the capital.
	   Facing a worsening crisis, Kabila called an emergency meeting of
his staff and Cabinet on Monday.
	   Kabila returned Sunday to Kinshasa from the Angolan capital of
Luanda, where he met with the presidents of Namibia and Angola.
	   The topics discussed at the meetings were not released publicly,
but the leaders recommended have scheduled a meeting of regional
defense ministers in Zimbabwe's capital, Harare.
	   ``The heads of state expressed their concern over the intensity
of military actions in (Congo), jeopardizing the stability of the
southern African region,'' Angolan television said.
	   Hundreds of westerners left Kinshasa over the weekend, while a
team of 50 British commandos has been deployed to Brazzaville, the
capital of the neighboring Republic of Congo, to help the
evacuation of British subjects.
	   An Royal Air Force Hercules carrying 50 soldiers flew over the
weekend from Ascension Island, where the Marines had been on
standby, to Brazzaville, the Britain's Ministry of Defence said.
	   The deployment of British troops in Brazzaville did not mean
there were immediate plans to withdraw British nationals, a
ministry spokesman said.
	   Brazzaville is directly across the Congo River from Kinshasa.
	   French troops already in Brazzaville helped hundreds of French,
Belgian and other foreigners cross the river on Saturday. From
Brazzaville _ still scarred from last year's civil war in the
Republic of Congo _ the evacuees were flown to safety.
	   Despite apparent military setbacks, the Congolese government
said Sunday that it was securing bases in the east and west of the
country in order to attack rebel forces.
	   In eastern Congo, rebel commander Jean-Pierre Ondekane said
Monday his forces had taken the town of Lubutu, which is 210
kilometers (125 miles) from Kisangani, Congo's second-largest city.
	   Kabila's government has drawn support from the public in
Kinshasa by characterizing the rebel movement as a Rwandan Tutsi
war against Congo. Rwanda denies the charge.
	   Tutsis, an ethnic minority centered in eastern Congo and
neighboring countries, including Rwanda, have become the target of
attacks and arbitrary detentions in Kinshasa.
	    &UR; (hh/ids/tjs)
</TEXT>
