w1585 &Cx1f; wstm-
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Japan-Markets 4thLd-Writethru   08-17 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japanese stocks fall, dollar higher in Tokyo
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: CLARIFIES graf 4 to indicate that analysts predicting Nikkei
will fall below level in 1992 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Tokyo stocks plunged to a two-month low, following
declines on Wall Street and doubts about the new prime minister's
ability to resuscitate Japan's economy. The U.S. dollar rose
against the yen.
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average dropped 329.27
points, or 2.18 percent, to close at 14,794.66 _ its lowest since
June 17. On Friday, the Nikkei index sank 258.09 points, or 1.68
percent.
	   Analysts said the sharp fall could signal the start of another
miserable week for Tokyo stock prices, with financial instability
overseas compounding the dour outlook for domestic growth.
	   They predicted the Nikkei would soon dip under a low of
14,309.41, set in August 1992 _ the benchmark index's lowest level
since the bursting of Japan's asset-inflated bubble economy prices
eight years ago.
	   Worse, the pessimism in Tokyo, the world's second-largest
bourse, could spill back over into other major markets, driving
down share prices there even further, said analysts.
	   ``The external situation _ Russia and falls in the U.S. stock
market _ have made investors here very jittery,'' said Patrick
Mohr, a strategist at Merrill Lynch Japan.
	   On Friday, the Dow Jones industrial average closed down 0.4
percent to 8,425.00, its lowest close since late February and
almost a tenth below its peak of 9,337.97 on July 17.
	   Investors are worried about the fate of a set of bills put
forward by incoming Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi to stabilize
Japan's shaky financial system, said Eiji Tomaru, a manager in the
strategy section at Kankaku Securities Co.
	   Opposition lawmakers have criticized Obuchi's banking
legislation as a taxpayer-funded bailout which doesn't punish inept
executives.
	   Concerns the opposition could force the government to take
harsher measures, such as letting competition close down weaker
institutions, helped drive down the benchmark Nikkei average, said
Kevin Hebner, Japan equity strategist at Warburg Dillon Read.
	   While weeding out the weaker banks may be good in the long run,
the prospect drove down share prices of banks, the Tokyo market's
biggest component.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section tumbled 16.77 points, or 1.43 percent, to 1,152.03.
The TOPIX fell 12.91 points, or 1.09 percent on Friday.
	   An estimated 398 million shares changed hands on the first
section, below 433 million Friday. Declining issues overwhelmed
gainers almost 9-to-1.
	   On the currency exchange, the U.S. dollar rose on concerns about
a new round of financial turmoil in Russia and Asia.
	   The dollar bought 146.45 yen at late afternoon, up 1.57 yen from
late Friday in Tokyo and above its late New York rate of 146.35
yen.
	   Persistent doubts about Russia's currency and economy led to a
surge in the dollar against the yen and other currencies in New
York on Friday, traders said.
	   Concerns about a new round of sell-offs in Southeast Asian
currency and stock markets also sent investors scurrying for the
safe haven of the greenback.
	   The dollar traded as low as 145.90 yen and as high as 146.90
yen.
	   Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese
government bond fell to 1.150 percent from Friday's finish of 1.175
yen, pushing its price up to 112.11 yen from 111.94 yen.
 &UR; (dj-cd-mef)
</TEXT>
