<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Congo, 3rd Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kabila heads back to Lubumbashi, power cut in Kinshasa
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS with 19 grafs to UPDATE with Kabila returning to
Lubumbashi, said to be coming back to Kinshasa later Monday.
CHANGES overline. Picks up 17th graf previous `Kabila returned
...' &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By IAN STEWART &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KINSHASA, Congo (AP) _ Though defiant in words against an
advancing rebel army, President Laurent Kabila has left his
embattled capital for the second time in a week and headed to the
southern city of Lubumbashi, a government official said Monday.
	   Kabila had returned to Kinshasa Sunday afternoon after meeting
his counterpart in Angola in that country's capital, Luanda.
	   State television has repeatedly shown Kabila arriving at
Kinshasa's airport, smiling and defiantly denouncing the rebels.
	   What the state broadcasting service did not mention was that
Kabila quickly reboarded his presidential jet and headed back to
Lubumbashi, where he spent much of last week, a senior government
minister told The Associated Press on condition of anonymity.
	   ``The president is back in Lubumbashi, but he said he would be
returning to Kinshasa tonight,'' the official said.
	   A daily Congolese newspaper, the French-language Palmares,
reported the same information.
	   By Monday afternoon, electricity was lost throughout Kinshasa _
the second time since the rebels began their advance two weeks ago.
It was not immediate clear what caused the outage.
	   The loss of power cut off state radio and television.
	   Before the electricity failed, state radio had been repeatedly
broadcast Kabila saying his government will arm the people and
prevail against a rebel movement of ethnic Tutsi fighters, Rwandan
soldiers and disenchanted members of the president' own military.
	   He also lashed out at the international community and accused
the West of plotting against his government.
	   Western nations have ``never been supportive of President Kabila
simply because I do not represent their interests,'' Kabila said on
state-controlled Voice of the People radio. ``We have come and we
will stay here. In any case, the aggressors will fail.''
	   The rebels have been making steady progress toward the capital,
a western diplomat said on condition of anonymity.
	   Charging Kabila with corruption and nepotism, rebel leaders have
captured the western Congo River port town of Matadi in their bid
to overthrow Kabila.
	   Many in the rebel movement helped Kabila oust longtime dictator
Mobutu Sese Seko in May 1997, but now say they have been
marginalized by the government.
	   A diplomat in Kinshasa said he had received reports from his
government that the rebels were now near the town of Mbanza-Ngungu,
about 150 kilometers (95 miles) south of the capital.
	   Kabila said Congo was the victim of a plot by neighboring Rwanda
_ which he says is orchestrating the rebellion _ along with the
West.
	   ``The next 24 hours will be decisive,'' Kabila said. ``We must
understand that we must win. This is the message I have for my
people, I am asking them to face up to this plot, to arm
themselves, to support their army, and to defeat the aggressors.''
	   He did not elaborate on why the following 24 hours were so
important.
	   Facing a worsening crisis, Kabila had called an emergency
meeting of his staff and Cabinet on Monday.
	    &UR; Pickup 17th graf previous `Kabila returned ...'
	    &UR; (ids/tjs)
</TEXT>
