<HEADLINE>
Fossett rescued from sea after balloon goes down
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: CORRECTS spelling of ship `Endeavour'; UPDATES with officials
saying rescue was easy &QL; 
 &UR; With BC-US-Cross-Pacific Sail
 &UR; AP Photos SYD101-103
 &UR; By ROHAN SULLIVAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ The schooner Atlanta picked up American
millionaire-adventurer Steve Fossett on Monday from the Coral Sea,
where he landed when his balloon went down in a storm during his
around-the-world attempt, authorities said.
	   Fossett was safe aboard the 60-foot (18 meter) Atlanta and was
expected to be taken aboard the New Zealand navy tanker Endeavour
within the next couple of hours, New Zealand Defense Force
spokesman Bill Morley said.
	   Australian Maritime Safety Authority spokesman Brian Hill said
Fossett was safe and well, and would board the Endeavour about
midnight (1400 GMT).
	   ``The rescue was very straight-forward. Mr. Fossett is in good
health and given that he is out of danger, they might proceed to
Townsville tonight,'' Hill said.
