<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Border </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Israel approves plan to set up barriers along 1967 border
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ The government's decision to set up barriers
along the invisible Green Line between Israel and the West Bank,
ostensibly to stop car thefts, could hurt Israel in negotiations
with the Palestinians, a deputy minister said Monday.
	   The Cabinet voted Sunday to erect the barriers, including
boulders, concrete walls and electronic devices, along stretches
totaling about 80 kilometers (50 miles) of the 324 kilometer-long
(200 mile) pre-1967 border between Israel and the West Bank.
	   Police estimate that a car is stolen in Israel every 12 seconds,
with many of the them ending up in Palestinian-controlled areas.
	   The future border between Israel and a Palestinian entity will
be the key issue once Israel and the Palestinians hold negotiations
on a permanent peace agreement.
	   Deputy Education Minister Moshe Peled said Monday that by
deciding to set up the barriers, Israel could pre-empt the outcome
of the negotiations.
	   ``We are throwing money away,'' Peled said. ``I am sure this
intelligent country can think up better ways to fight theft and
terror than re_making a non_existent border.''
	   Peled said the Cabinet decision would give the Palestinians
false hope that Israel might one day return all of the West Bank.
	   Israel captured the West Bank from Jordan in the 1967 Mideast
War, getting rid of the barbed wire which marked the border and
building new roads and settlements across it.
	   Other critics said the government's decision was hasty. Uzi
Landau, chairman of parliament's Defense and Foreign Affairs
Committee, said the government should formulate a new security
doctrine before deciding whether to set up a divider, however
temporary.
	   Yossi Sarid, a legislator from the dovish opposition Meretz
Party, said the Cabinet decision was final proof that the hardline
government had abandoned its claims to all of the West Bank.
	   ``It has again been proven that the viewpoint of the dovish camp
is the more sober and practical one,'' Sarid told Israeli daily
Yediot Ahronot.
 &UR; dh-kl
</TEXT>
