<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Racketeering, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police arrest two men on suspicion of extorting airline
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with JAL president's comment in graf 7-8; CLARIFIES
JAL's suspected role in graf 6.

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Police on Monday arrested two men on suspicion of
extorting 22.8 million yen (dlrs 155,000) from Japan Airlines Co.,
a spokesman said.
	   The two were alleged ``sokaiya'' racketeer Hitoshi Ogasawara,
51, and Mamoru Arai, 53, the president of a leasing company,
Taihei, said a police spokesman who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
	   The alleged extortion was reportedly in return for promising to
ensure trouble-free shareholders' meetings for the airline, he
said.
	   JAL, Japan's largest airline, is the latest company to be named
in a widening crackdown on racketeering that brought the arrest
last year of executives from top companies such as Nomura
Securities Co., Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank Ltd. and Mitsubishi Motors
Corp.
	   A number of JAL executives have already admitted involvement in
the scheme and their case will soon be forwarded to the Public
Prosecutor's Office, news reports said.
	   JAL is suspected of hiding payments to the racketeers under the
pretext of leasing artificial flowers from Arai's company, the
newspaper Asahi reported.
	   JAL president Isao Kaneko said the payment was part of a
business contract until the end of last year.
	   ``What happened, however, was very regrettable from the
corporate ethics point of view,'' Kaneko told a news conference,
nationally televised on Japan's semi-government network NHK.
	   Ogasawara allegedly is a senior member of a sokaiya racketeer
group, the police spokesman said.
	   Sokaiya are a unique feature of the corporate Japanese
landscape. Famous for blackmailing executives by threatening to
reveal embarassing corporate secrets at annual shareholders
meetings, many are actually hired by companies to silence hostile
shareholders.
	   Authorities believe Arai's company to be controlled by the
notorious Sumiyoshi-kai underworld syndicate, according to the
Asahi.
	   Police suspect the men helped manage JAL shareholders' meetings
since 1990, the Asahi said. The men have allegedly receive a total
of 76 million yen (dlrs 520,000), but the charges only cover part
of that, Kyodo said.
 &UR; (mef-may)
</TEXT>
