<SLUG> BC-Northern Ireland, 4th Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Little Northern Ireland town struggles with enormity of loss
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: denial by chairman of suspect group, Spanish deputy prime
minister flies in &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos XONG101-103 MA102-105, TOU101-102
 &UR; By KRISTIN GAZLAY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   OMAGH, Northern Ireland (AP) _ Police arrested five people
Monday on suspicion of killing 28 men, women and children in the
little town of Omagh, whose residents struggled to come to grips
with its entry into the province's grim history books.
	   The five suspects were arrested at dawn in two villages north
and southeast of Omagh and taken to the main police interrogation
center in Belfast, 70 miles (110 kms) to the east, where under
British anti-terrorist law they can be held for up to a week before
being charged or released.
	   Francis Mackey, a leading member of a group under suspicion in
connection with the bombing, denied on Monday that the organization
was to blame, and said his 19-year-old son, Shane, was one of those
arrested. Mackey is chairman of the 32 County Sovereignty
Committee, which denies allegations it is affiliated with the
``Real IRA,'' a group of IRA dissidents trying to wreck the
province's April peace agreement.
	   Two of the dead and 10 of the injured were visiting from Spain,
and the country's deputy prime minister, Francisco Alvarez-Cascos,
flew to the province to be with the victims and their relatives
and, he said, to ``express with my presence the solidarity of the
community enduring this situation.''
	   In the town of Omagh, each resident seemed to have a story to
tell, offered in flat tones of disbelief: A school chum who won't
be in class next month. A father and son who no longer will enliven
a neighborhood. A shopkeeper who never again will greet customers
with a ready smile.
	   ``I don't understand why I'm living,'' pvs graf 4
