<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Politics </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
German opposition says tax cuts will take time
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BONN, Germany (AP) _ After promising tax cuts for their first
100 days in office if elected, the Social Democrat party chairman
conceded Monday it would take longer than that before voters saw
the full benefit.
	   Franz Muentefering, the Social Democratic administrative
manager, told a Berlin newspaper over the weekend that his party
planned to move quickly to reduce taxes, saying the average family
of four would save 2,500 marks (dlrs 1,400) a year.
	   But after a session of top party leaders Monday in Bonn,
chairman Oskar Lafontaine said the full amount would probably have
to be achieved in several steps, which would take more than a year.
He blamed the stretched federal budget.
	   Finance Minister Theo Waigel has also said that Chancellor
Helmut Kohl's tax reform plan would probably require two phases and
take until 2000 at least.
	   While Kohl's center-right coalition is promising total tax cuts
of 30 billion marks (dlrs 16.9 billion), the Social Democrats say
only about a third of that is doable.
	   At the forefront of their 100-day plan, to be presented by the
party's chancellor candidate, Gerhard Schroeder, in Berlin
Thursday, are efforts to cut unemployment by boosting domestic
buying power and thus, hopefully, demand for German products,
Lafontaine said.
	   He said the party intends to repeal reforms that would are to
begin cutting pensions in 1999 from 70 percent to 64 percent of
past salary.
