<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Italy-Fires </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Fires rage in central Italy, threatening popular national park
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ Firefighters struggled Monday to extinguish a fire
that has burned more than 20 hectares (50 acres) of forest close to
one of Italy's most popular national parks.
	   Workers used four planes and a helicopter to drop water on the
blaze in the Abruzzo region, about 200 kilometers (125 miles)
northeast of Rome. Authorities fear the fire, which started Sunday,
will spread to the Gran Sasso national park.
	   Fires also broke out in the Marche region north of Abruzzo.
Flames raging near the town of Castelletta di Fabriano blackened
400 hectares (990 acres) and forced the evacuation of 200
residents, Canale 5 television reported.
	   In Calabria, the toe of the boot-shaped Italian peninsula,
authorities evacuated a hospital Monday to get patients away from
the smoke of a nearby blaze.
	   Weeks of temperatures in the mid- to upper 30s (90s) and sparse
rain have fed fires throughout Italy. Authoritities believe some of
the fires were intentionally set.
	   (ar-ek)
