<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Embassy Bombings-Albright,0535 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Albright leaves for Tanzania, Kenya
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By LAURA MYERS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ANDREWS AIR FORCE BASE, Maryland (AP) _ U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright headed to Africa Monday for a one-day visit to
Kenya and Tanzania to show support for bomb-struck embassy workers
and for East Africans caught in the terrorist attacks.
	   ``To America's embassy personnel in Nairobi and Dar es Salaam, I
will bring a message of solidarity in their sorrow, admiration for
their courage and support for their continued efforts on behalf of
our country,'' Albright said before leaving. ``To the people of
Kenya and Tanzania, I will bring a message of friendship, made
deeper by our shared grief, and of support in doing all we can to
ease their suffering and help them start anew.''
	   Just ahead of Albright's trip, the State Department on Sunday
issued an updated ``worldwide caution'' to U.S. travelers in the
aftermath of the Aug. 7 bombings at American embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania and because of fresh threats to U.S. interests abroad.
	   An accompanying statement specifically warned ``against all
travel to Pakistan.'' The State Department also ordered the
departure of all non-emergency personnel and families of employees
from the embassy at Islamabad and from U.S. consulates in Karachi,
Lahore and Peshawar.
	   The warnings came after Pakistan handed over to Kenyan officials
a suspect in the U.S. Embassy bombings, Mohammed Saddiq Odeh, also
known as Mohammad Sadiq Howaida and Abdull Bast Awadh.
	   Albright's visit to East Africa was designed in part to
demonstrate U.S. resolve in the face of growing terrorist threats
to Americans.
	   Some Kenyans have complained that after the Nairobi bombing,
rescuers gave priority to finding American victims and to
protecting evidence at the expense of saving African lives. But
Albright and other U.S. officials have strongly disputed that
notion, saying the priority had been rescuing all possible, African
and American.
	   On Friday, when Albright set aside vacation plans for the
hastily planned trip to East Africa, the State Department had
lifted a warning against travel to Kenya, whose economy relies
heavily on foreign visitors, to further ease any strain in the
aftermath of the tragedy.
	   Albright, after a 16-hour flight, is scheduled to spend only
five hours on the ground in Dar es Salaam, her first stop Tuesday
morning, and then about 5 1/2 hours in Nairobi later in the day
before returning immediately home without an overnight rest.
	   Over the weekend, President Bill Clinton extended condolences to
the families and friends of Kenyans and Tanzanians killed in the
bombings and said he was praying for the recovery of the injured.
	   ``We grieve together,'' he said in a videotaped message.
	   Clinton also praised the joint nature of the investigation in
which more than 200 FBI agents are working closely with local
authorities.
	   ``I am proud that our nations have also renewed our commitment
to stand together to bring the offender swiftly to justice, to
combat terrorism in all its forms and to create a more tolerant and
peaceful world for our children,'' Clinton said. 	   
</TEXT>
