<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Czech-Politics </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Social Democrat government faces vote of confidence Tuesday
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PRAGUE, Czech Republic (AP) _ The one-party minority government
of Social Democrats is set to face a vote of confidence Tuesday in
Czech parliament.
	   The vote will come less than two months after the election of
the first center-left government since communism ended in 1989.
	   The three-party coalition government of Vaclav Klaus collapsed
in November and was replaced by an interim government designed to
lead the country until a new government could be chosen in early
elections.
	   Opposition Social Democrats, led by Milos Zeman, won the ballot.
The Civic Democratic Party of ex-premier Klaus came in a close
second.
	   After Zeman, as premier, failed to negotiate a coalition
government with smaller parties, he struck a stability pact with
Klaus.
	   Czech law requires that after a government takes office,
parliament must conduct a confidence vote to determine whether the
cabinet has enough political power to implement its programs.
	   Social Democrats control 74 seats in the 200-seat legislature,
way short of the simple majority needed to win the confidence vote.
	   According to the agreement, all 63 of Klaus' deputies will walk
out before the vote. That will leave just 137 legislators present,
meaning the government will need only 69 votes to survive the vote
of confidence.
	   The motion then could be carried by Social Democrats alone, even
if all other deputies voted against it.
	   The Christian Democrats and the Freedom Union, which control a
total of 39 deputies, have said they would vote against Zeman.
	   Both parties say they disagree with his Social Democratic
policies.
	   The position of Communists, with 24 deputies, was not
immediately clear.
	   In foreign policy, the Social Democrats' priorities, such as
integration into the European Union and NATO, are similar to those
of previous governments.
	   The Social Democrats want to slow down privatization and price
liberalization as the country's economy stagnates at zero growth.
	   However, their intention to strengthen the role of the state and
trade unions in the fledgling free market of the post-communist era
is likely to meet with opposition.
	   ``We are prepared to tolerate this government, but the real
battle will take place over individual laws as they are
presented,'' said Klaus, now the parliament's speaker.
	   (oh/scl)
</TEXT>
