<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Chelsea-Petrescu </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Romanian star set to leave Chelsea
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Romanian international Dan Petrescu could become
the first foreign casualty at Chelsea as Gianluca Vialli tries to
balance the budget after splashing out 12 million pounds (dlrs 19.7
million) on players during the off-season.
	   Petrescu, who scored the winning goal in Romania's victory over
England in a World Cup group match this summer, was not named in
Chelsea's squad for its season opener against Conventry on
Saturday.
	   Chelsea, which fielded nine foreign players in its starting 11,
lost the game 2-1.
	   Vialli told the 30-year-old defender he was free to leave
Stamford Bridge, the Express newspaper reported Monday.
	   ``I am very sad,'' Petrescu was quoted as saying. ``Chelsea want
to sell me. Vialli said I will not be playing in the first XI this
year. If can find a club to go to, I will leave.''
	   Chelsea, which has an annual salary bill exceeding 23 million
pounds (dlrs 37.4 million), is expected to place a 2 million pound
(dlrs 3.25 million) transfer fee on Petrescu.
	   Veteran Welsh international Mark Hughes was the first
high-profile departure from Stamford Bridge after the Chelsea boss
signed Brian Laudrup, Pierluigi Casiraghi, Albert Ferrer and Marcel
Desailly in the off-season.
	   Hughes, who signed with Chelsea in 1995 _ the same year as
Petrescu _ transfered to Southampton.
	   Petrescu, who was in Bucharest this week, has been linked with
moves to Dutch club Ajax or Read Madrid. He has 60 caps for
Romania. He played 31 games for Chelsea last season and scored five
goals.
	   (jp)
</TEXT>
