w1656 &Cx1f; wstm-
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MiddleEastBusinessBri     08-17 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Middle East Business Briefs </SLUG>

 &UR; Eds: Contains items on Kuwait, Bahrain, Lebanon. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   KUWAIT (AP) _ The Kuwait Investment Projects Co. announced
Monday it has posted 8.28 million dinars (dlrs 27.05 million) in
net profits in the first half of the year, down from 16 million
dinars (dlrs 52.28 million) in the corresponding period last year.
	   Ahmed al-Ajeel, vice president for marketing and public
relations, told The Associated Press that KIPCO had ``extraordinary
revenues'' last year from selling its stake in a local bank. He
said the generally low prices at the Kuwait Stock Exchange this
year were also partly responsible for the drop because most of the
companies owned by KIPCO are listed.
	   KIPCO is a conglomerate investment holding company that controls
dlrs 6 billion (1.83 billion dinars) in assets in Kuwait and
abroad. It invests in industries, real estate and media ventures.
	   It is listed on the exchange with a paid-up capital of 105
million dinars (dlrs 343.13 million).
 &UR; ___
	   MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) _ The Bahrain-based Arab Insurance Group,
B.S.C., said Monday that its net profit for the first half of this
year slumped 64 percent to dlrs 8.1 million compared with gains
during the same period last year.
	   Net profit for the 1997 first half ending June 30 totaled dlrs
22.6 million, the company said in a statement.
	   However, the assets for the 1998 first half surged heavily by 58
percent to dlrs 1.51 billion from dlrs 959 million in the first six
months of last year, the company popularly known as ARIG said.
	   ARIG, which is the world's 50th largest insurance company, did
not comment on the decline in profits or increase in assets.
	   The insurance company, the Arab World's largest, has 50.5 shares
listed on several Arab stock exchanges, including Bahrain, Kuwait,
Oman and Cairo. It also has global depository receipts in the
London Stock Market.
	   The remaining shares are held equally by the governments of
Kuwait, Libya and the United Arab Emirates.
 &UR; ___
	   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) _ Middle East Airlines, Lebanon's
debt-ridden national carrier, might be sold to the private sector
to avoid further loss, An-Nahar newspaper reported Monday.
	   It quoted an unnamed expert in the aviation industry as saying
that ``a secret plan'' was being studied to privatize MEA's basic
services to spare the company losses that may reach dlrs 100
million this year.
	   A report prepared by Christian Ballan, a member of MEA's board
of directors and a former chairman of the French national carrier,
Air France, confirmed that MEA might become ``a profit-making
company if it was cleaned from corruption and the policy of
nepotism and commissions was halted,'' the paper said.
	   The state-owned MEA, which employs about 5,000 people, is
Lebanon's second biggest employer after the public sector. It has a
fleet of 15 aircraft and their destinations include South America
and Singapore.
	   MEA, which flourished before the 1975-90 civil war when Lebanon
was a regional hub, fell victim to the conflict. The airline
incurred dlrs 100 million losses in the past few years.
	   The government bought a 99 percent stake in the company after
debts owed to the Central Bank were converted into shares.
 &UR; de-am-hd-sf
</TEXT>
