<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Romania-Helicopters </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Romania wants to get old planes and helicopters from Clinton
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) _ Prime Minister Radu Vasile has asked
U.S. President Bill Clinton to help the Romanian army obtain used
planes and helicopters, the defense ministry confirmed Monday.
	   In a letter published in Adevarul daily on Saturday, Vasile
wrote to Clinton in July asking for a donation of 50 to 60 retired
Cobra attack helicopters and six to eight fighter planes to be used
for training Romanian troops on western equipment.
	   ``In this way, we would be conserving our limited financial
resources while gaining the experience we need,'' to reach NATO
standards, Vasile wrote. He also said American and Romanian
companies could be employed in any renovation work needed on the
aircraft.
	   Vassal's letter comes amid heated discussions over the
government's decision to guarantee a dlrs 1.45 billion loan to
purchase 96 attack AH1RO Dracula helicopters to be produced by U.S.
company Bell Textron and a Romanian company.
	   Critics, including the International Monetary Fund, argue that
the 14-year loan needed to purchase the choppers, which would cost
Romania an additional dlrs 120 to 200 million each year, would
cripple the country's already ailing economy.
	   The defense ministry, which supports the deal that has been
under negotiations for the past four years, says having the
helicopters will enhance Romania's chances of receiving an
invitation to join NATO.
	   Romania did not meet the requirements to be among the first east
European countries asked to join the military alliance in July
1997, when Hungary, Poland and the Czech Republic were given
invitations.
	   In a statement, the defense ministry said the premier's proposal
was not an alternative to the Bell Textron deal, but for training
until the new ones arrived.
	   Discussions have become so heated, that even the Romanian
Orthodox Church has entered the fray. In his Saturday Ascension Day
mass, a prominent Church leader said the helicopter deal was too
costly.
	   ``Let them come and make as many helicopters as they want there,
but we don't need them. Let's keep within our means,'' Adevarul
daily quoted Pimen as saying.
	   (ma/am/me)
</TEXT>
