<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMF-Russia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMF urges immediate tax reform in Russia
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With Russia-Economy &QL; 
 &UR; By HARRY DUNPHY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ The head of the International Monetary Fund
urged on Monday Russia's parliament, the Duma, to quickly approve
measures aimed at increasing tax revenues to help the country
through its prolonged financial crisis.
	   Michel Camdessus, the IMF's managing director, said in a
statement the IMF will immediately analyze steps taken by the
Russian government to stabilize plunging financial markets. These
include a devaluation of the ruble, announced earlier in the day,
that is expected to reach 50 percent.
	   The IMF's top negotiator for Russia, John Odling-Smee, arrived
in Moscow Monday for talks with Russian officials, an IMF spokesman
said.
	   Last month the IMF approved a dlrs 22.5 billion rescue package
to help Russia overcome sharp losses on its financial markets and
stabilize the ruble. However the plan failed to restore investor
confidence.
	   Camdessus said the government has been satisfactorily
implementing economic measures that were part of the plan.
	   ``Despite this, confidence in financial markets has not been
reestablished and as a result Russia has continued to lose reserves
and asset prices have fallen sharply,'' Camdessus' statement said.
	   He said that even though the government had stopped using
reserves to defend the ruble, it had to continue implementing the
plan.
	   ``As a preliminary reaction, I am of the view that, in the new
context created by these measures, it will be especially important
for the Russians authorities to take all necessary steps to
strengthen the fiscal position.''
	   ``Prompt passage of the fiscal measures in the forthcoming
session of the Duma will be essential to this end,'' Camdessus said
referring to the need to boost tax revenues.
	   The Duma meets Aug. 21 to consider the government's anti-crisis
measures.
	   ``I hope that the government's economic program will continue to
be implemented in full, so that the economic and financial
situation will improve and the IMF will be in a position to
disburse the second trance under the enhanced fund program in
September, as scheduled,'' Camdessus said.
	   The IMF disbursed a first installment of dlrs 4.8 billion when
the rescue package was first announced last month. The second
payment that Camdessus referred to totals dlrs 5.6 billion.
	   Some investors were hoping for more aid to Russia from the IMF
and Western lenders who put together the July package. But White
House spokesman Mike McCurry said the U.S. and Russian president's
did not discuss new aid in their phone conversation Friday.
</TEXT>
