<HEADLINE>
Northern Ireland calls off soccer international after Omagh bomb
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BELFAST, Ireland (AP) _ Wednesday's scheduled international
soccer friendly between Northern Ireland and Malta in Belfast was
called off Monday in the wake of the bombing in Omagh.
	   The Irish Football Association announced the move after
consulting with the government and the Malta Football Association.
	   An under-21 international between the two countries scheduled
for Tuesday was also canceled as a mark of respect to the victims
of the bombing.
	   A car bomb killed 28 people and injured more than 220 when it
exploded in the Northern Ireland town of Omagh, 70 miles west of
Belfast, on Saturday.
	   It was the worst single terrorist attack in 30 years of conflict
in the province.
