<SLUG> BC-Poland-Auschwitz Crosses </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Half of Poles against new crosses by the Auschwitz memorial
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   WARSAW, Poland (AP) _ About half of Poles say they are against
the crosses that Catholic activists have recently erected near the
former Nazi death camp of Auschwitz, according to a poll published
on Monday.
	   But 73 percent of respondents said the papal cross that has
stood there since 1988 should remain.
	   Conservative Catholics have erected more than 50 crosses in
recent weeks to protest Jewish calls for the removal of the 8-meter
(26-foot) papal cross, which memorializes 152 Poles executed at the
site by the Nazis.
	   Jewish groups have said the large cross, which was used in a
1979 papal Mass at the camp, disturbs the memory of the 1.5 million
Jews who died there.
	   Almost all Poles _ 89 percent _ said they have heard of the
crosses conflict. Only 32 percent were in favor of keeping the new
crosses, while 48 percent said they should go.
	   Some 90 percent in this nation of 39 million declare themselves
as Catholics.
	   The poll of 968 adults was done Aug. 7-10 by the private
Demoskop agency. Its margin of error was plus or minus 3 percentage
points.
 &UR; (ms-pfg)
