<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Africa-Briefs </SLUG>

 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 
 &UR; Eds: Contains items on Zimbabwe, Nigeria, Kenya, South Africa &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   -----
	   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) _ A downtown electrical sub-station, newly
rebuilt since a fire last October caused dlrs 1 million damage,
exploded Sunday and blacked out much of Zimbabwe's capital and
causing widespread disruption due to power surges.
	   Many businesses Monday reported modems and other sensitive
telecommunication and computer equipment had blown and the
state-run Zimbabwe Broadcasting Corp. forecast long delays on
circuits this week as technicians try to effect repairs.
	   No one was hurt in Sunday's blaze at the sub-station adjoining
Harare Central Gardens when a newly rebuilt 20 kilovolt board burst
into flames, for reasons that had yet to be established. Firemmen
fought the blaze for more than an hour in dense billowing smoke.
	   Last Thursday Zimbabwe's links with the Internet and
international e-mail were severed for over 18 hours due to fault
experienced by the government-owned Posts and Telecommunications
Corp.
	   -----
	   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) _ Peter Chanetsa, governor of Mashonaland
West province for President Robert Mugabe's ruling Zanu party, said
900 families of squatters had been evicted from commercial farms
owned by both blacks and whites in his area west of the capital.
	   Chanetsa told the official news agency Ziana Sunday: ``We are
not going to tolerate haphazard settlements from people who think
they can take the law into their own hands and illegally settle
themselves on land that does not belong to them.''
	   There were no reports of violence or unrest in the area, and
Ziana did not say whether force was used to persuade the squatters
to return to their homes.
	   Ziana said most came from ``resettlement areas'' -- former white
commercial farms taken over after 1980 independence on a voluntary
basis with British aid monies, and redistributed to peasants.
	   Ziana said the squatters complained the resettlement farms were
now inadequate and alleged officials were soliciting bribes to
allocate new land under Mugabe's plan to redistribute 1,400
commercial farms in the next five years.
	   A spate of squatter invasions of commercial farms has followed
unveiling of the plan, which Mugabe says will go ahead whether or
not western donors pledge funds to compensate white owners. Support
is being sought at a conference here, scheduled for next month.
	   -----
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ Nigeria's leader is on a tour of the
country's southwest, where he is meeting with soldiers to discuss
his plan to end military rule in May 1999.
	   Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar was warmly welcomed by officers when he
arrived in Lagos on Saturday. On Monday, he was to visit the city
of Ibadan where he will meet with state military administrators.
	   Abubakar will be discussing ``the policy thrust of his new
government and the transition program,'' said a statement released
by the army.
	   Lagos has long been the base of Nigeria's pro-democracy movement
and Abubakar's predecessor, Gen. Sani Abacha, made very few visits
to the city during his five years in power.
	   Unlike Abacha's visits, security was not notably tighter in
Lagos during Abubakar's stay.
	   Abacha died of an apparent heart attack in early June. Abubakar
has pledged to return his country to civilian rule next year.
	   Nigeria has been ruled by soldiers for all but 10 years since
independence from Britain in 1960.
	   -----
	   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) _ A hearing to determine whether the
suspended chief of the Kenya Anti-Corruption Authority is competent
to perform his duties opened Monday and served John Huron Mwau with
a copy of the allegations against him.
	   President Daniel Arap Moi suspended Mwau last month after he
sought and obtained arrest warrants for four senior treasury and
tax officers whom he accused of failing to collect dlrs 3.8 million
in duties on imported wheat and sugar.
	   The warrants were revoked.
	   The president later set up a commission to look into Mwau's
suitability for the job to which Moi appointed him.
	   Commission chairman Rian'ga Omollo said the purpose of Monday's
pre-hearing was to make sure Mwau knew what the allegations against
him were.
	   The anti-graft unit was set up a year ago after the
International Monetary Fund suspended a dlrs 220 million loan to
Kenya because of the government's failure to deal with high-level
corruption.
	   ``At the end of this, I will come out as clean as ice,'' Mwau
said.
	   Omollo said the commission will hold its first hearing Aug. 26.
	   -----
	   PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) _ An unusually stiff sentence for
illegal trade in rhino horn was handed on Friday to a 29-year-old
woman from Empangeni in KwaZulu-Natal, police said on Monday.
	   Endangered Species Protection Unit spokeswoman Captain Petronel
Niewoudt said Nomsa Charlotte Nkhwanazi was sentenced to four
years' imprisonment or a 60,000 rand (dlrs 10,000) fine in the
Durban Regional Court.
	   She was arrested in February this year after trying to sell a
rhino horn weighing 1.2 kilograms (2.5 pounds).
	   (gm/sl/djw) 	   
