<HEADLINE>
Russian Minister visits Angola to expand trade, cooperation
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LUANDA, Angola (AP) _ Russia's Defense Minister arrived here
Monday for a three-day visit designed to deepen bilateral ties and
sign a five-year rearmament program for the Angolan armed forces.
	   ``We have no doubt that we can achieve our aims in the area of
military cooperation,'' Igor Sergeyev told reporters on his arrival
at Luanda airport.
	   He declined to give details of the rearmament plan.
	   Sergeyev's visit came as the United Nations is struggling to
keep a lid on the latest crisis in the implementation of the 1994
peace pact between the government and the former rebel movement
UNITA. The accord ended a two-decade civil war in this oil- and
diamond-rich nation.
	   The government has accused UNITA of attacking remote towns in
recent months, killing hundreds of civilians and police. UNITA
claims the government is preparing to launch a military strike
against towns still under rebel control.
	   Sergeyev was accompanied by a delegation of officials and
businessmen from the oil, diamond and fisheries sectors.
	   His visit was a follow-up to last June's meeting in Moscow
between Russian President Boris Yeltsin and Angolan President Jose
Eduardo dos Santos.
	   (cs/bh/cg) 	   
