<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Economy, 9th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Amid unrelenting financial turmoil, Russia lets ruble drop
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs. RECASTS, UPDATES with fresh quotes, analysis. Trims.
CHANGES byline. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos MOSB101-108 &QL; 
 &UR; By JUDITH INGRAM &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ After spending billions of dollars over the past
three months to prop up Russia's weak currency, the government gave
up on Monday and let the ruble's value drop by up to 50 percent.
	   Russians have already been hit hard by the country's fiscal
troubles, which have robbed many of their salaries for months. The
sharp drop in the currency is an even harsher blow for
rank-and-file consumers, as it will vastly increase the prices of
imports that which account for a large percentage of Russian
consumer goods, including groceries.
	   Russia's 1,500 banks, will also suffer, and up to half are
expected to go belly-up in the next few weeks.
	   The government-sanctioned drop in the currency is likewise
expected to shake foreign investors, whose confidence in the
government's ability to overcome the crisis has already been
shrinking steadily. Prices on European markets dropped on the news
that the government would let the ruble's lower limit sink from 6.3
to 9.5 to the dollar.
	   Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko insisted that the ruble's new
lower limit did not constitute a devaluation _ the step that
government officials have sworn repeatedly they would not allow.
	   ``This is just a new approach to monetary policy,'' Kiriyenko
told reporters.
	   Nevertheless, the move was a concession of defeat in the one
area where Russia's often painful economic reforms had yielded an
achievement that financial analysts and consumers alike could feel:
keeping the ruble steady and inflation low.
	   But the price of defending this feat had become too high,
Kiriyenko and Central Bank President Sergei Dubinin said in a joint
statement explaining the government's new exchange rate policy.
	   The new rate ``will make it possible to ease the acuteness of
speculative attacks on the Russian ruble that have led to
unjustified spending of the currency reserves of the Bank of
Russia,'' the statement said.
	   Those reserves had dropped this month to about dlrs 17 billion _
even including last month's multibillion dollar loan from the
International Monetary Fund.
	   The government blamed the difficult economic situation on the
Asian financial crisis and a recent drop in the world price of oil,
Russia's biggest export earner. Already, the government has
introduced an austerity program to close the huge gap between
government revenues and spending, and secured a dlrs 22.6 billion
bailout from international organizations led by the IMF. But
sagging investor confidence hasn't improved.
	   President Boris Yeltsin, who had cut short his vacation and
returned to his country residence outside Moscow, decided Sunday to
let the ruble sink during a meeting with Kiriyenko and Anatoly
Chubais, the president's envoy to international lending
organizations, presidential spokesman Sergei Yastrzhembsky said,
according to the Interfax news agency.
	   Yeltsin and Kiriyenko also met on Monday to discuss the
government's strategy for battling the economic crisis, while
Chubais met with a delegation led by senior IMF negotiator John
Odling-Smee.
	   Immediate public reaction to the announcement was muted, with
some Russians approaching exchange booths only to turn back when
they saw the massive increase.
	   ``It was hard to survive before on my pension of 350 rubles a
month,'' said pensioner Yelena Bochet, 68. ``But now I simply don't
know what to do because all the prices will certainly soar.''
	   Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov denounced the de facto
devaluation as a ``full-scale bankruptcy'' of Yeltsin's government.
	   A ruble devaluation had been widely rumored, in part because the
government faces heavy payments on ruble-denominated debt in coming
days and weeks. The government also said it would halt payment on
government treasury bills and impose a 90-day moratorium on
payments of foreign debt.
	   Chubais insisted that the government was not defaulting.
	   ``We are not reneging on our debts,'' he said. ``We realize that
many of our partners will feel uncomfortable, but any hesitation on
our part would cost them far more.''
	   The main currency exchange suspended dollar trades last week, so
it was not possible to fix a new market rate for the ruble. The
stock market opened 45 minutes late, but after an initial drop the
index was up slightly _ 0.19 percent _ by midday.
	   The drop in the ruble was also expected to lead to the collapse
of many Russian commercial banks, which are over-dependent on
now-devalued ruble assets. The government and Central Bank said
they would pool the resources of the country's 12 leading banks,
which account for the majority of the country's private deposits,
to limit the damage.
	   (pvs/ji/mr)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Russia-Economy, 9th Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:INDI;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:ASIA;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
