<DATE_TIME> 08/17/1998 10:23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w1711 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Nepal-EverestPollutio     08-17 0282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Nepal-Everest Pollution,0282 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bottled drinks banned from Everest region
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KATMANDU, Nepal (AP) _ The Nepalese government on Monday banned
all bottled drinks from the Everest region to minimize littering on
the slopes of the world's highest peak.
	   Empty bottles left by climbers have been a main concern of
Nepali environmentalists for years. An average of 30,000 trekkers
each year are said to leave about 200,000 bottles of water, beer
and other beverages on the slopes.
	   Only drinks bottled in aluminum cans would be permitted in the
area as they can be crushed and easily carried back to the base,
and were good value for trash collectors, said Umesh Singh, an
official at the Nepalese Tourism Ministry.
	   Bottled beer and beverages are carried on yaks or by porters
from the base. Some stocks are flown in by helicopter.
	   But bringing the bottles back is expensive and the three rupees
(5 cents) offered by recyclers does not cover even a fraction of
the cost, officials say.
	   The ban will be imposed throughout the Everest region, which is
a national park, and will be monitored by the Everest Pollution
Control Committee, an agency funded by the ministry and the World
Wildlife Fund, Singh said. The Nepal Mountaineering Association
welcomed the ban.
	   Since the committee was established in 1991, it has urged local
hotel owners to help collect the trash. Bottles are brought to the
nearest airfield, sacked and flown to Katmandu by helicopter
operators free of charge whenever extra space is available.
	   The committee would impose the ban at Jorsalle, at 2,800 meters
(9,240 feet) above sea level, which is the only entry point into
the Everest area. 	   
</TEXT>
