w1730 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-Impeachment     08-17 0355
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Impeachment </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Parliament commission resumes hearings for impeaching Yeltsin
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Boris Yeltsin's parliamentary foes on Monday sent
an invitation to former Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev to
testify before a commission trying to impeach the president, the
ITAR-Tass news agency reported.
	   The Communist-led opposition in the lower house of parliament,
the State Duma, has accused Yeltsin of instigating the collapse of
the Soviet Union. The impeachment campaign started long before
Russia's latest, unfolding financial crisis.
	   The commission has also invited former Presidents Leonid
Kravchuk of Ukraine and Stanislav Shushkevich of Belarus, who
together with Yeltsin signed the 1991 agreement declaring the
Soviet Union defunct and creating the Commonwealth of Independent
States, a loose coalition of former Soviet republics. Neither has
responded, said commission chairman Vadim Filimonov.
	   Gorbachev was leader of the Soviet Union at that time. Yeltsin,
who was then head of the Russian republic, Kravchuk and Shushkevich
effectively sidestepped Gorbachev by signing the agreement, which
also made Gorbachev's job moot.
	   Communist lawmakers call Yeltsin's action high treason, claiming
that Russia lost much of its wealth and military might in the
Soviet collapse. Supporters of the impeachment motion also accuse
Yeltsin of launching the botched war in Chechnya, ruining Russia's
economy and military, and using troops and tanks against his foes
in the former Russian parliament in October 1993.
	   Several previous attempts to oust Yeltsin have failed, and this
initiative is expected to meet the same fate.
	   Russia's constitution gives the president a strong hand in
confrontations with parliament. The constitution is vague on the
grounds for which a president can be impeached, citing only treason
and grave misconduct.
	   An impeachment motion would also require approval from both the
Constitutional and Supreme Courts, as well as the upper chamber of
parliament _ a body made up of regional leaders, most of whom are
loyal to Yeltsin.
	   (ad/ji)
</TEXT>
