<SLUG> BC-Nepal-Gurkhas,0165 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Gurkhas protest outside British Embassy demanding hike in pension
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KATMANDU, Nepal (AP) _ Nearly 300 retired Gurkha soldiers sat
outside the British Embassy Monday at the start of a three-day
protest to demand pensions at par with British ex-servicemen.
	   The Gurkhas waved banners and placards demanding an ``end to
discrimination.'' Their monthly pension is 16 times less than what
a retired British soldier gets.
	   They plan to continue their daytime protest until Wednesday,
said Krishna Rai of Gurkha Ex-Servicemen's Organization.
	   The organization rejected a recent 23-51 percent hike ordered by
the British government for 26,375 retired Gurkha soldiers. After
the latest increase, the pension for a retired Gurkha rifleman
would be dlrs 42 a month, compared with dlrs 750 for a British
soldier.
	   Nearly 3,000 Nepalese Gurkhas are still serving the British
army. Gurkha soldiers from Nepal have served in the British Army
for nearly 200 years. 	   
</TEXT>
