<HEADER>
w1748 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Congo 4thLd-Writethru   08-17 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Congo, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kabila heads back to Lubumbashi, power cut in Kinshasa
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS throughout to RECAST to raise diplomatic elements.
Edits. No pickup. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By IAN STEWART &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KINSHASA, Congo (AP) _ Traipsing from Cuba to southern Congo and
into neighboring Angola, President Laurent Kabila has been mounting
a last minute drive to rally support for his embattled government,
threatened by an advancing rebel army.
	   Over the weekend, Kabila met with Angolan President Jose Eduardo
Dos Santos to ask for arms and troops to help hold off the rebel
force that reportedly has closed to within 200 kilometers (125
miles) of Kinshasa.
	   A senior Kabila adviser familiar with his trip Angola said
Monday that the meetings were cordial, but would not disclose the
outcome.
	   Late last month, during a surprise visit to Cuba, Kabila
apparently did the same, a former military intelligence officer
with close ties to the government told The Associated Press on
condition of anonymity.
	   Kabila returned briefly Sunday to Kinshasa, but reboarded his
presidential jet and went to the southern city of Lubumbashi _ his
former rebel stronghold.
	   Angolan troops, along with former Rwandan and Ugandan allies,
helped Kabila in his march across this vast central African country
last year to oust longtime dictator Mobutu Sese Seko. Angolan
soldiers also played a key role last year in helping Gen. Denis
Sassou-Nguesso seize control of the neighboring Republic of Congo.
	   The outcome of both the Cuban and Angolan meetings was unclear,
but the former intelligence officer said they were part of an
effort by the president to find troops, arms and other supplies for
his crippled military.
	   One report indicates Kabila may have ordered or purchased a MiG
fighter jet while in Cuba.
	   Rwandan Tutsi troops _ once the core of Kabila's military _
defected en mass to join an ethnic Tutsi-led rebellion against his
government. Just days before the rebellion began, Kabila had
ordered all the Rwandans out of his country.
	   ``Kabila had learned of an assassination plot against him that
was being planned by the Rwandans,'' the former intelligence
officer said.
	   The president, with his 15-month-old regime in jeopardy, made an
unannounced visit to the Cuban capital of Havana last month. Days
after his return, he fired Col. James Kabari _ a Rwandan soldier
and Kabila's top commander _ and ordered all Rwanda troops out of
the country.
	   Rwandan troops played an instrumental role in helping Kabila
oust Mobutu. Disaffected and acting on their government's concern
that Kabila had done little to secure the turbulent eastern border
region, the Rwandans revolted in their barracks in Kinshasa and
teamed up with other disgruntled Tutsi rebels to stage a rebellion
against the president.
	   His former Rwandan and Ugandan allies gone, Kabila is now
turning to old friends in Angola and Cuba for help.
	   While a guerrilla warrior in the jungles of southern Congo in
the 1960s, Kabila briefly recruited the support of legendary rebel
leader Ernesto ``Che'' Guevara.
	   That rebellion failed, and his new regime appears in jeopardy as
well.
	   On Monday, Kabila has left his embattled capital for the second
time in a week and headed to the southern city of Lubumbashi.
	   State television has repeatedly shown Kabila arriving at
Kinshasa's airport, smiling and defiantly denouncing the rebels.
	   What state broadcasters did not mention was that Kabila quickly
reboarded his jet and headed back to Lubumbashi, where he spent
much of last week, a senior government minister told The Associated
Press on condition of anonymity.
	   ``The president is back in Lubumbashi, but he said he would be
returning to Kinshasa tonight,'' the official said.
	   By Monday afternoon, electricity was also lost throughout
Kinshasa _ the second time since the rebels began their advance two
weeks ago. It was not immediate clear what caused the outage.
	   The loss of power cut off state radio and television.
	   Before the electricity failed, state radio had been repeatedly
broadcast Kabila saying his government will arm the people and
prevail against a rebel movement of ethnic Tutsi fighters, Rwandan
soldiers and disenchanted members of the president' own military.
	   He also lashed out at the international community and accused
the West of plotting against his government.
	   The rebels have been making steady progress toward the capital,
a western diplomat said on condition of anonymity.
	   Many in the rebel movement helped Kabila oust longtime dictator
Mobutu Sese Seko in May 1997, but now say they have been
marginalized by the government.
	   A diplomat in Kinshasa said he had received reports from his
government that the rebels were now near the town of Mbanza-Ngungu,
about 150 kilometers (95 miles) south of the capital.
	   Kabila said Congo was the victim of a plot by neighboring Rwanda
_ which he says is orchestrating the rebellion _ along with the
West.
	   ``The next 24 hours will be decisive,'' Kabila said. ``We must
understand that we must win. This is the message I have for my
people, I am asking them to face up to this plot, to arm
themselves, to support their army, and to defeat the aggressors.''
	   Hundreds of westerners left Kinshasa over the weekend, while a
team of 50 British commandos has been deployed to Brazzaville, the
capital of the neighboring Republic of Congo, to help the
evacuation of British subjects if need be.
	   French troops already in Brazzaville helped hundreds of French,
Belgian and other foreigners cross the river on Saturday.
	   Despite apparent military setbacks, the Congolese government
said Sunday that it was securing bases across the country to attack
rebel forces.
	   Kabila's government has drawn support from the public in
Kinshasa by characterizing the rebel movement as a Rwandan Tutsi
war against Congo. Rwanda denies the charge.
	   Tutsis, an ethnic minority centered in eastern Congo and
neighboring countries, including Rwanda, have become the target of
attacks and arbitrary detentions in Kinshasa.
	    &UR; (hh/ids/tjs)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Congo, 4th Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
