<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Northern Ireland-Spain </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Spanish deputy premier flies to Northern Ireland
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With Northern Ireland &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) _ Spain's deputy prime minister
flew to Northern Ireland on Monday to visit the Spanish victims of
the deadly bombing in Omagh and to express solidarity with the
local community.
	   Two of the 28 people killed in the Saturday bombing were
Spanish.
	   Francisco Alvarez Cascos arrived at Aldergrove air force base
from Madrid shortly after relatives of the injured Spaniards
touched down. A third aircraft carrying medical staff also arrived
at the base on the outskirts of Belfast to transport the injured
who are well enough to travel back to Madrid later in the day.
	   Police identified the slain Spaniards as Ricio Abad Ramos, 23,
of Victor De La Serra, Madrid, and Fernando Blasco Baselga, 12,
Arturo Sorita, Madrid. They were part of a group on an exchange
trip to Northern Ireland. Ten other members were injured in the
blast.
	   ``My presence here is to be with the families, meeting all these
people injured in the hospital and being able to accompany families
taking casualties back,'' Alvarez Cascos said.
	   ``I would like to be at the place of the terrorist bombing and
express with my presence the solidarity of the community enduring
this situation, and who have been affected by terrorism for so
long,'' he said in Spanish. his remarks were interpreted by Alberto
Aza, Spanish ambassador to Britain.
	   ``Terrorist activities all over the world have something in
common. They are the activities of fanatical, mad people,'' he
said. ``There are always minority groups. They are savage and
cowards.''
	   (acw)
