w1754 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Cyprus-Missing     08-17 0354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cyprus-Missing </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Wives of missing soldiers try to dig up grave of unknown soldier
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo NIC-101 available

<TEXT>
	   NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) _ Desperate for clues, wives of two Greek
Cypriot soldiers missing since the 1974 Turkish invasion tried to
exhume the bodies of two unidentified soldiers Monday in a military
cemetery.
	   They had dug two feet (60 centimeters) down when police arrived
and dragged them away as they wailed.
	   ``We have been waiting for 24 years to find out about the fate
of our loved ones, but nobody bothers,'' said Maroula Shamishi, one
of the two middle aged women. Both women wore black dresses in sign
of mourning.
	   ``We will do this again until the government does something to
settle the drama of the families of the missing,'' said the other
woman, Maroula Palma.
	   The grave is one of several in the cemetery marked ``unknown
soldiers.''
	   A total of 1,609 Greek Cypriots and 700 Turkish Cypriots are
listed as missing in the wake of the 1974 invasion and earlier
intercommunal clashes. The island has been split into a Greek
Cypriot-controlled south and a Turkish-occupied north since 1974. A
breakaway Turkish Cypriot state in the north is only recognized by
Turkey which maintains 35,000 troops there.
	   A Missing Persons Committee from both communities and chaired by
a representative of the International Committee of the Red Cross
has been meeting for years without having been able to trace the
missing.
	   Many Greek Cypriots disappeared after being listed by the Red
Cross as prisoners of war held in camps in Turkey, leading
relatives to believe their loved ones may still be alive.
	   The committee agreed last year to the simultaneous opening of
mass graves and other burial sites in both communities and to try
to identify the remains through DNA tests. But the operation has
been delayed by Turkish reluctance to implement the agreement.
	   A U.S. Congressional mission, which visited the occupied north
two years ago to determine the fate of five missing Greek
Cypriot-American citizens, succeeded in tracing the grave of one of
them.
 &UR; ae-sf
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Cyprus-Missing; CT:i; 
