<HEADER>
w1757 &Cx1f; wstm-
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Track-European     08-17 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Track-Europeans </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bubka, Perec notable absences; Drechsler goes for 4th straight
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By STEPHEN WADE &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) _ Russian pole vaulter Maksim Tarasov is
here. But, in the absence at the European Championships of his
great rival Sergey Bubka, he doesn't sound that enthused about it.
	   Bubka, the world record-holder and a six-time world champion
outdoors, will be the most notable no-show _ along with French
Olympic champion Marie-Jose Perec _ when the six-day Euros open
Tuesday.
	   ``I've never done the Europeans, only the world championships
since I was a junior,'' said Tarasov, who should be among the
favorites with French Olympic champion Jean Galfione. ``I live in
Budapest, so that's a reason I'm here.''
	   ``Apparently the Europeans aren't that interesting, there is no
money,'' added the '92 Olympic champion and silver medalist in last
year's worlds behind Bubka. ``I don't do the European indoors
either.''
	   ``I still want to save my best for the end of the season. I hope
you haven't seen my best yet.''
	   Bubka is skipping these championships because he said they
didn't figure in his training schedule. Perec is out because of a
reported squabble with the French track federation.
	   The field includes more than 1,300 athletes from 44 countries
with Germany fielding the largest team (123) followed by France
(103), Russia (101), Italy (83), Hungary (80) and Spain (76).
	   With North American men dominating this season's sprints and the
Africans cleaning up in the distance races, the men's side here
seems weak with most of the world-class performances expected in
the field events _ particularly the high jump, triple jump and the
strength events.
	   The women are stronger. With the exception of the sprints, they
figure prominently among the world leaders this season in most
events.
	   The most-watched woman will be Germany's 33-year-old long jumper
Heike Drechsler, who is trying to equal the European record of four
straight gold medals in one event, which has been done by two
others, Janis Lusis in the javelin, 1962-1971, and Nadezhda
Chizhova in the shot put, 1966-74.
	   She looks in good shape to do it, coming off a jump of 7.05
(23-1 3/4) last week in Zurich. She also has a wind-assisted 7.12
(23-4 1/2) this season, her longest jump since winning the European
title four years ago.
	   Drechsler, coming off operations on both Achilles tendons 10
months ago, is free of injuries for the first time in three years.
	   ``I've got my confidence back, and that was on of my aims for
1998,'' she said.
	   The top challenge will come from British-born Italian Fiona May,
the '96 Olympic silver medalist who has gone 7.08 (23-2 3/4) this
season.
	   Four others will be after their third consecutive European golds
_ British hurdler Colin Jackson and javelin thrower Steve Backley,
and Germans Sabine Braun (heptathlon) and Ilke Wyludda (discus).
	   The British men will probably benefit most not having the North
American sprinters around. That's particularly true in the 400,
where Britain could finish 1-2-3 with Mark Richardson, Iwan Thomas
and Solomon Wariso.
	   ``The competition in Britain is stiff, and that's good. On the
other side, it's too bad only three could come here,'' he said,
referring to two-time European champion and Olympic silver medalist
Roger Black, who failed to make the British team.
	   ``One shouldn't read too much into the results so far,'' said
Thomas, who has beaten Richardson only once this season. ``I've
been experimenting a lot.''
	   ``The track (in Budapest) is not all that fast, but the European
record (44.33) could go if we have a good race.''
	   The most interesting local rivalry will be '96 Olympic hammer
throw champion Balazs Kiss against Hungarian countryman Tibor
Gecsek, who is returing from a two-year drug ban.
	   One of Europe's most decorated women Fernanda Ribeiro of
Portugal will defend her 10,000 title, an event where she's also
the '96 Olympic champion and '95 world champion. She's has the
world's best time this year (30:48.06), just ahead of Britain's
Paula Radcliffe (30:48.58).
	   (scw)	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
