<HEADLINE>
Gadhafi meets with Tunisian president
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: CORRECTS Gadhafi's title in 1st graf &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi met with his
Tunisian counterpart Zine el Abidine Ben Ali Monday for talks on
boosting relations between the two countries, Libyan television
reported.
	   Ben Ali, on the first visit by a Tunisian leader to Libya in
five years, received a red-carpet welcome by Libyan officials
outside the ruins of an apartment building that was bombed during
the 1987 U.S. air raids on Tripoli, the Libyan capital.
	   Gadhafi, who is recovering from hip surgery, did not attend the
welcoming reception said the television broadcast, monitored by the
British Broadcasting Corporation.
	   Speaking to reporters, Ben Ali reaffirmed his country's
commitment to seeing U.N. sanctions on Libya lifted, Egypt's Middle
East News Agency said.
	   The United Nations imposed economic and political sanctions on
Libya in 1992 to force Gadhafi to surrender two Libyans wanted in
connection with the 1988 bombing of a Pan Am jet over Lockerbie,
Scotland, that killed 270 people. So far, he has resisted.
	   The embargo, banning air travel to the country and freezing
Libyan assets abroad, also aims to punish Libya for supporting
international terrorism.
	   The sanctions have increased land crossings from Libya into
Tunisia, which borders Libya on the east. 	   
</TEXT>
