<HEADLINE>
Defense ministers arrive to discuss Congo Kinshasa crisis
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES in new graf 4 with Zimbabwe spokesman saying Kabila
not expected; no pickup

<TEXT>
	   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) _ Defense ministers from Namibia and
Angola arrived here Monday for talks on the civil war in Congo, the
official news agency Ziana said.
	   ``There are no new developments yet, but the ministers want to
find a lasting solution to the crisis which seemingly is
deepening,'' a government official told Ziana.
	   The agency quoted ``government sources'' as saying they had
arrived for talks with their counterpart from Zimbabwe. A
representative of President Laurent Kabila's government had yet to
arrive.
	   Kabila is defense minister, but a spokesman for Zimbabwean
President Robert Mugabe said he was not aware that Kabila planned
to come.
	   Earlier reports had said foreign ministers of Namibia, Tanzania,
Zambia and Zimbabwe would gather here to report back on the peace
initiative launched earlier this month by the Southern African
Development Community.
	   However, Zimbabwean Foreign Minister Stan Mudenge on Monday was
said to be in the Great Lakes region, studying Kabila's allegations
that Rwanda is backing the mutiny by fellow Tutsi ethnic group
soldiers.
	   Ziana quoted government sources that Monday's scheduled defense
ministers' meeting was a follow-up to the Victoria Falls summit
chaired by Mugabe.
	   Kabila met over the weekend with Namibia's President Sam Nujoma
and Angola's President Eduardo dos Santos in Luanda, repeating
requests for military assistance he made to Mugabe here in early
July, according to news reports.
	   (mh/djw)
