<SLUG> BC-Russia-Parliament </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russia's lower chamber of parliament to meet Friday
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-Russia-Economy

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russia's lower house of parliament decided Monday
to hold two emergency sessions to debate the government's austerity
measures, a news agency said.
	   The chamber, known as the State Duma, will discuss an array of
bills, including amendments to tax, pension, and financial
insolvency laws, on Friday and on Aug. 25, the ITAR-Tass news
agency said, citing the Duma's press service.
	   The proposals are part of the government's austerity package,
designed to boost income to Russia's empty coffers and put an end
to months of economic slide. The parliament has stalled on many key
bills, but top government officials are demanding they be reviewed.
	   Duma leaders agreed to call the meetings after the government
let the national currency, the ruble, lose 50 percent of its value
Monday. The exchange rate on the streets rose from around 6.4
rubles to the dollar to around 9.5 rubles to the dollar early in
the day, then slid back to 8-8.5.
	   Parliament's upper house, the Federation Council, said it would
meet on Aug. 28 to debate any bills that the Duma may have passed
by that time, ITAR-Tass said.
	   (nw/ji) 	   
</TEXT>
