w1780 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Italy-Immigrants-Esca     08-17 0354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Italy-Immigrants-Escape </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Illegal immigrants set fire in escape attempt at Sicilian detention
</HEADLINE>
center &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   POZZALLO, Italy (AP) _ Authorities had 13 illegal immigrants
under arrest Monday after the men allegedly set fire to their
sheets and mattresses in a chaotic attempt to escape a detention
center on Italy's southern island of Sicily.
	   Three of the immigrants were recovering from smoke inhalation;
another man sustained a broken wrist and another a cut in Sunday's
escape attempt, Italy's ANSA news agency said.
	   The unrest started when one of the men drank shampoo with the
idea of distracting guards with a faked illness so the immigrants
could make their escape, news reports said. Once in an ambulance,
the man kicked out a window; others started the fire and tried to
force a gate at the center.
	   None of the immigrants succeeded in getting away from the center
at Pozzallo, a community on Sicily's southern coast. ANSA said the
arrested men were believed to be 11 Moroccans and two Algerians.
	   Also Monday, police detained 45 illegal immigrants thought to
have newly landed in Italy's southeastern region of Puglia, across
the Adriatic from Yugoslavia. Thirteen were believed to be Iraqi
Kurds; the rest apparently were ethnic Albanians, including women,
children and others from the embattled Yugoslav province of Kosovo,
ANSA said.
	   Police in Puglia arrested another 166 immigrants in a crackdown
on illegal workers, ANSA said.
	   Italy has been trying to better control its borders, in part at
the insistence of northern countries where many of the illegal
immigrants wind up. A new law lets authorities detain illegal
immigrants for up to 30 days, but officials frequently are unable
to process them for deportation within that time. Authorities then
resort to handing the immigrants expulsion papers warning they face
arrest if they don't leave the country on their own.
	   Many Italian politicians now are calling for tougher measures.
On Monday, Giampaolo Bettamio of the opposition Forza Italia said
the time had come to institute a European coast guard.
	   (ek)
</TEXT>
