<SLUG> BC-EU_NIreland Reaction, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
With NIreland-Arrests
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with more reactions &QL; 
 &UR; Omagh blast condemnations continue as do calls to pursue peace
process &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ The bomb in Omagh that killed 28 and
wounded 220 drew more condemnations worldwide Monday along with
pleas that it must not derail the Ulster peace process.
	   European Commission President Jacques Santer issued a statement
expressing his ``very deep shock and dismay ... We extend our
deepest sympathy to all the families and friends of those killed,''
he said on behalf of the 20-member EU executive Commission.
	   ``We believe unequivocally that supporting the peace process is
the only way forward toward lasting peace and reconciliation'' in
Northern Ireland, he added.
	   Others reacted similarly.
	   German Chancellor Helmut Kohl expressed sympathy for the victims
and relatives of the weekend bombing in a letter of condolence to
British Prime Minister Tony Blair.
	   ``The answer to this can only be to intensify the peace and
healing process.'' Kohl wrote.
	   Half a world away, the government in Beijing condemned the blast
saying, ``We were shocked by the serious bombing on August 15. The
Chinese government opposes and condemns all forms of terrorist
acts.''
	   Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao said in a statement
through the official Xinhua News Agency that Beijing hoped Britain,
Ireland and parties in Northern Ireland will push ahead with an
April peace agreement.
	   ``An early and lasting peace ... will fully accord with the best
interests of all concerned,'' the statement added.
	   The Geneva-based Council of Churches denounced Saturday's blast
as an ``unspeakable crime (that has) appalled people throughout
Europe and other parts of the world who have the cause of peace in
Northern Ireland in their hearts and prayers.''
	   The Council said that to many people the road to a peace in
Ulster ``may now seem still more difficult and perilous (but) it is
our hope and prayer that the people and their leaders will remain
firm in their commitment to pursue peace by negotiation.''
