w1783 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-China-Floods 3rdLd-Writethru   08-17 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Floods, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
River breaches dike, threatening China's largest oil field
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS to UPDATE with dike being breached; more soldiers
dispatched, deaths from landslides in Sichuan; picks up 16th graf
pvs `In Inner ... '
 &UR; AP Photos
 &UR; By RENEE SCHOOF &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Despite day and night sandbagging by thousands of
soldiers, a rain-swollen river breached a dike Monday, threatening
to inundate China's largest oil field.
	   The flooded Nen River pounded a 50-meter-wide (50-yard-wide) gap
in the embankment, the second of three lines of defense for the
Daqing oil field and the northeastern city of 2.3 million people of
the same name, the official Xinhua News Agency reported.
	   China's northeastern regional military command urgently sent
10,000 more soldiers to the area, doubling the number of troops
already there fighting floods, Xinhua said.
	   To the south, in central China, the Yangtze River reached a new
record height of 45.22 meters (149.2 feet) Monday morning at Shashi
city, home to a half million people.
	   Officials earlier warned that if the river went over 45 meters
(148.5 feet) dikes might be dynamited to deliberately flood an area
south of Shashi and safeguard cities down river. But water levels
began falling later Monday.
	   ``There's been a turn for the better,'' said a flood control
official who gave his surname, Xu. He predicted the water would not
rise so high to make destroying dikes necessary.
	   Official reports sounded less certain. On a visit to Shashi,
Vice Premier Wen Jiabao, the senior most government official in
charge of flood control, told state television that dikes
downstream were undergoing ``a great historical trial.''
	   Xinhua said 335,000 people had been moved out of Hubei's
Jingjiang area in case a diversion was necessary.
	   This summer's floods are the Yangtze's worst in 44 years, with
more than 2,000 people killed. Some 2.7 million civilians and
soldiers worked on embankments of the river to protect farms and
cities from floods.
	   Water levels on the Yangtze's mid-reaches have stood above the
danger mark for 50 days, Xinhua said. Upstream, in Sichuan
province, more heavy rains brought landslides last week that buried
20 people in Suining city, the news agency said in a separate
report.
	   Near the Daqing oil field, 1,000 kilometers (600 miles)
northeast of Beijing, the second of three dikes collapsed Saturday.
Soldiers worked round-the-clock to pile sandbags two meters (six
feet) high along a five-kilometer (three-mile) embankment by
Monday, Xinhua said. But their efforts fell short.
	   Raging waters pushed through the dike Sunday, opening a more
than 10-meter (yard) hole, and by noon Monday the gap had widened
to 50 meters (yards), Xinhua said.
	   China's two most senior generals, Zhang Wannian and Chi Haotian,
telephoned the northeast region's military commander and ordered
him to ensure the safety of the Daqing oil field, Xinhua said.
	   Flooding at Daqing closed 527 oil wells, reducing output by more
than 2 million gallons (7.6 million liters) last week. Daqing has
25,000 wells that produced 17.9 billion gallons (68 billion liters)
of oil last year, about a third of the nation's total.
	   The partial collapse of the second dike Saturday forced the
evacuation of more than 2,000 people.
	   ``I heard people start to scream and run around blindly when
they learned the dike was breached,'' the China Daily quoted Liu
Hai, a farmer living 3 kilometers (two miles) from the second dike,
as saying.
	   Although Xinhua said the Nen had yet to reach the Daqing wells,
the third dike marked a ``life-and-death defense'' for Daqing, the
official China Daily quoted Wang Yang, an army captain in charge of
the dike, as saying.
	   In Inner Mongolia in north China, authorities were trying to
rescue 76,000 people stranded by the flooded Ulyji Muren River,
Xinhua said. About 70,000 other people cut off by the river had
been rescued, it said.
	   Rescuers also moved 52 Siberian tigers from a breeding and
research center near Harbin, the capital of Heilongjiang province
east of Daqing, to another station of the center 250 kilometers
(150 miles) away.
	   The tiger preserve, a tourist attraction, is near the Songhua
River, which is expected to crest at Harbin on Wednesday bringing
the worst flooding in 50 years.
</TEXT>
