u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Cyprus-Turkey     08-17 0435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cyprus-Turkey </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cyprus accuses Turkey of military buildup in occupied north
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) - Cyprus accused Turkey Monday of
bolstering its forces in the occupied north of the island with more
tanks and artillery.
	   It said Turkey was moving its forces ``in attack formations.''
	   ``In the past week alone, 50 more tanks and self-propelled
artillery pieces arrived in the Turkish-occupied north where
Turkish forces are being deployed in attack formations,'' said
Defense Minister Yiannakis Omirou.
	   He charged that the new tanks were made in the United States. He
did not elaborate.
	   ``This constitutes a violation of American law which forbids the
use of U.S.-made weapons in such cases,'' Omirou said.
	   The Cyprus government says Turkey maintains more than 50,000
troops and 500 tanks in northern Cyprus.
	   Omirou's comments came a day before Thomas Miller, the U.S.
State Department special moderator for Cyprus, was due in Ankara to
try to defuse a looming crisis over the planned deployment by
Cyprus of Russian S-300 anti-aircraft missiles.
	   Miller is scheduled to hold talks Tuesday with Turkish Foreign
Minister Ismail Cem and Sukuru Siuna Gurel, minister of state in
charge of Turkey's relations with northern Cyprus, the U.S. Embassy
in Ankara said.
	   Turkey has warned that it will take action to prevent the
arrival of the Russian missiles in Cyprus. Greece, which has a
joint defense agreement with Cyprus, said it will defend Cyprus if
attacked.
	   This has raised the specter of hostilities between Greece and
Turkey, both members of the NATO alliance.
	   The United States and other Western governments have been
pressing Cyprus to cancel the deployment of the Russian missiles,
planned for next November. But President Glafcos Clerides said he
will only do so if Turkey accepts his proposal for the
demilitarization of the island or if there is progress in the
deadlocked U.N._sponsored talks for the reunification of the
island.
	   ``Cyprus has every right to strengthen its defenses in view of
the Turkish threats. It would be better if those pressing for the
cancellation of the deployment of the missiles pressured Turkey
instead to agree to our demilitarization proposal,'' said Omirou.
	   Cyprus has been divided into a Greek Cypriot controlled south
and a Turkish-occupied north since Turkey invaded and occupied the
northern third of the island in 1974 in the wake of an abortive
coup by supporters of union with Greece. A breakaway Turkish
Cypriot state established in the north is only recognized by
Turkey.
 &UR; ae-sf
</TEXT>
