<HEADER>
w1791 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SouthAfrica-BothaTria 2ndLd-Writethru   08-17 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Botha Trial, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New date for verdict set in South Africa Botha trial
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs; recasts &QL; 
 &UR; With AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By PAUL HARRIS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   GEORGE, South Africa (AP) _ Smiling and joking with supporters,
apartheid-era president P. W. Botha on Monday listened for the last
time to lawyers argue his defense on charges of snubbing a body
probing apartheid atrocities.
	   In closing argument, Botha's lawyer told Magistrate Victor
Lugaju that technical flaws in legal papers served on the former
hard-line president were a cause for dismissing the case.
	   Attorney Lappe Laubscher said the summons had instructed Botha
to appear before the Truth and Reconciliation Commission as a
whole, whereas the hearing he was ordered to attend was being held
only by a sub-division of the panel.
	   ``He was subpoeanaed to appear before the TRC, not the Human
Rights Violation Committee. End of story,'' Laubscher said.
	   Adjourning the case after the lawyers had finished their
arguments, Lugaju, who is black, said he would deliver a verdict on
Friday.
	   If found guilty Botha, 82, could face up to two years in jail or
an unspecified fine. Given his age and frail health, a fine is
considered more likely.
	   Botha's spokesman, Paul Lombard, said Botha was looking forward
to the end of a tiring case. ``It doesn't matter who you are, or
how old you are. Something like this will take it out of you,'' he
said.
	   However, Botha appeared in a jovial mood on Monday. Wearing a
dark blue suit, he chatted to supporters and relatives in court,
including his daughter Elanza Maritz and new wife Barbara.
	   Dubbed the ``Big Crocodile'' for his stubborn political style,
Botha ruled South Africa with an iron fist for 11 years before a
stroke in 1989 saw him edged from power in a palace coup.
	   Commission lawyers wanted to quiz Botha on the role of the State
Security Council, a shadowy inner cabinet he headed which organized
a violent crackdown on anti-apartheid groups in the 1980s.
	   Botha alleges the commission wanted to humiliate him by forcing
him to appear in person after he submitted more than 1,700 pages of
written testimony.
	   The case has highlighted racial fault lines still dividing South
Africa four years after all-race elections ended apartheid.
	   Conservative whites sympathize with Botha's claim that the Truth
Commission is conducting a witch hunt against the old regime, while
blacks relish the spectacle of a black man sitting in judgement of
a hard-line apartheid leader.
	   For the commission, forcing Botha to appear became a key test of
its credibility in the face of criticisms from some blacks who saw
it as too soft on top apartheid politicians.
	   Supporters of the governing African National Congress say that
his continued defiance has damaged the commisson's quest for truth.
	   ``The impression you get is that through his defiance he is
hiding something, protecting some people or covering up,'' said ANC
Southern Cape organizer Lanvar Reid.
	   (djw)	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-South Africa-Botha Trial, 2nd Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:ENGL;)
