<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Kosovo </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russia calls for peaceful settlement in Kosovo
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russia reiterated its call for a peaceful
settlement of the conflict in Kosovo on Monday, after sending its
troops to a NATO-led exercise in the southern province in Serbia.
	   The military exercise that began Monday is ``an important factor
for streamlining the mechanism for dealing with humanitarian
problems and helping establish monitoring on the border in order to
shut down channels of arms trafficking and penetration of
terrorists into Kosovo,'' Foreign Ministry spokesman Valery
Nesterushkin was quoted as saying by the ITAR-Tass news agency.
	   At the same time, Nesterushkin stressed the need for ``maximum
caution in order to prevent hostilities that might threaten
dialogue,'' ITAR-Tass reported.
	   Russia supports broad autonomy for Kosovo, but not its secession
from Serb-led Yugoslavia, a longtime Slavic ally. Moscow has
adamantly opposed any NATO plans to use force to end the fighting
in Kosovo.
	   Russia has voiced concern over previous NATO air maneuvers in
June intended to put pressure on Serbia to stop its crackdown on
ethnic Albanians.
	   But it did sent troops to the new NATO exercises, which are to
run until Saturday and bring together more than 1,200 troops from
the United States, Canada, Germany, France, Greece, Spain, Britain,
Belgium, the Netherlands, Turkey, Italy, Albania, Russia, and
Lithuania.
	   Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev has also insisted that Russia's
participation in the maneuvers, being held in Albania and
Macedonia, does not mean a change in Moscow's policy, but he did
not elaborate.
	   (ad/ji)
</TEXT>
