<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Syria </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Israeli defense minister sets off debate on Golan withdrawal
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai touched off
a debate Monday over whether Israel might be now willing to return
much of the Golan Heights in a peace agreement with Syria in
exchange for security measures.
	   In an interview with the German magazine Focus published Monday,
Mordechai was asked his opinion of late Prime Minister Yitzhak
Rabin's formula for peace with Syria _ that the extent of Israel's
withdrawal from the Golan would depend on the extent of peace
offered by Syria.
	   Mordechai was quoted as saying in response that he had
``invented this formula.''
	   ``The greatest interest of the Syrians is territory _ our
greatest interest is security,'' he was quoted as saying. ``It's
simple: the more security we receive, the more land we can give
back.''
	   The statement drew a storm of protest from Cabinet ministers who
said Mordechai was violating the government's basic guidelines _
that the Golan is vital to Israel's security.
	   ``Peace with Syria, as we understand it, cannot be, because
Syria doesn't recognize the existence of Israel,'' said Agriculture
Minister Rafael Eitan, a retired general who fought in the Golan in
the 1973 Mideast War.
	   Netanyahu said Monday that the government's policy had not
changed, and Mordechai said he had been misquoted. But in an
interview on Israel Radio, Netanyahu's policy adviser Uzi Arad
linked the idea of a withdrawal with Israel's security demands in
the Golan.
	   Arad said such an equation was ``only logical,'' and said that
he had raised the possibility during a recent conference in Texas
attended by Syrian representatives.
	   Arad gave no specifics, however, about Israel's security
demands, and gave no indication that the current government would
be willing to meet Syria's demands for a withdrawal from all of the
Golan, which Israel captured in the 1967 Mideast War.
	   Israel has in the past demanded security provisions that would
allow it to monitor Syria's compliance from the Golan Heights.
	   Israel's Maariv newspaper quoted unnamed political sources as
saying that Netanyahu supported Mordechai's statement, and that
several of the prime minister's advisers had used similar phrasing
recently.
 &UR; dk-hla
</TEXT>
