<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-Pebble Beach,0497 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Golf tournament to conclude six months after start
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ROB GLOSTER &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PEBBLE BEACH, California (AP) _ When the tournament began in
February, waves from the Pacific Ocean were crashing onto the 18th
fairway. Torrential rain was turning sandtraps into water hazards
and gusty winds were snapping treetops.
	   The AT and T Pebble Beach National Pro-Am resumed Monday on a
dry morning on the Pebble Beach, Poppy Hills and Spyglass Hill
courses.
	   But the change in weather did not occur overnight. It took more
than six months.
	   The tournament, suspended in early February by El Nino-inspired
miserable weather, resumed with Americans Tom Watson and Tim Herron
tied for the lead.
	   Of the 168 pros who started the tournament, 135 were expected to
return to Pebble Beach for the final round.
	   Among those not returning were Tiger Woods, who finished the
second round 14 strokes off the lead, and fellow American Jack
Nicklaus. Also dropping out was Vijay Singh of Fiji, who won the
PGA Championship Sunday near Seattle.
	   The AT and T tournament chartered a plane to take players from
Seattle to Monterey Sunday night. Those continuing to the next tour
stop, the International in Denver, will get another chartered
flight Monday night.
	   Watson, at 10-under 134, won the Pebble Beach tournament in 1977
and 1978. If he wins this year, the two-decade separation between
victories would be a tourney record.
	   ``I have a chance to win a golf tournament, albeit a little
late,'' Watson said of the delayed finish.
	   PGA Tour officials said it's the first time a portion of a
tournament has been played, then completed months later.
	   The tournament was washed out after two rounds in 1996, making
it the first PGA Tour event that could not be completed since 1949.
	   There have been other tournaments delayed for months by the
weather. In 1991, the Independent Insurance Agent Open in Texas was
wiped out in early April and rescheduled for late October.
	   But this year's Pebble Beach tournament is different in that it
was halfway completed when it had to be halted for six months.
	   Players managed to squeeze in two soggy rounds in late January,
and organizers reduced the event to 54 holes. But heavy rains wiped
out play 1 1/2 hours after tee-off Feb. 1, and again Feb. 2 when
officials tried to extend it to Monday.
	   The third round was reset for March 2, then rescheduled for
Monday _ the day after the PGA Championship ended at the Sahalee
Country Club.
	   When play was interrupted six months ago, water had collected on
the greens and shots were disappearing into the muck. Because of
the bad weather, golfers were allowed to pick up their ball, clean
it and place it within a club's length of where it landed.
	   The lift, clean and place rule was in force again Monday to
prevent problems with tire marks on the fairways from a vintage car
show that wrapped up Sunday night.
</TEXT>
