<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Italy-Drugs, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Prosecutor investigating doping interrogates former Juventus star
</HEADLINE>
Gianluca Vialli &QL; 
 &UR; EDs: UPDATES with quotes from national team doctor &QL; 
 &UR; With AP photos &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TURIN, Italy (AP) _ Former Juventus star Gianluca Vialli on
Monday met with a prosecutor looking into allegations that he and
other players in Italy's top division soccer league took
performance-enhancing substances.
	   Vialli, now player-coach of English club Chelsea, was summoned
after AS Roma coach Zdenek Zeman told Italian media he was amazed
by the quick muscular development of players including Vialli and
Alessandro Del Piero, a star-forward for Juventus.
	   Vialli, who left Juventus in 1996, walked past reporters without
commenting following a 2 1/2-hour session with Turin prosecutor
Raffaele Guariniello. He has hotly denied taking illegal
substances, calling the prosecutor a ``terrorist trying to
destabilize the soccer world.''
	   During questioning Friday, Del Piero told Guariniello his
strength was the result of ``years of hard work.''
	   The prosecutor, who has been investigating doping in sports for
years, met with Zemen last week. The Czech coach stuck to his
allegations, but did not say which banned drugs the players
allegedly use.
	   Vialli, Del Piero and Juventus have all announced that they are
suing Zeman for libel.
	   In Bologna Monday, prosecutor Giovanni Spinosa interrogated
Italy's national soccer team doctor Paolo Zeppilli.
	   ``We absolutely did not speak about doping,'' Zeppilli said
following the hour-long session.
	   Spinosa is investigating whether the banned drug EPO, or
Erythropoietin, is used in soccer. Several cyclists in the Tour de
France allegedly took the drug to boost their performance.
	   Zepilli said he mainly answered questions on the relationship
between Italy's Soccer Federation and a Bologna pharmacy which
allegedly supplied the national team during the 1996 European
Championships in England.
	   ``We ordered some medicine from this pharmacy _ iron and
vitamins _ like many other teams, federations and athletes,''
Zepilli said.
	   Zepillo said he expected to discuss doping Tuesday during a
meeting with a panel of Italian Olympic Committee experts.
	   World Cup stars Dino Baggio and Enrico Chiesa of Parma were
interrogated by the Bologna prosecutor last week.
	   (vg) 	   
</TEXT>
