w1834 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo 2ndLd-Writethru   08-17 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Major Albanian stronghold falls to Serb police
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS and UPDATES with diplomats pushing to return to
negotiating, INCORPORATES NATO exercises in Albania. Trims outdated
information. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos PRI102-106.
 &UR; By ISMET HAJDARI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ After Serb forces drove rebel
Albanians from their last major strongholds in western Kosovo,
diplomatic efforts turned towards organizing talks on Kosovo's
future Monday.
	   According to the pro-Albanian Kosovo Information Center,
fighting subsided Monday in the restive province of Kosovo,
following a weekend push when Serb forces captured a series of key
Albanian strongholds.
	   Yugoslavia's state-run Tanjug news agency said Monday Serb
police had ``crushed'' bases of the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army in
the villages of Lodja, Grabovac and Rausic, all on the outskirts of
the province's second city of Pec on Sunday.
	   The rebel Kosovo Liberation Army is fighting Serb security
forces for independence of Serbia's Kosovo province, where
Albanians account for 90 percent of the population of 2 million.
	   Monday's lull in the fighitng revivied hopes that negotiations
stalled since May might be revived. Fehmi Agani, the top ethnic
Albanian negotiator, wrote to his Serbian counterpart Ratko
Markovic, saying the Albanians wanted the talks to resume, on the
condition that Serbs halt their offensive.
	   ``We expect violence will stop and units used against the
civilian population will be withdrawn,'' Agani said.
	   Agani did not mention a date, but said he hoped U.S. envoy
Christopher Hill would establish a time when talks could resume.
Hill traveled to Belgrade Monday, to meet with Serb leaders and
negotiators.
	   Over the past two weeks, government forces have succeeded in
driving the KLA from several key villages in western Kosovo.
Government gains have, however, proven difficult to maintain, as
the KLA simply return to an area the moment police move on.
	   The attacks on villages have left tens of thousands of refugees
camped in the woods in western Kosovo. The U.N. refugee agency
based in Geneva, said in a statement Monday it rushed a convoy to
Pec, where refugees who fled earlier fighting reportedly came under
attack and were forced south into the mountains.
	   Kris Janowski, spokesman for the agency also said the second in
command is to meet with leaders on both sides later in the week and
call for a cessation of hostilities and full access for
humanitarian operations.
	   The U.N. now estimates that more than 231,000 people have been
uprooted in the six months since the conflict began. Many of them
have fled across the mountainous border with Albanian, where the
KLA also maintains bases.
	   In the Albanian capital Tirana, Monday troops from 14 nations
gathered to conduct training for parachute supply drops, vehicle
and foot patrols, marksmanship and other non-offensive drills in
the Albanian mountains.
	   Although the Albanian government says it supports a peaceful
solution to the crisis in Kosovo, Americans and Europeans fear the
fighting could spill over into neighboring countries with large
Albanian communities.
	   (pvs/jg/me)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 2nd Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
