w1843 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANALYSIS-Russia-Ruble     08-17 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANALYSIS-Russia-Ruble Wreck </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Boris Yeltsin gives up his primary success to prevent bigger
</HEADLINE>
failures &QL; 
 &UR; With BC-Russia-Economy, BC-Russia-Ruble Rage &QL; 
 &UR; An AP News Analysis &QL; 
 &UR; By MAURA REYNOLDS
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Until it went crashing on Monday, the ruble had
perhaps been Boris Yeltsin's only economic boast.
	   Russians have endured wave after wave of financial pain since
Yeltsin dismantled the Soviet Union in 1991, suffering through
several cycles of hyperinflation that gutted their savings and
robbed their pride.
	   Since then his one inarguable success was that he managed to
stabilize the currency, giving Russians a measure of confidence
that what they earned today would buy something tomorrow.
	   That confidence was shattered on Monday, when the government set
in motion a sharp devaluation of the ruble. And the reverberations
are likely to last for months and maybe even until presidential
elections in 2000.
	   First, consumer prices will climb _ some quickly, some over
time. The pain will be widespread, since a large number of consumer
goods are imported, including half the groceries sold in Russian
stores.
	   In addition, many banks _ some estimates say half the country's
1,500 banks _ have weak hard currency reserves and will collapse.
	   However, several factors suggest that those developments will be
less of a blow than one might expect. Most Russians grow at least
some of their own food, and very few keep their money in banks.
Those who do tend to hold the deposits in dollars, not rubles.
	   Moreover, many of the banks expected to collapse are not real
banks in the Western sense _ they don't hold deposits and they
don't make commercial loans. Instead, they are effectively money
speculation companies, buying and selling stocks and bonds without
providing banking services. Their collapse will have little effect
on the rest of the economy.
	   Perhaps the highest costs will be political.
	   Opposition leaders say that after years of hardship, the
population is primed to explode in anger. Coal miners across the
country have been striking sporadically throughout the summer.
	   However, Alan Rousso, director of the Carnegie Endowment's
Moscow office, points out that historically, Russian unrest tends
to be localized, not national in scope. And the government's
decision to halt payment on foreign debt means that for the first
time in years, it is expected to be able to pay all the back wages
owed to state workers _ including the miners.
	   Russians have endured so much economic hardship that they have
developed strong survival skills. It remains to be seen whether the
latest blows are strong enough to upset their traditional
fortitude.
	   That was a gamble Yeltsin didn't want to take. He held out
against devaluation for most of the summer, hoping a rise in oil
prices or a return of investor confidence would replenish the
government's wallet.
	   When they didn't, his hand was forced. It is a measure of the
seriousness of the financial crisis that Yeltsin spent his most
valuable political capital to try to get out of it.
	   In the end, Yeltsin's political standing is probably secure. He
is more than halfway through his second term, there are no
potential challengers in a position to force him from power, and he
is likely to deflect the blame to his subordinates, as he has in
the past.
	   But without a stable ruble, Russia's economy leaves him little
to boast about.
	    &UR; ___
	   Maura Reynolds is a correspondent for The Associated Press based
in Moscow.
	   (mr/ji) 	   
</TEXT>
