<SLUG> BC-IMF-Russia, 1st Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US, IMF urge urge quick action by Russian parliament
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With IMF-Russia-Economy &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Rubin statement. &QL; 
 &UR; By HARRY DUNPHY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ The U.S. government and the International
Monetary Fund urged Russian authorities Monday to act without delay
on economic reform measures that will be needed to bolstern
investors' confidence following the decision to devalue the ruble.
	   ``We believe it is critically important that the Russian
authorities move quickly to take actions to restore confidence,
including the adoption of a careful and cooperative approach to
dealing with its creditors and the full implementation of the
measures outlined in the Russian stabilization program agreed with
the IMF,'' U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin said in a
statement.
	   Stressing that ``the United States and the international
community have a great stake in successful Russian economic
reform,'' Rubin said it would be critical going forward for the IMF
to work with Russian officials to find appropriate ways to support
Russia's economic recovery.
	   Rubin made no mention in the statement of whether the United
States would be prepared to support further Western aid to Russia.
	   In a separate statement, Michel Camdessus, the IMF's managing
director, said the IMF will immediately analyze steps taken by the
Russian government to stabilize plunging financial markets. These
include a devaluation of the ruble, announced earlier Monday, that
is expected to reach 50 percent.
	   The IMF's, 3rd graf pvs
