<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Embassy Bombings, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Suspect in embassy bombings: Hot lead or false trail?
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Recasts for AMs. Changes byline. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos NAI101-106 of Aug. 16 &QL; 
 &UR; By CANDICE HUGHES &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) _ Is he a hot lead to the exiled Saudi
fanatic who might be behind the U.S. Embassy bombings in East
Africa? Or is he a false trail?
	   After three days of questioning, a suspect flown in from
Pakistan has not admitted any role in the crimes or implicated
anyone else, the FBI said Monday.
	   But reports out of Pakistan, have said he had confessed and
named his co-conspirators.
	   The reports also said the man had ties to a renegade Saudi
multimillionaire Osama bin Laden, whom the United States says is
one of the world's major sponsors of terrorism.
	   In a joint statement, the FBI and Kenyan police identified the
suspect as Mohammed Saddiq Odeh, also known as Abdull Bast Awadh
and Mohammad Sadiq Howaida.
	   He was arrested in Karachi after arriving on a flight from
Nairobi on Aug. 7, the day blasts in the Kenyan capital and in Dar
es Salaam, Tanzania, killed 257 people and injured more than 5,500.
	   The FBI and Kenyan police said they were questioning Odeh, but
revealed no breakthroughs.
	   ``Mr. Saddiq Odeh has not admitted any responsibility in the
bombings in Nairobi or Dar es Salaam, nor has he implicated anyone
else in those events,'' they said in a terse joint statement.
	   The Pakistani Foreign Ministry has said Odeh was returned to
Nairobi because Pakistani officials believe he is linked to the
bombings.
	   The Nairobi blast, which caused most of the deaths and injuries,
was the worst-ever attack on a U.S. embassy.
	   Coils of barbed wire, mounds of sandbags, tense soldiers and
sniffer dogs confront visitors at the temporary new U.S. embassy in
Nairobi.
	   In Pakistan, most U.S. Embassy personnel were leaving Monday and
other Americans were urged to join them after Odeh's transfer to
Nairobi.
	   The State Department issued a ``worldwide caution'' to U.S.
travelers over the weekend because of fresh threats to U.S.
interests abroad.
	   Bin Laden, the exiled heir to a Saudi construction fortune, is
said to be a fanatic Muslim on a crusade to drive U.S. troops from
the Middle East.
	   He is suspected of being behind several terrorist attacks on
American targets, including a 1995 truck bombing in Saudi Arabia
that killed five U.S. servicemen.
	   The FBI and Kenyan police refused to comment further on reports
that Odeh had confessed to Pakistani authorities, saying the
attacks were sponsored by bin Laden.
	   The Pakistani national newspaper, The News, said Odeh is a
34-year-old Palestinian engineer. Other reports said he is married
to a Kenyan and familiar with Nairobi.
	   He reportedly told investigators that six co-conspirators had
slipped through the Karachi airport Aug. 7 and made it to
Afghanistan, where bin Laden has a hideout.
	   A spokesman for Afghanistan's Taliban militia told The
Associated Press Monday that bin Laden had pledged not to engage in
terrorism while living under Taliban protection and had nothing to
do with the embassy bombings.
	   A Kenyan newspaper, meanwhile, reported Monday that FBI agents
had flown a second suspect back to Nairobi, also on Friday. It said
the suspect was arrested in the United Arab Emirates.
	   Spokesmen for the U.S. Embassy in Nairobi and Kenyan police both
declined comment. A Pakistani Embassy spokesman said he was unaware
of the arrest.
	   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright was to visit Nairobi and
Dar es Salaam on Tuesday in a show of support for the victims and
of resolve in the face of growing terrorist threats to Americans.
	   Departing Washington on Monday, Albright said she was bringing a
``message of solidarity'' to embassy personnel in Nairobi and Dar
es Salaam.
	   ``To the people of Kenya and Tanzania,'' she added, ``I will
bring a message of friendship, made deeper by our shared grief, and
of support in doing all we can to ease their suffering and help
them start anew.''
	   (cph/dc)
</TEXT>
