<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Insider Trading </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
German TV journalist is accused of insider trading
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ A German television journalist is
under investigation for allegedly telling his friends which stocks
he was going to recommend buying on his weekly program, a German
newsmagazine reported Monday.
	   Frankfurt prosecutors confirmed charges of insider trading were
being considered against 33-year-old Egbert Prior, who has been
heralded by investors as ``Germany's first international stock
market guru.''
	   Prior allegedly tipped off friends before his program's Friday
time slot, enabling them to purchase the stocks he recommended late
in the week and then profit by selling them the following Monday,
after his viewers followed the same advice.
	   Prior, a former newspaper editor who also puts out a financial
information service bearing his name, was unavailable for comment
Monday.
	   Job Tilmann, spokesman for the Frankfurt prosecutor's office,
confirmed they had joined an investigation begun by federal stock
market regulators months ago. The federal office refused to
comment.
