<SLUG> BC-Israel-Bike Bandit </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Israeli bank robbing legend to get early prison release
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ An Israeli businessman turned bank robber whose
motorcycle getaways were legendary in Israel during the late 1980s
will be released early for good behavior, the prison authority said
Monday.
	   Roni Liebowitz, nicknamed the ``Bikerbank,'' became a popular
cult figure after claiming that robbing banks was the only way to
maintain a decent lifestyle in Israel. Liebowitz, whose trademark
was firing one shot in the air before taking off on his bike, stole
over 300,000 shekels (then about dlrs 175,500) in 22 heists.
	   In 1990, he was sentenced to 20 years in prison but a parole
committee this week found Liebowitz to be a model prisoner and
recommended an early release, prison authority spokeswoman Orit
Messer-Harel said. She said Lebovitz would be paroled Sept. 2,
after having served half his sentence.
