<HEADLINE>
Yeltsin urges evacuation of Russians from Congo
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ President Boris Yeltsin on Monday urged an
evacuation of Russian citizens from Congo, where rebel fighters
have been closing in on the capital Kinshasa.
	   Yeltsin urged all Russian citizens, including those who are
permanent residents of Congo, to leave the country, and ordered
evacuation assistance to citizens of other former Soviet republics,
the Interfax news agency reported, citing the presidential press
service.
	   Yeltsin also ordered an evacuation of Russian embassy staff and
their families, the report said.
	   Hundreds of foreigners fled Congo over the weekend, amid fears
that President Laurent Kabila's government will not survive the
advance of a rebel coalition of ethnic Tutsi fighters, Rwandan
soldiers and disenchanted members of Kabila's military.
	   Many of the rebels had helped Kabila oust longtime dictator
Mobutu Sese Seko in May 1997, but now say they have been
marginalized by the government and accuse Kabila of corruption and
nepotism.
