<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Holocaust Memorial </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
German Jewish leader says Holocaust memorial could still be built
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BERLIN (AP) _ The head of Germany's Jewish community said Monday
that a national Holocaust Memorial could still be built in Berlin
even if the city government votes against the plans, as the mayor
wants.
	   Ignatz Bubis, chairman of the Central Council of Jews in
Germany, noted that private backers initiated the project and the
federal government has already donated a large plot in the heart of
the city.
	   Berlin's city government is to discuss the much-delayed project
on Aug. 25, and could vote on a design the same day, or put it off
again. Spokesman Eduard Heussen said there was no clear majority
either way.
	   Some support a reworked design by U.S. architect Peter Eisenman,
which Chancellor Helmut Kohl is also known to favor. But others _
like Mayor Eberhard Diepgen _ don't like any of the three
finalists.
	   Diepgen said in a newspaper interview Sunday that he found the
proposals too ``monumental'' and thought the chosen site was wrong
as well. He has said he does not want Berlin to become a ``city of
mourning,'' with one memorial after another.
	   Diepgen has only one vote and can not alone block the plan,
however.
	   Kohl has promised to announce a winner in the design competition
before national elections on Sept. 27, but his spokesman in Bonn
said Monday the chancellor would wait to see what the Berlin city
government decides.
	   Kohl's challenger for chancellor, Gerhard Schroeder of the
Social Democrats said in a TV interview this month that he would
call for a new national debate on the memorial if he's elected.
	   Schroeder's pick to be culture czar, Michael Naumann, caused a
stir this summer by saying he thought a monument was too grandiose
and the money might be better spent maintaining former
concentration camps, which carry more direct emotional impact.
 &UR; (pfg)
</TEXT>
