<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Syria,0394 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Israeli defense minister sets off debate on Golan withdrawal
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ The return of land on the Golan Heights depends
on the security measures Syria offers Israel in exchange, Israel's
defense minister says, touching off a debate within his government
on Monday over whether the strategic plateau was even negotiatable.
	   In an interview with the German magazine Focus published Monday,
Yitzhak Mordechai went beyond Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's
deliberately vague pronouncements on what the Syrians would receive
for peace.
	   ``The greatest interest of the Syrians is territory _ our
greatest interest is security,'' Focus quoted him as saying. ``It's
simple: the more security we receive, the more land we can give
back.''
	   Mordechai said he was in agreement with the late Yitzhak Rabin's
thinking on the issue.
	   Netanyahu had assailed Rabin's Golan policies in opposition, and
Mordechai's statements drew a storm of protest from Cabinet
ministers who said he was violating one of the government's basic
guidelines _ that the Golan is vital to Israel's security.
	   ``Peace with Syria, as we understand it, cannot be, because
Syria doesn't recognize the existence of Israel,'' said Agriculture
Minister Rafael Eitan, a retired general who fought in the Golan in
the 1973 Mideast War.
	   Netanyahu said Monday that the government's policy had not
changed, and Mordechai said he had been misquoted.
	   But in an interview on Israel Radio, Netanyahu's policy adviser
Uzi Arad linked the idea of a withdrawal with Israel's security
demands in the Golan.
	   Arad said such an equation was ``only logical,'' and said that
he had raised the possibility during a recent conference in Texas
attended by Syrian representatives.
	   Arad gave no specifics, however, about Israel's security
demands, and gave no indication that the current government would
be willing to meet Syria's demands for a withdrawal from all of the
Golan, which Israel captured in the 1967 Mideast War.
	   Rabin demanded security provisions that would allow it to
monitor Syria's compliance from the Golan Heights.
	   Israel's Maariv newspaper quoted unnamed political sources as
saying that Netanyahu supported Mordechai's statement, and that
several of the prime minister's advisers had used similar phrasing
recently. 	   
</TEXT>
