<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Russia Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Precede FRANKFURT
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Kohl expresses concern over ruble devaluation &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BONN, Germany (AP) _ Chancellor Helmut Kohl expressed concern
Monday over Russia's devaluation of the ruble, but said that any
negative impact could be mitigated through careful economic
policies.
	   His finance minister, Theo Waigel, warned that Russia's plan to
control the free flow of capital must not jeopardize the trend to
liberalize capital markets.
	   ``Under no circumstances must the fundamental liberalization of
capital movement be questioned,'' Waigel said in a news release.
``Russia would hurt itself the most.''
	   The decision to devaluate the troubled ruble had an immediate
impact on the German stock exchange, bringing down share prices in
some of Germany's largest commercial banks.
	   Commerzbank shares closed down 3.2 percent, and Dresdner Bank
shares slipped 2.8 percent. Deutsche Bank shares bucked the trend,
rising 1.4 percent.
	   The Dax stock index closed up 0.2 percent from Friday, at
5456.58 points.
	   German banks exposure to the Russian market totaled dlrs 30.4
billion at the end of 1997, according to the Bank for International
Settlements. Most of banks' outstanding credits, however, are
guaranteed by the German government.
	   A Finance Ministry spokeswoman said Russia's 90-day moratorium
on the payment of foreign credits could affect 500 million marks
(dlrs 280 million) in credits guaranteed by the German government.
	   German government credit guarantees to Russia totaled 84 billion
marks (dlrs 47 billion) at the end of 1997, the Finance Ministry
said in a statement.
	   Stock exchanges across Europe also dipped on the devaluation.
	   _The French stock market recouped by the end of the day after
falling early on following the news of the devaluation of the
ruble. Still, the CAC 40 index was down 11.10 points, or 0.3
percent to close at 3983.81 points.
	   The French market exhibited nervousness in part because of
German bank exposure in Russia.
	   _At the Helsinki Stock Exchange, companies that deal in
foodstuffs dropped 4 percent, and analysts predicted that chemical,
textile, clothing and electronics industries also would suffer if
the devaluation continues.
	   _Share prices on Milan's stock market fell sharply at first news
of the devaluation but ended the day up 335 points, or 1 percent.
Traders said Italian banks and companies have only limited exposure
in Russia, and expected the devaluation to have no major impact
here.
	   _The Athens Stock Exchange's general share prices index closed
at 2,539.35 points, down 42.08 points, or 1.6 percent from Friday's
close.
 &UR; (apdj/buros/cb-pfg)
</TEXT>
