<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Immigrants Stopped </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Turkish authorities detain 331 would-be immigrants
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BODRUM, Turkey (AP) _ Turkish authorities detained 331 would-be
immigrants as they prepared to board a ship for illegal passage to
Greece, paramilitary police said Monday.
	   The group, arrested Sunday night near the popular Aegean resort
of Bodrum, included 231 Turkish citizens, the semi-official
Anatolia news agency reported. The rest were 87 Iraqis, seven
Nigerians, four Moroccans and two Canadians, the news agency said.
	   Paramilitary police in Bodrum, 700 kilometers (440 miles)
southwest of Ankara, said the illegal immigrants were caught while
they were traveling on buses near the resort community, soon before
they were to get on the ship.
	   The nature of the involvement of the Canadians was not clear,
and the Canadian Embassy was unable to confirm their presence among
the detainees.
	   Illegal immigrants often try to go from Turkey into Greece, and
then on to northern Europe.
	   On the Turkish-Greek border, in Thrace, 41 would-be immigrants _
including Iraqi, Iranians, Pakistanis and Bangladeshis _ were
detained near the Meric River that separates the two countries,
Anatolia reported.
	   The river is known as Evros in Greek.
	   (ht-ek)
</TEXT>
