<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ukraine-Crimean Tatars </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Crimean Tatars adopting Ukrainian citizenship at slow pace
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) _ More than 7,000 Crimean Tatars who returned
to their homeland adopted Ukrainian citizenship this year, but many
more still lack it, Ukraine's senior immigration official said
Monday.
	   Some 81,000 Tatars holding citizenship of a different country
cannot become Ukrainian citizens because the country's legislation
bans double citizenship, said Nadiya Poyarkova, chief of the
immigration department of the Interior Ministry.
	   About 15,000 Tatars have no citizenship at all, she added,
according to the Interfax news agency.
	   Poyarkova said that many Tatars lack the required identification
documents or are unwilling to undertake registration procedures.
Some don't have enough money to pay the required fees.
	   Hundreds of Tatars clashed with Ukrainian police earlier this
year, during election-time rallies that demanded voting rights for
non-citizens and a representation quota in the regional parliament.
	   Some 260,000 Tatars have returned to their homeland on the
Crimean peninsula over the past decade. Soviet dictator Josef
Stalin exiled the Muslim people to Central Asia in 1944 for
allegedly helping the Nazi cause.
	   (vl/ji) 	   
</TEXT>
