<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0480 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Major Albanian stronghold falls to Serb police
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS and UPDATES with diplomats pushing to return to
negotiating; NATO exercises in Albania. TRIMS outdated
information. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos PRI102-106.
 &UR; By ISMET HAJDARI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Serb forces have driven rebel
Albanians from their last major strongholds in western Kosovo, and
diplomatic efforts turned Monday towards organizing talks on the
province's future.
	   According to the pro-Albanian Kosovo Information Center,
fighting subsided Monday following a weekend push when Serb forces
captured a series of key Albanian strongholds.
	   Yugoslavia's state-run Tanjug news agency said Monday Serb
police had ``crushed'' bases of the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army in
the villages of Lodja, Grabovac and Rausic, all on the outskirts of
the province's second city of Pec on Sunday.
	   The rebel Kosovo Liberation Army is fighting Serb security
forces for independence of Serbia's Kosovo province, where
Albanians account for 90 percent of the population of 2 million.
	   Monday's lull in the fighitng revivied hopes that negotiations
stalled since May might be revived. Fehmi Agani, the top ethnic
Albanian negotiator, wrote to his Serbian counterpart Ratko
Markovic, saying the Albanians wanted the talks to resume on the
condition that Serbs halt their offensive.
	   ``We expect violence will stop and units used against the
civilian population will be withdrawn,'' Agani said.
	   Agani did not mention a date, but said he hoped U.S. envoy
Christopher Hill would establish a time when talks could resume.
Hill traveled to Belgrade Monday, to meet with Serb leaders and
negotiators.
	   Over the past two weeks, government forces have succeeded in
driving the KLA from several key villages in western Kosovo.
Government gains have, however, proven difficult to maintain, as
the KLA simply returns to an area the moment police move on.
	   The attacks on villages have left tens of thousands of refugees
camped in the woods in western Kosovo.
	   The U.N. refugee agency based in Geneva said in a statement
Monday it rushed a convoy to Pec, where refugees who fled earlier
fighting reportedly came under attack and were forced south into
the mountains.
	   The U.N. now estimates that more than 231,000 people have been
uprooted in the six months since the conflict began. Many of them
have fled across the mountainous border with Albania, where the KLA
also maintains bases.
	   In the Albanian capital Tirana, troops from 14 nations gathered
Monday to conduct training for parachute supply drops, vehicle and
foot patrols, marksmanship and other non-offensive drills in the
Albanian mountains.
	   The United States and Europeans fear the fighting could spill
over into neighboring countries with large Albanian communities. 	   
</TEXT>
