<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Bosnia-War Crimes,0545 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Six Croats in dock for start of U.N. court's largest mass trial
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By MIKE CORDER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) _ Six Bosnian Croats accused of
taking part in a notorious 1993 massacre of more than 100 Muslims
went on trial Monday in the Yugoslav war crimes tribunal's largest
mass prosecution.
	   The defendants allegedly were among Bosnian Croat troops who
swarmed through the central Bosnian village of Ahmici on April 16,
1993, killing at least 103 Muslims including some 33 women and
children. Entire families were gunned down and their houses
torched.
	   One victim, shot and left to die in a burning house, was just
three months old, according to the tribunal indictment.
	   British soldiers who visited Ahmici on the day of the massacre
``saw some 20 bodies,'' tribunal prosecutor Frank Terrier said in
his opening statement.
	   ``Bodies of civilian people. Some were female bodies, some were
bodies of children. One woman was killed while she was still
holding the hand of her child,'' he said.
	   Locals claimed the operation, aimed at driving Muslims out of
the region, was codenamed ``48 Hours of Ashes,'' Terrier told
judges. He also played video footage of a British Broadcasting
Corp. news program in which British soldiers were shown recovering
charred bodies from the wreckage of houses in Ahmici.
	   The defendants _ brothers Zoran and Mirjan Kupreskic; their
cousin, Vlatko Kupreskic; and Vladimir Santic, Drago Josipovic and
Dragan Papic _ all sat calmly in court Monday, flanked by seven
United Nations guards.
	   In preliminary statements Monday, attorney Ranko Radovic,
defending Zoran Kupreskic, described the men as ``peasants ...
defending their homes.''
	   Vlatko Kupreskic was arrested Dec. 18 by Dutch and U.S. NATO
troops in the town of Vitez near Ahmici. The remaining five
defendants surrendered to the tribunal a year ago after pressure
from Croatian authorities who had been pushed by the United States
to get the suspects to the court.
	   All six are jointly accused of a crime against humanity for
persecuting the inhabitants of Ahmici. The defendants face an
additional 18 charges relating to specific allegations of murder
and inhumane treatment of the village's Muslim inhabitants.
	   They have all pleaded innocent to the charges, which carry a
maximum sentence of life imprisonment.
	   The trial is the sixth currently running at the U.N. court,
which was set up in 1993 to prosecute those responsible for
atrocities in the wars in the former Yugoslavia.
	   Although the case, expected to last months and hear evidence
from dozens of witnesses, is one of the tribunal's biggest, the
defendants were allegedly no more than rank-and-file soldiers in
the Croatian Defense Council militia.
	   The force's regional commander, Gen. Tihomir Blaskic, is also on
trial at the tribunal charged with planning and organizing a
systematic campaign of terror aimed at driving Muslims out of the
region surrounding Ahmici.
	   Just two war criminals have so far been convicted and sentenced
by the 11-judge court. Its two most-wanted suspects, former Bosnian
Serb leader Radovan Karadzic and his wartime military chief, Gen.
Ratko Mladic, remain at large. 	   
</TEXT>
