<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Lithuania-Hunting </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
No special hunting grounds for pols, Lithuanian president vows
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   VILNIUS, Lithuania (AP) _ The former U.S. official who now is
president of Lithuania said Monday that he wants to get rid of the
country's practice of having exclusive hunting grounds for
high-ranking officials.
	   President Valdas Adamkus said he couldn't justify tax money
being spent on the grounds, which he said hearkened back to the
Middle Ages when Lithuania was a monarchy, the Baltic News Service
reported.
	   ``How can we officials have exclusive rights to such
festivities, as if we were dukes in the Grand Duchy of Lithuania,''
he said. ``Officials with a passion for hunting can pay for the
sport as all mortals do.''
	   Adamkus was born in Lithuania, but fled as a young man during
the turmoil of World War II, in which Lithuania was occupied both
by the Nazis and the Soviet Union. He emigrated to the United
States, eventually becoming a top official in the Environmental
Prrotection Agency.
	   He returned to Lithuania last year and campaigned for the
presidency on a platform of greater openness and accountability in
government.
	   (mt-jh)
</TEXT>
