<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Lebanon-Israel,0238 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Israeli jets attack guerrilla bases in south Lebanon
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MARJAYOUN, Lebanon (AP) _ Israeli warplanes blasted suspected
guerrilla hideouts in southern Lebanon Monday, Lebanese security
officials said.
	   There was no immediate word on casualties from the 6.20 p.m.
(15:20 GMT) air raid, the second in south Lebanon in four days.
	   Two fighter jets fired two air-to-surface missiles on hills of
Sojod and Mazraat Iqmata in the Iqlim al-Tuffah province, a
Hezbollah stronghold that faces an Israeli-occupied border enclave
in south Lebanon, the officials said, speaking on customary
condition of anonymity.
	   Last Thursday, Israeli warplanes fired two missiles on Mazraat
Iqmata, an area in a no-man's land about 500 meters (yards) from an
Israeli military outpost in Sojod inside the occupied zone. There
were no casualties in that raid.
	   On Sunday, Israeli-allied militiamen killed a leftist Lebanese
guerrilla and captured another as the pair infiltrated the occupied
zone.
	   Iqlim al-Tuffah is a frequent target of Israeli warplanes.
	   The area is used by the Iranian-backed Hezbollah guerrilla group
as a base to launch attacks on Israeli troops and their allied
Lebanese militiamen in the occupied zone.
	   Hezbollah is leading a guerrilla war to oust about 1,500 Israeli
soldiers and 2,500 members of the Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army
militia from the occupied zone. 	   
</TEXT>
