</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Triple Transplant </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World's first triple transplant patient dies
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ The world's first triple transplant patient has
died 12 years after the operation that gave her a new heart, lungs
and liver.
	   Davina Thompson died Thursday at Papworth Hospital in Cambridge
from lung disease, hospital spokeswoman Kate Lancaster said Monday.
She was 47.
	   Mrs. Thompson's operation in 1986, to fight a progressive
illness, was generally considered a success, and led the way for
other triple transplants, Lancaster said.
	   ``She enjoyed good health for the majority of the time after she
had the operation,'' Lancaster said. ``It was just in the last
couple of months that her condition deteriorated.''
	   Mrs. Thompson's husband, Peter, released a statement through the
hospital thanking friends, family and hospital staff for their
support throughout the years.
	   Details on Mrs. Thompson's other surviving family members were
not available, nor were funeral plans.
	   (mb/eml)
</TEXT>
