<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-Tourism </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Disneyland tops Notre Dame as most popular tourist attraction
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Where do tourists flock when they come to Paris?
Notre Dame? The Eiffel Tower? The Arc de Triomphe?
	   Yes, but even more are going to Disneyland.
	   The theme park outside Paris knocked Notre Dame out of first
place in the hearts of visitors to the capital last year, French
tourism officials said Monday.
	   Last year, Disneyland Paris drew 12.6 million visitors compared
to 12 million who visited Notre Dame, the Paris Regional Office of
Tourism said.
	   The theme park endured a shaky start six years ago.
	   But now, the make-believe world of Disney apparently has become
more compelling than France's real castles and cathedrals.
	   On a busy day, a wait at rides like Space Mountain and Big
Thunder Mountain can stretch to two hours _ even longer than the
wait to get to the top of the Eiffel Tower, now in third place with
5.7 million tourists last year.
	   The Louvre Museum and the Georges Pompidou Center followed with
5.1 and 4.4 million people respectively.
	   Paris also boasts a new tourist attraction: the Stade de France.
The gleaming national sports stadium where the French won the World
Cup in July has attracted 18,000 paying visitors, mostly French,
since it opened to the public Aug. 1.
	   A ticket costs 35 francs (dlrs 6), but most visitors opt for the
90-franc-ticket (dlrs 15) that gets them into the locker rooms.
	   (ma-dgs-jn) 	   
</TEXT>
