w1962 &Cx1f; wstm-
i r &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Britain-Leeson     08-17 0237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Leeson </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rogue trader Nick Leeson has 70 percent survival chance
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Imprisoned securities trader Nick Leeson, who had
a cancerous tumor removed from his colon last week, has been given
a 70 percent chance of surviving for another five years, his
London-based lawyer said Monday.
	   Leeson, 31, was diagnosed with cancer Aug. 5 after serving more
than 2 1/2 years of a 6 1/2 year prison sentence in Singapore. He
was convicted of fraud and forgery that led to the 1995 collapse of
Barings Bank, Britain's oldest merchant bank.
	   Initial reports said the cancer had spread to his lymph nodes,
but lawyer Stephen Pollard said surgeons now believe that is not
the case.
	   ``The surgeon believes that the cancer has, happily, not spread
to the lymph nodes. No chemotherapy will therefore be necessary,''
Pollard said.
	   He faces a 30 percent chance of the cancer recurring within the
next two years, Pollard said.
	   ``This prognosis is not as good as we had hoped, nor as bad as
we had feared,'' the lawyer said.
	   Leeson, who is recovering in the prison ward of the New Changi
Hospital, has applied for early release from the Singapore prison.
	   Constitutionally, pleas for early release on compassionate
grounds are decided by President Ong Teng Cheong. Ong himself is
suffering from a recurrence of lymphoma, a cancer of the lymphatic
system.
	   (mb/eml)
</TEXT>
