<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Bosnich-Police </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bosnich's xxxx
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LIVERPOOL, England (AP) _ Aston Villa's Australian goalkeeper
Mark Bosnich could face disciplinary action after an off-duty
policeman reported him for swearing at spectators during his team's
Premier League opener against Everton on Saturday.
	   Merseyside police confirmed Monday that soccer taskforce police
were investigating two complaints from fans against Bosnich after
the 0-0 draw at Goodison Park.
	   A police spokesman said it was unlikely Bosnich would be charged
but the incident would be reported to the Football Association.
	   One of the fans who complained was 49-year-old Tony Williamson,
who was at the match with his 11-year-old son. ``Bosnich should
know better. It was offensive and insulting behavior,'' he said.
``It was unacceptable and an awful impression to give to
children.''
	   Bosnich received a stern warning from the FA two years ago after
he made a Nazi-style salute during a match against Tottenham.
Bosnich later apologized.
	   (jp)
</TEXT>
