w1970 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Poland-FloodInvestiga     08-17 0212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Poland-Flood Investigation </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Poland's auditing chamber alleges mismanagement in last year's
</HEADLINE>
flood rescue &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   WARSAW, Poland (AP) _ Government auditors have concluded that
the reaction to last year's deadly floods was seriously hampered by
mismanagement, and have asked state prosecutors to open a criminal
investigation, the Polish news agency PAP reported Monday.
	   Auditors said the flood committee in the southern city of
Wroclaw issued a flood warning too late and had failed to circulate
updated evacuation plans. In one example, a municipality evacuated
620 cows and pigs to a farm that was later flooded because it never
received updated evacuation plans changing the site.
	   The former Wroclaw governor, Janusz Zaleski, and Wroclaw Mayor
Bogdan Zdrojewski, who headed the city and provincial flood
committees, denied any wrongdoing.
	   Auditors also asked investigators to look into flood committees
in Wlabrzych and Klodzko.
	   Officials convicted of neglecting their duties and causing
damages to public good face up to five years in prison.
	   The Wroclaw area was one of the worst hit by last July's floods
which killed 55 people, swamped 46,000 homes and caused an
estimated 12 billion zlotys (dlrs 3.4 billion) in damage.
	   (bp-cb) 	   
</TEXT>
