<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Iraq,0501 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Security Council meets to consider Iraq response
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By NICOLE WINFIELD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Responding to the latest confrontation
with Iraq, Security Council members considered Monday a
Japanese-drafted letter affirming the work of U.N. weapons
inspectors who have been banned from searching for evidence of
banned weapons.
	   With the low-key response, the council was trying to force Iraq
to make the next major move after its Aug. 5 decision to freeze
cooperation with U.N. weapons experts, diplomats said.
	   Weapons inspectors must certify that Baghdad has dismantled its
chemical, biological and nuclear weapons programs, and its
long-range missiles, before the Security Council will lift
sanctions imposed after Saddam Hussein invaded Kuwait in 1990,
sparking the Gulf War.
	   The letter under consideration could give inspectors the
go-ahead to try to launch an inspection, which would test the Iraqi
resolve in enforcing its freeze, the diplomats said, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
	   Before adopting the draft, the council was to be briefed on
recent meetings between U.N. envoy Prakash Shah and Iraqi Deputy
Prime Minister Tariq Aziz, said U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard.
	   Shah told reporters Thursday, after his first meeting with Aziz,
that he urged Baghdad change its mind and agree to cooperate with
arms monitors in their ongoing inspections.
	   Iraq froze cooperation with the United Nations after the chief
U.N. weapons inspector, Richard Butler, refused to certify that
Baghdad had destroyed its weapons of mass destruction.
	   Despite the stalemate, Secretary-General Kofi Annan does not
plan to get personally involved as he did last February, when the
United States and Britain threatened to bomb Iraq if it didn't
allow inspectors access into certain presidential sites, Eckhard
said.
	   Annan brokered an accord that allowed inspectors access but ``he
personally does not foresee any role for himself at this time,''
Eckhard said.
	   The difference this time is that there is no threat of war, he
said.
	   Shah has kept Annan up to date with his progress in Baghdad and
has sent a report of his activities in Iraq to New York, U.N.
officials said. Rolf Knutsson, director of the U.N. office of
political affairs, was relaying Shah's report to the council
Monday.
	   Shah himself was expected to return to New York on Thursday,
Eckhard said.
	   The Japanese-drafted letter is to be sent to Butler and the head
of the International Atomic Energy Agency, Mohammed ElBaradei, who
both reported last week that their work was being undermined by
Baghdad's decision.
	   Not only new inspections but ongoing monitoring of suspected
weapons sites was being affected, the inspectors told the council.
	   The council's letter would reaffirm the work of inspectors,
acknowledge that their mandate was being undermined and say that
Baghdad's decision was unacceptable, the diplomats said.
</TEXT>
