<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Nuclear </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russia to test new container for storing nuclear waste
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russia will test a new container for storing spent
nuclear fuel on Tuesday, as it tries to improve the security of its
nuclear waste storage.
	   The metal-and-concrete container can be used to store up to 5
tons of nuclear waste for about 50 years, senior Atomic Energy
Ministry official Nina Yanovskaya said Monday, according to the
Interfax news agency.
	   The container will be tested at the Mednoye Ozero lake-side base
near St. Petersburg, she said.
	   Russia's methods of storing nuclear waste have been under
international scrutiny, especially since a retired naval officer
spoke out two years ago against the dangers posed by the careless
handling of the waste.
	   Capt. Alexander Nikitin has been charged with treason for his
aid to a Norwegian environmental group, the Bellona Foundation, in
compiling the report that focused on the potential hazards caused
by improper storage of radioactive waste by Russia's Northern
Fleet.
	   The United States and Norway helped finance development of the
new storage container, Yanovskaya said.
	   (ad/ji) 	   
</TEXT>
