<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-Pebble Beach, 1st Ld,0257 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tournament to conclude six months after start
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Love taking lead &QL; 
 &UR; By ROB GLOSTER &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. (AP) _ Six months after they were driven
off the course by torrential rain and strong winds, golfers on
Monday resumed the AT and T Pebble Beach National Pro-Am on a dry,
overcast morning.
	   Davis Love III, who tied for seventh in the PGA Championship
that ended Sunday, made an eagle on his third hole today to
temporarily take over the lead as the long-delayed tourney
concluded with its final round.
	   Love, starting at the 10th hole on the Poppy Hills course, moved
to 11-under with his eagle on the 531-yard, par-5 12th hole. He had
started his round with a birdie.
	   Fellow Americans Tom Watson and Tim Herron started the day tied
for the lead, but both slipped to 9-under with early bogeys.
	   Watson won the Pebble Beach tournament in 1977 and 1978. If he
wins this year, the two-decade separation between victories would
be a tourney record. Herron was last among the players who
completed all four rounds of the PGA Championship this past
weekend.
	   When the AT and T tournament began in late January, waves from
the Pacific Ocean were crashing onto the 18th fairway. Sheet-like
rain was turning sandtraps into water hazards and gusty winds were
snapping treetops.
	   Today, months after the demise of El Nino, the tourney resumed
on a dry morning on the Pebble Beach, Poppy Hills and Spyglass Hill
courses.
