<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Auto Strike,0231 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Auto workers accept settlement in South African strike
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) _ Automobile manufacturers
conceded some wage demands to striking auto workers, settling a
6-day work stoppage on Monday.
	   The National Union of Metalworkers of South Africa claimed a
victory for the second and third year of the wage agreement that
provides pay hikes above the cost-of-living increase.
	   Both sides had agreed to an 8 percent pay raise for the first
year, but manufacturers objected to the other demands.
	   The 21,000 auto workers will receive a 5 percent hike if
inflation is 3.9 percent or lower; and 7 percent if inflation
exceeds 5 percent, the union said.
	   ``Demanding better sustainable wages in the industry will result
in the lowering of poverty and increased purchasing power in the
poorer communities,'' the union said in a statement.
	   The settlement was proposed by mediators Friday and approved by
the rank- and-file on Monday.
	   Automobile Manufacturers Employers Organization chairman Brian
Smith said the agreement would help provide stability and
predictability in employment costs for the next three years.
	   NUMSA spokesman Tony Kgobe said workers lost about 4.2 million
rand (dlrs 666,000) in wages.
	   South African inflation has been more than 6 percent over the
past year.
</TEXT>
