w1989 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EmbassyBombings-Disas     08-17 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Embassy Bombings-Disaster Fund </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kenyans to ask Albright about aid; doubts raised about disaster
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; RETRANSMITTING to conform to digest &QL; 
fund &QL; 
 &UR; With BC-Embassy Bombings &QL; 
 &UR; By SUSAN LINNEE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) _ Kenyan officials are expected to raise the
issue of victim compensation and aid for reconstruction when
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright meets them Tuesday to discuss
the bombing of the U.S. embassy.
	   But despite some claims that the Aug. 7 blast resulted in at
least 30 billion shillings (dlrs 500 million) in material and
commerical losses, no detailed estimate of damages has been drawn
up.
	   After the bombing in which 247 people, 12 of them Americans,
died, President Daniel arap Moi set up yet another disaster fund
managed and controlled by his office.
	   There is concern that this fund will turn out to be too much
like previous ones that collected money for other disasters, then
disappeared.
	   ``There is a track record on these disaster funds ... It is such
that it does not give confidence that this money is actually going
to where it is intended and that the operation is accountable,''
said Robert Shaw of the private Institute for Economic Affairs.
	   Chris Kirubi, an influential businessman and head of the Kenya
Manufacturers Association who has close ties with Moi's ruling
Kenya African National Union Party, is spearheading efforts to
establish a private sector fund ``that will work, that will have
accountability.''
	   ``We're doing the donkey work of setting up. We're trying to get
people to be on the board, to represent different interests,''
Kirubi said. ``We are interested even to join hands with the
government _ as long as their conditions meet our conditions.''
	   Joshua Matui, a senior official in Moi's office who is
coordinating the Bomb Blast fund, said he didn't know how much
money had been received into the bank account set up at the
state-owned National Bank of Kenya.
	   But he said although ``the modalities are still being worked out
... already we have started spending the money.''
	   Erastus Mwongera, another senior civil servant, said the Bomb
Blast fund had handed over 12 million shillings (dlrs 200,000) to
its funeral committee to pay for funeral and burial expenses and
had so far assisted in the burials of 125 of the 235 non-American
victims.
	   Following the 1994 sinking of a ferry boat in Mombasa in which
at least 300 people drowned, Moi's office set up a disaster fund.
Another was set up for street children, another for families whose
daughters died in a school fire in March, another for youth and
another for the disabled.
	   To date, there has been no public accounting for how the funds _
many of them ostentatious donations from government officials _
were spent.
	   Shaw pointed out that the bombing, however devastating and
shocking, was far from the worst disaster to strike Kenya this
year.
	   The El Nino weather phenomenon earlier in the year caused
widespread flooding and devastation in remote, underdeveloped
northeastern Kenya where more than 1,000 people died in the floods
or from the waterborne diseases that followed.
	   No fund was set up for victims there.
	   There is a strong tradition among the different peoples of Kenya
to pitch in and help members of their communities in times of need.
	   Called ``harambee'' _ the Swahili word for ``all pull
together,'' the practice is still very much in use. But all
participants know where the money is going _ and also how much
everyone else contributed.
	   (sl/dc)
</TEXT>
