<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Northern Ireland, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Northern Ireland calls off soccer international after Omagh bomb
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS quotes from manger and IFA official &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BELFAST, Ireland (AP) _ Wednesday's scheduled international
soccer friendly between Northern Ireland and Malta in Belfast was
called off Monday in the wake of the bombing in Omagh.
	   The Irish Football Association announced the move after
consulting with the government and the Malta Football Association.
	   ``We thought how can we have a friendly game of football after
this?'' Northern Ireland manager Lawrie McMenemy said. ``Nothing is
important after this, particularly a game of football.''
	   An under-21 international between the two countries scheduled
for Tuesday was also canceled as a mark of respect to the victims
of the bombing.
	   A car bomb killed 28 people and injured more than 220 when it
exploded in the Northern Ireland town of Omagh, 70 miles west of
Belfast, on Saturday.
	   It was the worst single terrorist attack in 30 years of conflict
in the province.
	   McMenemy said soccer was the last thing on his players' minds
after the bombing.
	   ``My stance normally is that football brings people together to
forget their problems, but this is so monumental that there is no
normality about anything this week,'' McMenemy said Monday.
	   IFA president Jim Boyce said his organization had never called a
game off because of a tragedy but on this occasion it would have
been wrong to go ahead.
	   ``To have people coming along to a game, where they are supposed
to enjoy themselves, while some of the funerals of the victims were
taking place would have been highly inappropriate,'' he said.
	   The Malta game was to be Northern Ireland's final warm-up match
before its opening European Championship qualifying match against
Turkey on Sept. 5.
	   (jp)
</TEXT>
