<SLUG> BC-UN-Tajikistan,0357 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UN chief says Tajik security situation limiting UN role
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By NICOLE WINFIELD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Secretary-General Kofi Annan condemned the
July 20 slayings of four U.N. workers in Tajikistan and urged both
sides Monday to implement their 1997 peace accord.
	   Annan's comments, in a report to the Security Council, came as
Tajik and opposition officials said the government had identified
four suspects and was negotiating with the opposition for their
arrest.
	   The victims, who worked for the U.N. Mission of Observers in
Tajikistan, were ambushed while on patrol in the mountains about 90
miles (140 kilometers) east of the capital Dushanbe. All were shot
in the head.
	   ``I cannot find words strong enough to condemn the murder of the
four members of UNMOT, who were on a mission of peace and were
unarmed,'' Annan wrote.
	   In his report, Annan said that the deaths, and a crisis sparked
by the government's decision to ban religious-based political
parties, ``highlight the continuing precariousness of the peace
process.''
	   The government subsequently revoked the provision.
	   ``I hope that the Tajik parties will muster the will and
determination to implement in good faith and at a steady pace the
general peace agreement they signed more than one year ago,'' Annan
wrote.
	   Tajikistan, which suffered through a five-year civil war and
borders Afghanistan, is one of several countries in Central Asia
that fears the growth of Islamic political movements.
	   The United Tajik Opposition protested the bill, since its
largest member, the Islamic Revival Party, would presumably have
been banned.
	   Annan also protested the proposed legislation, saying it could
undermine the 1997 peace accord between the government and the
largely Muslim opposition.
	   Sporadic clashes have also undermined the accord and the
security situation continues to impede U.N. operations, Annan
wrote. A special detachment for U.N. security, comprised of
government and opposition troops, has been formed but is still not
operational, he noted.
</TEXT>
