w2015 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Congo-Rebels     08-17 0539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Congo-Rebels </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Congolese rebels secure eastern borders; warn civilians in their
</HEADLINE>
movement &QL; 
 &UR; With BC-Congo
 &UR; By HRVOJE HRANJSKI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BUNIA, Congo (AP) _ Congolese rebels fighting to oust President
Laurent Kabila on Monday consolidated their gains in the east and
warned the political leaders in their movement not to repeat the
mistakes of the embattled Congolese head of state.
	   ``I told them I will personally shoot them one by one if they
steal money and isolate themselves from the people,'' said rebel
chief Jean-Pierre Ondekane. ``Then, there will be a third
revolution.''
	   On Monday, Ondekande flew from his eastern stronghold at Goma
360 kilometers (225 miles) north to Bunia, a hot and dusty trading
town on the border with Uganda.
	   Bunia fell to the rebels last week without a fight, local
commander Bob Ngoy told several reporters who accompanied Ondekane.
He said troops loyal to Kabila scattered, leaving their weapons
behind.
	   Thousands of residents who gathered to listen to Ondekane's pep
talk _ it was his first appearance in Bunia _ showed little
enthusiasm.
	   The 36-year-old career military officer, who served in the
forces of longtime dictator Mobutu Sese Seko before going over to
Kabila's rebels nearly two years ago, spoke for two hours, and then
took questions from the curious crowd.
	   Asked whether he, like Kabila, would declare himself president
after a rebel victory, he replied in Swahili, the lingua franca of
eastern Congo:
	   ``I am not a politician, I am a soldier. What will happen next
to this country depends on who are you going to choose as your
leaders.''
	   Some in the crowd were openly skeptical.
	   ``I don't understand what this is all about. It's the army, not
people, doing it,'' one man said.
	   Ondekane's warning to the politicians in the rebellion, who on
Sunday formed the Congolese Democratic Coalition _ a kind of
government-in-waiting complete with eight cabinet posts _ was
further evidence that the two-week-old rebellion is spearheaded by
the military.
	   Like Ondekane, the others in the 60,000-strong rebel force
reportedly closing in on the capital, Kinshasa, are also
disgruntled officers and soldiers who served under Mobutu and
intially supported Kabila's rebellion. But as Kabila consolidated
his power, they felt increasingly marginalized _ and were not paid.
	   Kabila claims Rwanda and Uganda are supporting the rebels with
equipment and troops, a charge Ondekane denies.
	   But Ali Agume, a trader from Arua across the border in Uganda,
said he had seen Ugandan troops and tanks alongside the rebels in
Bunia.
	   Ondekane said the rebels were approaching Mbanza-Ngungu, 120
kilometers (75 miles) southwest of Kinshasa.
	   They already control Muanda and Kitona air base near the
Atlantic Coast, and Congo's only ocean-going port, Matadi, on the
Congo River, as well as the Inga power plant that supplies
electricity to the capital, southern Congo and northern Zambia.
	   When Kabila began his rebellion in October 1996 that eventually
ousted Mobutu eight months later, it took his forces three months
to capture the territory the current crop of rebels holds after two
weeks.
	   (hh/sl)	   
</TEXT>
