r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Ukraine-Currency     08-17 0378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ukraine-Currency </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ukraine's currency falls sharply on news of Russian ruble plunge
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By VIKTOR LUHOVYK &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) _ Ukraine's hryvna currency fell sharply on
Monday in response to a decision by the government of neighboring
Russia to let the ruble drop dramatically.
	   The hryvna fell to 2.1805 to the U.S. dollar at Ukraine's main
Interbank Currency Exchange, down from 2.1435 to the dollar on
Friday.
	   The trading was conducted late in the evening following an early
morning ban by the Central Bank on selling or buying rubles and
dollars at the exchange.
	   The ban was sparked by an announcement from the Russian Central
Bank that it would permit the value of the ruble to fall about 34
percent _ from about 6.3 to the dollar to 9.5 to the dollar.
	   The trading at the exchange was suspended early in the morning
when the ruble started to fall sharply after its supply topped 8
million rubles, with demand practically absent.
	   After hours of suspense, the National Bank postponed trading in
rubles until Tuesday and allowed trade in dollars.
	   The hryvna's sharp fall came amid wide speculation that the
Russian government's decision to devalue the ruble would
immediately exert negative pressure on the Ukrainian currency by
increasing foreign investors' mistrust in the country's financial
markets, which are considered highly dependent on those of Russia.
	   President Leonid Kuchma ordered Prime Minister Valery
Pustovoitenko and central bank chief Viktor Yushchenko to take
unspecified measures to maintain the stability of the country's
financial system and prevent the hryvna from falling.
	   No concrete measures were immediately announced.
	   The hryvna has been falling steadily this year under strong
pressure from foreign investors who were withdrawing their money
from the country.
	   Efforts by the National Bank to defend the currency resulted in
a sharp fall in its reserves from dlrs 2.34 billion at the
beginning of the year to dlrs 1.15 as of last week.
	   The hryvna sank to 2.14 to the U.S. dollar last week, but still
remains in the currency fluctuation band of 1.8 to 2.25 to the
dollar, which was announced by the government for 1998.
	   (vl/ji)
</TEXT>
