w2019 &Cx1f; wstm-
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Germany-RussiaEconomy 3rdLd-Writethru   08-17 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Russia Economy, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kohl expresses concern over ruble devaluation; stock markets
</HEADLINE>
nervous &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: SUBS 10th graf, `Total German ...' to CORRECT 84 billion
figure is for all former Soviet countries, not just Russia &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BONN, Germany (AP) _ Chancellor Helmut Kohl expressed concern
Monday over Russia's devaluation of the ruble, but said that any
negative impact could be mitigated through careful economic
policies.
	   Stock markets in countries like Germany with big stakes in the
Russian economy dipped on the news from Moscow, although the German
Dax stock index recovered, closing up 0.2 percent from Friday at
5456.58 points.
	   Share prices in some of Germany's biggest banks slipped,
however, making traders in neighboring countries like France and
Holland nervous as well.
	   German Finance Minister Theo Waigel warned that Russia's plan to
control capital flows must not jeopardize the trend toward open
capital markets.
	   ``Under no circumstances must the fundamental liberalization of
capital movement be questioned,'' Waigel said in a news release.
``Russia would hurt itself the most.''
	   Commercial bank stocks in Germany reacted immediately to the
devaluation. Their exposure to the Russian market totaled dlrs 30.4
billion at the end of 1997, according to the Bank for International
Settlements.
	   Commerzbank shares closed down 3.2 percent, and Dresdner Bank
shares slipped 2.8 percent. Deutsche Bank shares bucked the trend,
rising 1.4 percent.
	   Most of banks' outstanding credits, however, are guaranteed by
the German government.
	   A Finance Ministry spokeswoman said Russia's 90-day moratorium
on the payment of foreign credits could affect 500 million marks
(dlrs 280 million) in credits guaranteed by the German government.
	   Total German government credit guarantees to Russia and other
parts of the former Soviet Union totaled 84 billion marks (dlrs 47
billion) at the end of 1997, the Finance Ministry said.
	   Elsewhere in Europe:
	   _The French market exhibited nervousness in part because of
German bank exposure in Russia. The CAC 40 index was down 11.10
points, or 0.3 percent to close at 3983.81 points.
	   _Prices on the Amsterdam Stock Exchange finished mostly lower,
with the AEX Index down 11.73 points, or 1 percent, as traders
reacted to the developments in Russia. Shares in major Dutch
companies were hit, including Unilever, which closed down 3.3
percent.
	   _The Stockholm bourse swung down after the news, but recovered
most of the drop during the day and ended with the general index
down only 0.2 percent.
	   _The Baltics took it a bit harder, reflecting that Russia is the
single largest market for each of these countries. The Tallinn
exchange was down 2.93 percent, Riga down 3.88 and Vilnius down
2.81.
	   _At the Helsinki Stock Exchange, companies that deal in
foodstuffs dropped 4 percent, and analysts predicted that chemical,
textile, clothing and electronics industries also would suffer if
the devaluation continues.
	   _Share prices on Milan's stock market fell sharply at first news
of the devaluation but ended the day up 335 points, or 1 percent.
Traders said Italian banks and companies have only limited exposure
in Russia, and expected the devaluation to have no major impact.
	   Some traders interpreted a slight increase in Fiat shares as a
result of the devaluation. The automaker is planning investments in
Russia, and the devaluation could make that cheaper.
	   _The Athens Stock Exchange's general share prices index closed
at 2,539.35 points, down 42.08 points, or 1.6 percent from Friday's
close.
 &UR; (apdj/buros/cb-pfg)
</TEXT>
