<SLUG> BC-Northern Ireland, 5th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sinn Fein dissident's son arrested over Omagh atrocity
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-NIreland-One Family
 &UR; Eds: NEW throughout for AMs
 &UR; By SHAWN POGATCHNIK &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) _ Police arrested the son of a
leading Sinn Fein critic Monday on suspicion he helped commit
Northern Ireland's worst-ever terrorist attack, a car bomb in a
small town that killed 28 people from all sides of society.
	   Police took Shane Mackey, 19, and four other people at dawn from
their homes near Omagh, scene of Saturday's blast, 70 miles (110
kms) east to Belfast. Under British anti-terrorist law they can be
interrogated for up to a week before being released or charged.
	   Dubbed the ``Real IRA,'' the defectors and their novice recruits
have been blamed for planting car bombs in several Northern Ireland
towns this year, but never before with such horribly lethal effect.
They oppose the IRA ceasefire, and the support of its political
ally, Sinn Fein, for the Northern Ireland peace accord.
	   At Stormont, the British government's headquarters in Northern
Ireland, police and military chiefs from both parts of Ireland
plotted how to rout Irish Republican Army dissidents.
	   Mo Mowlam, Britain's minister responsible for governing Northern
Ireland, and the Irish Republic's justice minister, John
O'Donoghue, also attended the four-hour security conference at
Stormont in east Belfast.
	   Afterward Mowlam announced increased army and police deployments
along the border between the two states, but said she wouldn't
reveal other details, ``because it would be stupid.''
	   When asked whether both governments were discussing whether to
change their laws so that Real IRA suspects could be convicted
based only on testimony from anti-terrorist detectives, she said:
``You're in the right ballpark.''
	   Convicting even high-profile militants of belonging to one of
Northern Ireland's many outlawed paramilitary groups has usually
been impossible to prove.
	   In Omagh, the young suspect's father, local councilman Francis
Mackey, emphasized that the attack was a ``terrible tragedy'' _ but
steadfastly refused to condemn the bombers.
	   He said his son had been arrested as part of a British
conspiracy ``to demonize me for being honest and open in expression
of my political opinions.''
	   Mackey, re-elected by the area's militant Catholics last year
while still a member of Sinn Fein, resigned after party leaders
formally accepted April's compromise Belfast agreement on how
Northern Ireland should be governed.
	   He now aligns himself with an anti-agreement group called the 32
County Sovereignty Committee led by Bernadette Sands-McKevitt, wife
of the martyred IRA hunger striker Bobby Sands _ and common-law
wife of the Real IRA's reputed commander.
	   Like his diehard colleagues, Mackey opposes the agreement's
acknowledgement that Northern Ireland's six counties should
continue to exist as a Protestant-majority state linked with
Britain so long as most citizens here want that.
	   He has previously said that the IRA cease-fire of July 1997 was
misguided, but refused to discuss this Monday.
	   ``No amount of words from me will in any way alleviate the
suffering of the bereaved and the injured,'' Mackey said.
	   And the full horror of Omagh began to sink in Monday as police
confirmed the identities of all but one of the dead, among them two
baby girls aged 18 and 20 months old.
	   Of 220 wounded, 108 remained in hospitals across Northern
Ireland, 11 in critical condition. Many others were crippled or
blinded.
	   Unlike most attacks in Northern Ireland, the dead came from both
sides of the religious divide and from every political allegience.
They included Sinn Fein supporters as well as moderate Catholics, a
Protestant activist of the Ulster Unionist Party, and a niece of
Omagh's most hard-line Protestant politician.
	   ``This is not a crime against any particular section of our
people, Protestant or Roman Catholic,'' said the Democratic
Unionist politician, Oliver Gibson, whose niece Esther perished
with the rest.
	   ``This was a bid to destroy an entire community,'' he said,
noting that he knew most victims by first name.
	   For the first time in the three-decade course of Northern
Ireland's conflict, foreign tourists were among the dead _ a
teacher and 12-year-old student from Spain.
	   Spain's deputy prime minister, Francisco Alvarez Cascos, toured
Omagh with relatives of the dead and 11 wounded Madrid students,
including two girls hospitalized in Belfast's Royal Victoria
Hospital with critical head injuries.
	   ``There is good and evil everywhere,'' said Helguero Peuch,
mother of one of the most seriously injured Spanish girls,
9-year-old Beatrez.
	   Two days on, Saturday's horrors are coming back to haunt
survivors and rescuers alike.
	   A Catholic bus driver, Mickey McAnally, described his nightmare
journey to the hospital with a cargo of screaming wounded and
severed body parts. He marshaled walking wounded into his bus, then
carried a few with missing or maimed arms and legs.
	   ``You could feel the warmth of their blood coming through your
clothes,'' he said, noting he had to coax onto the bus two Spanish
girls bleeding ``head to toe,'' who didn't want to go without a
missing friend.
	   A Protestant father, Michael Gallagher, recalled in a wrenching
interview with BBC television his overnight wait to learn whether
his missing 21-year-old son, Adrian, had survived.
	   Gallagher _ whose brother was shot dead by the IRA in 1984 _
said he'd already concluded Adrian was dead when the social workers
and police escorted him to visit Omagh's makeshift morgue.
	   At the entrance, he said, his fists clenched and his voice
falling to a desperate whisper, ``I really wanted to run ... to get
out and run away.''
	   (sp/eml)
</TEXT>
