<SLUG> BC-Rwanda-Genocide Trial </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rwandan police chief pleads innocent to genocide
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ARUSHA, Tanzania (AP) _ A former Rwandan military police officer
pleaded innocent Monday to crimes of genocide in his initial
appearance before the International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda,
the tribunal said.
	   Alphonse Nteziryayo has been jointly charged with Sylvain
Nsabimana with crimes associated with the 1994 genocide in Rwanda
in which at least half a million people, most of them minority
Tutsis, were slaughtered. Nsabimana also has pleaded innocent.
	   Nteziryayo, who was arrested April 24 in Ouagadougou, Burkina
Faso, entered his innocent plea to all six charges against him in a
trial chamber composed of Presiding Judge Laity Kama and Judges
Yakov Ostrovsky and Navanethem Pillay. Counsel Titinga Frederic
Pacere from Burkina Faso is defending him, the tribunal said.
	   The tribunal is holding 31 genocide suspects in this northern
Tanzania town.
	   Nteziryayo succeeded Nsabimana as police chief in Butare, the
major town in southern Rwanda, in June 1994 and is alleged to have
ordered and participated in the killing of all the Tutsis who had
survived earlier killings.
	   The slaughter began April 6 after President Juvenal Habyarimana,
a Hutu, died when his plane was shot down on approaching to land in
the Rwandan capital, Kigali.
	   Nteziryayo is also alleged to have supervised the training of a
militia, distributed weapons and publicly called for the killing of
all Tutsis.
	   The tribunal has indicted 35 people for their role in the
state-orchestrated genocide.
	   A Tutsi-led rebel force ousted the Hutu extremist government and
ended the killings in July 1994.
	   (dc/sl)	   
</TEXT>
