<SLUG> BC-NIreland-One Family </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
One bomb, one moment: Three generations of a family die in
</HEADLINE>
carbombing &QL; 
 &UR; With BC-Northern Ireland &QL; 
 &UR; By KRISTIN GAZLAY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   AUGHER, Northern Ireland (AP) _ One minute, they were shopping
on a Saturday afternoon. The next minute, three generations of a
family were gone.
	   Townspeople say it was family that mattered most to 30-year-old
Avril Monaghan, pregnant with twins, and it was family she died
with in the Omagh carbombing _ her 18-month-old daughter Maura and
her 65-year-old mother, Mary Grimes.
	   ``The family have strong faith,'' said the Rev. Lawrence Dawson,
the Catholic parish priest who will preside Tuesday over the
funerals of Avril and her daughter. ``It's the only way you can
cope with this kind of problem.''
	   Mrs. Monaghan lived in the rolling green hills above Augher with
her husband, Michael. He makes his living as a carpenter; she found
work as a secretary. But, mostly, she was a mother, raising a son
and three daughters, the oldest 6 years old.
	   A widely published picture shows Mrs. Monaghan grinning at her
groom on her wedding day, a crown of flowers resting on her dark
hair.
	   Dawson said Mrs. Monaghan, who attended Mass with her children
the last morning of her life, was a stalwart contributor to the
church, helping organize functions at the parish school and putting
together quizzes for the students.
	   It is almost impossible for the 700 souls of Augher and nearby
Clogher, where the family sometimes attended church, to accept the
triple blow the Monaghan and Grimes clans have suffered, he said.
	   That pain stretches the 20 miles (32 kms) north to Beragh, where
Mrs. Grimes _ who had 10 other children _ lived with her husband
Mick, a dairy farmer.
	   Mrs. Grimes will be buried, probably Wednesday, in Beragh, and
the two Monaghans in the cemetery ringing St. Macartan's Catholic
Church, perched high on a hill not far from the house Michael
Monaghan had built for them.
	   The running of that house has been taken over by the Monaghans'
neighbors, who are providing a steady stream of food and other
practical support, which ``leaves the family just to grieve,''
Dawson said.
	   Michael Monaghan was doing about as well as could be expected
for a man who lost his wife and his youngest child, the priest
said.
	   One resident in Augher said Monaghan initially tried not to
worry when word came about the carnage in nearby Omagh, about 70
miles (110 kms) west of Belfast. Family and friends urged Monaghan
to drive to the scene to search for his wife, but he kept repeating
the same phrase over and over, with lessening conviction: ``She'll
ring, she'll ring.''
	   Louise McGirr, a clerk at the Costcutter store where Mrs.
Monahan shopped that last morning, offered a happier memory from
that day, though it still brought tears to her eyes in the telling.
	   Chubby-cheeked little Maura Monaghan, outfitted in pigtails and
purple shorts, took a lollilop from the candy shelves and started
to walk out without paying. Her mother sternly suggested her
daughter not do that, whereupon Maura reached for her pockets to
hide the lollipop away _ only to find her shorts didn't have any.
	   Ms. McGirr remembers how mother and daughter were laughing as
they left the store, on their way to just another shopping day in
Omagh.
	   She didn't even bother to say goodbye.
	   (kg/eml)
</TEXT>
