<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Olympics-Drugs </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOC anti-doping chief assails Samaranch
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ANDREAS EVAGORA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ The head of the International Olympic Committee's
anti-doping campaign has sharply criticized IOC president Juan
Antonio Samaranch for proposing a reduction in the list of banned
drugs.
	   In an article published Monday in the French daily Le Figaro,
Alexandre de Merode, chairman of the IOC medical commission, said
the IOC should continue its drive to stop the use of doping
substances and strive to standardize doping regulations and improve
education.
	   De Merode said he was shocked by Samaranch's recent comments,
made in a Spanish newspaper interview, in which he called for a
drastic reduction in the list of banned drugs and suggested that
only drugs which are harmful to health should be prohibited.
	   ``The president can have his opinions,'' de Merode told Le
Figaro. ``I do not understand, and they make me aghast.''
	   The IOC president ``was always against doping and supported the
action of the commission. How can we believe that he supports a
reduction in the list at the same time that we have, in a short
period, completely managed the problem?''
	   ``People who want to reduce the list are the people who want to
let doping function,'' he said.
	   De Merode said that Samaranch, who is Spanish, is backing the
philosophy of many doctors in Spain.
	   Some Spanish doctors ``have rejected the ethics of their
profession,'' de Merode said. ``One must not forget that Spanish
sports, for a long time, has had tendencies toward doping. A
president of the Spanish athletics federation has even been
excluded because he refused to select athletes who hadn't taken
doping substances!''
	   It was no coincidence that a Spansh team _ Festina _ was thrown
out of the Tour de France for systematic drug use, de Merode added.
	   De Merode's comments come just three days before the IOC
executive board is due to meet to discuss the growing drug scandals
in sports. The IOC has scheduled a worldwide anti-doping summit in
January.
	   In recent weeks, the Tour de France was dominated by revelations
of drug taking, Olympic gold medal swimmer Michelle Smith was
suspended for four years for manipulating a urine sample, U.S.
athletes Randy Barnes and Dennis Mitchell were suspended after
positive tests, and AS Roma coach Zdenek Zeman implied that illegal
drug taking was rife in Italian soccer's Serie A.
	   Drug scandals continued Monday when it emerged that French
customs officials seized products from the Cofidis cycling team
north of Bordeaux last week.
	   ``The current mess is unacceptable,'' said de Merode, who has
been head of the IOC's anti-doping commision for more than 30
years.
	   De Merode said that he was not surprised at the revelations of
drug taking at the Tour de France.
	   ``We were talking about that for a long time,'' he said. ``Now
we know that the problem is real, that there is systematic
doping.''
	   ``When I hear a rider say `I have never been tested positive so
I am not taking drugs,' that makes me smile.''
	   Still, de Merode said that the Tour's anti-doping effort had
controlled the taking of banned substances among cyclists.
	   Now, sports federations need to redouble their efforts to crack
down on drug taking, he said.
	   ``Some people say `it is acceptable to prohibit four products:
anabolic steroids; testosterone; EPO; and growth hormones.' But
that only opens the doors to all forms of doping.''
	   The fight against ``minor'' hormones must continue, he said.
	   De Merode agreed that detecting the use of banned drugs was a
tough task.
	   Sports bodies have spent six years trying to combat EPO and
three looking to detect growth hormones, he said.
	   But the battle against testosterone is close to success, he
said.
	   When asked who is responsible for doping, Merode said: ``The
athletes themselves cannot be absolved in any cases. You don't give
something to someone who doesn't want it.''
	   (ae/sw)
</TEXT>
