<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sweden-Ikea Founder </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ikea founder's life detailed in new book
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With AP Photo &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) _ Ikea founder Ingvar Kamprad is going
public about his own life in a new book, but vows to keep his
company private.
	   Kamprad gave author Bertil Torekull access to Ikea archives and
participated in long interviews for Torekull's book on the
furnishings giant, which was released Monday.
	   The book, whose Swedish title is ``The History of Ikea _ Ingvar
Kamprad Recounts,'' contains two chapters dealing with Kamprad's
involvement with Nazism. In 1994, a Swedish newspaper reported he
had attended Nazi meetings in 1945-48, which Kamprad quickly
admitted and said he regretted.
	   ``Now I have told all I can,'' he said at a book-release
ceremony at an Ikea store in suburban Stockholm. ``Can one ever get
forgiveness for such stupidity?''
	   The book also contains details about his struggles with alcohol
and his successes and failures in business.
	   He told the Swedish news agency TT on Monday that he is
determined to keep close hold of the company.
	   ``Would one be daring enough to make decisions involving
billions of kronor if we were forced to come to the stock exchange
and report a profit every quarter?'' he said.
	   Ikea plans to expand into Russia and Kamprad said he isn't
deterred by Russia's decision Monday to devalue the ruble. ``In
Russia, people need millions of small apartments, and an Ikea
speciality is in how to live in a small space,'' he said.
	   (jh)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
