<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Shearer-Hoddle </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
England captain supports Hoddle
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BURNHAM BEECHES, England (AP) _ England soccer captain Alan
Shearer came out in support Monday of embattled England coach Glenn
Hoddle.
	   The Newcastle striker, who was in camp with England's squad
preparing for the Sept. 5 Euro 2000 qualifier against Sweden, said
Hoddle's controversial World Cup diary was ``straight forward.''
	   ``I didn't think any of my confidences were broken,'' Shearer
said from the team hotel at Burnham Beeches.
	   Sections of the British media called for Hoddle to resign as
England coach after excerpts of his book ``The 1998 World Cup
Story'' were serialized in the Sun newspaper.
	   He was condemned for breaching the trust of his players.
	   In the book, Hoddle revealed how Paul Gascoigne went beserk
after being told he had been dropped from the English World Cup
squad and also criticized other players.
	   England vice-captain Paul Ince admitted over the weekend that
some players might find it difficult to trust Hoddle in future but
Shearer couldn't see what all the fuss was about.
	   ``I have read all the extracts relating to me, as well as
several other bits which caught my eye as I went along,'' he said.
``It seemed fairly straight forward to me.''
	   ``Everyone else named in the book will want to read the parts
that are relevant to them and form their own views but, when they
do, I doubt if there will be any real problem,'' he added.
	   England's Football Association has backed the England manager
amid the controversy and has reportedly renewed its bid to sign
Hoddle to a long-term contract securing him for the 2002 World Cup.
	   ``Ideally a new contract should be sorted out very quickly and
it should give us a long period of stability right the way through
to the next World Cup,'' an FA spokesman said Monday.
	   (jp)
</TEXT>
