<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Congo, 6th Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Embattled Kabila searches for support
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to CLARIFY that rebel position is unclear,
quotes from information minister. Picks up 8th graf previous,
`During his talks ...' &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos
 &UR; By IAN STEWART &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KINSHASA, Congo (AP) _ Fifteen months ago to the day, an
exuberant Laurent Kabila was in the southern Congolese city of
Lubumbashi, where he declared himself president of this vast
central African country. Back in Lubumbashi on Monday, Kabila is
now struggling for his government's survival.
	   After weekend meetings with Angolan President Jose Eduardo Dos
Santos in that country's capital of Luanda, Kabila briefly returned
to his embattled capital and then headed to Lubumbashi to continue
his efforts to rally support against an advancing rebel army.
	   In recent weeks, Kabila has been traipsing from Cuba to southern
Congo to Angola looking for friends to help hold off the rebels _
an army of his former Rwandan allies, ethnic Tutsi fighters and
disaffected members of the president's own military.
	   But back in Kinshasa, tension was again mounting amid a second
city-wide power outage since the rebellion began and growing rumors
over the stability of the ruling regime.
	   The rebels _ who are believed to be between 150 kilometers (95
miles) and 200 kilometers (125 miles) south of Kinshasa _ last week
captured the town of Inga, where a key power dam is located. The
rebels now say they also control a power station in Nzongo near the
border with the Republic of Congo.
	   Information Minister Didier Mumengi told reporters Monday that
Inga had been ``taken hostage by Rwandan aggressors.''
	   ``They have cut off the electricity,'' he said. ``These are
terrorist methods.''
	   He said the government would take measures to ensure that people
can get fuel and water in the coming days.
	   From Lubumbashi, Kabila was reportedly heading back to the
capital later Monday or to Harare, Zimbabwe, where defense
ministers from Namibia and Angola had arrived for regional talks on
the Congolese war.
	   Asked where Kabila was Monday evening, Mumengi would only say he
was in Congo. He denied the president had gone to Zimbabwe.
	    &UR; Pickup 8th graf previous, `During his talks ...'
</TEXT>
