<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Yorke-Aston Villa </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yorke disappointed after Manchester United deal falls through
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BIRMINGHAM, England (AP) _ Dwight Yorke is committed to staying
at Aston Villa this season but says he is disappointed transfer
negotiations with Manchester United broke down.
	   The Trinidad and Tobago striker was targeted in the off-season
by United manager Alex Ferguson, who reportedly offered Villa a 10
million pound (dlrs 16.25 million) transfer deal.
	   Yorke figured in Ferguson's attempt to lure a key striker to Old
Trafford and was first choice when the other candidate, Dutch
striker Patrick Kluivert, elected to stay at Italian club AC Milan.
	   However, Villa boss John Gregory rejected the approaches from
Manchester United, saying the offer was not big enough.
	   ``I would have liked to have joined Manchester United,'' Yorke
said Monday. ``Opportunities like this only come along once in a
lifetime and I had asked John Gregory and the Villa board for their
understanding.''
	   The 26-year-old striker has told Gregory he will not stay at
Villa beyond the remaining two years of his contract.
	   ``Regardless of what happens now, I won't sign a new contract
and I won't leave before my current contract expires in 2000,'' he
said.
	   ``I don't want Villa fans to see me as disloyal. I would ask
every supporter to think what they would do if they were offered
another job which they would really like to do.''
	   (jp)
</TEXT>
