<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
After rebel setbacks, diplomats try to set up negotiations
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs. RECASTS and UPDATES with U.S. envoy meeting Serbs,
Albanians, Serbs accusing each other of atrocities; EDITS &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos PRI102-106.
 &UR; By ISMET HAJDARI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Envoy Christopher Hill pursued
Monday an American diplomatic initiative to set up talks between
the Serbian government and ethnic Albanian officials on the future
of Kosovo.
	   A decline in fighting revived hopes that negotiations stalled
since May might be resumed. Fehmi Agani, the top ethnic Albanian
negotiator, wrote to his Serbian counterpart Ratko Markovic, saying
the Albanians wanted the talks to resume, on the condition that
Serbs halt their offensive.
	   However, such negotiations may not be successful because they
are boycotted by ethnic Albanian opposition parties and the Kosovo
Liberation Army fighting for independence of the Serbian province.
	   An American diplomatic source said a meeting in Belgrade between
Hill and Serbian officials was meant to ``keep this momentum to
resume negotiations.''
	   He referred to the announcement last week of an ethnic Albanian
negotiating team that contains only associates of pacifist leader
Ibrahim Rugova, who also wants Kosovo's independence but is
despised by the KLA.
	   No details of the meeting were revealed. Belgrade's state-run
Tanjug news agency reported that after the meeting between Serbian
President Milan Milutinovic and Hill's team participants expressed
hope a dialogue would resume to resolve the Kosovo crisis.
	   Fighting ebbed Monday in the restive province, following a
weekend push when Serbian forces captured a series of key Albanian
strongholds.
	   Tanjug said Monday Serbian police had ``crushed'' KLA bases in
the villages of Lodja, Grabovac and Rausic, all on the outskirts of
the province's second city of Pec on Sunday.
	   The pro-Albanian Kosovo Information Center reported sporadic
fighting and shooting in the border area near Junik, apparently
mop-up operations after government forces took control of the
village, formerly a major guerrilla stronghold.
	   The center also accused Serbs of setting ablaze parts of the
villages from which the armed militants were purged. A total of
50,000 civilians remain displaced in the border area, it said.
	   In the province of Kosovo, Albanians account for 90 percent of
the population of 2 million.
	   Meanwhile, the two sides exchanged allegations of atrocities.
	   The Kosovo Information Center said an official of Rugova's
Democratic League of Kosovo died in a Pristina hospital after being
beaten by police in a prison of his hometown Urosevac, 35
kilometers (20 miles) to the south.
	   Conversely, Tanjug said the mutilated bodies of two Serb
policemen missing since July 6 were found Monday in Lodja when
government forces forced KLA rebels to retreat there.
	   Another policeman, wounded in the same village July 6 but
evacuated and hospitalized, died Monday in the main military
hospital in Belgrade, it said.
	   Two other Serbian policemen were killed on Sunday and Monday in
different parts of Kosovo on Sunday and Monday, the pro-government
Serbian Media Center in Pristina reported.
	   The attacks on villages have left tens of thousands of refugees
camped in the woods in western Kosovo. The U.N. refugee agency
based in Geneva, said in a statement Monday it rushed a convoy to
Pec, where refugees who fled earlier fighting reportedly came under
attack and were forced south into the mountains.
	   The U.N. now estimates that more than 231,000 people have been
uprooted in the six months since the conflict began. Many of them
have fled across the mountainous border with Albanian, where the
KLA also maintains bases.
	   (pvs/ms/rp) 	   
</TEXT>
