w2058 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Pakistan-USEvacuation     08-17 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Pakistan-US Evacuation,0609 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Americans told to seriously consider leaving Pakistan
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With Embassy Bombings
 &UR; AP Photos KAR101,LHR101 &QL; 
 &UR; By DONNA BRYSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) _ Americans in Pakistan have lived
through wars with neighboring India, anti-U.S. fervor during the
Gulf War and the murders of their compatriots. But even those used
to living with danger say there's something different about the
latest U.S. warning to get out.
	   ``It's a bit more severe,'' said development consultant Marilee
Kane, expressing quiet amazement that the U.S. Embassy was moving
so quickly to send its own non-essential staff away, and urging so
strongly that other U.S. citizens to follow.
	   Americans in Pakistan learned of the warning Monday morning,
just over a week after the deadly bombings at two U.S. embassies in
East Africa.
	   Facing an auditorium filled with 100 or so U.S. business people,
aid workers, missionaries and diplomats, Ambassador Thomas Simons
acknowledged Monday that the State Department had been unusually
firm in urging the estimated 6,700 Americans living throughout
Pakistan to ``consider seriously departing Pakistan.''
	   U.S. Embassy spokesman Richard Hoagland said all but about 50 of
120 people in the embassy in Islamabad and consulates in Karachi,
Lahore and Peshawar were leaving. They, their families and the
families of essential staff will fly out Tuesday morning for
Brussels.
	   ``My advice would be to be careful, but don't panic,'' Simons
told non-embassy Americans.
	   There was no panic at the question-and-answer session Simons
held for the American community in Islamabad. But there were sharp
questions from many, including a woman who wanted to know ``what
we're running away from?''
	   The ambassador cited only a ``pattern of threats'' since the
simultaneous bombings Aug. 7 of the U.S. embassies in Nairobi,
Kenya and Dar es Salaam, Tanzania that killed 257 people and
injured thousands.
	   The U.S. Embassy in Islamabad has withstood bloody assaults,
though none as serious as those in East Africa. A mob incensed at
the rumor U.S. forces were attacking Muslim holy places in Saudi
Arabia attacked and burned the Islamabad embassy in 1979, killing
two American and two Pakistani employees.
	   The embassy compound now resembles a not-unpleasant federal
prison, hidden from the street by a 3-meter (10-foot) brick wall
topped with rolls of barbed wire. Concrete barricades slow traffic
on surrounding streets.
	   An U.S. Christian missionary recalled Americans leaving
predominately Muslim Pakistan during the 1991 Gulf War. U.S.
intervention to reverse Iraq's invasion of Kuwait was seen by some
in Pakistan and elsewhere as proof of Washington's desire to
control the Muslim world.
	   Other Americans have lived here long enough to recall the
tension with foreigners and Pakistanis alike during Pakistan's wars
with India in 1965 and 1971.
	   Sunday, the Pakistani government said a suspect in the African
bombings had been caught trying to slip from Nairobi through
Pakistan to neighboring Afghanistan. He was sent back to Nairobi
for questioning by U.S. and Kenyan agents. The move could anger
some in Pakistan, but Simons said the warning to Americans was not
directly linked to the transfer.
	   Simons also dismissed the possibility the U.S. was planning to
use Pakistan as a staging ground for an attack on a terrorist
leader holed up in neighboring Afghanistan who has been identified
as a possible suspect in the African bombings. Pakistani Foreign
Minister Sartaj Aziz said Monday his country had not been asked to
facilitate such an attack. 	   
</TEXT>
