w2061 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SouthAfrica-Botswana-     08-17 0234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Botswana-Elephants,0233 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sale of young elephants criticized by chiefs, experts
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) _ A Botswana-based environmental
group Monday criticized the legal capture and sale of 30 young
elephants from Botswana's Tuli Reserve.
	   Sekai, a branch of the Tuli Lion Trust, said in a statement
released in Johannesburg that the four to seven year-old elephants
were taken from their family groups and sold to a wild animal
trader in Botswana's southern neighbot, South Africa.
	   Under the Convention for International Trade in Endangered
Species (CITES), the elephant export was legal, the statement said.
The trade was carried out between the landowners of the Tuli
Reserve, the Botswana Department of Wildlife and National Parks and
the animal trader.
	   The elephants were sold for 12,000 rand (dlrs 1,904) each.
	   Tribal headmen and chiefs in the Tuli area complained in the
statement that they were not consulted and that they would seek to
prevent capture of another 20 young elephants targeted for sale.
	   Kenya-based elephant specialist Daphne Sheldrick, who runs an
orphanage for baby elephants outside Nairobi, said in the statement
that she was appalled by the trade.
	   ``A mother elephant that loses her baby will suffer all the
grief and misery of the loss of a loved one, as would a human
mother under such circumstances,'' she said. 	   
</TEXT>
