w2063 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-Islam     08-17 0197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Islam </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russia's Islamic leaders seek to prevent spread of fundamentalism
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Islamic leaders from Russian republics in the
North Caucasus on Monday formed an organization aimed at countering
the spread of Islamic extremism in the region, a news agency
reported.
	   Most residents of Russia's Caucasus regions traditionally
practice a moderate version of Islam. But extremist movements,
especially Wahhabism, recently have been on the rise and have been
blamed for violence in several parts of the former Soviet Union.
	   The new organization has declared as its purpose the
stabilization of the situation in the North Caucasus, and
countering the spread of fundamentalism, the ITAR-Tass news agency
reported.
	   ``The Wahhabi movement is a plague introduced to split Islam,''
Chechnya's Mufti Hajji Akhmad Kadurov was quoted as saying.
	   Besides Chechnya, the group includes Islamic leaders from
Russia's republics of Dagestan, Ingushetia, Kabardino-Balkaria,
Karachayevo-Cherkessia and North Ossetia, ITAR-Tass reported. They
decided to set up the organization's headquarters in Ingushetia's
capital Nazran.
	   (ad/ji)
</TEXT>
