w2070 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Spain-OmaghReaction     08-17 0246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Spain-Omagh Reaction </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Radical Basque party breaks with custom to lament Omagh bomb 
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MADRID, Spain (AP) _ The political party linked to armed Basque
separatist group ETA broke with its custom of not condemning bomb
attacks when it issued a statement Monday saying it lamented the
car-bomb blast in the Northern Ireland this weekend that killed 28
people.
	   Herri Batasuna said it wished to convey its condolences to those
injured and to the families of those killed in the Omagh bomb blast
Saturday which it described as an attack on the Irish peace
process.
	   Sometimes compared to the Sinn Fein party of Northern Ireland
which is linked to the IRA armed group, Herri Batasuna has never
condemned any of the attacks carried out by ETA in its 30-year
campaign for a Basque state independent of Spain.
	   ETA, whose name is a Basque-language acronym for Basque Homeland
and Freedom, is blamed for the deaths of nearly 800 people since
1968. Twenty-three executive board members of Herri Batasuna were
jailed last year after being convicted of collaborating with ETA.
	   The party, whose name stands for ``Our Country'' and which has
close ties with Sinn Fein, praised what it described as the
``political maturity'' of Northern Ireland's politicians following
the Omagh blast and said it hoped Spanish and Basque politicians
could show a similar maturity and initiate a peace process to end
the Basque conflict.
	   (cg) 	   
</TEXT>
