<SLUG> BC-India-Prime Minister's Health,0341 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Government denies report that prime minister has cancer
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ India's government dismissed a newspaper
report Monday that claimed Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee's
wobbly walk at the national Independence Day parade showed he was
suffering from cancer.
	   A front-page report Monday in The Asian Age newspaper claimed
Vajpayee was making regular visits to a New Delhi referral center
purportedly for a bone scan. ``The prime minister is suspected to
have a tumor in the prostrate gland,'' the report said.
	   ``(The) report may make colorful reading for those who delight
in denigrating the prime minister of India by casting unfounded and
motivated aspersions on his health, but it does great disservice to
the readers, not to mention the fact that it defames Shri Atal
Bihari Vajpayee,'' a spokesman for Vajpayee said in a letter to the
paper's editor.
	   ``He has no medically confirmed symptoms of any ailment, leave
alone a prostrate tumor,'' said the letter, a copy of which was
faxed to news agencies.
	   Sunday's newspapers splashed pictures of Vajpayee's wobble after
he took the salute at the main Independence Day parade on Saturday
in New Delhi. The prime minister had to be supported by his
security guards.
	   An official spokesman said Saturday that Vajpayee suffered ``a
momentary muscle pull in the lower back.''
	   But The Asian Age said it was a sign of prostrate cancer, adding
its symptoms are physical weakness, a slight drop in blood pressure
and problems in walking.
	   It said the prime minister was being treated at the Sitaram
Bhartiya Institute, ``the best place in Delhi for a bone scan.''
The report said a bone scan was not done on a patient unless a
tumor was suspected.
	   It added Vajpayee had had a kidney removed in 1987 because of a
tumor.
	   The spokesman's letter confirmed one of Vajpayee's kidneys was
removed in 1986 on medical advice. It said the operation was widely
known and had not come in the way of a hectic public life. 	   
</TEXT>
