<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-Pebble Beach, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0459 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tournament to conclude six months after start
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Furyk taking lead; Edits to conform. &QL; 
 &UR; By ROB GLOSTER &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PEBBLE BEACH, California (AP) _ Six months after they were
driven off the course by torrential rain and strong winds, golfers
on Monday resumed the AT and T Pebble Beach National Pro-Am on a
dry, overcast morning.
	   Jim Furyk, who missed the cut in his last two tournaments, had
an eagle on the sixth hole of the Pebble Beach course to
temporarily take over the lead as the long-delayed tourney
concluded with its final round.
	   Furyk, who started the day two strokes behind co-leaders Tom
Watson and Tim Herron, moved to 12-under to take a two-stroke lead
over four players. Watson and Herren dropped to 9-under.
	   Furyk tied for fourth in the British Open last month, but has
struggled since then. He missed the cut this weekend at the PGA
Championship.
	   Fellow Americans Davis Love III, Tom Watson and Tim Herron each
lead earlier in the day.
	   Watson won the Pebble Beach tournament in 1977 and 1978. If he
wins this year, the two-decade separation between victories would
be a tourney record. Herron was last among the players who
completed all four rounds of the PGA Championship this past
weekend.
	   When the AT and T tournament began in late January, waves from
the Pacific Ocean were crashing onto the 18th fairway. Sheet-like
rain was turning sandtraps into water hazards and gusty winds were
snapping treetops.
	   On Monday, months after the demise of El Nino, the tourney
resumed on a dry morning on the Pebble Beach, Poppy Hills and
Spyglass Hill courses.
	   Of the 168 pros who started the tournament, 135 were expected to
return to Pebble Beach for the final round.
	   Among those not returning were Tiger Woods, who finished the
second round 14 strokes off the lead, and fellow American Jack
Nicklaus. Also dropping out was Vijay Singh of Fiji, who won the
PGA Championship Sunday near Seattle.
	   The AT and T tournament chartered a plane to take players from
Seattle to Monterey Sunday night. Those continuing to the next tour
stop, the International in Denver, will get another chartered
flight Monday night.
	   PGA Tour officials said it's the first time a portion of a
tournament has been played, then completed months later.
	   The tournament was washed out after two rounds in 1996, making
it the first PGA Tour event that could not be completed since 1949.
	   Players managed to squeeze in two soggy rounds in late January,
and organizers reduced the event to 54 holes. But heavy rains wiped
out play 1 1/2 hours after tee-off Feb. 1, and again Feb. 2 when
officials tried to extend it to Monday.
</TEXT>
