<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Politics,0474 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Prime minister seeks evidence of bribe-taking by aides
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By NEELESH MISRA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari
Vajpayee sought evidence Monday for accusations that a media baron
bribed his close associates to have the country's top economic
offenses investigator transferred from his job.
	   The charges ``merit immediate attention,'' Vajpayee's top aide
Brajesh Mishra said in a letter to Jayaram Jayalalitha, a powerful
southern Indian leader who props up the government with crucial
parliamentary support but is growing restive in the alliance.
	   Jayalalitha alleged Sunday that M.K. Bezbaruah, who headed the
Enforcement Directorate, was transferred from his job because the
owners of a ``well-known group of publications'' had ``paid hefty
bribes to persons very close to the prime minister,'' Monday's
newspapers said.
	   Jayalalitha did not name the newspaper group. Ashok Jain,
proprietor of the mass-selling Times of India newspaper, has been
charged by the Directorate with violating India's foreign exchange
laws. Jain has denied the charges, and he did not immediately react
to Jayalalitha's allegation.
	   The reply from Vajpayee's office was part of weeks-old sparring
between his Hindu nationalist Bharatiya Janata Party and
Jayalalitha, who faces several charges of financial wrongdoing
doing an earlier tenure as the top elected official of the southern
Tamil Nadu state.
	   Jayalalitha got bad press last week when her reported threat to
pull down the government was linked to an administrative revamp in
which the government transferred top officials _ some investigating
cases of corruption and foreign exchange violations against her.
	   Jayalalitha denied she had anything to do with the transfers,
urged the government to reinstate Bezbaruah and issued the bribery
accusation. The prime minister's office said Sunday the charges
were baseless.
	   The main opposition Congress Party demanded a probe into the
accusation, and a regional party opposed to Jayalalitha demanded
Vajpayee's resignation over the issue.
	   Jayalalitha, whose Tamil regional group is one of the 19 parties
in the governing coalition, has repeatedly threatened to pull out
of the government over several local issues. She has not carried
out her threat so far.
	   Her All India Anna Dravida Munnetra Kazagham and four local
allies together have 30 lawmakers whose support is crucial for
Vajpayee's government in the 545-member federal Parliament.
	   On Thursday, Jayalalitha announced she would stay in Vajpayee's
government after nearly all the lawmakers supporting her warned
against the move.
	   Minutes after the meeting, Vajpayee moved Bezbaruah, the chief
investigator of her cases, to the transport department saying his
expertise was wanted there. 	   
</TEXT>
