<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Market Blast </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Istanbul's spice market explosion caused by a bomb
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) _ Investigators now suspect a bomb planted
by Kurdish rebels caused last month's deadly explosion at
Istanbul's centuries-old spice market, Turkey's semiofficial
Anatolia news agency said Monday. The blast killed seven people and
injured more than 100.
	   Officials initially thought a faulty gas canister at a food
stand caused the July 9 explosion, although the possibility of a
bomb was never ruled out.
	   Independent NTV television reported that 21 people were being
detained in Istanbul, suspected of helping to place the bomb at the
entrance of the spice market. Anatolia put the number of suspects
held at 15, and said they were Kurdish rebels.
	   Kurdish guerrillas have been fighting for autonomy in Turkey's
southeast since 1984: An estimated 37,000 people have died in the
conflict. Rebels have claimed responsibility for several attacks on
tourist sites.
	   Istanbul's head of police was expected to make an official
announcement on Tuesday. Officials were unavailable for comment
late Monday.
	   The 17th-century spice market, known in Turkey as the Egyptian
market, is located near the Blue Mosque and Istanbul's renowned
covered bazaar. The covered market_ offering exotic food, spices
and dried fruits in hundreds of stands _ is a favorite stop on most
tourist itineraries.
	   (ht-ek)
</TEXT>
