<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Afghanistan,0545 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Opposition: Taliban bombs injure children
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos KAB101-102 &QL; 
 &UR; By ZAHEERUDDIN ABDULLAH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) _ Taliban bombs hit the opposition
stronghold of Bamiyan in central Afghanistan on Monday, injuring
three children, an opposition source said.
	   Spokesman Azizullah Shashaq of the Hezb-e-Wahadat militia also
claimed an opposition victory Monday. He said that after heavy
fighting, his militia reclaimed the town of Khawjah Ghuar, just
north of the Takhar provincial capital of Talqor that the Taliban
recently captured. Khawjah Ghuar has an airport, making it an
important prize.
	   There was no confirmation Khawjah Ghuar changed hands, and no
confirmation of the bombing of Bamiyan, 100 kilometers (60 miles)
east of the capital, Kabul. Shashaq had no details on casualties
beyond the three children he said were wounded.
	   In southern Afghanistan, Taliban spokesman Abdul Hay Muttayn
said Taliban leaders met Monday with an Iranian delegation seeking
information about 11 missing Iranians, including diplomats. Iran
has accused Taliban forces of seizing the 11 when they captured
Mazar-e-Sharif on Aug. 8.
	   The loss of Mazar-e-Sharif, about 300 kilometers (190 miles)
north of Kabul was a major blow to the northern-based opposition
alliance, and one of several recent victories for the Taliban. The
Taliban, who profess an extreme version of Islam, could soon
control all of Afghanistan. They have held the capital since 1996.
	   Taliban officials reiterated Monday that they were not holding
the missing Iranians and did not know where they could be found,
Muttayn said.
	   The independent human rights group Amnesty International raised
the missing Iranians and several other issues in a statement
Monday, calling on the Taliban to allow independent monitoring of
the human rights situation in Afghanistan.
	   Amnesty's chief concern were reports Afghans from minority
ethnic and religious groups were being killed or harassed as the
Taliban consolidated control over Afghanistan.
	   ``The Taliban's refusal to allow independent monitoring of the
situation in the northern areas of Afghanistan _ following the fall
of Mazar-e-Sharif and several other major towns to the Taliban last
week _ could serve to conceal the human rights violations in the
area,'' Amnesty said.
	   Also Monday:
	   _President Boris Yeltsin ordered his border chief to Tajikistan
to ensure that the former Soviet Union's southern borders were
secure following recent Taliban victories. The former Soviet
republics of Tajikistan, Uzbekistan, and Turkmenistan, now part of
the Commonwealth of Independent States, fear a complete Taliban
victory could send an influx of refugees and weapons across their
borders.
	   _A committee comprising Taliban, United Nations and independent
aid group representatives met for the first time in Kabul to try to
resolve a dispute over relocating the aid groups to war-damaged
dormitories in the capital.
	   Aid workers were expelled from Kabul nearly a month ago after
refusing Taliban orders to move. A U.N. spokesman said Monday it
was difficult to determine to what extent health and other
conditions in Kabul had deteriorated since the aid workers
departed. 	   
</TEXT>
