</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Chechnya-Oil </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chechnya prohibits private oil condensate extraction, trade
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Citing the threat of an environmental disaster,
the president of Chechnya signed a decree Monday prohibiting
individuals and private businesses from the extraction and trade of
oil condensate, the ITAR-Tass news agency reported.
	   Khozh-Akhmed Yarikhanov, an advisor to President Aslan
Maskhadov, said that only state organizations would be authorized
to deal in oil condensate.
	   Chechen authorities are concerned about environmental damage
from the oil condensate wells, which according to ITAR-Tass have
sprung up in virtually every yard in the capital Grozny. The
province's fuel and energy ministry and environment department
estimate that millions of tons of oil condensate are 10-15 meters
(32.8-49.2 feet) underground on Grozny's outskirts.
	   Some oil condensate has reportedly leaked into the water table
and a Chechen river, ITAR-Tass said.
	   (ji) 	   
</TEXT>
