</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Nicaragua-Cuban Refugees,0366 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nicaraguans criticize granting of tourist visas to Cuban refugees
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By FILADELFO ALEMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) _ A wave of suspicion and criticism has
risen against the government of President Arnold Aleman for
granting tourist visas to seven Cuban refugees, including four
baseball players, who landed in Nicaragua last week.
	   Critics question why a Cuban exile group in Miami knew of the
refugee's arrival well before Nicaraguan officials.
	   The daily El Nuevo Diaro, a mouthpiece for the previous
Sandinista administration, said Aleman's government participated in
``the illegal trafficking of immigrants'' with the goal of
provoking a break in ties with Cuba.
	   The seven Cubans landed Thursday in Puerto Cabezas, in the
extreme northeast of the country, where they said a Costa Rican
ship carried them after rescuing them at sea when their small boat
broke apart.
	   From Miami, the Cuban American National Foundation announced the
refugees landed in Nicaragua on Thursday, the 72nd birthday of
Cuban leader Fidel Castro.
	   But even by midday Friday, Nicaraguan authorities said they had
no knowledge of the reported arrival. Then shortly after noon, the
refugees appeared in Managua and received tourist visas from the
General Director of Migration and Foreign issues.
	   They were assisted in their negotiations by Ninoska Perez,
president of the Cuban-American Association of Miami, who arrived
in Nicaragua a few days earlier.
	   Perez said the group was welcomed in Nicaragua under a promise
Aleman made in June to give humanitarian refuge to nearly 100
Cubans who landed in the Bahamas.
	   Augusto Zamora, a Foreign Ministry official during the
Sandinista administration, criticized the welcome, saying Aleman
was bowing to interests of the U.S. Cuban exile community, which
supported his presidential campaign.
	   ``The tourist visa is for people who enter the country
legally,'' he said.
	   The Aleman administration is opening ``a sea and land bridge''
at the margin of official institutions for use by Cuban exiles to
take people out of Cuba, he said in Sunday's edition of El Nuevo
Diaro. 	   
</TEXT>
