<SLUG> BC-Sudan-Rebels 1st Ld Writethru,0340 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sudanese opposition vow to continue struggle against government
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS throughout with closing statement; CHANGES overline. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Sudanese rebel leaders vowed Monday to
continue their war against the Khartoum government while
maintaining the country's unity.
	   The announcement was made after rebel leaders wound up a
three-day meeting in Cairo which was convened at the behest of the
Egyptian government.
	   Egypt fears the civil war in southern and eastern Sudan could
lead to a division of the country and affect control of the Nile
River, the source of Egypt's water.
	   Farouk Abu Eissa, a spokesman for the National Democratic
Alliance, said a final communique of the meeting will be issued
Tuesday.
	   Rebel leader John Garang, former Prime Minister Sadiq el-Mahdi
and Mohammed Osman al-Mirgani, who heads the National Democratic
Alliance, agreed to ``expand the scope of the popular uprising in
all areas of Sudan,'' Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
	   They said they favored a united Sudan based on respect for
cultural differences, equality for all Sudanese and the separation
of church and state, MENA reported.
	   Garang _ whose Sudan People's Liberation Army has led the
15-year insurgency in southern Sudan _ left Cairo for Nairobi,
Kenya, before the National Democratic Alliance held the final
ceremonial session to close out its discussions.
	   Sudan complained that Egypt's organizing of the meeting was a
boost to the opposition. But President Hosni Mubarak said in an
interview published Monday that he met with the rebels to try to
keep the neighboring nation unified.
	   ``This meeting was held in the interest of our brothers in
Sudan,'' he told the weekly newspaper Mayo of Egypt's ruling
National Democratic Party.
	   The southern rebels took up arms in 1983 to demand more autonomy
for the Christian, animist south from the Muslim, Arab north. More
than 1.5 million people have died in the conflict and related
famines.
</TEXT>
