<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Libya-Tunisia 2nd Ld-Writethru,0314 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Gadhafi meets with Tunisian president
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Leads throughout with Ben Ali's departure; CLARIFIES in lead
that Ben Ali is Tunisian president; CORRECTS in 2nd graf that U.S.
air raids on Tripoli were in 1986. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi met with
Tunisian President Zine el Abidine Ben Ali on Monday for talks on
boosting relations between the two countries, Libyan television
reported.
	   Ben Ali, on the first visit by a Tunisian leader to Libya in
five years, received a red-carpet welcome by Libyan officials
outside the ruins of an apartment building bombed during the 1986
U.S. air raids on Tripoli, the Libyan capital.
	   Gadhafi, who is recovering from hip surgery, did not attend the
welcoming reception, said the television broadcast, monitored by
the British Broadcasting Corporation.
	   Speaking to reporters, Ben Ali reaffirmed his country's
commitment to seeing U.N. sanctions on Libya lifted, Egypt's Middle
East News Agency said.
	   Ben Ali returned home later Monday, MENA said. It did not give
any details.
	   The United Nations imposed economic and political sanctions on
Libya in 1992 to try to force Gadhafi to surrender two Libyans
wanted in connection with the 1988 bombing of a Pan Am jet over
Lockerbie, Scotland, that killed 270 people.
	   The embargo, which bans air travel to the country and has frozen
Libyan assets abroad, has also punished Libya for supporting
international terrorism.
	   Ben Ali also said he came to check on Gadhafi's health. Gadhafi
underwent surgery last month after breaking his hip during
exercise.
	   Gadhafi told reporters that the trip comes as part of continued
contacts between the two neighboring countries, MENA said.
	   Tunisia, which borders Libya on the east, is frequently used as
a land crossing into Libya due to the current sanctions. 	   
</TEXT>
