w2168 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UN-Iraq 1stLd-Writethru   08-17 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Iraq, 1st Ld-Writethru,0564 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Security Council meets to consider Iraq response
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with envoy saying Iraq unwilling to move &QL; 
 &UR; By NICOLE WINFIELD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ After days of discussion in Baghdad, the
U.N. envoy to Iraq reported Monday that Iraq is still unwilling to
back down in its standoff with U.N. weapons inspectors, diplomats
said Monday.
	   The report from Prakash Shah was being delivered to the Security
Council by Rolf Knutsson, director of the U.N. office of political
affairs.
	   ``There doesn't seem to be any progress,'' said one Western
diplomat, familiar with Shah's message. ``They haven't been able to
come to any sort of resolution or agreement.''
	   Iraq's ambassador, Nizar Hamdoon, said as much in comments to
reporters, saying that Iraq's Aug. 5 decision to freeze cooperation
with weapons inspectors was unchanged.
	   ``We found nothing in Shah's initiative that would satisfy our
concerns,'' Hamdoon said.
	   Negotiations with Shah were continuing, but ``our concerns will
have to be met,'' he said.
	   Iraq has demanded an end to sanctions imposed after Baghdad
invaded Kuwait in 1990, touching off the Gulf War. Iraqi officials
claim they have complied with U.N. resolutions demanding that they
destroy their long-range missiles and chemical, biological and
nuclear weapons.
	   Iraq froze cooperation with U.N. inspectors after the chief
inspector, Richard Butler, refused to certify that Baghdad had
destroyed its weapons of mass destruction.
	   After receiving the briefing from Knutsson, the council was
expected to consider Japanese-drafted letters that would encourage
U.N. weapons inspectors to try to carry out inspections in the face
of Iraq's new ban.
	   With the low-key response, the council was trying to force Iraq
to make the next major move after its Aug. 5 decision, diplomats
said.
	   If Baghdad blocks an inspection, council members could more
easily hold Baghdad in violation of U.N. resolutions and a February
agreement that gave them unconditional access to suspected weapons
sites. To date, the council has only said Iraq's Aug. 5 freeze on
inspections ``contravened'' the agreement, a semantic detail but
one which prevented council members from threatening tougher
action.
	   Despite the stalemate, Secretary-General Kofi Annan does not
plan to get personally involved as he did last February, when the
United States and Britain threatened to bomb Iraq if it didn't
allow inspectors access into certain presidential sites, U.N.
spokesman Fred Eckhard said.
	   Annan brokered an accord that allowed inspectors access but ``he
personally does not foresee any role for himself at this time,''
Eckhard said.
	   The difference this time is that there is no threat of war, he
said.
	   The Japanese-drafted letters were to be sent to Butler and the
head of the International Atomic Energy Agency, Mohammed El
Baradei, who both reported last week that their work was being
undermined by Baghdad's decision.
	   Not only new inspections but ongoing monitoring of suspected
weapons sites was being affected, the inspectors told the council.
	   The council's letter would reaffirm the work of inspectors,
acknowledge that their mandate was being undermined and say that
Baghdad's decision was unacceptable, the diplomats said.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
