<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIreland-One Family, 2nd Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
One bomb, one moment: Three generations of a family die in
</HEADLINE>
carbombing &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with shop owner saying women didn't suffer &QL; 
 &UR; With BC-Northern Ireland &QL; 
 &UR; By KRISTIN GAZLAY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   AUGHER, Northern Ireland (AP) _ One minute, they were shopping
on an ordinary Saturday afternoon. The next minute, three
generations of a family were gone.
	   Townspeople say it was family that mattered most to 30-year-old
Avril Monaghan, pregnant with twins, and it was family she died
with in the Omagh carbombing _ her 18-month-old daughter Maura and
her 65-year-old mother, Mary Grimes.
	   ``The family have strong faith,'' said the Rev. Lawrence Dawson,
the Catholic parish priest who will preside Tuesday over the
funerals of Avril and her daughter. ``It's the only way you can
cope with this kind of problem.''
	   Mrs. Monaghan lived in the rolling green hills above Augher with
her husband, Michael. He makes his living as a carpenter; she found
work as a secretary. But, mostly, she was a mother, raising a son
and three daughters, the oldest 6 years old.
	   A widely published picture shows Mrs. Monaghan grinning at her
groom on her wedding day, a crown of flowers resting on her dark
hair.
	   Dawson said Mrs. Monaghan, who attended Mass with her children
the last morning of her life, was a stalwart contributor to the
church, helping organize functions at the parish school and putting
together quizzes for the students.
	   It is almost impossible for the 700 souls of Augher and nearby
Clogher, where the family sometimes attended church, to accept the
triple blow the Monaghan and Grimes clans have suffered, he said.
	   That pain stretches the 20 miles (32 kms) north to Beragh, where
Mrs. Grimes _ who had 10 other children _ lived with her husband
Mick, a dairy farmer.
	   Workers from a Omagh curtain shop have visited the Grimes family
to assure them their loved ones, struck by the bomb just after they
left the store, did not suffer.
	   ``They were dead right away,'' said Stephen McKervey, the
manager of R.D. Kells.
	    &UR; Mrs. Grimes, 9th graf pvs
	   (kg/eml)
</TEXT>
