<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Canada-Dog Attack,0257 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Woman, son killed by pack of sled dogs in Canada
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ZACHARIAS ISLAND, Newfoundland (AP) _ A pack of sled dogs
attacked and killed a woman and her 10-year-old son as they picked
berries on an island off the Labrador coast, police said Monday.
	   ``It would rank with some of the worst incidents I've ever had
to deal with,'' said Constable Richard Langille of the Royal
Canadian Mounted Police.
	   Langille said Betty Gauntlett and her son, Daniel Obed, were
picking berries Sunday when they were set upon by eight sled dogs.
	   The woman's common-law husband and an 8-year-old boy, whose
names were not released, escaped to their boat after fending off
the animals with rocks and sticks, he said.
	   ``They're big dogs,'' Langille said. ``They range anywhere from
60 to 80 pounds (28 to 36 kilos), maybe more, and when they get
into a frenzy like that in a pack, it wouldn't take very long at
all to disable someone.''
	   It is common practice for dog owners in northern Canada to
deposit their animals on islands during the summer when they are
not in use pulling sleds. The practice was adopted so the idle dogs
wouldn't create a noise problem in their owners' communities.
	   After Sunday's attack, police and area residents destroyed the
dogs. The carcasses were handed over to wildlife officials to be
tested for rabies.
	   Labrador is the mainland portion of the province of
Newfoundland. Zacharias Island is near the coastal town of
Hopedale, home to about 600 Inuit, formerly known as Eskimos.
</TEXT>
