<HEADER>
w2267 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-France-Obit-Green 1stLd-Writethru   08-17 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-Obit-Green, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
American author who wrote about South dead at 97
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with details, background; ADDS byline. &QL; 
 &UR; By MARILYN AUGUST &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ American novelist Julien Green, who enriched the
French language with tales of the American South over a career that
spanned more than six decades, has died at the age of 97, French
media reported Monday.
	   Radio France Info and LCI television said Green died last
Thursday in Paris, and was buried in a private ceremony outside the
country. They cited no source. The U.S. Embassy in Paris said
Monday night it hadn't heard of Green's death.
	   The Paris-based Green became, in 1971, the first foreigner to be
elected to the Academie Francaise _ the elite panel that serves as
a watchdog over the French language.
	   But in November 1996, he made headlines by announcing he was
relinquishing his seat, saying he felt ``exclusively American'' and
citing his advanced age, his difficulty in getting around and his
profound distaste for honors.
	   Born in Paris to American parents, Green once described himself
as ``a southerner lost in Europe, regardless of what I do.''
	   Completely bilingual, he wrote mostly in French, with the
exception of ``Memories of Happy Days.'' Published in 1982, the
work recalled, in simple prose, the lost happiness of his
childhood.
	   Green was extremely prolific, producing more than a dozen
novels, four short stories, five plays, an autobiography, numerous
biographies and essays, and a multi-volume daily journal _ all in
French. He also wrote five works in English.
	   He was active until his late 80s, attending the Thursday
afternoon meetings of fellow Academie members and devoting several
hours a day to writing his autobiography. But in his final few
years he led a reclusive existence.
	   In March 1988, at age 87, he published ``L'Arc-En-Ciel (The
Rainbow),'' the 13th volume of his journal, dealing with the years
1981-84. At 81, he read the works of Franz Kafka for the first
time.
	   It was in 1987 that Green became a household name in France with
his bestseller, ``Pays Lointain (Faraway Country),'' a historical
novel about the American South that he began in 1934 but abandoned
because of the huge success of Margaret Mitchell's ``Gone With The
Wind.''
	   His best known works included ``Sud (South),'' a 1953 play about
the Civil War, and ``Moira'' (1950), a novel dramatizing the
struggle between man's sensuality and spirituality.
	   A devout Roman Catholic who converted from Protestantism, he
once said the greatest influence on his life and work was religious
philosopher Blaise Pascal and his tragic portrait ``Man Without
God.'' In ``Vers l'Invisible (Toward the Invisible),'' he described
the suffering of his early years when he oscillated between doubt
and faith.
	   Many of Green's novels were characterized by a kind of Gothic
atmosphere because of the subject matter: murder, suicide, sadism
and madness. ``Adrienne Mesurat,'' translated as ``The Closed
Garden'' (1927) and ``Midnight'' (1936), were dominated largely by
images of darkness and fear.
	   Julien Green was born in Paris in 1900, the son of an American
import-export dealer from Virginia who settled in France in 1895
with his Georgia-born wife.
	   He spoke English at home and was regaled by his mother with
stories of the old South, its lush plantations and easy living.
	   He received a French public school education and joined the
French army at 18. Toward the end of World War I, he drove
ambulances on the French and Italian fronts.
	   His first visit to the United States was at age 20, when he
entered the University of Virginia. Though he only stayed two
years, his deep feelings about the South were to influence his
later writings.
	   During World War II, he worked in the United States on radio
programs destined for the French public. He returned to France
after the war.
	   His 1949 ``Dixie,'' written in French, was an instant
bestseller.
	   In 1971 he became the first non-Frenchman to be elected to the
Academie Francaise, after receiving special dispensation from then-
President Georges Pompidou.
	   Details on survivors weren't immediately available.
	   (ma-var-jn) 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-France-Obit-Green, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:INDI;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:ASIA;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
