<SLUG> BC-Puerto Rico-51st State,0549 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Governor calls referendum on Puerto Rican statehood
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By CHRIS HAWLEY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) _ Ignoring criticism from allies and
opponents, Gov. Pedro Rossello on Monday authorized a referendum on
Puerto Rico's ties to the United States, telling islanders it was
time to choose between statehood or independence.
	   The bill signed by Rossello sets a Dec. 13 plebiscite that the
governor hopes will spur the U.S. Congress to resolve a wrangle
over the Caribbean island's status that began when U.S. troops
wrested it from the Spanish in 1898.
	   ``I trust that when this process is finished, we will have
managed to eradicate from our daily lives a 100-year debate that
weighs us down,'' Rossello said in a TV address.
	   Rossello wants Puerto Rico, a U.S. territory defined since 1952
as a ``commonwealth,'' to become the 51st state.
	   Rossello is expected to lobby Republicans for a change in Puerto
Rico's status during a meeting here this month of the Southern
Governors Association, over which he presides. Rossello is also
president of the Democratic Governors Association.
	   The Popular Democratic Party, which favors retaining the
commonwealth arrangement, vowed to challenge the law in court.
	   The party objects to the ballot's definition of commonwealth as
a territory under the control of Congress _ suggesting the 3.8
million Puerto Ricans' cherished U.S. citizenship can be revoked.
	   In a reflection of how charged the status debate has become, the
ballot will refer to statehood, independence and commonwealth by
numbers because lawmakers felt the words were too loaded.
	   ``What we have today is a bill that used to be bad, and that
(legislators) turned into grotesque,'' said Puerto Rican Sen.
Eudaldo Baez Galib, a commonwealth advocate, referring to the
results of a two-week dispute over wording among legislators here.
	   The planned vote has even inspired doubts among Rossello's
allies _ including Carlos Romero Barcelo, Puerto Rico's
pro-statehood delegate in Congress who has spent more than two
years trying to convince U.S. lawmakers to authorize such a vote on
the island.
	   His bill, which passed the U.S. House of Representatives by a
single vote in March, appears stalled in the U.S. Senate.
	   On Friday, Romero said the ballot in Rossello's plebiscite
``tends to deceive the people'' by offering them a second
independence option under a vaguely defined ``free association''
treaty with the United States.
	   On the ballot, voters will be able to choose between statehood,
the current commonwealth status, independence, independence with
the free association treaty, or ``none of the above.''
	   The ballot proposed by the Congressional bill offered only the
first three options.
	   Rossello said Monday that Puerto Ricans should choose ``one way
or the other'' _ between being independent like Cuba, which was
also ruled by Spain until 1898, or joining the union like Hawaii,
which came under U.S. control that year too.
	   Apparently referring to the House of Representatives vote and
supportive statements by President Clinton, Rossello insisted that
for the first time ``the U.S. government has clearly expressed its
commitment to listen to our demands.'' 	   
</TEXT>
