<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Iraq, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0629 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Security Council meets to consider Iraq response
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with draft of letter, voicing support for UN mandates;
TRIMS; minor edits. &QL; 
 &UR; By NICOLE WINFIELD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ After days of discussion in Baghdad, a
U.N. envoy reported Monday that Iraq is still unwilling to back
down in its standoff with U.N. weapons inspectors, diplomats said.
	   The report from Prakash Shah was delivered by Rolf Knutsson,
director of the U.N. office of political affairs, to the Security
Council, where diplomats worked on a response to the impasse.
	   ``There doesn't seem to be any progress,'' said one Western
diplomat, familiar with Shah's message. ``They haven't been able to
come to any sort of resolution or agreement.''
	   Iraq froze cooperation with U.N. inspectors after the chief
inspector, Richard Butler, refused to certify that Baghdad had
destroyed its weapons of mass destruction.
	   Iraq's ambassador, Nizar Hamdoon, said that Iraq's Aug. 5
decision to freeze cooperation with weapons inspectors was
unchanged.
	   ``We found nothing in Shah's initiative that would satisfy our
concerns,'' Hamdoon said.
	   Negotiations with Shah were continuing, but ``our concerns will
have to be met,'' he said.
	   Iraq has demanded an end to sanctions imposed after Baghdad
invaded Kuwait in 1990, touching off the Gulf War. Iraqi officials
claim they have complied with U.N. resolutions demanding that they
destroy their long-range missiles and chemical, biological and
nuclear weapons.
	   After receiving the briefing from Knutsson, the council
considered Japanese-drafted letters that diplomats said would
encourage U.N. weapons inspectors to try to carry out inspections
in the face of Iraq's new ban.
	   The letters were to be sent to Butler, the head of the U.N.
Special Commission, and the head of the International Atomic Energy
Agency, Mohammed El Baradei, who both reported last week that their
work was being undermined by Baghdad's decision.
	   According to a draft of the letter, the council called Iraq's
actions ``totally unacceptable,'' and said its members ``reiterate
their full support of the IAEA and UNSCOM in the full
implementation of their mandates.''
	   ``Iraq is obliged under the relevant Security Council
resolutions to provide the IAEA/UNSCOM with the cooperation
necessary for them to undertake their activities,'' it said.
	   With the low-key response, the council was trying to force Iraq
to make the next major move after its Aug. 5 decision, diplomats
said.
	   If Baghdad blocks an inspection, council members could more
easily hold Baghdad in violation of U.N. resolutions and a February
agreement that gave them unconditional access to suspected weapons
sites. To date, the council has only said Iraq's Aug. 5 freeze on
inspections ``contravened'' the agreement, a semantic detail which
prevented council members from taking tougher action.
	   Shah was expected to return Thursday to New York, and council
members were expected to get a personal briefing from him soon
thereafter. On Monday, Aziz briefed President Saddam Hussein and
the Iraqi cabinet on the outcome of the discussions.
	   ``What is happening right now is a record is being established,
a documentary record of Iraq's violations and its refusals to
comply,'' said U.S. Ambassador Bill Richardson.
	   The current council president, Danilo Turk of Slovenia, rejected
suggestions that the council's tame reaction pointed to a
reluctance to take action to force Iraqi compliance.
	   ``This is only the beginning of the situation,'' he said, adding
that it took months for the council to formulate a tough stance
during the last dispute over inspections.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-UN-Iraq, 3rd Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
