<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-du Maurier Open,0186 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Jeyaseelan rains on Pratt's parade
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MONTREAL (AP) _ Sonya Jeyaseelan gave Canadian tennis fans
something to cheer about Monday.
	   The Oakville, Ontario, native, a wild-card entrant ranked 125th
in the world, benefited from a lengthy rain delay to knock off
Nicole Pratt of Australia 7-5, 6-3 and advanced to the second round
of the du Maurier Open.
	   ``I started off pretty nervous and I tried to overhit the ball,
but when we had the rain delay, I talked to my coach and he told me
to just calm down and relax,'' the 22-year-old Jeyaseelan said. ``I
came out feeling much more comfortable.''
	   The match was delayed by rain for more than an hour with the
score tied 4-4 in the first set. When play finally resumed,
Jeyaseelan dictated tempo and covered the court well, reaching and
often punishing Pratt's short balls in a grueling baseline duel.
	   In other matches, 12th-seeded Dominique Van Roost of Belgium
eliminated Canada's Jana Nejedly 6-4, 6-2 and No. 16 Ai Sugiyama of
Japan ousted Nathalie Dechy of France 7-6, 7-5 (7-2).
</TEXT>
