<SLUG> BC-Guyana-Telephone,0190 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Commission to investigate Guyana's telephone monopoly
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   GEORGETOWN, Guyana (AP) _ The Guyanese government said Monday it
will begin reviewing its monopoly agreement with the country's
telephone company.
	   The Public Utilities Commission will begin hearings Aug. 24 to
probe the contract with the Guyana Telephone Company, which is
controlled by U.S. Virgin Islands-based Atlantic Tele Network.
	   The government of this South American country has a 20 percent
stake in the utility.
	   Atlantic Tele Network and government regulators have had an
uneasy relationship following the 1991 privatization agreement that
gave the company a 20-year monopoly.
	   Politicians were outraged when the company began opening
international sex chat lines, but Atlantic Tele Network claimed the
lines helped subsidize cheap telephone service.
	   The government allowed the company to raise its rates by 60
percent in January, but later cut the increase to 30 percent and
began an investigation into the company's complaints that income
from the chat lines had dropped.
	   Guyana Telephone has about 60,000 subscribers. 	   
</TEXT>
