<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Balloon Quest, 9th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
The man who fell to Earth: Balloon adventurer ends up in the ocean
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Fossett moved to New Zealand ship, expected
arrival in Townsville &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos SYD101-103
 &UR; By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ Adventurer Steve Fossett's dream of
flying his balloon nonstop around the world turned into a nightmare
as lightning storms and hail knocked him out of the sky and sent
him crashing into the South Pacific.
	   The schooner Atlanta picked up the U.S. millionaire-adventurer
Monday night from the Coral Sea about 500 miles (800 kilometers)
off Australia's east coast, New Zealand Defense Force spokesman
Bill Morley said.
	   Fossett was safe aboard the 60-foot (18 meter) Atlanta and was
taken aboard the New Zealand navy tanker HMNZS Endeavour on Tuesday
morning, Morley said.
	   Nearby rescue ships and planes had stood guard as Fossett bobbed
in a life raft dropped Monday morning by a French air-sea rescue
plane sent from Noumea, New Caledonia.
	   Fossett was in regular radio contact with a Royal Australian Air
Force Hercules C-130, the Australian Maritime Safety Authority
said.
	   ``The rescue was very straight-forward. Mr. Fossett is in good
health and given that he is out of danger, they might proceed to
Townsville (Australia) tonight,'' Authority spokesman Brian Hill
said.
	   He is expected to be at Townsville in about 2-1/2 days.
	   After drifting swiftly around two-thirds of the world nonstop,
Fossett's balloon Solo Spirit was ripped by a violent lightning
storm.
	   ``He said he was caught in a giant thunderstorm with hail and
lightning which actually ruptured his balloon,'' said Darren Curtis
from Australia's TV 7 Network, aboard the Australian Hercules
C-130.
	   ``He says when he hit the ocean his balloon capsule caught fire
and he had to evacuate into a tiny life raft,'' Curtis said, after
talking to Fossett via the plane's radio.
	   Fossett said it was a wild ride from his initial altitude of
29,000 feet to the water.
	   ``Amazing,'' he said in an interview with Curtis. ``Tremendous
sheets of hail just flooding me and my greatest descent rate on
altimeter was 25,000 feet a minute.''
	   At Solo Spirit balloon mission control in St. Louis, Missouri,
media control spokesman Alan Blount said the rate of descent
described by Fossett would amount to dropping at a rate of almost
45 miles (72 kilometers) per hour.
	   ``He is fortunate. There are not too many of us around that have
been in a storm like that,'' said Blount.
	   Mission Control had alerted Australian authorities at 1 a.m.
Monday (1500 GMT Sunday) that Fossett's emergency beacon had been
activated in the Coral Sea.
	   But his splashdown in the wreckage of the Solo Spirit among
uncharted coral reefs near the Chesterfield Islands meant rescue
ships had to navigate cautiously after sunset.
	   The first boat to arrive was the Australian yacht Atlanta, whose
skipper Laurie Piper negotiated the maze of reefs in darkness.
	   Solo Spirit Mission Control director Alan Blount said a severe
thunderstorm system that showered 10,000 lightning strikes over the
Coral Sea most likely caused the crash landing.
	   Fossett had dreaded the possibility of ditching at sea.
	   ``An ocean landing would be very scary,'' he said before setting
off from Argentina 10 days ago in his bid to be the first to fly a
balloon around the world nonstop.
	   About five hours before Fossett's warning locator sounded,
meteorologist Bob Rice had cautioned the balloonist he was
approaching strong thunderstorms _ and that they would be nearly
impossible to avoid.
	   Fossett had a long stretch of the Pacific Ocean between
Australia and Argentina to go and had at least another five days of
travel before he was expected to reach South America, where he left
from on Aug. 7.
	   He had traveled 15,200 miles (24,460 km) when he crashed.
	   The 54-year-old Fossett, from Chicago, was making his fourth
attempt to fly around the world. He has also run marathons, climbed
mountains and raced in the Iditarod dog sled race in Alaska. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Balloon Quest, 9th Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
