<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP News Summary,0729 </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   A summary of late news from The Associated Press. Some items
have moved on this circuit in expanded form with ``i'' or ``f''
category codes:
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ U.S. President Bill Clinton underwent more
than 5 1/2 hours of grand jury questioning Monday about his
relationship with Monica Lewinsky. His attorney, David Kendall,
said the president ``testified truthfully'' and hoped the
appearance would end the investigation into the president's
``private life.'' Clinton planned to address the nation later
Monday, Kendall said. Clinton had been prepared by his lawyers to
acknowledge in his testimony that he had an ``inappropriate
relationship'' with the former White House intern and answer the
inevitable questions about whether it was sexual and whether he
sought to conceal it, advisers said. The speech being drafted for
Clinton acknowledged an intimate relationship with Ms. Lewinsky and
expressed regret at not setting the record straight sooner, an
official said on condition of anonymity. (US-CLINTON
INVESTIGATION-TESTIMONY)
	   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) _ Police arrested the son of a
leading Sinn Fein critic on suspicion he helped commit Northern
Ireland's worst-ever terror attack, a car bomb that killed 28
people and tore up the center of a small town. Police took Shane
Mackey, 19, and four other people at dawn Monday from their homes
near Omagh, scene of Saturday's blast, 70 miles (110 kilometers)
east of Belfast. Under British anti-terrorist law they can be
interrogated for up to a week before being released or charged. At
Stormont, the British government's headquarters in Northern
Ireland, police and military chiefs from both parts of Ireland
brainstormed Monday about how to rout Irish Republican Army
dissidents opposed to Northern Ireland's peace accord. (NORTHERN
IRELAND)
	   KINSHASA, Congo (AP) _ After weekend meetings in Angola with the
Angolan and Namibian leaders, Congo's President Laurent Kabila
briefly returned Monday to his embattled capital, Kinshasa, where
he defiantly claimed he would defeat an advancing rebel army. Then
he headed to Lubumbashi to try to rally support. Kabila has been
traipsing from Cuba to southern Congo to Angola in recent weeks,
looking for friends to help hold off the rebels _ an army of his
former Rwandan allies, ethnic Tutsi fighters and disaffected
members of the president's own military. (CONGO)
	   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) _ A suspect in the twin U.S. Embassy
bombings in East Africa has not admitted any role in the crimes or
implicated anyone else, the FBI said. Reports out of Pakistan,
where the man was apprehended, said the suspect confessed and named
his co-conspirators. The reports also said the man had ties to
renegade Saudi multimillionaire Osama bin Laden, who the United
States says is one of the world's major sponsors of terrorism. In a
joint statement, the FBI and Kenyan police identified the suspect
as Mohammed Saddiq Odeh, also known as Abdull Bast Awadh and
Mohammad Sadiq Howaida. He was arrested in Karachi after arriving
on a flight from Nairobi on Aug. 7, the day of the blasts in the
Kenyan capital and in Dar es Salaam, Tanzania, that killed 257
people and injured more than 5,500. The FBI and Kenyan police
revealed no breakthroughs Monday. (EMBASSY BOMBINGS)
	   SYDNEY, Australia _ American adventurer Steve Fossett's dream of
flying his balloon nonstop around the world ended when a fierce
thunderstorm knocked him out of the sky, hurling him 29,000 feet
(8,840 meters) into the Coral Sea. The Chicago millionaire was
rescued late Monday by a yacht that plucked him out of a life raft
500 miles (805 kilometers) off Australia's east coast. He had
traveled 15,200 miles (24,460 kilometers), completing two-thirds of
his planned journey, since taking off from Mendoza, Argentina, on
Aug. 7. Fossett was safe and in good condition aboard the 60-foot
(18-meter) schooner Atlanta, which was on its own around-the-world
trip when it received a ham radio report that Fossett was down,
spokeswoman Judy Jasper said from Fossett's flight operation
headquarters in St. Louis. Fossett told Australia's TV 7 Network
that his 150-foot (45-meter)-high, helium-and-hot air balloon _ the
Solo Spirit _ was pulled into a hail and lightning storm whose
strong winds ruptured the balloon's Mylar skin. (BALLOON QUEST)
</TEXT>
