<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   A summary of financial and business news from The Associated
Press at 0000 GMT. Stories carry ``f'' or ``i'' category codes and
move on this circuit in expanded form:
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ Blue-chip stocks rose sharply Monday as
investors looked for bargains amid turmoil in financial markets
abroad. The Dow Jones industrial average rose 149.85 points _ or
1.8 percent _ to 8,574.85 after wiping out an early 56-point slide.
The rally still left the Dow more than 750 points shy of record
terrain. The month-long slide from July 17's record of 9,337.97 has
been largely fueled by continuing turmoil on foreign markets and
signs of a domestic economic slowdown. (US-CLOSING STOCKS)
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ After spending billions of dollars during the past
three months to prop up Russia's weak currency, the government gave
up on Monday and let the ruble's value drop by up to 34 percent.
The policy turnaround will hit long-suffering Russians hard,
raising the price of imports that make up a large percentage of
consumer goods, including groceries. It also could provide more
pain for Russia's 1,500 banks _ up to half already were expected to
go belly-up in the next few weeks. The government also said it
would halt payment on government treasury bills and impose a 90-day
moratorium on payments of foreign debt. (RUSSIA-ECONOMY)
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ The U.S. government and the International
Monetary Fund urged Russian authorities Monday to act without delay
on economic reform measures that will be needed to bolster
investors' confidence following the decision to devalue the ruble.
``We believe it is critically important that the Russian
authorities move quickly to take actions to restore confidence,
including the adoption of a careful and cooperative approach to
dealing with its creditors and the full implementation of the
measures outlined in the Russian stabilization program agreed with
the IMF,'' U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin said in a
statement. (IMF-RUSSIA)
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ A dlrs 57 billion megamerger of NationsBank
Corp. and BankAmerica Corp., creating the largest bank in the
United States, won final regulatory approval Monday from the
Federal Reserve Board. The merger, announced in April and approved
by a 6-0 vote at a closed meeting of the Fed, vaults the combined
bank ahead of the nation's two largest: Citicorp and Chase
Manhattan. With 4,800 branch offices in 27 states and assets of
dlrs 580 billion, it will become the largest bank in the United
States and the third largest in the world. (US-NATIONSBANK-BANK
AMERICA)
	   STUTTGART, Germany (AP) _ Daimler-Benz said Monday it has hooked
up with Shell to expand fuel-cell technology for cleaner cars, the
latest in a series of joint ventures between oil and car companies.
Daimler has been working on fuel cells since 1992, which use
hydrogen and oxygen to generate electricity to power a vehicle.
Daimler has been looking for a way to produce hydrogen on board so
that the cars wouldn't have to carry special tanks. The
Stuttgart-based automaker said Shell will bring to the partnership
a technology for extracting hydrogen from hydrocarbon fuels such as
gasoline and diesel, meaning electric-car drivers in the future
could fill up at regular gas stations.
(GERMANY-FUEL-CELL-PARTNERSHIP)
	   PARAMUS, New Jersey (AP) _ Toys R Us Inc.'s second-quarter
earnings dropped more than 60 percent from a year ago, hurt by weak
sales of video game players, virtual pets, plush dolls and action
figures. The world's largest toy retailer earned dlrs 13.5 million,
or 5 cents a share on a diluted basis, in the quarter ended August
1, compared with dlrs 36.7 million, or 13 cents a share on a
diluted basis, a year ago. The 1998 results included a dlrs 3.7
million charge for the early retirement of debt. Sales were dlrs
2.02 billion, compared with dlrs 1.99 billion last year.
(US-EARNS-TOYS R US)
	   PALO ALTO, California (AP) _ Hewlett-Packard Co. on Monday
reported marginally higher third-quarter profits, weighed down by
Asia's economic slump and slower demand for its high-tech products.
The results exceeded Wall Street's diminished expectations.
Hewlett-Packard, the world's third-largest computer company, earned
dlrs 621 million, or 58 cents a share on a diluted basis, in the
three months ended July 31. That was 1 percent higher than the
profit of dlrs 617 million, also 58 cents a diluted share, reported
a year ago. The company had slightly more outstanding shares in the
just-ended quarter. Revenue rose 5 percent to dlrs 10.98 billion
from dlrs 10.47 billion. (US-EARNS-HEWLETT-PACKARD)
</TEXT>
