w2398 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Norway-SpanishFlu     08-17 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Norway-Spanish Flu,0604 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Scientists set to probe frozen Arctic graves for deadly virus
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By DOUG MELLGREN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONGYEARBYEN, Norway (AP) _ Eighty years ago, the Spanish Flu
virus killed tens of millions before it disappeared. Scientists
trying to pry its secrets out of an Arctic cemetery are taking no
chances that they might bring it back to life.
	   The four-nation team believes frozen remnants of the virus are
in six bodies buried in permafrost in this island outpost north of
the Norwegian mainland. On Monday, they were assembling equipment
for exhuming the bodies.
	   The research team, which includes experts from Norway, Canada,
Britain and the United States, hopes the viral material that may
have been frozen in the bodies will permit the construction of a
genetic profile of the virus.
	   According to Kirsty Duncan, a Canadian medical geographer who
leads the 15-member team, that could help explain how the 1918
virus killed so many people and then disappeared.
	   ``My first focus in the next few weeks is safety,'' Duncan said.
	   Experts say there is virtually no chance of finding a living
sample of the virus that killed more people than fighting in World
War I. The virus, first detected at Fort Funstan, spread rapidly
among troops sent to Europe in World War I. Victims suffered a
sudden fever, chills, headache, malaise, muscle pain, pneumonia and
rapid death.
	   The illness ended up with the misnomer ``Spanish Flu'' because
Spain was neutral, and openly admitted an epidemic while warring
nations kept it secret, according to Tom Bergan, a Norwegian
physician on the team.
	   Duncan, 31, of the Universities of Windsor and Toronto in
Canada, began a quest to uncover the secrets of the Spanish Flu
five years ago, after reading of its depredation.
	   ``I was horrified when I realized that we still didn't know what
this disease was that killed 20 to 40 million people,'' she said
Monday.
	   Duncan believes frozen bodies of victims could provide tissue
samples holding the virus' secrets. She checked in Alaska, Iceland
and Russia until the search lead to Longyearbyen, a town with a
population of 1,200. It is a mining outpost on Norway's glacial
Svalbard Archipelago, just 950 kilometers (500 miles) from the
North Pole.
	   In a small cemetery, below a steep mountainside and the
weathered wooden derricks of a coal mine, she found the
gravemarkers of seven flu victims, all of whom died in the first
week of October 1918.
	   Duncan said the graves were hard to find. Svalbard did not
become Norwegian territory until 1925. Before that, there were no
church or government death records. Mining companies kept records,
but they seemed long-gone. However, a local schoolteacher had kept
them.
	   Duncan set up a team of experts and gained permission from local
and national authorities in Norway and from all but one of the
seven families of the victims buried in the graves.
	   Before the digging, the team will have erected an inflatable
tent over the graves. It has airlocks, like a space ship, to
prevent any contamination, however unlikely, from spreading.
	   The few scientists allowed to enter the tent will wear
protective clothing, and have outside air supplies. Precious
samples of the tissue will be sent, on separate aircraft, to
laboratories in Norway, the United States, Canada and England. The
work will take about three weeks, while analysis could take 1.5
years.
	   Local officials seem convinced there is no threat.
	   ``I have not felt that there is any unrest or fear,'' said
Svalbard Governor Ann-Kristin Olsen.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Norway-Spanish Flu; CT:i; 
