w2399 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Congo-Kabila'sRecruit     08-17 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Congo-Kabila's Recruits,0583 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Searching for money, jobless men sign up for Kabila's army
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo KIN102 &QL; 
 &UR; By IAN STEWART &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KINSHASA, Congo (AP) _ Holding in his hand a crumpled sheet of
paper covered with a diagram of an AK-47 assault rifle, Edmund
Mboyo is ready to go off to war for President Laurent Kabila _ if
he's paid.
	   Faced with an army of rebels approaching Congo's capital of
Kinshasa, Kabila has launched a massive drive to recruit new
soldiers to defend his troubled government.
	   ``The people must be brave,'' Kabila declares during a state
radio broadcast. ``This is the message I have for my people, I am
asking them to face up to this plot, to arm themselves, to support
their army, and to defeat the aggressors.''
	   Elsewhere, Kabila has been shuttling to countries near and far,
including Angola and Cuba, in search of support for his government.
	   But at home, Kabila's call to arms has been answered by
thousands of out-of-work men who sign up for the money, if not for
love of country.
	   ``Many of the men here haven't eaten for days, some of them have
been sleeping on the ground,'' Mboyo said of the thousands of men
who every day for more than a week have converged on Kinshasa's
main soccer stadium, where the recruiting is taking place.
	   On Monday, at least 10 trucks filled with young men, still in
their civilian clothes and unarmed, shipped off for short-term
training _ perhaps a few days worth, one recruiting officer said on
condition of anonymity.
	   From there, they'll head to a front line that each day
reportedly moves closer and closer to Kinshasa.
	   An initial wave of support from all quarters of society to join
Kabila's military ranks has dwindled, apparently leaving the job of
defending the city to the jobless.
	   Many now joining the army say they are desperate for a paycheck.
But it is far from certain whether they would get one _ many of
Kabila's soldiers-turned-rebels say they quit the government force
for lack of pay.
	   Although government statistics are not available, independent
surveys and estimates by international aid agencies indicate that
as many as 75 percent of Kinshasa's young men are out of work.
	   Gone unfulfilled are pledges by Kabila to rejuvenate an economy
left impoverished by former dictator Mobutu Sese Seko.
	   Where weeks and months ago groups of men milled on streets
corners, they now line up in regimental rows on the dusty grounds
outside the soccer stadium.
	   The elite corps of Kabila's army _ mostly former Rwandan allies
_ defected weeks ago to join the rebellion. Those troops still
loyal to Kabila are already fighting to hold off the enemy's
advance.
	   One new recruit, Suku Landu Elusee, a 24-year-old unemployed
television repairman, suspects most of the president's new recruits
may not actually fight if they don't get paid.
	   ``If we go to fight it's because we have nothing else here,'' he
said. ``Joining the army means money for us and our families.''
	   Dozens of would-be recruits clustered on the stadium grounds to
discuss their khaki-colored future and the state of the country.
	   Asked for show of hands of how many had jobs, not one hand was
raised. Would they would fight for their country? A flurry of
hands.
	   Would they fight if they weren't paid? Hands drop, people murmur
and drift away from the gathering.
	   ``We're happy to be soldiers,'' said Mboyo, ``But the way to win
this war is to pay your soldiers.'' 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
