<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Kenya-Embassy in Limbo,0583 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Security tensions prevail at relocated Nairobi embassy
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With Embassy Bombings &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos NAI101-103 of Aug. 17 &QL; 
 &UR; By DAVE CARPENTER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) _ Coils of barbed wire, mounds of sandbags
and sniffer dogs confront visitors to the temporary new U.S.
Embassy in Kenya's capital. Tense soldiers man barricades a block
away, and a sharpshooter glares down from the roof.
	   If a siege mentality prevails at the nine-story red brick
building on a quiet side street, it's understandable. Officials are
determined that what happened Aug. 7 won't happen again.
	   Just two kilometers (a little more than a mile) away stands the
badly damaged shell of the embassy attacked by a truck bomb,
killing 247 people and raising immediate questions about safety at
U.S. missions worldwide.
	   A sense of shock and emergency is evident too inside, where
embassy workers are crammed into offices of the U.S. Agency for
International Development.
	   ``The adrenaline is still pumping and you don't go back to
normal overnight,'' Stephen Nolan, the embassy's administrative
counselor, told reporters Monday.
	   Nolan said he feels safe at the temporary facility. More than
security concerns or the disarray of the sudden move, he added,
they are still dealing with the trauma of human loss. At least 46
people, a dozen of them Americans, were killed inside the downtown
embassy building.
	   No damage estimate has been issued for the five-story building,
where the bomb's violent impact smashed in windows and walls and
left mounds of wrecked cabinets, computers and desks. Nolan
characterized damage only in the millions of dollars, calling the
building ``a complete writeoff.''
	   ``We lost over 500 years of experience in terms of personnel _
that's the real loss,'' he said. And ``they were friends and
colleagues.''
	   Last week, trying to return to business as usual, the embassy
shifted functions to the USAID building. It is wedged into a
neighborhood where residents of adjacent flats are so close they
could peer in the embassy's windows while hanging laundry on their
balconies.
	   The close proximity may partially account for the tension of the
Americans guarding it, suspiciously scrutinizing all non-Americans.
``He's got to stay with you!'' an Air Force soldier barks at
American reporters, warning that they keep an eye on a Kenyan
colleague even though he has journalist's credentials.
	   Washington has sent a team of officials to look at interim
office space and study where the new, permanent embassy will be
located. No formal decision has been made on what to do with the
old embassy.
	   Some Kenyans have suggested turning the site into a memorial,
but that seems unlikely considering the value of prime downtown
real estate.
	   The United States holds a 99-year lease on the property, which
it secured from the Kenyan government before building the embassy
in the mid-1970s. As the leaseholder in perpetuity, it has the
right to rent out the building, raze it or build another.
	   Whatever happens, U.S. spokesman Chris Sharf said last week:
``We're not going back there _ that's for sure.''
	   On Tuesday, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright was
expected to stop briefly at the new site during her one-day trip to
Kenya and Tanzania, to show support for East Africans and embassy
staffers alike.
	   ``It's important for her to be here and important for us to have
her come,'' Nolan said.
</TEXT>
