r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UN-Iraq     08-17 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Iraq,0647 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Security Council meets to consider Iraq response
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS and UPDATES with council approving letters. TRIMS
outdated material. &QL; 
 &UR; By NICOLE WINFIELD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ With Iraq still defiant in its standoff
with U.N. weapons experts, the Security Council has approved a
muted message of support for inspectors that backs their work but
leaves it up to them to decide whether to test an Iraqi ban on
searches.
	   Council members on Monday finalized drafts of letters to send to
the top two weapons inspectors, who reported last week that their
work was being undermined by Baghdad's Aug. 5 decision to freeze
cooperation with the United Nations.
	   The council was expected to send the letters Tuesday. The drafts
fell short of what U.N. inspectors had sought when they asked for
council guidance on the impasse and indicated continued divisions
among the 15 members about how to deal with Iraqi noncompliance.
	   The drafts emerged after the council received a briefing on the
so-far unsuccessful outcome of meetings in Baghdad between U.N.
envoy Prakash Shah and Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz.
	   Iraq's ambassador, Nizar Hamdoon, said Baghdad's decision was
unchanged.
	   ``We found nothing in Shah's initiative that would satisfy our
concerns,'' Hamdoon said. Negotiations in Baghdad with Shah were
continuing, but ``our concerns will have to be met,'' he said.
	   Iraq has demanded an end to sanctions imposed after Baghdad
invaded Kuwait in 1990, touching off the Gulf War. Iraqi officials
claim they have complied with U.N. resolutions demanding that they
destroy their long-range missiles and chemical, biological and
nuclear weapons.
	   Iraq froze cooperation with U.N. inspectors after the chief
inspector, Richard Butler, refused to certify that Baghdad had
destroyed its weapons of mass destruction.
	   Letters to Butler, the head of the U.N. Special Commission, and
the head of the International Atomic Energy Agency, Mohammed El
Baradei, were to try to encourage them to carry out their work in
the face of Iraq's new ban, diplomats said.
	   The resulting drafts didn't go so far as to encourage
inspections but instead repeated the council's backing for
inspectors' work.
	   According to a final draft of the letter, the council called
Iraq's actions ``totally unacceptable.'' It said council members
``reiterate their full support of the IAEA and UNSCOM in the full
implementation of their mandates.''
	   Russia, France and China _ traditionally more sympathetic to
Baghdad _ opposed U.S. efforts to give inspectors clear
instructions that they should conduct searches according to their
mandates, a Western source said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
	   The letter ``doesn't explicitly instruct UNSCOM. It's more
reminding them that they have the power to do this themselves,''
said the source.
	   The tame response was an indication of the disunity in the
council but also was intended to try to force Iraq to make the next
major move, diplomats said.
	   If Baghdad blocks an inspection, council members could more
easily hold Baghdad in violation of U.N. resolutions and a February
agreement that gave them unconditional access to suspected weapons
sites. To date, the council has only said Iraq's Aug. 5 freeze on
inspections ``contravened'' the agreement, a semantic detail which
prevented council members from taking tougher action.
	   ``What is happening right now is a record is being established,
a documentary record of Iraq's violations and its refusals to
comply,'' Richardson said.
	   Richardson called the letters strong, though he said the council
must now rely on Secretary-General Kofi Annan to try to work out an
end to the crisis.
	   U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said Monday that Annan sees no
personal role in the standoff.
</TEXT>
