<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-Pilot Pen,0363 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Soggy start mars beginning of Pilot Pen
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By EVAN BERLAND &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW HAVEN, Connecticut (AP) _ Geoff Grant beat Slava Dosedel in
straight sets Monday in the only match to be completed before rain
halted much of the first day of play at the Pilot Pen International
tennis tournament.
	   The rain had stopped by nightfall, allowing workers to dry one
court for the two scheduled evening matches: Alex O'Brien, the 1996
tourney champ, was to face Max Mirnyi, and Marat Safin was to play
Mark Woodforde.
	   A constant rain earlier in the day left several matches
dangling, including that of Jan Siemerink, the highest seed playing
Monday. The ninth seed from the Netherlands took a 5-4 lead over
Ecuadoran Nicholas Lapentti into the locker room.
	   Crowd favorite MaliVai Washington was leading 6-4, 1-3 when rain
stopped his match against Canadian Sebastien LaReau.
	   Grant, a wild card player, won 6-2, 6-3 over Dosedel and faces
Wimbledon finalist Goran Ivanisevic on Tuesday.
	   ``It really couldn't be a better time to have that kind of
challenge,'' Grant said.
	   He has won twice on the Challenger Tour this year and said he is
especially pleased with his service returns, which will be needed
against the big-hitting Ivanisevic, who is seeded eighth.
	   Grant broke Dosedel's serve five times en route to the win.
	   Israeli Harel Levy was leading 7-5, 5-3 over Argentinian
Guillermo Canas and Frenchman Nicholas Escude was leading 6-4, 0-1
over German Rainer Schuttler when rain halted play.
	   Six day singles matches were postponed without players even
taking the court. Monday's day matches were pushed back to Tuesday.
	   Washington said he would rather have continued playing, but said
weather delays are just part of the game.
	   ``If you can deal with it over in London at Wimbledon ... you
can deal with it anywhere,'' he said.
	   Wimbledon champion Pete Sampras, the tournament's top seed, is
scheduled to play his first match Wednesday. Defending champ
Yevgeny Kafelnikov also had a first-round bye and is expected to
play Tuesday.
</TEXT>
