w2425 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Barbados-MostWanted     08-17 0241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Barbados-Most Wanted,0240 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Most wanted criminal in Barbados has death sentence overturned
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BRIDGETOWN, Barbados (AP) _ A mercy tribunal has overturned the
death sentence for Barbados' most famous ex-fugitive, the Barbadian
governor-general's office said Monday.
	   The Barbados Privy Council, a tribunal of island citizens that
considers appeals of sentences, ordered that 34-year-old murder
convict Winston Hall be imprisoned for life.
	   Hall was long considered Barbados's most-wanted criminal. He and
two other men, David Oliver and Peter Bradshaw, were sentenced to
hang in 1985 for the murder of the manager of Francia Plantation, a
farm on Barbados.
	   He escaped from police that year while on the way to a
courthouse and was recaptured in 1989 while stowing away on a
cruiseliner in St. Vincent.
	   He, Oliver and Bradshaw broke out of prison again in September
1991. Oliver and Bradshaw were captured soon afterward, but Hall
remained a fugitive until he was arrested in Trinidad and Tobago
earlier this year on an arson charge.
	   Oliver and Bradshaw also saw their death sentences converted to
life terms in prison because of a ruling by the British Privy
Council that convicts should not be kept on death row for more than
five years.
	   The British Privy Council is the supreme court for former
British colonies in the Caribbean.
	   Hall is being kept in a high-security cell specially built to
hold him.
</TEXT>
