r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LatinAmericanBriefs     08-17 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Latin American Briefs,0794 </SLUG>

 &UR; Eds: Contains items from Mexico and Colombia. &QL; 
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ An apparently drunk driver plowed his car
into a block party injuring 12 people, mostly teen-agers, the
government news agency Notimex reported Monday.
	   The party celebrating a girl's 15th birthday, a major event in
Mexican culture, was held in the street, not uncommon in poor
Mexico City neighborhoods.
	   The injured were between ages 9 and 15, Notimex said.
	   Party guests tried to lynch the car's owner and his son who was
driving, Notimex said.
	   Police rescued owner Hector Solache Chavez. He was taken to a
hospital with serious injuries. The name of the driver, who is a
minor, was not released.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) _ An estimated 300,000 Bogota motorists
are forbidden from driving their cars during rush hour under a
four-month trial that takes effect Tuesday in one of Latin
America's most congested cities.
	   Under the restrictions, drivers must take turns garaging their
cars during peak weekday morning and afternoon hours, according to
the last number of the vehicles' license plates. Violators face a
dlrs 25 fine equivalent to five times the minimum daily wage.
	   Bogota officials hope the prohibition will unclog arteries in a
chaotic metropolis where it can take two hours to cross town during
rush hour.
	   Buses, one of the city's main sources of congestion, are exempt
from the rules.
	   Skeptics say the measure, which resembles restrictions that had
limited success in other Latin American capitals such as Mexico
City, Caracas and Venezuela, could be circumvented by those who
acquire forged license plates, buy a second car or alter their
schedules to avoid rush hour. Tie-ups could occur all day instead
of just at rush hour, they warn.
	   ``The cure could be worse than the illness,'' influential
columnist Enrique Santos Calderon wrote in El Tiempo newspaper
Sunday.
	   Santos called the measures well-intentioned, however, and said
they would test the civic spirit of Bogotanos, who have grown to
accept originally controversial laws prohibiting late-night alcohol
sales and reserving some arteries for bicyclists and walkers on
Sundays and holidays.
	   ``It will be an interesting experiment, '' he wrote.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   SAN CRISTOBAL DE LAS CASAS, Mexico (AP) _ Fifteen prisoners at a
jail in San Cristobal de la Casas tried Monday to intimidate and
extort money from all 215 of their colleagues.Other prisoners,
armed with sticks and stones, fought back.
	   Five prisoners, apparently from both sides, were injured before
guards stepped in.
	   Jail Director Carlos Ramirez Cruz said the fight started in the
facility's main patio.
	   The injured were treated at a medical office inside the jail,
about 450 miles (725 kilometers) southeast of Mexico City.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Nine inmates who tried to climb a prison
fence to escape were thwarted by guards who opened fire on them,
the prison director said Monday.
	   While accomplices staged a fight in another part of the prison
to distract guards, nine inmates used a handmade wooden ladder to
try to scale the fence, said Victor Reyes Tapia, prison director
for Puebla, 65 miles (104 kilometers) southeast of Mexico City.
	   Guards in observation towers spotted the escape attempt and
opened fire. There were no injuries, Reyes Tapia told the
government news agency Notimex.
	   He said the inmates were confined in cells after the escape
attempt. In the Puebla prison, most inmates roam freely in a
central courtyard filled with restaurants, stores and prostitutes.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ A giant high-frequency telescope being built
in Puebla state with U.S. and Mexican funding is expected to begin
operating in 2000, opening a new channel for scientists to study
the origins of the universe, a report said Monday.
	   The Grand Millimetric Telescope will be the largest and most
powerful of its kind in the world, project director Emmanuel Mendez
Palma told the El Universal daily. It will sit at an altitude of
15,945 feet (4,860 meters) on La Negra, Mexico's fifth-highest
mountain, southeast of Mexico City.
	   The telescope's parabolic antenna, measuring nearly 55 yards (50
meters) across, will pick up high-frequency waves emitted by
objects in the universe, Mendez Palma said.
	   ``Construction of the Grand Millimetric Telescope is a crucial
jump in the scientific and technological development of Mexico,''
he said.
	   At a cost of more than dlrs 60 million, the project is being
funded by Mexican and U.S. government institutes, as well as the
state of Massachusetts.
	   President Ernesto Zedillo approved the project in 1992, when he
was public education minister.
</TEXT>
