<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tokyo stocks higher, dollar lower in early trading
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Tokyo stocks opened higher on Tuesday, led by blue
chip exporters such as Sony Corp., following a rally overnight on
Wall Street. The U.S. dollar edged lower.
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 81.71 points,
or 0.55 percent, to 14,876.37 in the first 30 minutes of trading.
On Monday, the Nikkei average plunged 329.27 points, or 2.18
percent.
	   The dollar bought 146.09 yen in early morning trading, down 0.36
yen from late Monday in Tokyo but above its late New York rate of
145.96.
	   The Dow Jones industrial average, which has fallen almost 10
percent since its peak of 9,337.97 on July 17, rebounded Monday,
soaring 149.85 points, or 1.8 percent.
	   The Dow, which has been volatile recently, shrugged off the news
Monday that Russia implemented a sharp devaluation of its currency,
along with a forced restructuring of domestic debt.
	   Wall Street's rally boosted shares of Japanese high tech
manufacturers, whose fortunes are closely tied to sales in the U.S.
market.
	   Exporters Sony, TDK Corp. and NEC Corp. all gained.
	   Stocks also got a boost as investors started buying after
judging prices had fallen far enough given earnings expectations,
traders said.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section rose 6.14 points, or 0.53 percent, to 1,158.17. The
TOPIX tumbled 16.77 points, or 1.43 percent, on Monday.
	   In currency trading, the U.S. dollar slipped after Japanese
officials repeated their willingness to intervene to prop up the
ailing yen.
	   On Monday, Haruhiko Kuroda, who heads the Finance Ministry's
International Bureau, and Eisuke Sakakibara, vice finance minister
for international affairs, both said Japan was committed to
defending the yen.
	   Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese
government bond rose to 1.155 percent from Monday's finish of 1.150
yen, pushing its price down to 112.07 yen from 112.11 yen.
 &UR; (dj-mef) 	   
