w2448 &Cx1f; wstm-
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEA-India-SoftwareSwi     08-17 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-India-Software Swindlers,0815 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rogue firms in India's job-strapped software industry promise U.S.
</HEADLINE>
jobs &QL; 
 &UR; By NEELESH MISRA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ In the business world, they're called
head hunters. In the software trade, employment agents are called
body shoppers, and India has become a vast arcade offering new
talent seeking high paying jobs abroad.
	   But the industry is rife with fraud, and computer engineers are
increasingly becoming victims of high-tech swindlers.
	   K. Sambasiva Reddy gave up his job and paid his life savings of
350,000 rupees (dlrs 8,300) to register with a company promising
him specialized training, a visa and a job in the United States.
	   Neither a visa nor a job materialized. A year later, Reddy
poured gasoline and tried to burn himself to death in despair at
being cheated. He survived, and his evidence later led to the
arrest of the company's owner.
	   Dozens of advertisements appear every week in Indian newspapers
appealing to computer professionals. Some body shoppers are
legitimate. Their candidates land good American jobs, joining some
1 million ethnic Indians living in the United States.
	   But some companies are bogus. Their clients often languish in
cramped apartments, shuttling between job interviews for which they
are underqualified. Some, like Reddy, don't go at all.
	   Body shopping is proliferating in a country with world-class
manpower in an industry growing by 55 percent a year, but where
venture capital is scarce. A software firm lacking finance may find
it easier to market its engineers than its product, trade officials
say.
	   The practice will grow even more if the U.S. government raises
its ceiling of visas for highly skilled workers to 190,000
annually. The American high-tech industry has been clamoring for an
increase in H-1B visas, now capped at 65,000. That limit was hit in
May, four months before the start of the new fiscal year.
	   ``This is the highest priority item for our industry,'' John
Boidock, vice president of government relations for Texas
Instruments, said in Washington. The Senate in May swiftly adopted
the legislation, but it has run aground in the House amid criticism
over a lack of safeguards ensuring Americans wouldn't be displaced
by cheaper foreign labor.
	   The passage of the bill is likely to lead to a spurt in the
number of Indian computer engineers moving to U.S. jobs.
	   ``Over 60 percent of Indian firms indulge in body shopping,''
said R.H. Naqvi, executive director of the federally-funded
Electronics and Computer Software Export Council, one of the
largest industry bodies in the country with over 700 members.
	   Naqvi said only 5 percent of all software companies were engaged
in actual on-site software projects abroad and in developing new
packages.
	   ``The big players are committed and honest, but some small
companies see this as a quick moneymaking opportunity,'' said Ravi
Warriar, president of Advanced Technology Labs. ATL partners
Microsoft in teaching engineers the Computer Object Model _
Microsoft's showpiece technology _ and then provides them
employment in the United States.
	   ``Mavericks know how to make a quick buck in a boom market,'' he
said. ``They falsify documents to push people to the States. There
are several cases of people starving because they did not have the
qualifications which were claimed and so didn't get jobs,'' Warriar
said.
	   India's software industry employs between 150,000 and 200,000
skilled workers, according to industry estimates.
	   For companies in the employment business which lure these
professionals, the 1996 U.S. immigration legislation in the U.S.
marked a significant victory.
	   Technology concerns lobbied successfully for the elimination of
language that would have restricted business immigration, allowing
software companies to continue hiring foreign engineers because of
a shortage of qualified U.S. college graduates. Many Indian
computer experts have three-year visas that may be renewed for
another three.
	   A powerful conglomerate of Indian software companies said it
will launch a clampdown this month on firms found defrauding
engineers.
	   ``We are beginning with an advertising campaign to make people
aware of the way these companies operate,'' said Dewang Mehta,
director of the National Association of Software and Service
Companies. The campaign will begin in Hyderabad, the southern city
that has become India's fastest developing high-tech center.
	   ``We have started taking strong action. We don't want people to
be cheated by these fraud firms,'' he said.
	   But that might be difficult in a country where few laws exist to
regulate the industry.
	   ``The training business has become like a travel agency
business,'' Warriar said. ``Give them money, they get you a visa
and they take you to the U.S.''
</TEXT>
