r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Chile-Abortion     08-17 0456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Chile-Abortion,0455 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Senator wants tougher prison sentences for illegal abortions in
</HEADLINE>
Chile &QL; 
 &UR; By EDUARDO GALLARDO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) _ In a country that already has Latin
America's toughest anti-abortion laws, a conservative senator has
proposed making them even tougher.
	   Abortion is illegal in all circumstances, and the law punishes
women obtaining abortions and the people providing them with prison
terms of up to five years.
	   Arguing that there are too many illegal abortions in Chile, Sen.
Hernan Larrain wants to increase possible prison sentences to up to
15 years.
	   Until 1989, abortions were legal only when the mother's life was
in danger. But the late Adm. Jose Merino, a dominant figure in the
former military dictatorship of Gen. Augusto Pinochet, abolished
that exception, claiming modern medicine has enough resources to
make it unnecessary.
	   Because it is always illegal, it is impossible to determine the
exact number of abortions in Chile. But experts agree the country
has one of the highest rates in predominantly Roman Catholic Latin
America.
	   Estimates based on a variety of factors, including the 37,000
women seeking care every year at public hospitals for
abortion-related problems, put the annual number of abortions
between 150,000 and 175,000. About 1 in 50 women get an abortion in
any given year.
	   Larrain says that shows the law is ineffective and allows ``a
highly profitable abortion industry to develop.''
	   ``In 1996, for example, only 13 people were sentenced for
violating the anti-abortion law,'' Larrain said in an interview.
``It's clear that the current penalties have not been a
deterrent.''
	   His proposal changes the definition of abortion from a crime
against public morals to a crime against people, making the penalty
more severe.
	   The bill also would reduce sentences for women undergoing an
abortion if they report those responsible. A similar law exists for
terrorism.
	   Although convictions for women undergoing abortions are rare,
spending days or weeks in jail during a trial is common.
	   The fate of Larrain's bill is uncertain.
	   Socialist Sen. Carlos Ominami said it would only make illegal
abortions more expensive.
	   ``The measures to face this situation should include an
effective family planning program, a government support to
unmarried mothers,'' he said.
	   Justice Minister Soledad Alvear said she is totally opposed to
abortion.
	   ``But I think current penalties for abortion are strong enough,
and increasing them is not the correct way to go,'' she said.
``Instead, it is the duty of the government to develop policies
aimed at preventing situations that may lead to abortion.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Chile-Abortion; CT:i; 
