w2463 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Track-European     08-17 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Track-Europeans,0600 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ny spt for tuesday pms, ints for relay after 2400 gmt
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Kipketer makes up for absence of many other stars &QL; 
 &UR; By NESHA STARCEVIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) _ It may take a Kenyan to shine some
light on the European Championship in athletics.
	   Wilson Kipketer is now a Danish citizen, but he was born in
Kenya.
	   While Kipketer is eager to perform well at his first major
European competition as a Danish citizen, many other European stars
are staying away from the quadrennial event that starts Tuesday in
the Hungarian capital.
	   The most notable absentees are Sergey Bubka, the Ukrainian world
record holder in the pole vault and a six-time world champion, and
Marie Jose-Perec, the 200 and 400-meter Olympic champion from
France.
	   Bubka is skipping the championship because he said they didn't
figure in his training schedule. Perec is out because of a reported
squabble with the French track federation.
	   It leaves Kipketer, 800-meter world champion and record holder,
as probably the biggest star in the six-day championship.
	   With Bubka out, Russian pole vaulter Maksim Tarasov looks set to
take the pole vault crown, although he didn't sound particularly
excited about it.
	   ``I've never done the Europeans, only the world championships
since I was a junior,'' said Tarasov, whose greatest rival should
be French Olympic champion Jean Galfione. ``I live in Budapest, so
that's a reason I'm here.''
	   ``Apparently the Europeans aren't that interesting, there is no
money,'' added the '92 Olympic champion and silver medalist in last
year's worlds behind Bubka. ``I don't do the European indoors
either.''
	   ``I still want to save my best for the end of the season. I hope
you haven't seen my best yet.''
	   The field includes more than 1,300 athletes from 44 countries
with Germany fielding the largest team (123) followed by France
(103), Russia (101), Italy (83), Hungary (80) and Spain (76).
	   The event lacks depth, especially in the men's events.
	   The North Americans have been dominating the sprints this year,
while the Africans have been taking the distance races.
	   But world-class performances could come in the field events,
such as the high jump, triple jump, the shot put, hammer and
discus, in which European men usually dominate.
	   On the women's side, however, Europeans have been strong this
year, apart from the sprints.
	   Among the most watched women will be Germany's 33-year-old long
jumper Heike Drechsler, who is trying to equal the European record
of four straight gold medals in one event, which has been done by
two others, Janis Lusis in the javelin, 1962-1971, and Nadezhda
Chizhova in the shot put, 1966-74.
	   She looks in good shape to do it, coming off a jump of 7.05
(23-1 3/4) last week in Zurich. She also has a wind-assisted 7.12
(23-4 1/2) this season, her longest jump since winning the European
title four years ago.
	   Drechsler, coming off operations on both Achilles tendons 10
months ago, is free of injuries for the first time in three years.
	   Another German, Grit Breuer, will be trying to win her second
400-meter title after 1990 _ and a three-year drug ban.
	   The first medals to be awarded Tuesday will come in the men's
20K walk, the men's shot put and the men's 10,000 meters, where
Antonio Pinto of Portugal leads the field with a time of 27
minutes, 15.76 seconds this year.
	   In the shot put, Yugoslavia's Dragan Peric leads the Europeans
with 21.77 meters this season.
</TEXT>
