<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-US-Kids' Mall,0488 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mackie's World: Specialty mall caters to kids
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos NY181-182 &QL; 
 &UR; By LISA SINGHANIA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   GRAND RAPIDS, Michigan (AP) _ At the first mall for children,
conceived by husband-and-wife real estate developers as a tribute
to their 3-year-old son Mackie, parents shop where their kids want
to go.
	   The nearly dlrs 11 million enclosed mall has shoe, clothing and
music stores geared toward children, as well as a learning center,
a movie theater with car-shaped seats, and a food court that
includes one restaurant with more than 50 types of peanut butter
and jelly sandwiches.
	   For older children, there's a sports city with miniature golf,
basketball games and a racetrack. For the youngest, the mall
provides yellow cab-style strollers so their parents can taxi them
around.
	   ``Parents shop where their kids want to go,'' says Deb Colvin,
who began the project with husband, Pete, after their son died in
1995 of a rare intestinal disorder.
	   ``He would have loved it, especially the dinosaur,'' says
13-year-old Chris, Mackie's older brother, referring to the
life-size Tyrannosaurus rex that towers over the mall lobby.
	   The mall, which opened Aug. 15, grew out of a mealtime
discussion just two days before Mackie's death about the lack of
places for children to shop. It has since become an outlet for the
family's grief.
	   The Colvins say they hope profits from the mall will allow them
eventually to help neglected and abused children.
	   ``We wouldn't put Mackie's name on something that exploits
children,'' Mrs. Colvin says. ``The only way for us to help kids is
to do good business. You might not believe this of most developers,
but our main goal is to bring families together.''
	   Mrs. Colvin says the mall is perfect for a family town like
Grand Rapids, with about 200,000 people, 25 percent of them under
12.
	   ``We were finding in major cities there wasn't that much just
for kids, and you had to drive everywhere to get there,'' she says.
	   Coca-Cola and baby food-maker Gerber Products Co. agreed to put
their names on the project in exchange for the right to sell their
products. A bond sale on Wall Street netted more than dlrs 19
million.
	   ``I have seven grandchildren and I'm sure they'll want their
parents to come here every week,'' says Dixie Barnaby, one of 10
other investors who contributed dlrs 50,000 each.
	   The Colvins figure the mall will draw 2 million people a year
and could turn a profit by next year.
	   Mackie's World capitalizes on a growing trend toward specialty
malls, says Malachy Kavanagh, a spokesman for International Council
of Shopping Centers.
	   Other malls have created special areas for children, but he
knows of no mall dedicated to the younger set.
	   ``The only challenge they have is that as the population grows
up, there has to be a new generation to replace them,'' he says.
</TEXT>
