<SLUG> BC-APTV Advisory,1009 </SLUG>


<TEXT>
 &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  APTV'S 0100 OUTLOOK FOR TUESDAY 18 AUGUST 1998  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC; 
----
For Planner / Newsdesk use - stories expected to move in the next 12
hours  &QC;  &QC; 

 &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  CLINTON ADDRESS TO THE NATION LIVE
 &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC; 
----
Please note that President Bill Clinton is due to address the nation
to make a statement concerning his sworn testimony before the grand
jury at 0200 GMT.
----
It follows his testimony under oath about his relationship with
Monica Lewinsky, which was televised to the grand jury on Monday. A
knowledgeable source, speaking on condition of anonymity, claims
that in his testimony, Clinton acknowledged an extramarital
relationship with the former White House intern.
----	
Please be advised that APTV will carry Clinton's address to the
nation LIVE on our Global Video Wire from 0200 GMT until it
finishes.
----
All material will be Pool  &QC;  APTV Clients Only.
----
PLEASE NOTE: Timing of all tape replay and LIVE events may be
subject to change beyond APTV's control. Clients wishing to use
material live to air are advised to contact the Editor of the Night
on +44 171 427 4100 or Output on +44 171 427 4180.
----
EXPECTED:  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC; 
----
US: TESTIMONY WRAP - Sources close to the president claim that in
his testimony to the grand jury, President Bill Clinton did testify
that he had engaged in an inappropriate relationship with White
House intern Monica Lewinsky. APTV's comprehensive wrap includes
coverage of Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr leaving the White
House following the testimony, excerpts of a statement by
presidential lawyer David Kendall, analysis and file of President
Clinton's January 26 comment in he emphatically denied that he had
sexual relations with Lewinsky. (FIRST RUN 0300 EUROPE EARLY)
----
US: ADDRESS - Highlights of President Clinton's address to the
nation, in which he is expected to assure Americans he didn't
violate any laws and offer an explanation and perhaps an apology for
his denials last January. (FIRST RUN 0300 EUROPE EARLY)
----
US: ADDRESS REAX - APTV joins Americans in New York and Los Angeles
as they watch President Clinton's address to the nation and talks to
analysts about the contents of the address and the impact on the
presidency. (FIRST RUN EUROPE EARLY 0300)
----
IRAN: MEDIA - The media has become the latest battlefield in the
fight between Islamic hardliners and the more moderate government of
Iran. President Mohammad Khatami's liberation of the press has led
to a proliferation of independently-owned publications - which are
frequently shut down by Islamic hardliners. Meanwhile,
fundamentalists are using their papers to discredit supporters of
Khatami. (FIRST RUN 0300 EUROPE EARLY)
----
RUNNING:  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC; 
----
NIRELAND: MOWLAM WRAP - British and Irish ministers have hatched a
strategy for
crushing those responsible for the Omagh bombing, but shied away
from reintroducing internment in Northern Ireland. APTV has comment
from Ulster Secretary Mo Mowlam, Irish Justice Minister John
O'Donoghue, footage of Mowlam visiting the site of the blast and
speaking shortly afterwards, people signing condolence books and the
first of
several hearses leaving Omagh's makeshift morgue to carry caskets
back to grief-stricken homes for traditional Irish wakes. (FIRST RUN
0000 AUSTRALIA/NZ)
----
NIRELAND: OMAGH 4 - Wraps the day's events in Omagh, including
comment from Northern Ireland's First Minister David Trimble, wreath
laying, comment from the Reverend William McCrea - a former
Democratic Unionist Party MP - and stills of some of the victims.
(FIRST RUN 1700 F-L-A-S-H)
----
NIRELAND: SPAIN - Spain's deputy prime minister toured Omagh with
relatives of the Spanish dead and wounded. The package includes
comment from Francisco Alvarez Cascos. (FIRST RUN 1900 LATIN
AMERICA)
----
US: CLINTON 3 - Comprehensive wrap of the run-up to President
Clinton's testimony includes footage of Kenneth Starr and his team
and Clinton's lawyers arriving at the White house, the media corps
covering the story, aerials of the White House and sketches of the
president testifying in the map room. (FIRST RUN 1830 NORTHAM)
----
US: MARKETS - The Dow industrials rose nearly 150 points as
President Clinton began answering questions about Monica Lewinsky,
potentially removing one of the many
uncertainties dogging the stock market. (FIRST RUN 2355 F-L-A-S-H)
----
UN: IRAQ - APTV has the Iraqi U-N ambassador - Nizar Hamdoon - and
his U-S counterpart Bill Richardson commenting on the latest
developments in the standoff between Baghdad and U-N weapons
inspectors. (FIRST RUN 0000 AUSTRALIA/NZ)
----
ALBANIA: NATO 2 - NATO has begun a five-day military exercise in
Albania in a bid to display its collective might with regard to
easing the crisis in the besieged province of Kosovo. APTV has
coverage of the opening ceremony. (FIRST RUN 1930 NORTHAM)
----
DR CONGO REBELS - Congolese rebels have warned the political leaders
in their movement not to repeat the mistakes of Laurent Kabila, the
embattled Congolese head of state. APTV has coverage of rebel chief
Jean-Pierre Ondekane and his comments. (FIRST RUN 2130 LATIN
AMERICA)
----
CONGO: BRAZZAVILLE - The first ferry allowed to leave the Democratic
Republic of Congo in three days brought refugees fleeing the
unstable capital of Kinshasa to the neighbouring Congo Republic.
This package includes soundbites from evacuees. (FIRST RUN 1815
F-L-A-S-H)
