<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Northern Ireland,0756 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Northern Ireland prepares for first funerals from terrorist strike
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Recaps; will be topped after first funeral, tentatively
scheduled to begin at 1000 GMT &QL; 
 &UR; By KRISTIN GAZLAY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   OMAGH, Northern Ireland (AP) _ With all 28 victims finally
identified and five suspects in custody, the family of a mother and
young daughter killed in a terrorist car bombing prepared to say
goodbye Tuesday in the first in a long line of funerals.
	   The carnage and confusion that reigned on Omagh's Market Street
after the 500-pound (200-kg) car bomb exploded Saturday meant the
bodies were not released to their loved ones until Monday.
	   ``I'm sure we'll have a series of funerals through the week,''
said the Rev. Lawrence Dawson, the Catholic parish priest presiding
over back-to-back services Tuesday in nearby Augher for 30-year-old
Avril Monaghan, pregnant with twins, and her 18-month-old daughter
Maura.
	   Mrs. Monaghan's 65-year-old mother, Mary Grimes, also was killed
in the bombing. She will be buried Wednesday.
	   The Irish Republic town of Buncrana almost came to a standstill
as the hearses bearing the coffins of three local boys killed in
the bombing _ James Barker, 12, Sean McLoughlin, 11, and Oran
Doherty, 8 _ arrived home Monday night.
	   Hundreds of people waited for several hours at the County
Donegal border to see the coffins cross over, and mourners lined
the town's streets and stood in tearful silence as they passed.
	   ``This has been one of the most difficult and emotional duties I
have ever had to supervise,'' police superintendent Tom Long said.
	   Mo Mowlam, Britain's top official in Northern Ireland, toured
the destruction in Omagh on Monday night and assured residents that
authorities would stop at nothing to nail the bombers, whom she
called ``animals, obscene in what they have done.''
	   ``I just can't get out of my head the pain, the suffering that
is going on,'' she said. ``That is overwhelming.''
	   At dawn Monday, police had arrested five people in connection
with the attack _ the worst in Northern Ireland's history. The
suspects included 19-year-old Shane Mackey, the son of a leading
critic of the IRA-allied Sinn Fein party's support of April's peace
agreement.
	   No information was released about the suspects, believed to be
members of the ``Real IRA,'' made up of defectors from the Irish
Republican Army. Under British anti-terrorist law, the five can be
interrogated for up to a week before being released or charged.
	   Mowlam spent hours in talks Monday with police officials from
both Northern Ireland and the Irish Republic, grappling with how to
foil any further such deadly attacks.
	   After the session, she announced increased army and police
deployments along the border between the two states, but refused to
reveal other details.
	   When asked, however, whether both governments were discussing
whether to change their laws so that Real IRA suspects could be
convicted based only on testimony from anti-terrorist detectives,
Mowlam said: ``You're in the right ballpark.''
	   The young Omagh suspect's father, local councilman Francis
Mackey, said his son had been arrested as part of a British
conspiracy ``to demonize me for being honest and open in expression
of my political opinions.''
	   Mackey, re-elected last year while still a member of Sinn Fein,
now aligns himself with the 32 County Sovereignty Committee, a
group opposed to the peace agreement. It is led by Bernadette
Sands-McKevitt, sister of the martyred IRA hunger striker Bobby
Sands _ and common-law wife of the Real IRA's reputed commander.
	   Talk of politics was markedly absent in many of the towns across
Northern Ireland that numbered residents among the dead and 220
wounded. More than 100 people remained hospitalized, including 11
in critical condition. Nine children died, and a number of people
were blinded or crippled.
	   ``People are suffering in shock,'' said Gordon McLaren, a
shopkeeper in Augher who shook his head at the enormity of the
Monaghan family's loss. ``Has anyone talked of politics? No, they
have not.''
	   For the first time in the three-decade course of Northern
Ireland's conflict, foreign tourists were among the dead _ a
teacher and a 12-year-old student from Spain.
	   Spain's deputy prime minister, Francisco Alvarez Cascos, toured
Omagh with relatives of the dead and of the 11 wounded Madrid
students, including two girls hospitalized in Belfast with critical
head injuries.
</TEXT>
