<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-Pilot Pen, 1st Ld-Writethru,0407 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Soggy start mars beginning of Pilot Pen
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with suspension of both night matches &QL; 
 &UR; By EVAN BERLAND &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) _ Geoff Grant beat Slava Dosedel in
straight sets Monday in the only match to be completed before rain
halted play as the Pilot Pen International tennis tournament got
underway.
	   The rain stopped long enough to allow the start of one night
match, but a downpour about one hour later forced tournament
officials to call it a night and reschedule everything for Tuesday.
	   Tournament director Cliff Buchholz offered a positive spin.
	   ``Sometimes it's nice for the players to get a break. Some of
them probably need a day off,'' he said.
	   A constant rain earlier in the day left several matches
dangling, including that of Jan Siemerink, the highest seed playing
Monday. The ninth seed from the Netherlands took a 5-4 lead over
Ecuadoran Nicholas Lapentti into the locker room.
	   Crowd favorite MaliVai Washington was leading 6-4, 1-3 when rain
stopped his match against Canadian Sebastien LaReau.
	   Grant, a wild card player, won 6-2, 6-3 and faces Wimbledon
finalist Goran Ivanisevic on Tuesday.
	   ``It really couldn't be a better time to have that kind of
challenge,'' Grant said.
	   Grant has won twice on the Challenger Tour this year and said he
is especially pleased with his service returns, which will be
needed against the big-hitting Ivanisevic, who is seeded eighth.
Grant broke Dosedel's serve five times en route to the win.
	   Israeli Harel Levy was leading 7-5, 5-3 over Argentinian
Guillermo Canas and Frenchman Nicholas Escude was leading 6-4, 0-1
over German Rainer Schuttler when rain halted play. Alex O'Brien,
the 1996 Pilot Pen champ, had a one-set lead on qualifier Max
Mirnyi in the night match and was down 3-2 in the second set when
the rain put an end to Monday's competition.
	   Six day singles matches and one night singles match were
postponed without players even taking the court.
	   Washington said he would rather have continued playing, but said
weather delays are just part of the game.
	   ``If you can deal with it over in London at Wimbledon ... you
can deal with it anywhere,'' he said.
	   Wimbledon champion Pete Sampras, the tournament's top seed, is
scheduled to play his first match Wednesday.
</TEXT>
