<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japanese stocks rebound, dollar drops against yen in Tokyo
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with midday stock, late morning bond and
currency prices; ADDS 3rd graf stock trader quote, 6th graf comment
from Prime Minister Obuchi &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japanese stocks rebounded early Tuesday as
investors snapped up bargain-priced shares following a rally
overnight on Wall Street. The U.S. dollar fell against the yen.
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average surged 297.15
points, or 2.0 percent, to 15,091.81 as of midday. On Monday, the
average plunged 329.27 points, or 2.18 percent.
	   ``Selling yesterday was overdone, and Tokyo stocks may have
finally bottomed out,'' said Yasuo Ueki, general manager at Nikko
Securities Co.
	   The Dow Jones industrial average, which has fallen almost 10
percent since its peak of 9,337.97 on July 17, recovered Monday,
soaring 149.85 points, or 1.8 percent.
	   The Dow, which has been volatile recently, shrugged off the news
Monday that Russia implemented a sharp devaluation of its currency,
along with a forced restructuring of domestic debt.
	   Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi, meanwhile, expressed worry
Tuesday that Russia's devaluation of the ruble could negatively
impact economies around the world, Japan's Nikkei news wire
reported.
	   Still, Wall Street's rally boosted shares of Japanese high tech
manufacturers, whose fortunes are closely tied to sales in the U.S.
market.
	   Stocks also got a boost as investors started buying after
judging prices had fallen far enough given earnings expectations,
traders said.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section rose 17.03 points, or 1.48 percent, to 1,169.06. The
TOPIX tumbled 16.77 points, or 1.43 percent, on Monday.
	   On the Tokyo foreign exchange market, meanwhile, the dollar
bought 145.46 yen in late morning trading, down 0.99 yen from late
Monday in Tokyo and also below its late New York rate of 145.96.
	   The dollar lost ground against the yen after top Japanese
officials repeated their willingness to intervene to prop up the
ailing yen, traders said.
	   Japanese Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa said Tuesday that
Japan will conduct yen-supportive intervention in the foreign
exchange markets if necessary.
	   Also Tuesday, Haruhiko Kuroda, who heads the Finance Ministry's
International Bureau, reiterated that excessive weakness in the yen
is ``undesirable.''
	   In the fixed-income security market, the yield on the benchmark
No. 182 10-year Japanese government bond rose to 1.160 percent from
Monday's finish of 1.150 yen, pushing its price down to 112.04 yen
from 112.11 yen.
 &UR; (cd-dj-mef) 	   
</TEXT>
