<SLUG> BC-UN-Indonesia,0201 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Unicef calls situation in Indonesia international emergency
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Multiple threats to the health, well being
and basic education of Indonesia's children constitute an
international emergency, UNICEF said Monday.
	   Four million children under the age of 2 are severely
malnourished and more than 30 percent of the country's children are
at risk of failing to complete primary school, UNICEF chief Carol
Bellamy said in a release.
	   ``The fate of millions of Indonesian children and women is at
stake,'' she said. In addition, civil unrest has ``led to egregious
violations of human rights.''
	   Indonesia's economic crisis has seriously devalued the currency
and nearly doubled the cost of food, fuel and other basic consumer
goods.
	   Over dlrs 50 billion in emergency loans by the International
Monetary Fund, the World Bank and other agencies may not be enough
to turn things around, Bellamy said.
	   On the nutritional front, UNICEF is still well short of the dlrs
18 million a year needed to feed young children, despite generous
grants from Australia, Canada, Norway, the United States and
others, Bellamy said.
</TEXT>
