<HEADER>
w2539 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BalloonQuest     08-17 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Balloon Quest </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Downed balloonist feared he was plummeting toward death
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS previous, updates with new quotes from Fossett &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos SYD101-106
 &UR; By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ ``My gosh, I'm going to die,'' Steve
Fossett thought as his round-the-world balloon ripped apart in a
violent storm and plummeted 29,000 feet (8,800 meters) to the
shark-infested Coral Sea.
	   ``As I was going down, the balloon was just being thrown from
one side to another,'' the millionaire American adventurer said
Tuesday from the New Zealand naval ship Endeavour, which helped
rescue him.
	   Some 10,000 lightning strikes were recorded in the Coral Sea
area.
	   He said he saw huge sheets of hail, and laid down on the bench
in the capsule to prepare for the impact in the water.
	   ``Happily, the impact wasn't so bad,'' he said in an interview
with his mission control headquarters at Washington University in
St. Louis, Missouri. Fossett believes the capsule and the water
absorbed much of the impact of Monday's crash.
	   His capsule was falling at about 30 mph (48 kmph) while he used
burners under the damaged mylar balloon bag to slow the rate of
descent.
	   But he had told Australian TV that a fire broke out in his
capsule on impact, forcing him to ditch it and climb into a life
raft.
	   Fossett was being checked by medics on board the Endeavour but
was in fairly good health. He told his mission control people he
suffered half-inch (1.2 cm) burns on his wrist and nose but
otherwise was OK.
	   Fossett, who vies with British tycoon Richard Branson for the
title of the world's top balloonist, boarded the Endeavour on
Tuesday morning after being picked up overnight by the 18-meter
(60-foot) yacht Atlanta, on its own globe-circling trip, about 500
miles (800 km) off Australia's east coast.
	   Fossett was on the home leg of his fourth attempt to be the
first balloonist to fly non-stop around the world when his balloon,
Solo Spirit, was forced down in a thunderstorm.
	   Fossett set off from Mendoza, Argentina, on Aug. 7 and had
already broken his own distance record of 10,360 miles (16,673 km)
set in January 1997.
	   He had gone two-thirds of the way around the world, more than
15,200 miles (24,461 km) before the storm damaged the balloon,
sending it plunging into the sea.
	   His electronic position indicator beacon activated, sparking an
international search and rescue effort. A French military plane
from Noumea, New Caledonia, dropped him a life raft on Monday
morning containing food, water and a canopy to shield him from the
tropical sun.
	   Australian military rescue flights circled overhead Monday until
rescue ships could reach his position.
	   He is expected to arrive in Townsville, Australia, on the
Endeavour by Thursday evening.
	   Fossett said other ships were being dispatched to the area in
hopes of salvaging some of the capsule's items, including film,
fuel tanks, and cameras on board for the filming of a documentary.
	   Fossett had a long stretch of the Pacific Ocean between
Australia and Argentina to go and had at least another five days of
travel before he was expected to reach South America.
	   The 54-year-old Fossett, from Chicago, was making his fourth
attempt to fly around the world. He has also run marathons, climbed
mountains and raced in the Iditarod dog sled race in Alaska.
	   On his first around-the-world attempt in 1996, Fossett only
lasted 36 hours, ending up in eastern Canada.
	   His next try in January 1997 set a long-distance ballooning
record _ surpassed by Fossett on this trip _ and ended in
Sultanpar, India, where Fossett landed after running short of fuel
while awaiting clearance to fly over Libya.
	   In January, on his third effort, Fossett landed in a wheat field
in southern Russia.
	   Fossett's crash landing led to the sixth major rescue operation
in the seas surrounding Australia in recent years. Rescue costs,
which run into the millions of dollars, have been borne by
Australian taxpayers under international conventions covering
safety at sea.
	   There have been calls in recent years for ``contribution fees''
from around-the-world yacht race organizers, who receive hefty
commercial sponsorships, to help foot any rescue bills.
	   Had Fossett completed his flight, he would have set a world
record and won the Budweiser Cup and a U.S. dlrs 1 million prize.
Several more balloon syndicates plan to chase the prize in December
and January. 	   
</TEXT>
