<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-Pebble Beach,0715 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mickelson wins Pebble Beach tourney after six-month delay
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS previous &QL; 
 &UR; By ROB GLOSTER &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PEBBLE BEACH, California (AP) _ Against an idyllic backdrop,
Phil Mickelson won a tournament that began six months ago and
earned more than a half-million dollars in one round of golf.
	   Mickelson, rebounding from a lost weekend at the PGA
Championship, had six birdies in the final round Monday for a
one-shot victory over Tom Pernice in the AT and T Pebble Beach
National Pro-Am, a tournament that began in January.
	   The AT and T victory, his first since the opening week of the
season, earned Mickelson dlrs 450,000 as well as a dlrs 100,000
bonus for having the highest overall earnings in eight West Coast
events this year.
	   ``It was almost a golfer's dream to play Pebble Beach like
that,'' he said. ``To see those sea lions lying out on the rocks is
very relaxing. It was worth the wait.''
	   When the AT and T tournament began in late January, waves
crashed onto the 18th fairway. Sheets of rain turned sandtraps into
water hazards and gusty winds snapped treetops.
	   On Monday, months after the demise of El Nino, the tourney
resumed on an overcast, dry morning. The ocean was placid and there
was a cool breeze.
	   ``The course played totally different than it does in February
because the fairways were a lot firmer,'' Mickelson said. ``It was
such an enjoyable day to play Pebble Beach.''
	   Of the 168 pros who started the tournament, 125 returned for the
final round. Among those not returning were Tiger Woods, who
finished the second round 14 strokes off the lead, and Jack
Nicklaus. Also dropping out was Vijay Singh, who won the PGA
Championship on Sunday.
	   Mickelson's three-round total of 14-under 202 tied for the
lowest 54-hole score in AT and T tournament history. This was the
14th time the tournament had been shortened to 54 holes.
	   Pernice, playing the Poppy Hills course, was 13 under until he
three-putted No. 17 for a bogey. Still, he had an eagle putt on the
final hole with a chance to catch Mickelson, and missed it.
	   Jim Furyk shot a 68 on Pebble Beach to finish two shots behind
Mickelson. J.P. Hayes and Paul Azinger, playing on Poppy Hills,
also finished at 12-under.
	   Tom Watson, who entered the final round tied for the lead with
Tim Herron, carded a 72 and finished in a three-way tie for ninth
at 206. Herron was another two strokes back after a 74.
	   At the start of Monday's play, Mickelson was one stroke behind
the co-leaders, tied with Tom Lehman and Jay Haas. Haas shot a 70
and finished three shots off the pace, while Lehman, with a 71, was
another stroke back.
	   It took Mickelson only two days to recover from his collapse at
the PGA Championship.
	   Mickelson was just four strokes back heading into the third
round of the PGA Championship, but posted a 9-over 79 on Saturday
to fall out of the title chase.
	   He came back with a 67 on Sunday at Sahalee Country Club and
continued that strong play with a 5-under 67 on Monday at Pebble
Beach _ including a birdie on the final hole.
	   ``After Saturday's round at the PGA, I was disappointed with the
way I was playing, having put myself out of contention,'' Mickelson
said. ``I had to start seeing better shots, and I did that on
Sunday. I carried that with me today.''
	   Mickelson celebrated his Pebble Beach victory by hugging his
grandmother, who is in her mid-80s and walked all 18 holes with him
Monday.
	   The AT and T tournament chartered a plane to take players from
Seattle to Monterey on Sunday night. Those continuing to the next
tour stop, the International near Denver, got another chartered
flight Monday night.
	   Officials also had to do some last-minute scrambling to prepare
the course, which played host to a vintage car show on Sunday.
	   Pernice said finishing the tournament six months after it began
was the only fair thing to do. Two years ago, the entire AT and T
tournament was canceled because of lousy weather.
	   ``I think the tour did the right thing,'' he said. ``They tried
to do whatever they could to satisfy the people of Pebble Beach.
This is one of our special events.''
</TEXT>
