<HEADLINE>
Yankees 7, Royals 1
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KANSAS CITY, Missouri (AP) _ David Cone became the first 18-game
winner in the major leagues, and Tino Martinez, Tim Raines and
Bernie Williams homered Monday night to lead the New York Yankees
over the Kansas City Royals 7-1.
	   New York (91-30), on pace to break the 1906 Chicago Cubs' record
of 116 wins, is 9-0 against the Royals this year and has outscored
them 75-20. The Yankees, 61 over .500 for the first time since the
1939 club finished 106-45, has a 20-game lead, its largest since
they were 20 1-2 games ahead on Aug. 9, 1941.
	   Cone (18-4) allowed the one run and five hits in seven innings,
and Chili Davis returned from the disabled list with an RBI single
that made it 2-0 against Jose Rosado (6-9). Davis hadn't played
since the second game of the season.
 &UR; Orioles 3, Twins 2
	   In Baltimore, Scott Erickson (13-9) allowed two runs and seven
hits in seven innings and matched his career high with 10
strikeouts.
	   Harold Baines drove in two runs for the Orioles, who moved
within 6 1-2 games of Boston in the AL wild-card chase. Baltimore
trailed by 15 1-2 games at the All-Star break, but its 28-8 record
since that time is the best in the majors.
	   Jimmy Key pitched a perfect eighth and Armando Benitez got three
outs for his 18th save. LaTroy Hawkins (7-12) was the loser.
 &UR; Indians 4, Devil Rays 3
	   In Cleveland, rookie Richie Sexson was 3-for-4 with his first
major league homer and two RBIs as the Indians beat Wilson Alvarez
(5-12) and won for just the 18th time in 38 games since the
All-Star break.
	   Cecil Fielder, signed last Thursday, made his first start for
Cleveland and was 0-for-4. Manny Ramirez hit his 29th homer.
	   Bartolo Colon (13-6) allowed two runs and six hits in 6 2-3
innings, and Mike Jackson pitched the ninth for his 30th save,
throwing a called third strike past Quinton McCracken to end the
game with a runner on third.
	    &UR; MORE
