<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Racketeering </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Toyota Motor latest Japanese firm to admit ties with racketeers
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Toyota Motor Corp., Japan's largest carmaker, said
Tuesday it has severed relations with suspected corporate
racketeers, adding its name to a growing list of prestigious firms
linked to the Japanese underworld.
	   Toyota's announcement came one day after police arrested a pair
of alleged ``sokaiya'' racketeers on suspicion of extorting 22.8
million yen (dlrs 155,000) from Japan Airlines Co.
	   ``In accordance with recommendations from the authorities last
spring, we have moved to end relations with firms associated with
sokaiya racketeers,'' Toyota said in a statement released early
Tuesday.
	   The automaker also said it had severed ties to Taihei Co., a
leasing company run by one of the two suspected underworld
operatives taken into custody on Monday.
	   No specifics on the extent of Toyota's relationship with Taihei
were available, said company spokeswoman Ririco Takeuchi.
	   A number of executives at top Japanese companies, including
Nomura Securities Co., Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank Ltd. and Mitsubishi
Motors Corp., were tainted last year in a broad probe of corporate
ties to professional racketeers.
	   Sokaiya specialize in extorting hush money from companies. They
usually threaten to disrupt annual company shareholders meetings by
disclosing embarrassing business decisions or other sensitive
information.
 &UR; (cd)
</TEXT>
